ate with details of attack; no pickup. adds byline.</note>
sikh gunmen opened fire with automatic rifles and machine guns on a holiday gathering early friday in punjab state, killing at least 32 people and injuring 40 others, police said
the attack in hoshiarpur district was one of the bloodiest since sikh extremists launched their guerrilla war for an independent homeland in the northern state in 1982
punjab security forces and new delhi police were put on alert after the killing to prevent any backlash by hindus
there was no immediate claim of responsibility
police said both hindus and sikhs were among those killed and injured in the assault, which occurred as india began its celebration of holi, or the festival of color. the national holiday commemorates the triumph of the hindu god lord krishna over evil
sikhs, who make up about 2 percent of india's 780 million people, claim they are discriminated against by hindus who form the majority of the population. punjab state is predominantly sikh
the latest assault occurred as about 300 people gathered to celebrate the festival at kari sari village near the town of hoshiarpur, which is about 80 miles east of the sikh holy city of amritsar
suresh aurora, senior superintendent of police at hoshiarpur, said about 12 gunmen dashed onto the festival ground at about 12:30 a.m. friday and opened fire
he said the injured, many of them in ``extremely serious'' condition, were rushed to hospitals in hoshiarpur town and jalandhar, capital of the neighboring district
the gunmen fled and were being sought, he said
the attack was the worst in punjab since last july, when sikh gunmen waylaid three buses in two attacks and slaughtered 72 people, most of them hindus
the latest killings raised to more than 370 the number of people killed in attacks blamed on sikh extremists in punjab since the start of the year
last year, more than 1,000 people died in such attacks
on thursday, sikh extremists had gunned down a sikh family of eight and a paramilitary policeman in punjab
sikhism is an offshoot of hinduism that came into existence 500 years ago
punjab has been under direct federal rule since prime minister rajiv gandhi dismissed the moderate sikh state government last year for failing to curb terrorism
with the state health service in virtual bankruptcy, yugoslavia's communist authorities are weighing the possibility of using private medical practice on a large scale
some medical associations already have resorted to private practice in the republics of slovenia and serbia, partly because of large losses built up by the state medical service
the official tanjug news agency said authorities in belgrade are preparing a ``detailed analysis'' of private medicine and will announce a decision by the end of may
orthodox communist party dogma regards private medical practice as unacceptable
but under consideration are the use of privately operating doctors and small private clinics employing up to two physicians plus medical staff
yugoslavia's deepening economic crisis is the main reason for the financial troubles in the state-run health service
a sharp drop in the value of yugoslavia's currency, the dinar, which lost about 200 percent against western currencies in a year, has driven up the cost of imports of many medicines, raw materials for their production and medical equipment
in addition, a government price freeze has made the production of such goods from imported raw materials unprofitable and has resulted in a shortage of several medical and nutrition items, including baby formula
in january, due to virtual lack of baby formula in several yugoslav hospitals, new-born babies had to be fed intravenouly
private medical practice in yugoslavia was abolished after world war ii when the communist party took power
the statea health service is financed by deductions from yugoslavs' salaries
however, since the state is unable to entirely subsidize health care, most parts of yugoslavia have permitted patients to pay for medical services on a private basis
we cannot claim any more that our medical services are free of charge, and this shows that we don't have the system typical of a communist country,'' said dr. dragan djordjevic, a belgrade physician
this means that the ideological barrier, which would prevent introduction of private medical practice, no longer exists in yugoslavia.''
in addition to shortages of medical supplies, the state health service has been afflicted by a sharp drop in services and an increasing number of work stoppages by medical staff over wages
the state-run press reported recent strikes by doctors and nurses in belgrade, zagreb and ljubljana
the lack of drugs and medical supplies, including such basic items as soap, detergents and alcohol, has affected the work of many hospitals, the newspaper vecernje novosti said recently
hygiene has fallen to the lowest possible level, and even disposable items have to be sterilized for multiple use,'' it said, adding that patients are bringing their own soap to the hospital
faced with a 170-percent inflation rate, a $20 billion foreign debt and a sharp drop in living standards, communist-governed yugoslavia has been hit by its worst economic crisis in its history
the newspaper politika said some state hospitals may close down if a newly adopted bankruptcy law is strictly enforced
the bankruptcy law, designed to revive the ailing economy, forsees the closing down of all enterprises that lose money
serbian and slovenian doctors maintain that private medical practice would create additional jobs for at least 4,000 doctors currently registered as unemployed in yugoslavia
they said it would also bring a return of several thousand yugoslav medical specialists who have been working in western countries and have accumulated large foreign currency savings
thirty-one years ago, brigitte bardot wrapped her voluptuous body in a sheet, tantalizing moviegoers around the world who flocked to see france's new ``sex kitten'' in the film made by her director-husband, roger vadim
the film, ``and god created woman,'' became a movie classic, launched bb's career and defined the tone and content for the director's subsequent films
vadim has gone back to the same title for his latest film, which has little in common with the 1956 version except a continuing fascination with freedom, sensuality and bourgeois morality
if this sounds a bit pedantic, remember that vadim is the filmmaker who gave the world the avant-garde sci-fi romp ``barbarella'' starring his young, blond wife, jane fonda
his films are never short on beauty, especially the blond, blue-eyed kind. vadim has cast his 26 movies with women ranging from elegant catherine deneuve, his third wife, to earthy angie dickinson, and from intellectual jeanne moreau to sexpot susan sarandon
for the new ``and god created woman,'' which opens this month in the united states, vadim chose blond rebecca demornay, whose previous credits include playing the saucy strumpet opposite tom cruise in ``risky business'' and the angelic girl next door in ``the trip to bountiful.''
people tell rebecca that she has never looked more beautiful than in this film,'' said vadim, the gallic svengali, as he relaxed in a borrowed paris apartment after a morning of television interviews. ``but it wasn't intentional. i make people look beautiful, i can't help it
you wouldn't ask rodin to make an ugly sculpture, or me to make a film with an ugly woman. that's my style, that's my nature.''
bardot played a woman who marries a man in order to escape an orphanage, only to fall for the man's younger brother, played by jean-louis trintignent. although in the end she remains with her older husband, the film is an exploration of sexual freedom
i wanted to show a normal young girl whose only difference was that she behaved in the way a boy might, without any sense of guilt on a moral or sexual level,'' vadim said. ``there was really nothing shocking in what brigitte did, what was provocative was her natural sensuality.''
vadim said sexual liberty is taken for granted now and women in the 1980s are fighting for freedom of a different sort. he said he didn't want to remake his earlier film but wanted to illuminate the problems faced by a modern, young woman
women now seek the freedom to be themselves, to be successful in work without renouncing old-fashioned romanticism. women want to keep what they have gained without giving up those romantic ideas which are very nice in life,'' said the 60-year-old vadim, who looks more like a french lawyer in his gray slacks and navy pullover than an international film director
the film, shot in santa fe, n.m., tells the story of a young, female prisoner who meets a carpenter working at the jail and marries him as a way to show she is a stable candidate for parole
her husband is nice, but chauvinistic, and the film follows their relationship to an ``optimistic end, where they can stay together without her giving up herself.''
vadim moved to malibu, calif., after his divorce from fonda and rented a house across from her so the two could share in the raising of their daughter. he also has children by deneuve and his second wife, annette stroyberg
during the interview, he talked about the movie industry and said his counterparts in french film lack the professionalism that characterizes hollywood. he pointed out that 1987 was one of the worst years in a decade for box-office receipts in france, while the opposite was true in the united states
french filmmakers are beginning to realize they have to try harder, put more thought and effort into their films and make them more international,'' he said
vadim has been asked by several paris producers to shoot his next film in france and is considering making a science-fiction film or suspense thriller here in english
but you know i've never had great luck in france. when `and god created woman' was released the critics were horrible, especially to brigitte who they said couldn't act,'' he said. ``of course she couldn't, but she had another quality, she was and is inimitable, unique.''
after the film was an international success, the french critics changed their minds, he said
i am sure that these same critics will aggress my new movie, saying, `how can you touch such a classic, french masterpiece?''' results</head>
the good-news, bad-news assessment that ronald and nancy reagan gave of america's drug problem pretty much describes the administration's record in fighting it
while president reagan and his wife have alerted people to the threat, the administration's war against drugs has produced only mixed results, and consequently a lot of arguing and finger-pointing
nowhere was this more evident than at this week's white house conference on a drug-free america, where administration drug-fighting strategy came in for a lot of second-guessing
kicking off the conference monday, reagan claimed progress in attacking ``the supply side of the crusade against drugs.'' mrs. reagan gave a more pessimistic report on the demand side, saying ``we must face the fact that drugs are tearing our communities apart.''
reagan said ``we've strengthened the laws'' and ``drug seizures are at an all-time high.''
seizures of cocaine and the confiscation of drug-related assets are at record levels, he said, and arrests are up by 66 percent
yet, his drug-fighting performance came under attack because horror stories about abuse still abound _ in cities and in the suburbs. many drug-producing countries remain ambivalent about cooperative drug-fighting efforts, while traffickers skirt interdiction efforts
the conference turned into a critique of the administration's record. several speakers, including a member of reagan's cabinet, barked that not enough is being done
if we are winning the war on drugs, i wish the commanders would go out and tell it to the troops in the field,'' said rep. charles rangel, d-n.y., chairman of the house select committee on narcotics abuse and control
we need to get away from a policy of containment,'' said rep. clay shaw, r-fla. ``we want you to come up with a plan for victory. let's fight it like we fought world war ii, not like vietnam. let's fight to win.''
while an administration becomes accustomed to attacks from congress, sometimes from both the democratic and republican sides of the aisle, reagan's policy was also questioned by secretary of education william bennett
we are in real danger of losing the war against drugs,'' bennett told the conference. he called for direct u.s. military intervention in producing countries to destroy drug operations
reagan has taken comfort in a health and human services survey showing that for the first time in 13 years, a declining proportion of high school seniors admit having used cocaine
but a congressional report released tuesday, while the conference was in progress, seemed to cast some doubt on that. a study by the general accounting office said some experts fear the decline from 16.9 percent to 15.2 percent among the respondents saying they used cocaine may not have taken into account the newly popular ``crack'' form of cocaine which is smoked
the administration's war on drugs faces other problems. for instance, reagan's principal initiative aimed at attacking the demand side of the problem _ a program of wide-scale voluntary testing across america _ has never gotten off the ground because of legal problems
the supreme court just last monday agreed for the first time to decide a case involving the constitutionally thorny issue of mandatory work-place drug testing _ and its decision may not set widespread precedent because it deals specifically with law enforcement jobs rather than general employment
congressional critics also say the administration has shown little return on the more than $21.5 billion spent on combating drugs over the last seven years, and state and local officials have complained that reagan budget cuts have adversely affected their ability to deal with the problem
bennett came closer than anyone in the administration to admitting that the counter-attack wasn't working very well
we should consider broader use of military force against both the production and shipment of drugs,'' he said
the issue did not elude the attention of presidential hopefuls, either
pat robertson declared that ``if one of those drug planes is flying without giving identification ... coming into this country, i wouldn't hesitate to give orders to shoot him down.''
but jesse jackson said tough talk isn't enough
it's a cop-out to just say to children, `just say no to drugs.' ... children do not buy $150 billion worth of drugs. ... children do not grow the drugs, do not run the cartels,'' jackson said in a stump speech
we must stop the flow of drugs into our country. it's corrupting our society. if elected, i will ... cut the supply of drugs. but you the people must cut the demand for drugs.''
merrill hartson covers the white house for the associated press
attorney general edwin meese iii says a conservative republican's bill to ban undetectable plastic handguns would be effective against terrorists who might use such weapons
meese's endorsement of legislation sponsored by sen. james mcclure, r-idaho, is the latest development in a growing dispute over plastic guns
supporters of rival legislation say that mcclure's bill would still permit guns to slip by metal detectors and x-ray machines at their current settings
mcclure on wednesday released a letter by meese, saying: ``based on our review, we believe that your bill ... is an excellent legislative proposal to deal with the threat posed by criminals and terrorists armed with such weapons.''
the national rifle association also backs mcclure's bill
the mcclure proposal would make it illegal to manufacture or import a plastic firearm unless one of these conditions exists:
_the barrel is made in whole or in part of a metallic substance that can be detected by a magnetometer
_the serial number required by law is engraved on a metallic substance capable of detection
the measure also would require plastic portions of any such firearm to be infused with substances that would register on a x-ray machine
handgun control inc. and a coalition of law enforcement groups have joined to oppose mcclure's bill and support legislation sponsored by sen. howard m. metzenbaum, d-ohio. metzenbaum has support from republican sen. strom thurmond of south carolina
metzenbaum and his supporters say their legislation has the ingredient that mcclure's measure lacks: a requirement that the guns have enough metal to be detected at currently used settings of security machines
they contend that guns meeting the guidelines in mcclure's proposal would only set off alarms if detectors were operated at settings so low they would stop everyone with a key chain
plastic guns are not yet in production, but handgun control inc. said a florida manufacturer will be ready to produce them in a year
smoking-related deaths are costing the nation at least $65 billion each year ... one-third on direct health care costs, while the remaining two-thirds _ a whopping $43 billion _ is attributable to lost job productivity. ultimately, these staggering costs are borne by the average citizen _ and nearly 75 percent of americans don't even smoke
it makes no sense that while the surgeon general's office is waging a campaign against smoking, the federal government is involved in price supports for tobacco. and it's illogical for politicians to bemoan the grave health consequences of tobacco while, at the same time, supporting its production
i believe the federal government should get out of tobacco production, and continue its campaign to ducate the public on the dangers of smoking ... a user fee on tobacco products would serve as an added incentive to stop smoking. revenues from such a fee should be earmarked exclusively for meeting the long-term health care needs of our older citizens.''
here are the democrats' replies:
in massachusetts, i have supported policies to protect the rights of non-smokers. and as president, i would support a vigorous public health campaign to encourage smokers to quit and to incourage young people from taking up the habit
i do not favor direct taxpayer subsidies to farmers who grow tobacco. however, i do not oppose the tobacco industry's own effort to provide economic assistance through the existing commodity credit corporation loan program, which operates at no net cost to the taxpayer. and i strongly support efforts to encourage tobacco farmers to diversify so that they can deal with the economic impact of what i hope will be continuing progress towards a smoke-free society.''
i do support the current federal program. there are a lot of small- and medium-sized farmers who depend on that program to give them a fair price. when properly run, this program does not cost the government any money: it's paid for by the people who smoke cigarettes
i support measures to ban smoking on commercial airlines on short flights and to restrict smoking to certain areas on longer flights. also, although i do not favor a total ban on advertising and promotion of tobacco products, i do support an active public education campaign to inform people of the potential adverse effects that tobacco products can have on our health.''
i support the current federal program for tobacco which is funded entirely by the contributions of growers and processors and does not rely at all on taxpayers' dollars. the current program helps many small tobacco farmers stay in business
i believe the government should do everything in its power to educate the public about the hazards associated with smoking. i have been a strong supporter of stronger warning labels on cigarette packages and other mechanisms to inform the public of smoking-related health risks. i believe public education will result in a gradually decreasing demand for tobacco products
campaign aide jay angoff said hart does not support price supports because ``it makes no sense on the one hand to pay people to grow tobacco and then for us as a society to incur the tremendous costs that tobacco imposes.''
on anti-smoking efforts, angoff said hart ``certainly wouldn't spend a lot of money on it, but he would use the powers of the presidency to make people aware of the harm smoking causes.''
in general i support the federal tobacco program although .. . i would like to see the tobacco program reformed so that small family farms benefit more than they currently do. at the present time production quotas are distributed in a way that favors corporate farmers and neglects the family farmer who is the backbone of the rural south. ..
as long as there is a demand for tobacco and people who make their livelihood from meeting that demand, the federal government should offer its assistance
but we have to recognize that 350,000 deaths per year are related to smoking. the government must beef-up educational efforts to inform the public of this hazard. just as importantly, we must make every effort possible to assist farmers to diversify out of tobacco production if they so desire. we should consider using some portion of the 16 cent tobacco excise tax to fund such an effort.''
the tobacco industry is very clear about getting the message across that the current tobacco program does not cost the taxpayers. while that may be true of the program that assists tobacco farmers, the fact is that smoking costs all of us greatly
i believe we must expand government efforts to discourage people from smoking. ... i believe we must begin to take steps to protect non-smokers from the adverse effects of smoking. i generally support legislative efforts to discourage smoking. i am co-sponsor of legislation that would double the federal excise tax on tobacco products. ..
this would have the effect of pricing tobacco products out of the reach of those most susceptible to developing a long-term smoking habit: teen-agers.''
nancy reagan says doctors should be more circumspect about commenting in public on the health problems of presidents and their families
in a television interview to be broadcast friday night, mrs. reagan recalled an instance when she and president reagan were watching television while he was in the hospital recovering from an operation ``and some doctor came on and said, `well, i'll give him about four or five months.'''
i thought to myself: doesn't it ever occur to these people that we might be sitting watching?' what a terrible, terrible statement to make!''
she said reagan did not react adversely to the doctor's comment but she said he reasonably could have wondered at that moment whether information about his health was being withheld from him
it would be a normal reaction,'' she said
mrs. reagan made her comments in an interview with barbara walters for a segment of the abc-tv news ``20-20'' program. by coincidence, the program is being shown on the reagans' 36th wedding anniversary
mrs. reagan did not say in the interview what the president was recovering from at the time the gloomy prognosis was broadcast. nor did she provide any further details. reagan has undergone several operations during the seven years of his presidency
recalling her bout with breast cancer, the first lady also said she did not understand the criticism directed at her when she chose to have her breast removed rather than to undergo chemotherapy or radiation treatment
i really don't understand the people who criticize,'' she said. ``it was my choice to make. so don't criticize me for making what i thought was the right choice for me
you know the whole point about feminism is that you have a choice, that women have a choice. ..
and i think having doctors who know nothing about the case, who know nothing about you, and know nothing about the case at all coming on giving their opinion, i don't think that's right.''
the senate should not revise the pending arms pact with the soviet union to bind future administrations to the current understanding of its intent, says the state department legal adviser
i don't think it is necessary or desirable to do that kind of thing,'' legal adviser abraham d. sofaer said in an interview
the heart of the issue is not so much a treaty signed last december banning medium-range nuclear missiles from superpower arsenals as a treaty signed in 1972 which limits testing of president reagan's strategic defense initiative missile defense system, known as star wars
democratic whip alan cranston of california has been holding discussions with senators from both parties, and an aide said he expects ``there to be language in the ratification resolution addressing the treaty interpretation issues.''
cranston has predicted that the treaty will win the necessary 67 votes in the 100-member body to be ratified
few senators have expressed disagreement over the meaning of the intermediate-range nuclear forces pact signed at the washington summit last december calling on the superpowers to destroy their nuclear missiles with ranges of 300 to 3,000 miles
the central controversy is an interpretation of the abm pact written by sofaer in 1985 which would allow wider testing of star wars components
cranston's legislative aide, gerry warburg, said the language expected in the inf resolution ``would contain a more broad statement concerning the interpretation of treaties generally,'' including the abm pact
cranston, sen. sam nunn, d-ga., the chairman of the armed services committee, and sen. joseph biden, d-del., of the foreign relations committee, all oppose sofaer's ``broad interpretation'' of the abm pact. warburg said they had been discussing the inf resolution with secretary of state george p. shultz
the senators contend that allowing the broad interpretation amounts to changing the rules in the middle of the game and would set a dangerous precedent in which any administration could duck treaty requirements simply by reinterpreting them
sofaer said inclusion of restrictive language in a resolution ratifying the inf treaty would not be binding on the soviet union, and could complicate rather than resolve interpretation of the abm pact
i know that they are not going to get a settlement of the abm dispute this way,'' said sofaer. ``it is a potential problem for inf ratification and i think overwhelmingly people support inf ratification.''
sofaer noted that shultz had sent the senate the 31-volume negotiating record of the inf pact and had also agreed that any testimony by administration officials would be ``authoritative'' and reflect the president's understanding of the treaty
those practical things have been achieved,'' said sofaer, objecting to including in the ratification resolution any language that would commit future administrations to the current understanding of the treaty
if you want to go further, you might end up confusing or even harming international legal practice relating to treaty ratification,'' he said
while the senate can bind the administration to a particular interpretation of either the inf or the abm treaties, he said, it cannot bind the soviet union, unless the treaties are renegotiated
the treaty reflects two relationships,'' he said. ``it reflects a relationship between two sovereign nations, and then it also reflects the relations between the united states executive branch and the senate
when you talk about the meaning of a treaty, you are talking about the international relationship. you are talking about what binds the two nations.''
palestinian flags flutter from the power lines in this west bank community. plo grafitti adorns the walls. people here call kfar naami a ``liberated village.''
eight miles over the mountains, residents of bir zeit have blocked the roads with stones. they, too, claim their village is ``liberated.''
throughout the west bank, a few communities in the past few weeks have defied the israeli army and declared independence from the israeli occupation administration
these little pieces of ``palestine'' are the source of much pride among the arabs. but the reality is that the israelis do not want to take the trouble to ``unliberate'' many of the rebellious communities
this is a liberated village here,'' said aziz attaya of kfar naami, wearing a thick beard and a traditional arab headdress around his neck. ``we will all die for the creation of a palestinian state under the leadership of the plo.''
but, countered munir naser, a professor of biochemistry at bir zeit university, ``the occupation is everywhere. perhaps only our homes are liberated, and in reality, it's not true even there.''
hamad, another bir zeit resident who did not give his last name, admitted, ``we're not liberated in the true sense of lberation. there is a feeling of not being under the control of the israeli occupation. at the same time, we know that they are still here and still control the area.''
in most liberated villages, people have run up the palestinian flag, organized demonstrations, blocked roads, and in some cases, challenged the army to come and get them
the soldiers sometimes oblige. sometimes they do not
these rebellions are irritating, even embarrassing for israeli authorities, but they don't have any real practical effect beyond boosting the morale of local residents
the israeli authorities believe they should be put down but note that the priority is on keeping major roads open
the army is not everywhere, but deployed according to suitable priorities,'' maj. gen. amram mitzna, the west bank's military commander, told israel's army radio
they are on the main roads and secondary roads that must be guarded. they guard the movement of israeli residents, be it school buses or other traffic.''
but a high-ranking police officer sounded tougher during a crackdown on the imminently unliberated silwan, a village incorporated into jerusalem after being captured from jordan in 1967
the people in silwan for the last two months thought they belonged to palestine,'' said the officer. ``we are now teaching them they live in israel, and they will never forget it.''
in kfar naami, a village of 2,000, one palestinian died in a clash with soldiers, but the army hasn't been back. the road through kfar naami simply isn't important enough to be worth the trouble of reclaiming
bir zeit has a population of 2,000. the university, closed because israeli officials say they want to prevent disturbances, normally has about 2,800 students
there is a demonstration every friday and sunday in bir zeit. teachers believe the government stays away because it fears the university will become a breeding ground for increased dissent and organization
naser says another reason the israelis leave bir zeit alone is because it has a more sophisticated population. many of the teaching staff studied abroad, are articulate and can use their voices and outside contacts to tell the world what is going on
some villagers are itching for a fight
the army doesn't come into the village because there are no settlers who pass through here,'' said a teen-ager named ahmed
i'd like to see the army come here,'' he said. ``not coming is not good for the town because people elsewhere, like in gaza, think we are not doing anything here. i hope they come. i would like to fight them. i'd be happy to sacrifice my life.''
united press international's new managers need about $1 million in loans immediately to pay overdue bills for items such as health care, rents and telephones, according to a memo from the company's new president
at the end of our first week, our preliminary analysis shows that the financial condition of the company has been deteriorating steadily, and that monumental efforts are needed to save it from liquidation,'' paul steinle wrote in a letter to employees dated march 1
upi needs ``short-term financing to bridge its cash flow requirements until additional investors can be approached,'' steinle said
steinle works for wnw group inc., a media investment group that assumed control of the financially ailing wire service on feb. 19
wnw bought control of the company's stock from mexican publisher mario vazquez rana for an undisclosed sum. upi emerged from chapter 11 proceedings in u.s. bankruptcy court with vazquez rana's purchase of the company in june 1986
in his three-page letter, steinle said the wire service guild, the union representing company employees, has been offered ``the opportunity to participate'' in ``short-term loan financing.''
steinle's memo to employees included portions of a letter sent to the guild over the weekend. dan carmichael, a union spokesman, said he had no comment on the letter, which the guild received tuesday
but he said he was curious to find out what the company meant by a ``loan opportunity.''
in the letter to the union, upi management said the company is ``facing an immediate and critical situation in the form of the funding of its ongoing operations.''
it said wnw group ``must immediately obtain approximately one million dollars in loans to enable upi to begin paying past due bills for critical items such as health care, rents, telephones, etc.''
in the long run, upi's financial situation will require ``an infusion of capital, which can only be provided by a sale of stock or securities,'' the letter said
steinle said the company wants the guild to move quickly _ by march 14 _ to adopt an employee stock option plan. under conditions set by the bankruptcy court, upi's employees have the right of first refusal to buy the company if it is put on the block
announcing the change of management last week, steinle and dr. earl w. brian, wnw's chairman, said they hoped to have a business plan for upi's future within four to six weeks
steinle's letter said the company intended to raise money through the sale of stock as soon as the business plan is complete
the managers said that during vazquez rana's tenure, the company was losing about a $1 million a month
brian, 48, is also the chairman of infotechnology inc., an electronics communications company based in new york. among its subsidiaries are financial news network, a 24-hour cable television company. infotech, as the company is known, is a minority shareholder of wnw group
rep. james traficant, a declared candidate for president, has appealed a u.s. tax court decision saying he owes back taxes and penalties for failing to report bribes of $108,000 from reputed organized-crime figures in 1980
traficant, d-ohio, filed a notice of appeal with the tax court wednesday, throwing the case into the 6th u.s. circuit court of appeals in cincinnati
traficant has described himself as a regional candidate for president and so far has not appeared on a primary election ballot. spokesmen have said he will focus mainly on ohio and neighboring states
in an opinion issued last september, judge john williams said traficant's actions when he was campaigning for mahoning county sheriff in 1980 reflected an intent to evade taxes and the internal revenue service had convincingly established that the underpayment was due to fraud
they're intimidating,'' traficant said of the federal government. ``they beat you down, they wear you out, and they're working on me.''
the irs has calculated that traficant owes nearly $90,000 in back taxes and penalties
the civil tax case is based on testimony and evidence from traficant's 1983 criminal trial in which he was charged with bribery and income tax evasion. in that case, traficant defended himself and was acquitted
the charges alleged that traficant accepted money in exchange for his promise to ignore the illegal activities of reputed mobsters in youngstown, ohio
the case was based on tape recordings allegedly between traficant and the mobsters and a written statement to the fbi the government contended traficant had signed saying he took the money in exchange for a promise of cooperation
traficant argued that the money was not income because he returned most of it and used legitimate contributions in his campaign for sheriff
a senator says the cia is conducting an inquiry into whether the agency provided personal and political information on u.s. senators to panamanian military ruler gen. manuel antonio noriega
sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., said wednesday two officials identifying themselves as being with the cia's office of the inspector general interviewed jose i. blandon, a former top panamanian intelligence official, last week
blandon alleged at a senate hearing last month that the agency had provided information on senators to noriega, who in turn passed it on to him. the cia is prohibited by law from domestic spying on u.s. citizens
d'amato said blandon told him the cia investigators were interested primarily in his charges that noriega had received information about both the political beliefs and the personal lives of several senators and staff members
he said blandon had gone into the lengthy interview under the impression he would be talking to investigators from the justice department. ``he was surprised that it turned out to be intelligence people,'' d'amato said
he didn't take it as any kind of harassment. he indicated to the agency that he could help them if they were interested.''
d'amato and sen. john kerry, d-mass., called the hearings last month at which blandon and other witnesses publicly wove complicated tales about how noriega sold out his country to drug traffickers
a cia official, speaking on condition of anonymity, would not confirm the internal inquiry, but said ``it would make sense'' for the agency's investigators to want to speak directly to someone who had made such charges. the cia has categorically denied providing any such information to the panamanian government
d'amato said blandon related to the cia investigators the same story he gave to the senate foreign relations subcommittee on terrorism, narcotics and international operations feb. 9-10
blandon, who was fired in january as panama's consul general in new york, told investigators then that noriega received and passed to him materials on senators and their staff members, typed in english on plain white paper
in the lower right-hand corner was the signature of a panamanian intelligence official who forwarded the material, along with an indication of the original source of the information _ usually the cia or the national security council, said officials familiar with the classified portion of blandon's testimony. the sources spoke on condition of anonymity
these were not benign official biographies,'' one official said. ``they were very pointed descriptions, directed at the local market'' and apparently designed to curry favor with noriega
blandon said intelligence services of other countries in the region received similar materials regularly, the officials said
blandon also has made the allegations in conversations with sen. david boren, d-okla., chairman of the senate intelligence committee, and members of his staff. boren has said he has ``no reason to believe'' the allegations, but is looking into them
others involved in intelligence have sought to cast doubts on blandon's credibility and his motives for turning against noriega, whom he served as a longtime top adviser. but d'amato reiterated his belief that blandon is telling the truth
d'amato raised the possibility that the information about senators and staff members could have been compiled by either a low-level ``functionary'' at the cia or by an outside ``contractor'' working for the agency
in his final appearance on the nato stage, president reagan got virtually everything he wanted, including a bouquet for his peacemaking efforts with mikhail s. gorbachev and a mandate to demand more from the soviet leader this spring
reagan leaves brussels today with a strong reaffirmation of alliance solidarity, criticism of the soviet record on human rights, and nato demands for sweeping cutbacks in warsaw pact tanks, artillery and other non-nuclear forces
in the spirit of harmony, major differences were muted or ignored as nato leaders celebrated the signing of a u.s.-soviet treaty to eliminate a whole class of nuclear missiles in europe and asia
as the leader of the western alliance, reagan can take satisfaction that nato weathered the disarmament storm of 1982 and deployed intermediate-range nuclear missiles, a step that brought the soviets back to the negotiating table and produced the inf treaty
now, with just 10 months remaining in office, he has a vote of confidence for negotiations with the kremlin toward a 50 percent cut in strategic nuclear arms, as well as a strategy for east-west talks in which nato will insist on lower levels of warsaw pact tanks, artillery, planes and ground forces
gorbachev has scored points in europe with his talk of peace and disarmament, and now reagan has been put in the same spotlight with new attention focused on the inf treaty
over the last several months, a number of people have said the inf agreement has caused fissures within the alliance; the alliance is troubled; europe is adrift; they're not sure of the united states' commitment,'' said lt. gen. colin powell, the president's national security adviser
well, the president reaffirmed our commitment to europe. he did it clearly, and that reaffirmation was welcomed by the other members of the alliance,'' powell added. ``so i think it's been a most useful meeting, one that was necessary, one that was important.''
the summit was a bright spot in what is likely to be a difficult year at home for reagan
as a lame-duck president with a democratic-controlled congress hoping to keep republicans out of the white house, reagan will have little chance to advance his legislative agenda
traditionally, then, foreign policy becomes the focus of outgoing presidents, and reagan is no exception
the nato summit with the leaders of 15 other countries was another in a series of farewell sessions, though he will see five of the officials in toronto at the annual economic summit in june
before the economic summit, however, comes the trip to moscow, his fourth meeting with gorbachev. it is expected sometime in late may or early june
both sides seem eager for reagan's visit, even though it appears unlikely the leaders will be able to sign another major arms pact. reagan said in a recent interview it appeared unlikely there would be enough time to wrap up a strategic arms treaty before the moscow summit, but he said he thought it could be completed before he leaves office
regardless, a reagan trip to moscow, to the heart of what he once called the evil empire, would dominate world attention and give both the president and the soviet leader another forum to seek a legacy as peacemaker
terence hunt has covered ronald reagan since 1980 and is the ap's white house correspondent
measuring the difference in nato and warsaw pact conventional forces is more than just a numbers game. it is a complicated and tricky task that goes beyond simply counting tanks and soldiers
western leaders meeting in brussels on wednesday issued a special statement demanding huge cutbacks in soviet bloc conventional forces, highlighting an issue that has divided negotiators for years
since 1973, negotiators for the alliances have been trying to agree on how many troops the blocs could throw into a fight in europe. western analysts say it would be more than 2 million on a side
now, as europe heads for elimination of medium-range nuclear missiles under a treaty signed by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev, new attention has been focused on conventional forces
the pentagon says the soviet bloc has a substantial edge over nato in five major ground force categories
according to the pentagon's 1987 report ``soviet military power,'' moscow and its european allies have 230 divisions compared with nato's 121. the soviet edge in main battle tanks is 52,000 to 24,250. they lead in antitank guided weapons launchers 28,000 to 22,580
the report says the east bloc has 42,000 artillery and mortar launchers compared with the west's 18,350 and has 54,000 armored personnel carriers, while nato has 41,500
of the direct comparisons, nato leads only in attack helicopters, 1,250 to 970
the numbers include forces deployed in europe and those that can be rapidly deployed from the united states
when he was supreme allied commander in europe from 1979 to 1987, gen. bernard w. rogers used such figures in a set speech on the subject. he would say, in effect: ``we'd give them a good fight if deterrence failed and a war broke out, but it wouldn't be long before i'd have to pick up the phone and ask the nato politicians to let me use nuclear weapons.''
even rogers warned, however, against what has become known as ``bean counting'' _ judging strength by mere numbers
joshua epstein, a brookings institution scholar, for example, has said ``neither the pentagon nor the congress actually behave as though numerical equality mattered. if either did, it would be frantically shoveling money out of aircraft carriers, where we lead 14:1 _ and into tanks ...''
there are many variables that have to be weighed. they include:
_ the difference in requirements of defensive and offensive forces. military history has shown that offensive forces need massive superiority at any given point of an attack against well-fortified positions
since nato is a defensive alliance, it presumably does not need more or even equal numbers of troops to stop an attack, according to nato doctrine
_ the quality of weaponry. nato considers its forces have better and more modern equipment than the soviets have
_ troop reliability. would soviet allies fight as fiercely in an invasion of west europe as u.s. allies defending their homelands? many analysts doubt they would, and the authors of ``soviet military power'' concede it ``is not a certainty.''
_ terrain. the potential battlegrounds of nato's central front _ west germany in particular _ are full of streams, forests, bogs, cities and other choke points that could lower the effectiveness of tanks. ``wars are not fought on paper,'' wrote george perkovich, a world policy institute fellow who recently studied the conventional balance
_ asymmetries. even with the soviet edge in ground forces, the west has an advantage of 3,450 to 2,800 in fighter-bombers for ground attack, which would be used to hit forces massed for offensives
the london-based international institute for strategic studies _ whose annual report ``the military balance'' is the quintessence of bean counting _ says the ``conventional balance is still such as to make general military aggression a highly risky undertaking for either side.''
there would still appear to be insufficient overall strength on either side to guarantee a victory,'' the iiss said
