leno joins such talents as bill cosby, john candy and robin williams as recipients of the award named in memory of elmer green, ``longtime caretaker and friend of the lampoon,'' the magazine said in a statement wednesday
the lampoon, founded in 1876, is the oldest humor magazine in the nation
singer john denver thought he'd have some fun at a recent performance near lake tahoe, nev., so he sang ``the ballad of gary hart.''
the reaction has been terrific,'' denver's agent, dan schrier of los angeles, said in a telephone interview. ``he did it for fun, with no maliciousness at all.''
but hart spokesman rolf wiegand indicated little amusement wednesday and called denver's performance ``one man's exercise in poor taste.''
the tune, written by singer-songwriter tom paxton, recounts hart's career in the senate and his campaign problems after he was linked with miami model donna rice
as the song describes it:
well, he met her at a party, and her name was donna rice
she was gary's kind of woman, she was pure miami vice
she thought he was gary collins, and could get her on tv
she suggested monkey business, and the rest is history!''
spanish opera star jose carreras has been discharged from a hospital here, where he was successfully treated for leukemia and has returned to his home in barcelona, hospital officials say
carreras, 41, received four months of treatment at the fred hutchinson cancer research center for acute lymphocytic leukemia, including a nov. 16 bone marrow transplant. he was free of the disease when discharged friday, spokeswoman susan edmonds said wednesday
ms. edmonds said carreras had discussed returning to seattle for a concert to benefit the center when he resumes his singing career
carreras will remain under a physician's care in spain, and is to return to seattle for a checkup in a year. people with acute lymphocytic leukemia, an especially severe form of the disease, have a survival rate of about 25 percent to 40 percent over three to five years
former presidential press secretary jody powell, whose confederate ancestors fought in the battle of second manassas, is joining the attack on plans to build a shopping mall near the battlefield
powell said the fight to preserve the site near the manassas battlefield national park is worthy because encroaching development is a problem at many battlefields and historic sites
goodness, if you can't stop something this bad, then what hopes do you have of fending off more creeping sorts of problems, where a park gets nibbled to death?'' powell said tuesday
powell is putting the resources of his firm, ogilvy &amp; mather public affairs of washington, at the disposal of the save the battlefield coalition
ten of his ancestors fought at the battle of second manassas in 1862, part of which was waged on land where the hazel-peterson cos. of fairfax plan to break ground for william center
rolling stone magazine's choice to cover the impeachment trial of gov. evan mecham has some experience with embattled chief executives _ former nixon aide john ehrlichman
ehrlichman, who spent 18 months in prison for his role in the watergate scandal, called the assignment ``a match made in heaven.''
i'm working on a novel and it has an impeachment scene in it, so i was going to come over and take a look at this anyway,'' ehrlichman said tuesday. ``it's a ready-made opportunity to observe. secondly, it's a subject that intrigues me. i certainly have some feel for the underlying issues.''
ehrlichman, 63, lives in santa fe, n.m., and is working on his seventh novel, a story about a fictional u.s. president
millionaire philanthropist armand hammer wants to wipe out cancer by the year 2000, and is leading a campaign to raise $1 billion a year for research on the killer disease
hammer said he hopes to raise $500 million in private contributions, then have that matched by federal funds. some members of congress already have agreed to support the effort, he said in a telephone interview wednesday
hammer, chairman and chief executive officer of occidental petroleum corp., already has donated $100,000 for cancer research and has received commitments from nine other industrialists to do the same
the money will go directly to research at the national cancer institute in bethesda, md., said hammer, a non-practicing physician who turns 90 in may. ``there will be no overhead charges,'' he said
the institute's annual research budget is $1.4 billion
the nikkei stock average closed at 25,596.31 points, down 86.51 points, on the tokyo stock exchange thursday
about one in 500 american women giving birth is infected with the aids virus, a study published today suggests
the authors used a survey of blood samples routinely taken from newborn babies to help estimate the scope of aids infection. most surveys of aids infection have concentrated on male homosexuals, drug addicts and others at high risk of catching the disease
this paper gives a more accurate way to judge the scope of the epidemic in women,'' said dr. rodney hoff. ``nothing else comes close to this in being able to measure the prevalence in the united states.''
the study found that one of every 476 women giving birth, or 2.1 for each 1,000, were infected with the virus. however, this varied greatly, depending on where they lived
at three inner-city boston hospitals, eight per 1,000 were infected. in suburban and rural hospitals, just under one per 1,000 carried the virus
hoff directed the study of massachusetts women at the state department of public health using tiny samples of blood routinely drawn from babies to check for phenylketonuria, or pku, and other diseases
dr. george f. grady, the state epidemiologist, said the state's infection rate probably mirrors the nation's, because the rate of actual aids cases in massachusetts is virtually the same as throughout united states
he said the low suburban and rural infection rate in massachusetts is likely similar across much of the united states
i think it is not higher than that, and probably lower, in less coastal and less urban states than massachusetts,'' grady said
dr. timothy dondero, chief of aids surveillance at the u.s. centers for disease control, cautioned against placing too much emphasis on the massachusetts data
it's not scientifically wise to try to make a national projection from one or two points,'' he said
dondero noted that a similar study conducted in new york, which has more aids cases than any other state, found a significantly higher level of infection. the new york state health department study indicated about one in every 116 women giving birth in the state carried the aids virus
the massachusetts research was based on anonymous aids antibody testing on 30,708 babies born in massachusetts during the first six months of last year. the results were published in the new england journal of medicine
the researchers assumed that the babies received the antibodies _ but not necessarily the infection _ from mothers who carried the aids virus. dondero said about 40 percent of babies of aids-infected women get the infection
projecting the massachusetts figures nationally, the doctors calculated that if as few as 20 percent of babies of aids carriers get the virus, then 1,620 aids-infected infants are born in the united states annually. if the figure is as high as 60 percent, then 4,860 infected children are born in a year
acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. as of feb. 29, the centers for disease control in atlanta had received reports of 54,723 americans with aids, 30,715 of whom had died
a judge's ruling that the gov. mario cuomo's administration blacklisted construction companies and then allowed them to buy their way off the list is ``a personal assault on my integrity,'' says the state's transportation commissioner
justice harold hughes of the trial-level state supreme court cited federal extortion laws wednesday in refusing to dismiss a lawsuit filed by paving companies that challenged, among other things, state-imposed affirmative action requirements on contractors
hughes did not say that any crimes had been committed by officials but that he was referring the case to federal and state prosecutors and the state's commission on goverment integrity for review
state transportation commissioner franklin white, one of the administration's highest-ranking blacks, characterized hughes' decision as ``a personal assault on my integrity as a public official and i'm outraged by it.''
white denied any blacklist for contractors existed and said the ruling will be appealed immediately
the lawsuit was filed by the new york state asphalt pavement association, which represents 34 contractors, against white and state office of general services commissioner john egan
in denying a state motion to dismiss the lawsuit, hughes said one company had agreed to pay $150,000 to benefit the state's disadvantaged, minority, women's business enterprise program to get off the blacklist
compelling contractors to enter into the agreements ... constitutes unethical and possibly criminal conduct,'' hughes wrote in his eight-page opinion
hughes said that as part of the agreements, the companies had to promise not to sue the state over their blacklisting
the lawsuit stems from white's attempt to crack down on contractors who are not meeting state and federal minority hiring requirements, or who have established ``front'' companies that falsely claim to be minority owned, or who have engaged in criminal activity such as bid-rigging
white has moved against companies under criminal investigation or that have been convicted of crimes that relate to public works projects
state courts recently have ruled against some of dot's attempts to force minority hiring by contractors. those decisions are on appeal
white's spokesman, timothy hulbert, said there was nothing illegal about barring contractors from doing business with the state if they had violated state laws or regulations. he said that was done only on a ``case-by-case basis'' and denied a blacklist was maintained
he also said there was nothing illegal about having those companies pay money to improve minority hiring programs as part of any agreements for them to get back in the state's good graces
a grass-roots campaign focusing on contributors to his former television ministry helped give pat robertson a 2-to-1 victory over vice president george bush in the alaska republican precinct caucuses
robertson claimed 47 percent of the votes compared to bush's 24 percent in a preference poll of 2,020 delegates elected at the precinct level. sen. bob dole took third with 20 percent and jack kemp trailed at 7 percent, party officials announced wednesday
robertson's effort was a low-cost affair concentrating on telephone canvassers and volunteers handing out pamphlets and inspirational cassette tapes at shopping malls, said walter wood, robertson's statewide coordinator
the focus was on getting ``disenfranchised'' voters involved in the political process, wood said. it helped to have lists of contributors to the christian broadcast network, which robertson headed before starting his presidential campaign, he said
you go where your strength is,'' wood said. ``it yielded us some great benefits. our sparks would start with the church and then they would expand out. get beyond the label of television evangelist, and people perk up. he's got answers.''
other campaign coordinators vowed to turn things around as the delegate selection process continues
these delegates aren't bound'' to robertson, said frank bickford, state coordinator for the dole campaign. ``there will be a chance to pick up delegates.''
clifford groh, bush's state coordinator, said that campaign could have done better with an investment of ``time and effort, maybe a little money, too.'' the bush campaign put less than $1,000 into the caucus effort, he said
bickford said the dole campaign spent about $25,000. wood did not reveal the cost of robertson's campaign, but said it was considerably less than $25,000
the 2,020 precinct delegates will be winnowed later this month to 400 district delegates, who then will choose 19 delegates to attend the national convention in august
allegiances can shift among the precinct and district delegates, but gop delegates to the national conventions have never abandoned their chosen candidates, said jim crawford, chairman of the alaska republican party
nearly 4,000 of the state's 55,000 registered republicans turned out for the caucuses, held throughout the state from saturday to tuesday, crawford said
there were a lot of strange faces,'' said linda shafer, volunteer media coordinator for the party. ``there were people new to the political process. you could tell by their political platforms _ things like anti-marijuana and anti-abortion _ that they were church folks.''
alaska, with only 19 of the 2,270 delegates at the national republican convention, has not been a high priority for the candidates. none has made a campaign stop here
legislation granting banks broad new securities powers cleared its first big hurdle after two days of contentious debate behind closed doors by the senate banking committee
the committee voted 18-2 late wednesday night to repeal most of the glass-steagall act, which has separated commercial banking from the securities business since the depression
but the approval came only after sen. christopher dodd, d-conn., pushed through an unrelated amendment limiting the ability of banks to expand into the insurance business
the bill faces a vote in the full senate. similar legislation still must pass the house, where two powerful committee chairmen, reps. john dingell, d-mich., and fernand j. st germain, d-r.i., have expressed great skepticism about expanding bank powers too much
however, sen. william proxmire, d-wis., said the lopsided committee approval of the compromise package improves the chances for its enactment
the vote ``means a good strong bill will not only pass the senate but will survive in conference,'' he said
the legislation, as orginally proposed by proxmire and sen. jake garn of utah, the panel's senior republican, addressed only securities powers
but, dodd, who represents a state where insurance companies are important employers, added a new element to the debate that stalemated the committee for two days. he successfully pushed for closing several loopholes that have permitted some banks to enter insurance in states which authorize that
under the bill adopted by the committee, bank holding companies would be permitted to underwrite and sell mortgage-backed securities, commercial paper and municipal revenue bonds immediately after enactment of the bill. they would be allowed to underwrite and sell corporate bonds and mutual funds six months after enactment
however, a separate vote by congress by april 1, 1991, would be required before banks could deal in corporate stocks
dodd said he did not obtain everything he wanted, but paul a. equale, a lobbyist for the independent insurance agents of america, said, ``we think chris dodd did a terrific job.''
under the insurance compromise, bank holding companies could deal in insurance in states that authorize it, provided those activities are limited to that state. the bill imposes no restrictions on state banks not owned by holding companies
bank holding companies could not sell insurance through banks located in another state. a loophole that had permitted some national banks to deal in insurance would be closed
the committee left to the senate as a whole a decision on whether several states could agree to allow each others' banks to engage in insurance activities across state borders
the glass-steagall act was passed in the wake of the 1929 stock market crash to preserve the safety of the banking system during future market downturns. but banks have argued that the internationalization of financial markets and the development of new securities products have made the glass-steagall barriers outdated
voting for the compromise bill were proxmire; garn; dodd; and sens. alan cranston, d-calif.; donald w. riegle, d-mich.; paul sarbanes, d-md.; alan dixon, d-ill.; james sasser, d-tenn.; terry sanford, d-n.c.; richard shelby, d-ala.; bob graham, d-fla.; timothy wirth, d-colo.; john heinz, r-pa.; william armstrong, r-colo.; chic hecht, r-nev.; christopher bond, r-mo.; john chaffee, r-r.i., and david karnes, r-neb
voting against the bill were sens. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., and phil gramm, r-texas. 4th graf pvs bgng, before the ...</note>
the u.s. dollar continued to rise against the japanese yen after opening above the 129-yen barrier, and stock prices temporarily topped pre-crash levels before closing lower in tokyo trading thursday
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues closed after moderate trading at 25,596.31 points, down 86.51 points or 0.34 percent from wednesday's close
the dollar closed at 129.30 yen, up 0.83 yen from wednesday's close of 128.47. the dollar opened at 129.05
before the october stock crash, the nikkei index stood at 25,746.56 points
basically we saw a bit of a fall off in early morning trading,'' said paul warren of the investment house salomon brothers. ``but the market has neatly switched to new areas, like electronics and utilities, which is keeping the momentum going.''
warren said he expected the market to return to its all-time high over the next two or three months
a currency dealer at a major commercial bank in tokyo, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the dollar's strength was due partly to a japanese news report that a senior u.s. monetary official in washington had suggested the united states would tolerate a considerable rise in the value of the dollar if the nation's trade deficit kept improving
the dollar had traded below 129 yen in tokyo since feb. 23
panama's attorney general said washington accused panama of not helping fight drug trafficking only because the united states has been unable to win its own war against drugs at home
attorney general carlos villalaz' statement wednesday followed by a day the u.s. government's denial to panama of certification as a nation doing its best against the drug trade
villalaz said washington had misrepresented the facts for political ends
it seems illogical that u.s. politicians, upon being unable to win the domestic war waged because of the large-scale consumption of drugs in their country, would pretend to resolve the problem by telling their electorate that the responsibility is panama's,'' said villalaz's statement
lack of certification means an end to u.s. military and economic aid, but aid to panama was cut off last year. it also could mean withdrawal of u.s. support for panamanian requests for loans from the world bank and other international agencies, but no applications are pending
having ... the evidence and reports that demonstrate that 1987 was the most successful year for joint (anti-narcotics) operations between panama and the united states, i declare that the current attitude of the north american government is inconceivable, illogical and immoral,'' the statement said
it said drug arrests, confiscation of drugs and seizure of profits from narcotics sales had increased, and noted reports by u.s. officials in 1987 praising the zeal of panamanian officials
gen. manuel antonio noriega, chief of the panama's 15,000-member defense forces and de factor ruler, was indicted in florida last month on trafficking charges
noriega has denied the drug trafficking accusations and claims they are part of a u.s. plot to renege on its agreement to turn over the panama canal to panama by the year 2000
we have told the americans time and again that, if they want to wipe out drug trafficking, they must be serious and set politics aside so that it does not interfere with stopping drugs,'' said the statement
nevertheless, it would seem that the attitude of the american government is intended to dishearten its allies in the fight against drugs, giving incentive to the traffickers and destroying even more its own youth
his flash and frenzy undiminished by time, little richard took over the grammy awards ceremony and was still in outrageous high spirits when he met reporters on the seventh floor of radio city music hall
hitting one of those fabulous high notes from his rock repertoir, little richard laughed and said, ``i'm going to scream like a white woman.''
little richard wasn't there wednesday night to win a grammy, but to present one
and the best new artist is _ me!'' he announced. ``i have never received nuthin' _ y'all never gave me no grammys, and i've been singing for years.''
i am the architect of rock 'n' roll,'' he shouted as his flustered co-presenter, buster poindexter, looked on and the crowd rose in a standing ovation. ``i am the originator!''
little richard repeated that he was the winner, but finally gave the grammy to jody watley
backstage, he sang the praises of michael jackson's performance on the telecast
i cried. `the man in the mirror,' i just love that,'' little richard said. ``i felt that. my big toe just shot up in my boot.''
asked if he was surprised that jackson didn't win any of the four grammys for which he was nominated, little richard's face expressed horror. ``i'm shocked. stunned. i think a whole lot of people are. i've never seen anything like michael in my life
he is a hard worker. he gives his all. he don't hold nothing back. he puts it all out there and you can pull it wherever you want to carry it.''
asked how long he'd been bitter at never receiving a grammy, little richard said, ``i'm not bitter, but it would be nice to have one.''
born richard penniman on dec. 5, 1932, little richard broke into rock _ smashed might be a better word _ in 1955 with ``tutti-frutti,'' and followed up with ``long tall sally'' and ``slippin' and slidin''' in 1956 and ``good golly, miss molly'' in 1958
he was the most outrageous of the early rockers with a 6-inch pompadour, pancake makeup, a pencil-thin mustache and an all-out attack on the piano
at the height of his fame, during a tour of australia in 1957, little richard got religion. according to one version he has told, he had a horrifying dream of the apocalypse during an airplane flight. once safely on the ground, he threw his jewelry off the sydney harbor bridge
he came back to rock in 1964 with ``bama lama bama loo,'' and more recently had an acting part in the film ``down and out in beverly hills.'' working with bette midler was fun, he said wednesday. ``the only thing that got me was the dog. he bit me.''
in 1986, little richard announced he had converted to judaism
little richard's on-stage tirade started when he accused poindexter (a.k.a. david johansen) of stealing his upswept hairdo. later, little richard admitted he had borrowed one his trademarks _ that ``whooo.''
i got that from (gospel singer) clara ward. i don't have to pass it on; everybody done took it,'' he said. ``michael is using it. and they're welcome.''
asked whether he, jackson and prince could perform together, little richard said he thought jackson would be willing ``but i think prince would shoot me. i love prince. i can talk to michael. he is very humble. i can get to bruce springsteen, bob dylan, paul mccartney. i just can't get to prince.''
his favorites? ``i like michael, bruce, bob seger, prince. i think prince is a genius. i love paul mccartney. i love all of them. they come from me.''
the naacp is moving a convention and demanding an apology from a popular country club after a telephone recording during which the club's manager allegedly made racial slurs
the comments were recorded on the telephone answering machine of howard county naacp member sherman howell, who had phoned the turf valley country club last week to ask why it seemed no black waiters and waitresses worked there
the washington post obtained a copy of the tape, and included comments from the recording in an article in today's editions
according to the tape, a man identifying himself as club manager fred grimmell returned the call, and left a short message on howell's answering machine. but then after a click, the voice continued in a conversation with two other people and made several racial slurs, the post said
at one point, the voice on the tape said: ``this nigger, i am going to put him against the wall ... he should say, `this is sherman nigger.' yo nigger, yo bub.'' as the man who had identified himself as grimmell and an unidentified woman discussed whether howell had ever visited the club's restaurant, a third voice said, ``well, we don't like niggers. ... i'm discriminated because all the niggers get all the jobs.''
a black washington post reporter then went to interview grimmell, and heard another racial slur from behind closed doors about a person ``that wants to grill me.''
later, the post said, grimmell told the reporter: ``i have no time to talk to you at all. here's the door, sweetheart. our conversation is over.''
the howard county naacp chapter, which had planned to hold its spring ``freedom fund'' meeting at the club on march 24, is moving it elsewhere
maryland naacp president rev. john wright, at a news conference wednesday, said his organization is demanding grimmell's immediate resignation and an apology. the naacp is also considering picketing and demonstrations if the issue is not resolved quickly, wright said
this is 1988 and we have this type of statements... this is blatant, outright racism,'' said wright
louis mangoine, son of club owner nick mangione, said he would investigate the complaints about grimmell
here, ranked from best to worst, is a listing of 27 airports and the percentage of on-time arrivals during january, according to information provided by the airlines to the transportation department and released wednesday
the average on-time arrival percentage was 67.5
the percentage in parentheses reflects the on-time departure record at the airport
the ranking covers the 27 busiest airports in passenger volume as determined by the transportation department


