gop presidential candidate pat robertson isn't retreating from his firm denial of charges he avoided combat in korea although he wants to end a legal battle with a former congressman who made them
robertson and his lawyer have formally announced plans to ask a federal judge to dismiss the $35 million lawsuit against rep. paul n. mccloskey jr., r-calif., to avoid beginning a three-week trial on super tuesday
going to trial next tuesday means robertson ``is being asked to sacrifice his presidential campaign in order to vindicate his personal honor,'' attorney douglas rigler told reporters wednesday
we think that's extraordinarily unfair,'' rigler said, referring to u.s. district judge joyce hens green's refusal to postpone the trial date until june 20, when the primary season has ended
the decision to seek dismissal of the suit ``does not in any way indicate he is unwilling to confront mr. mccloskey or that he shies away from any judicial determination of the merits of the charges,'' rigler said
robertson does not intend to back away at any time from his denial of the charges that mr. mccloskey made,'' rigler added
mccloskey, meanwhile, said robertson is ``chickening out of the trial just like he chickened out 37 years ago.''
the former congressman's lawyer, george lehner, said he would oppose robertson's motion to dismiss the lawsuit and request to proceed with the trial on tuesday
i think the truth ought to be told,'' mccloskey said. ``i don't know any better place to get the truth than in the courtroom. he invoked the process, he ought to go through with it.''
mccloskey was sued in 1986 following publication of his charges that robertson called his father, the late sen. a. willis robertson, d-va., from japan to get out of combat in the korean war
mccloskey, who was on the troop ship from which robertson and five other marine officers were removed for special training, says the former television evangelist later was the ``liquor officer'' to a rear-echelon unit in korea
rigler distributed a statement from robertson saying ``the pretrial process has already demonstrated the total falsity of mr. mccloskey's statements about me.''
not one of his witnesss ever heard me make such a call or state that i had made it. the official records of the marine corps fully supported my denial of ever having sought or received special treatment,'' robertson's statement said
a number of former marines who were also aboard the uss breckinridge in 1951 have supported various parts of mccloskey's story
a report on the case prepared by rigler's office charged that the pre-trial testimony of mccloskey's `` handful of volunteer witnesses has been discredited. mr. mccloskey has been reduced to an admission that his charges constitute merely his `opinions' and `impressions.'''
by successfully opposing the motion to postpone the trial, ``mr. mccloskey is holding mr. robertson hostage,'' rigler said. ``mccloskey knows that the march 8 date is impossible.''
that is a terrible choice and i can't understand why a respected judge did it,'' rigler said
in her jan. 6 order denying robertson's motion, green noted that he filed the lawsuit and launched his candidacy ``at the same time.''
that these ventures might somehow come into conflct is a risk that plaintiff assumed when he began them,'' the judge wrote
under federal rules of civil procedure, the judge could order robertson to pay mccloskey's court costs and possibly legal fees
rigler acknowledged that ``it is quite possible that mr. robertson will be asked to pay a substantial amount of court costs'' to cover the expense of taking depositions from more than 50 witnesses
but rigler said he would be likely to appeal a large award
lehner said he would ask the judge to order payment of mccloskey's court costs and lawyers fees, which total more than $400,000
here is the 315-98 roll call wednesday by which the house passed the civil rights restoration act
a ``yes'' vote is a vote to pass the bill
voting yes were 242 democrats and 73 republicans
voting no were 4 democrats and 94 republicans
xxx denotes those not voting
present denotes those who voted they were ``present'' at the time of the vote but did not vote ``yes'' or ``no'' on the issue
there is one vacancy in the 435-member house
