diana ross says she still isn't talking with mary wilson, her former partner in the supremes
talking with reporters at the 30th annual grammy awards on wednesday, miss ross also said she wished she could have been at the recent rock 'n' roll hall of fame banquet for the induction of the supremes
i wasn't able to get there. the baby, the whole thing, i really couldn't get there,'' she said
miss wilson and a daughter of the third original supreme, the late florence ballard, attended the induction
asked whether she and miss wilson are talking, miss ross said, ``no.''
i'm really a good person,'' she added. ``i could be real good. somebody slaps you and slaps you and you'll still be good?''
told that miss wilson had said in los angeles that she's like to renew the friendship, miss ross said, ``of course she would feel that way.''
she said she hadn't read miss wilson's autobiography, ``but i think she said kind of not really nice things. insinuations in the book were not nice to me. and i was really hurt by it.''
panama's hard-pressed economy has become the focus of those trying to end the military rule of gen. manuel antonio noriega
ousted president eric arturo delvalle has joined other noriega foes in calling for fiscal actions to keep up pressure on the government
delvalle, who is in hiding, said in a videotape that the political crisis in panama would make it impossible for the nation to get new loans from international agencies, and described the country as ``totally bankrupt.''
nine months of political unrest already have eroded panama's service-oriented economy, which is particularly vulnerable to a loss of trust and confidence caused by political upheaval
in addition, financial experts say billions of dollars in bank deposits are being withdrawan from panama, destablizing it as a financial center
manuel solis palma, installed last week to replace delvalle, charged that the united states ``wants to asphyxiate the panamanian people economically, snatching away the salt and water of our existence.''
in a speech tuesday, solis palma denounced attempts to promote ``sanctions, pressure out of proportion (and) unjust recrimination against a people who has honored its commitments .... we will struggle without pause or truce for our survival.''
delvalle pointed to the deteriorating economic situation in his unsuccessful attempt feb. 25 to dismiss noriega as chief of the 15,000-member defense forces of panama, which include both the military and police
the reasons that might take us to fiscal and economic imbalance and that might push thousands of panamanians to unemployment, misery and despair cannot persist,'' delvalle said in announcing the general's dismissal
noriega rallied his officer corps and loyalist politicians, and the next day delvalle had been replace and in hiding
the backbone of panama's economy is formed by banks, insurance companies, a large duty-free zone, the panama canal and well-stocked retail and wholesale stores that attract buyers from throughout latin america
in new york, lawyers for delvalle sued in federal court wednesday to block a bank from transferring an estimated $10 million to the noriega regime. the lawyers later dropped the lawsuit against republic national bank of new york after the bank agreed to transfer the money to the u.s. federal reserve bank
on tuesday, delvalle froze all panamanian assets outside the country. the united states, which still recognizes delvalle as president, supported the action. state department spokewoman phyllis oakley called it ``the legitimate action of the constitutional government.''
panama's commercial bank debt is $2 billion and the total debt for banks and government agencies is $5.5 billion, said a banking source in the united states who spoke on condition of anonymity. he said about $85 million in interest and principal is due to banks and bond holders by march 31
the world bank said panama's total foreign debt was $4.8 billion at the end of 1986, the latest year for which figures are available. the debt, in a nation of 2.2 million people, is one of the world's highest per capita
an ongoing general strike to protest noriega's rule that began monday has had particular impact on construction and industrial activity
among the actions reported under consideration in the united states is withholding payments from panama canal activities
the u.s. commerce department said panama's gross income from the canal in 1986 was $532 million. revenue figures were not available for last year, but the number of ships passing through the waterway was said to be up slightly. evenue from the canal represents 10 percent of panama's gross national product
vice president george bush says the united states' flagging petroleum industry needs drilling incentives rather than an oil import tax, while agriculture is starting to rebound because of the reagan administration's farm policy
talking with reporters after a rally at louisiana state university on wednesday, bush, a former oilman, said making changes that will benefit the oil industry would enhance national security
the answer has to be national security and not economics. the answer has got to be there is no security for this country with increasing dependence on foreign oil. you can't make the case simply on economics,'' he said
in addition to providing drilling incentives, congress should repeal the windfall profits tax, passed during the late 1970s when the oil industry was deregulated, while petroleum prices are down and do away with controls on natural gas, bush said
i think if you take the case to the people in the fall for this, i think it can get done,'' bush said
the vice president was asked about suggestions by rival bob dole that panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega was on the cia payroll during bush's tenure as chief of the spy agency
he says he made all the decisions at the cia,'' dole said at a news conference in new orleans. ``what were they? was noriega on the payroll when he was cia director?''
dole, asked if he were accusing bush of having knowledge of noriega's alleged drug trafficking, said: ``all i'm saying is that bob dole said no to drugs, no to thugs, no to noriega.''
to that, bush replied: ``i find it amazing that a united states senator will talk about cia matters. i took an oath of office to protect sources and methods of intelligence and i would never discuss anything i was doing at the cia that would affect the national security
there has just been one charge after another in this campaign and i have just decided not to respond to mr. dole's charges.''
on another matter, bush said reagan administration farm policy was leading to a recovery in agriculture
the cattle people are doing much better now. beef prices are up. hog prices are up. don't fool with the farm bill,'' he said
bush said he wanted to encourage foreign markets to buy more american agricultural products, rather than enact protectionist legislation
if we go the protection route, they'll go the protection route,'' he said
in his speech before about 1,000 people, bush said wins in louisiana and the other 19 states in next tuesday's super tuesday primary could translate into the republican presidential nomination
if i do well in louisiana and that's an indicator of doing well in my home state of texas and across to florida, where i came from this morning, i am absolutely convinced that i will be the next president of the united states,'' bush said
rep. richard baker, who is serving as bush's state campaign chairman, told reporters that he was confident that the vice president would win at least five of the state's eight congressional districts
we will take a majority of the congressional districts and the ones we take won't be close,'' he said
during bush's speech, a group of about six protesters, describing themselves as members of the progressive student network, raised a banner saying: ``hey bush, tell us about contra drug running.'' a man sporting a bush campaign button reached up and tore part of the banner down, drawing applause from other supporters
the protesters also briefly chanted: ``tell us about contra aid,'' also in reference to the nicaraguan rebels
at the end of his speech, bush pointed to one of the protesters and said, ``give that man a little jambalaya. he sounds starved to death.''
bush then shed his suit coat and donned a white apron and served jambalaya _ a spicy cajun rice dish with sausage and chicken _ to some of those in attendance. says</head>
jimmy swaggart will need more than counseling and a three-month suspension from the ministry to overcome his attraction to pornography, says a psychologist
no matter how much he prays to god, no matter how sincere, it won't change him unless he seeks more extensive therapy,'' victor cline said wednesday at a gathering of the religious alliance against pornography
cline, a professor at the university of utah, described an effective treatment as one that treats pornography addicts in much the same way as alcoholics anonymous treats alcoholics _ with a 24-hour-a-day support system
swaggart last week confessed to unspecified sins. he reportedly paid a prostitute to pose naked numerous times over a period of about a year
assemblies of god church officials in louisiana have recommended barring swaggart from preaching for three months, but officials asked for reconsideration after receiving hundreds of calls protesting the penalty as too lenient
allliance chairman jerry kirk estimated that between a dozen and two dozen of the 5,000 or so ministers he has talked to in his travels for the alliance are hooked on pornography
in my travels, i've had pastors confess to me their addiction, and it truly is an addiction,'' alliance chairman jerry kirk said at a news conference during a break in the seminar
about 400 members of the alliance gathered at a washington hotel for a seminar on how to battle pornography
the religious alliance against pornography was formed in july 1986 to battle child pornography and obscenity not protected by the first amendment to the constitution
irish rockers u2 led the new wave and a brill building songwriting team represented the old guard with two awards each at a surprising 30th annual grammy awards, where michael jackson was shut out and paul simon won again for ``graceland.''
we don't see this as a peak for u2,'' lead singer bono said wednesday night after the socially conscious band copped its awards for ``the joshua tree,'' its 12-million selling album. ``it's just a beginning.''
simon, who won album of the year in 1987 for his south african project ``graceland,'' surprisingly captured record of the year honors in 1988 for the title cut, which featured backing vocals by the everly brothers
but little richard stole the show at radio city music hall by announcing, not once but three times, that he had captured the grammy for best new artist. richard, in a gold suit and sunglasses, finally broke down and declared one-time ``soul train'' dancer jody watley the winner
i have never received nothing _ y'all never gave me no grammys, and i've been singing for years,'' the manic voice of ``tutti-frutti'' and ``lucille'' proclaimed. ``i am the architect of rock 'n' roll!''
veteran songwriting team barry mann and cynthia weil, joined by co-writer james horner, won song of the year and best song written for a motion picture or television with their syrupy ballad ``somewhere out there,'' a tune performed by two mice in the animated movie ``an american tail.''
the pair is the last remaining songwriting team from the brill building, the manhattan offices where dozens of classic '60s songs were written
i don't think there can be a best song,'' weil told reporters. ``every song is unique. i love the u2 song (`i still haven't found what i'm looking for'), but it's apples and oranges.''
after u2 won album of the year for ``joshua,'' guitarist the edge gave a rambling acceptance speech in which he thanked bishop desmond tutu, martin luther king jr., james t. kirk, peewee herman, jimi hendrix, dr. ruth westheimer ``and sumo wrestlers around the world.''
the band sat sipping beer in the audience during the three-hour show, which featured an electrifying live performance by jackson. jackson, who captured eight grammys for his ``thriller'' album in 1984, received no awards for its follow-up, ``bad,'' despite four nominations
the los angeles-based band los lobos, whose version of ``la bamba'' was a bigger hit than the original adaptation of the mexican folk tune by the late ritchie valens, came away with nothing despite four nominations
and folk singer suzanne vega, with three nominations for her poignant song ``luka'' about a battered child, also went home empty-handed
i was hoping it would win, but i was prepared for anything to happen,'' said vega, a greenwich village favorite. ``i'm a little disappointed, i guess.''
bruce springsteen won his second grammy, best rock vocal performance, for his ``tunnel of love'' album but was not around to accept the award. the same was true of simon and of sting, who topped jackson and springsteen for best pop vocal performance on his ``bring on the night'' lp
aretha franklin, the grammy-winningest woman of all time, added two more to her 12 with best female r&amp;b performance and best r&amp;b performance by a duo or group _ her ``i knew you were waiting (for me)'' duet with george michael
one of aretha's protegees, whitney houston, took best female pop vocalist for her effervescent single ``i wanna dance with somebody'' from her ``whitney'' album. narada michael walden won the producer's grammy for his work on houston's second album
the world wants new faces in a way,'' said walden, who beat the michael jackson-quincy jones team. ``quincy's won so many awards anyway, this is good. and he told me in private that he voted for me.''
jackson's ``bad'' won just a single award: best engineered non-classical album, with bruce swedien and humberto gatica receiving the grammys
the grammys' two all-time leaders added to their impressive totals. sir georg solti, conductor of the chicago symphony, won his 26th grammy, for his recording of beethoven's 9th symphony
and pianist vladimir horowitz, who had 20 grammys entering the ceremonies, won two for best classical instrumental performance and best classical album for ``horowitz in moscow.'' he also received the president's special merit award from the national academy of recording arts &amp; sciences, which sponsors the grammys
i am so very happy the classical music still has an appreciation,'' the fiery pianist told the crowd as he accepted the special award. after he won the best album award, he simply smiled and carried it away, saying nothing
soprano kathleen battle, who starred on four of the five operas nominated for grammys, ended up winning two _ for the vienna philharmonic recording of richard strauss' ``ariadne auf naxos'' and for her solo album, ``salzburg recital.''
ladysmith black mambazo, the south african vocal group featured on the ``graceland'' album, won a grammy for best traditional folk recording for ``shaka zulu.'' simon produced it
first of all i thank god _ and then paul simon,'' said joseph shabalala, lead singer of the 10-man group
frank zappa's ``jazz from hell'' beat his son, dweezil, and springsteen for best rock instrumental _ zappa's first-ever grammy. ``trio'' by dolly parton, emmylou harris and linda ronstadt won as best country vocal duo or group performance
the show, televised by cbs, saluted recordings released between oct. 1, 1986, and sept. 30, 1987
the winners were elected by ballots cast by academy members in seven chapters around the nation. the academy's 6,000 members include recording artists, songwriters, musicians, producers and technicians
the u.s. dollar topped the 129-yen barrier and kept rising through the day, while stocks temporarily hit pre-crash levels before closing lower today in what traders saw as a healthy consolidation
the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues closed at 25,596.31 points, down 86.51 points, or 0.34 percent, from wednesday's close after finishing the morning session at 25,755.95 points, higher than pre-crash levels
the dollar closed at 129.30 yen, up 0.83 yen from wednesday's close of 128.47 yen. the dollar opened the day at 129.05 yen, breaking the 129-yen level for the first time since feb. 23
before the october crash, the nikkei index stood at 25,746.56 points
basically we saw a bit of a fall off in early morning trading,'' said paul warren of salomon brothers. ``but the final decline shows a healthy consolidation that will help the market in the future. we were seeing a change in rotational theme, into electronics and utilities.''
warren said he expects the market to return to its all-time highs and possibly go even higher in the next two to three months
personally, i think that the dollar will continue to rise,'' said a foreign exchange dealer, who demanded anonymity
a currency dealer at a major commercial bank in tokyo, who spoke on condition his name not be used, said the dollar's strength was attributed to a japanese news report that a senior u.s. government official in charge of monetary and credit policy had suggested the united states was willing to accommodate a substantial rise in the dollar
according to the report, carried in the nihon keizai shimbun, the unidentified official said the united states was preparing a reference range and indicated that the allowable upper limit could be as high as 160 yen
a former mental patient opened fire with two six-shooters near the alamo, shooting four people at random and trading shots with police before he was wounded and taken into custody, authorities said
marvin duncan, 55, shot in the left thigh by police, was charged with six counts of attempted capital murder, police spokesman sgt. paul buske said. bond was set at $1.5 million
the most seriously wounded victim, deborah reyes, 29, was shot in the chest and stomach and was in critical condition at brooke army medical center late wednesday, said hospital spokesman sgt. william banks
the three others, shot at point-blank range, were not injured seriously, officials said
witnesses said the shooting, which took place in the week that marks the 152nd anniversary of the fall of the mission to mexican troops, resembled something from a movie
all hell broke loose,'' said todd tarble, 20, who was waiting for a bus about three blocks from the alamo when the shooting began
he had two guns in his hands. i've never seen anything like that. the guy was acting like john wayne. this guy was crazy,'' tarble said
duncan was listed in good condition at medical center hospital
court records show duncan was placed in rusk state hospital for the mentally or criminally insane in october 1980 after being found incompetent to stand trial on an attempted murder charge
he was released in march 1981 to stand trial, but bexar county prosecutors dismissed the charge in favor of a civil commitment to san antonio state hospital. the records did not indicate duncan's status at the state hospital
duncan took a taxicab downtown about 9 a.m. wednesday, and about three blocks from the alamo he pulled out two .357-caliber magnum revolvers and began shooting from inside the cab, got out and continued firing, authorities said
taxi driver frank esquivel, 42, jumped from the cab when the shooting started. he said the man said nothing during the four-mile ride. ``i have no idea what set him off,'' he said
homicide lt. albert ortiz said the gunman was methodical in his shooting
from the time he was picked up at his residence, throughout the shooting he remained calm and his actions were deliberate, not hurried,'' ortiz said
duncan has been arrested numerous times since 1973 on charges including assaults and an attempted murder charge, said police chief william o. gibson
as to why the suspect began shooting, we don't know why, with the exception that he wanted to gain some attention,'' gibson said
as passers-by dived for cover, officer donald kawazoe, on his way to work, saw the man and ordered him to stop
the two traded shots and the gunman fled and confronted park ranger bennie burley. they also exchanged gunfire before the gunman was arrested, gibson said, but could not say which officer shot duncan. campaign</head>
jesse jackson will begin $100,000 worth of tv ads in the crucial campaign days before super tuesday and has borrowed $410,000 to keep his campaign going until after that contest, his campaign manager says
the tv buy, the largest to date for jackson's cash-poor campaign, will target alabama, florida, louisiana, mississippi, north carolina, south carolina, texas and virginia, said campaign manager gerald austin
the ads start friday
austin said the loan, for expenses other than the ads in those eight super tuesday states, was borrowed from adams bank in washington two weeks ago and will be paid back march 18
austin made the comments aboard jackson's plane as it hopscotched across five southern states wednesday
in his bid to woo southern whites and build on the white support he has won this year in iowa, maine, minnesota, new hampshire and vermont, jackson picked up the endorsement wednesday of jim hightower, the popular agriculture commissioner of texas
jackson was welcomed to selma, ala., by the white mayor who had martin luther king jr. and other civil rights activists arrested more than three decades ago
austin said jackson's success on super tuesday depends on getting out the black vote, attaining close to 10 percent of the white vote and the unknown potential of gop candidate pat robertson, the former tv evangelist, to pull demoratic voters into the republican primaries
the campign will spend about $350,000 on the super tuesday contests, austin said, which is far less than the $3 million-plus some democratic competitors are expected to shell out
austin would not say how many of the 1,307 super tuesday delegates he thinks jackson can get, but said the goal is to win more than the 222 jackson won in his 1984 race in those states
in selma, jackson received the key to the city from mayor joe smitherman, who was mayor in 1965 when state troopers forcefully stopped civil rights marchers from crossing the alabama river bridge that jackson's motorcade drove across on wednesday
i had dr. king arrested,'' smitherman said. ``the voting rights act was right. we were wrong. we've admitted that.''
jackson called smitherman's reception a sign of the ``new south.''
people grow,'' he said. ``we have a new challenge now. he fought it in '65 and he lost. now we have a common battle.''
in the texas state capitol, hightower said jackson speaks to ``an ignored majority of americans whose lives have been frustrated or flattened by the economic policies of recent years.''
jackson is appealing to whites with a message of ``economic common ground'' that binds the underprivileged of all races
jackson's message includes calls for a higher minimum wage, comparable worth pay for women, child care and housing programs
he often mentions the plight of hard-hit textile workers, saying he ``reluctantly'' supports congressional legislation to limit textile imports because of the ``dire emergency'' of the south's once-thriving industry
he encounters mixed reactions from whites
he began wednesday in his home state of south carolina, arriving just after dawn with a troop of reporters in tow, for a breakfast of grits, biscuits and eggs at tom trantham's dairy farm
trantham and three white neighbors talked farm policy with the presidential contender and told reporters how jackson supported them during the 1986 drought and helped unload hay brought in from other states
but when asked if they supported him for president, they were noncommital
i'm not supporting anybody at this point,'' said michael sly, a farmer organizer. east</head>
rep. richard gephardt says he would consider former presidents jimmy carter and gerald ford to serve as special envoys to the middle east if he is elected president
in a meeting with st. louis post-dispatch editorial writers, while on a swing through his home state wednesday, gephardt said he had discussed the idea with carter on tuesday when he stopped in plains, ga
we talked about it,'' gephardt said. ``he said he was ready, willing and able to do anything asked by a future president.''
elsewhere, gephardt's home-turf message was concentrated on the country's foreign trade policy. he told the st. louis board of aldermen that he would seek policies that reduce the trade deficit by enabling u.s. businesses to compete fairly in world markets
how do you tell people who are out of work that the trade deficit is a fact of life?'' gephardt asked. ``i don't accept the deficit and i don't think you do either. we have the power to make the nation better than it was before. this is your fight too.''
gephardt, called for new policies that ``ask trading partners to treat us as fairly as we treat them.''
without getting specific, gephardt said it was time for the government to enact trade policies that ``take the heat of unfair foreign competition off those who farm our land, forge our steel and build our cars.''
gephardt said he did not agree with a statement by president reagan that the trade deficit is a ``sign of strength.'' nor, he said, did he agree with the attitude that the trade deficit ``is a fact of life.''
gephardt also touched on agricultural issues in his speech
the agriculture program doesn't make sense,'' he said. ``isn't it time we had an agriculture program in this country that let the farmers vote and let the farmers decide what we're going to do?''
gephardt began a two-day swing through his home state wednesday for a series of speeches and four fundraisers six days before missouri's ``super tuesday'' primary
saying ``my, how good it is to be home,'' gephardt brought his campaign for the democratic presidential nomination to the place where he got his start in politics
after the address in the st. louis city hall chambers where he began his political career, gephardt traveled to springfield for a campaign fundraising reception. he returned to st. louis for a fundraiser wednesday night before flying to kansas city
gephardt arrived in springfield the day after the springfield news-leader endorsed sen. paul simon in the race for the democratic nomination
gephardt, who was a st. louis alderman from 1971 to 1976, used the economic rebirth of the city during those years as an example for his promise to return economic prosperity to those who work in the nation's factories, farms and steel mills
i began my career right here in this room when this was a city with many difficulties and troubles,'' gephardt said. ``a lot of people were giving up on st. louis. they said the future was elsewhere. but we didn't believe that. we did what needed to be done to make st. louis a success story.''
sam hamra, a springfield attorney and finance chairman for the gephardt campaign in missouri, said $25,000 was raised at the event. during the day $425,000 was raised, bringing the campaign-long total in missouri to nearly $2 million, said s. lee kling, gephardt's campaign treasurer. in 3rd graf is cq</note>
a 71-year-old retired coal miner who revived after being twice declared dead says he returned to life with a profound spiritual renewal
i think that it's from a spiritual standpoint that (my life) has changed,'' shirley barnett, who is also a retired baptist minister, said wednesday
when i came to ... i had nothing but a heart full of love and joy for everybody. i was refreshed in the holy ghost.''
barnett, who revived while his funeral arrangements were being made, was declared dead on jan. 21 after a cardiac arrest. doctors said he showed no vital signs for about 45 minutes during one episode and about 30 minutes during a second
the slender, smiling man spoke to reporters from his wheelchair during a news conference at hca park west medical centers. two of his doctors, who were at a loss to explain his revival, also were on hand to answer questions
i feel fine. a little weak, naturally,'' he said
the first thing i remember was my daughter telling me i was at park west,'' he said. ``she put it pretty bluntly that i had died.''
on jan. 16, barnett was admitted to methodist medical center in nearby oak ridge after suffering chest pains
a heart artery constricted five days later, and doctors and nurses spent 45 minutes trying to revive him with an external pacemaker and electric shock, but he showed no pulse, blood pressure or neurological responses, said dr. victor mclaughlin, a cardiologist at the oak ridge hospital
weak, sporadic heartbeats were detected thereafter but were considered ``a dying heart pattern,'' the physician said
it is very unlikely that if you can bring someone back (from that status) you'll have any functioning brain at all,'' mclaughlin said
mclaughlin said he told barnett's family members that the man had died, and he was disconnected from his intravenous feeding tubes and heart monitor
barnett's daughters signed papers to remove the body to the morgue and began calling family and friends to tell them of his death and to make funeral arrangements
a nurse who began cleaning out barnett's hospital room closet heard him start to breathe, mclaughlin said, and he was wheeled to the coronary care unit
there, personnel again found no pulse or blood pressure. barnett was hooked up to a pacemaker and respirator, but family members told doctors he had a ``living will'' requesting that he not be kept alive artificially
that period of apparent death lasted about 30 minutes, mclaughlin said
doctors disconnected barnett from the life-sustaining equipment, but once unhooked, he began breathing on his own again
the gentleman gradually began waking up ... and talked with us. he continued to do well on his own,'' said mclaughlin. ``there is no detectable short- or long-term memory loss in this man
i've never had an experience like this before,'' he said. ``there are obviously things that happen that we cannot explain.''
barnett later underwent heart bypass surgery
dr. gene aaby, another of barnett's doctors, has said a possible reason for the revival could stem from barnett's black-lung condition, an occupational respiratory disease of miners
we came up with the theory that perhaps his brain had gotten used to less oxygen. we know various cells can adapt and function'' in adverse situations, he said
the source at the syrian command in beirut, speaking on condition of anonymity, said schray was driven to damascus, 56 miles east of beirut, under heavy syrian escort
schray, an engineer, was kidnapped jan. 27 and a group called the holy warriors of freedom on wednesday claimed responsibility
