indians who fled into exile to escape war and government persecution are returning to their homes on the caribbean coast now that hostilities in the region have largely ceased, a u.n. official said
the number of returning indians is increasing dramatically,'' serge ducasse, head of the office of the u.n. high commissioner for refugees in managua, said in an interview wednesday
tens of thousands of miskito, rama and sumo indians left their tribal homelands beginning in 1981 after the leftist sandinista government tried to impose marxism in the area and said it would move them to relocation camps
the government said then that relocation was necessary because it had discovered a rebel plot that called for the killing of sandinista authorities and indians who collaborate with the government
many of the indians crossed the rio coco and sought refuge in honduras rather than move to relocation camps. thousands took up arms, creating rebel movements that, like the larger nicaraguan resistance, received u.s. aid
now, the sandinistas have acknowledged mistakes in their treatment of the indians and have agreed to work with them to set up a regional government along the 75-mile seaboard known as the mosquito coast
ducasse said that in 1986, the u.n. agency helped about 2,000 indians return from honduran refugee camps to the coast, which is isolated from most of nicaragua's 3.1 million people by tradition and a spine of rugged mountains
last year, 3,206 indians returned and in the first two months this year 1,502 returned, said ducasse
thousands of others returned on their own, without official help
i think it's the impact of the peace plan,'' ducasse said
a regional peace plan signed in august by nicaragua, guatemala, el salvador, honduras, and costa rica calls for the countries to aid the return of refugees. tens of thousands of people have fled civil strife in guatemala, el salvador and nicaragua. the peace plan also calls for democratic reforms, cease-fires and political amnesties
fighting continues in nicaragua despite government talks with the contra rebels, who began their insurgency in november 1981. but the sandinistas have succeeded in breaking up the indian rebel movements
interior minister tomas borge traveled to the coastal city of puerto cabezas in october to accept the amnesty request of indian rebel leader uriel vanegas and 400 of his troops
borge now is negotiating with another indian leader, brooklyn rivera
the caribbean coast is both economically and strategically important for the sandinistas. its ports are used to receive soviet arms shipments and east bloc supplies, and it is considered most vulnerable to a foreign invasion
the area was given little attention by nicaraguan governments until the sandinistas came to power in july 1979. it was controlled by the british until the last century and some of the inhabitants still speak english, along with their own dialects, rather than spanish
a majority of the 180,000 or so indians are protestants, while the rest of the nation is overwhelmingly roman catholic
there is relative calm in the zone now,'' ducasse said
but thousands of non-indian refugees from nicaragua still live in makeshift camps in honduras
ducasse said that just 136 non-indian nicaraguans returned last year from refugee camps in honduras
it will be slow for them to come back,'' ducasse said. ``most of them left conflict zones or to avoid (compulsory) military service.''
following reagan's four-minute statement before reporters, secretary of state george p. shultz hailed the two-day summit. ``here was freedom on display,'' he said. ``it was a very moving experience.''
the secretary seemed fatigued from his recent middle east peacemaking tour, and was leaving immediately for another round of talks with arab and israeli leaders on reagan's orders
nato secretary general lord carrington said the summit ``gives me some satisfaction'' because of the 16 alliance leaders' good will and harmony as they charted future policy
the final communique said alliance strategy must be ``based upon an appropriate mix of adequate and effective nuclear and conventional forces,'' and that nato's remaining short-range nuclear weapons must be improved ``where necessary.''
the communique avoided the term ``modernization'' of short-range missiles because of the opposition of west germany, where most of the weapons are based
carrington said the allies were concerned that some people might think ``modernization'' might signal introduction of new, more destructive weapons. ``modernization actually means weapons that are more accurate and possibly less destructive,'' he said
the allied leaders expressed solid support for reagan's efforts to negotiate sharp reductions in u.s. and soviet intercontinental ballistic missiles, and renewed their endorsement of the december agreement between reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev to ban ground-launched, medium-range missiles in europe
carrington said he was heartened that gorbachev has recognized the east-west imbalance in european conventional forces that favors the eastern bloc and ``is willing to do something about them.''
at least two people were killed today in riots outside polling places as the nation voted to choose a new parliament in an election marred by a general strike and charges of fraud
homemade bombs exploded as fighting between supporters of rival candidates broke out near pollings places in and around dhaka, injuring dozens of people, police, witnesses and hospital officials said
near dhaka university, a fire station and fire truck were set ablaze by supporters of opposition parties who charged that workers from the governing jatiya party were trying to steal ballot boxes at a nearby polling station
in old dhaka, two people were shot to death in fighting, hospital officials said. one election official was beaten in front of reporters at a voting station, and another was reportedly stripped of his clothes and chased from his post
major opposition parties, which have been trying for four months to oust president hussain muhammad ershad, called for a boycott of the election for parliament and some municipal offices. the opposition also called a general strike for wednesday and today in a bid to disrupt the election
on wednesday, bands of youths hurled bombs, burned cars and trucks, and shouted anti-government slogans, and at least eight people were injured
in dhaka, the strike appeared successful wednesday, shutting down shops and businesses and leaving streets empty of the bicycle rickshaws that make dhaka traffic a nightmare. but the strike appeared to have little effect outside dhaka other than preventing trucks and buses from operating
it was the 24th strike called by the opposition since nov. 10, when it began its campaign to oust ershad
no election, no election,'' young men and teen-agers from opposition parties shouted today near one polling station in old dhaka. ``go in there. you won't even find a dog,'' one of them shouted
the gates to the polling station were locked, and armed police could be seen peaking out of a doorway inside. witnesses said homemade bombs had been tossed outside the polling station earlier
outside a nearby voting station in a school, the pavement was littered with pieces of broken bricks tossed by supporters of rival candidates for municipal posts
the polling station was closed, and election official muhammad akbar ali, 45, said a gang of youths had burst in and made made off with five ballot boxes. he said he did not know who the attackers represented
a policeman at the scene, abul hasan, said police at opened fire with blanks to chase away agitators who set off small homemade bombs
after the policeman spoke, a young man wearing on his clothing the plow symbol of the jatiya party began shoving and punching an election official. he demanded that the polling station be reopened. police dragged him away
in narayanganj, an industrial area southeast of dhaka, an election official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he had been unable to prevent jatiya party supporters from stuffing ballot boxes
in a move to compromise with his opponents, ershad dissolved the 330-seat parliament last december, 3{ years before its term was to expire, and scheduled new elections
but opposition leaders have said no election conducted under ershad can be fair, and they are urging a voter boycott
at least 33 people have been died since nov. 10, either in clashes, by police gunfire, or in campaign-related violence
sheik hasina of the opposition awami league said she expected only 5 percent or 10 percent of the 47.8 million voters to cast ballots
more than 900 candidates from 102 political parties are running for parliament. eighteen candidates, all from ershad's jatiya party, already have been declared elected for lack of opposition, and voting in one district was canceled because a candidate was killed
in addition to the parliamentary election, municipal elections will be held in the cities of dhaka, chittagong, khulna, and rajshahi
in similar polling for town and village councils three weeks ago, more than 100 people were killed in battles between supporters of candidates
ershad seized power in a bloodless coup in 1982 and won election in 1986. he ordered 9,000 army troops and about 290,000 local police and paramilitary troops deployed to ensure security for the elections
eight people died and at least 25 others were injured early today when one passenger train rammed into a second one standing in a railway yard in this northern city, a government spokesman said
maximo regidor said rescue workers recovered the bodies of eight people, seven men and a young woman, trapped in the wreckage of a sleeping car just after noon
the accident happened just after 3 a.m., when the north-bound madrid-bilbao express of the state-owned railway company renfe rammed the stationary madrid-santander express train, he said
valladolid is 112 miles northwest of the spanish capital
regidor said two of the victims were government officials of the northern cantabria region, and he identified them as felix ducasse and vicente alcon
regidor said the young woman was estimated to be between 15 and 18 years of age
initially it appears the cause of the accident was a brake failure,'' he said
spanish national radio reported 25 people were treated for minor injuries at local hospitals and released
a 9-year-old girl whose lower legs were amputated after she suffered frostbite has recovered well enough to ride a bicycle and could be ``on roller skates'' next week, hospital officials say
darlwin carlisle may leave the hospital within two weeks, dr. paula jaudes, who is supervising darlwin's care at la rabida children's hospital and research center, said wednesday
i expect that we'll have darlwin on roller skates a week from friday,'' said physical therapist roberta kuchler-o'shea, who is helping the gary, ind., youngster learn to use artificial limbs
a construction worker found the girl locked in the freezing bedroom attic of her family's apartment jan. 17. authorities believe the girl was left there several days earlier by her mother, who has pleaded innocent to felony neglect
doctors at the university of chicago's wyler children's hospital determined they could not save darlwin's lower legs, and they amputated jan. 23. the girl later was transferred to la rabida to be fitted with artifical limbs
according to hospital spokeswoman kris bangert, custody of darlwin is to be decided by the state of indiana
the child's father, james carlisle, of fort wayne, has said he wants custody. foster parents are also an option, ms. bangert said
while at la rabida, darlwin has learned how to put on her artificial legs and progressed from walking with the help of parallel bars to using a walker, ms. jaudes said
the girl should be able to walk unassisted by next week, she said
ms. kuchler-o'shea said darlwin is learning to resume activities she could do before, such as bicycling and roller skating
the girl has learned to pedal a stationary bicycle and has received a real bicycle _ a pink one with training wheels _ that she has ridden in hospital halls and soon should be able to take outside
an explosion rocked a dynamite factory early today, killing at least four people and leaving one missing, local officials said
the explosion at the factory in ablon, near this port city in the calvados region of normandy, was the third there since 1985
today's blast occurred shortly after the factory opened at 9 a.m., police said. the regional prefecture said the explosion apparently occurred during the handling of nitroglycerine
an explosion at the factory in march 1985 killed three people. an explosion in march 1987 destroyed a storage area where nitroglycerine was kept but caused no injuries. the factory was closed for several months following that blast
excavators led by a former american green beret are digging in an old spanish fort for buried treasure, raising an outcry from filipino nationalists and bemused skepticism in the manila press
the loot is believed to be part of a fortune in gold which legend says was buried by the japanese in world war ii. estimates on its value range as high as $200 billion, more than enough to pay off this country's $29 billion foreign debt
but the search has also raised charges in a nationalist-minded congress that foreigners are desecrating hallowed ground where filipino and american soldiers died and where the country's national hero, jose rizal, was imprisoned before his execution in 1898
i have nothing against people having high hopes,'' wrote columnist larry sipin in the newspaper malaya. ``but when those who rule us act as if our only hope lies in a pot of gold at the end of a rainbow, or at the bottom of fort santiago, we're in trouble.''
rumors have circulated for decades that japanese gen. tomoyuki yamashita buried a fortune in gold and jewels which he looted from southeast asia before his transfer to the philippines near the end of the war. yamashita was hanged as a war criminal in 1946
last month, a team led by charles mcdougald, a former green beret captain and official of the las vegas-based international precious metals inc., began digging at fort santiago, a spanish fortress used by the japanese as a prison during the war
mcdougald says his group was hired in 1975 by former president ferdinand marcos to search for the treasure. according to mcdougald, robert curtis, president of international precious metals, pinpointed more than 170 sites but then fled to the united states, fearing marcos would double-cross him
mcdougald told reporters later today he had evidence that marcos, who was ousted in a civilian-military revolt in 1986, uncovered $6 billion in treasure from the site in 1983. he did not specify the evidence
marcos today urged the government to ignore a treasure-hunting craze that has swept the country and work instead to end the communist insurgency
after all the sacrifices, all they (officials) are talking about now is money, money, money,'' marcos told radio staion dzmm in manila from his exile home in honolulu. ``what will happen to the communists who are attempting to takeover the country? that is what our priority should be.''
marcos spoke in tagalog, the main philippine language. his remarks were translated by the associated press. he also denied published reports in manila that he had recovered billions of dollars in gold from the fort
under an agreement with president corazon aquino's government, mcdougald's team can keep 25 percent of whatever it finds. the rest goes to the philippine treasury. mcdougald told reporters this week he expects to find the booty within two weeks
the dig began in secret but word leaked out when the fort was closed to the public and filipino reporters began noticing troops of the elite presidential security group guarding the site. mcdougald and presidential aides then confirmed the excavation after two filipino workers were killed when the tunnel in which they were digging collapsed
catalino macaraig, presidential executive secretary, told reporters that the permit was issued ``in accordance with the rules and regulations of treasure hunting'' and that the government's interest would be protected
but sen. juan ponce enrile, a former defense minister, complained that the excavation was an insult to national honor. the senate unanimously approved a non-binding resolution to halt the dig
the upper chamber then subpoenaed mcdougald to appear before a senate committee investigating the project. producers</head>
negotiators for the writers guild of america and movie and television producers agreed to meet again, after the writers' union rejected the producers' latest offer and authorized a strike
we are ready to strike,'' george kirbo, president of the west coast unit of the guild, said wednesday after members, who voted in los angeles and new york over two days, overwhelmingly approved a strike
of 2,411 ballots cast, 97 percent of the writers on both coasts voted to reject the producers' offer and 96 percent voted to authorize a strike, said union spokeswoman cheryl rhoden
negotiators for the writers and producers planned to meet today to see if a strike can be averted, union officials said
first to feel the impact of a walkout would be daily daytime tv programs and talk shows that use the most scripts with the least lead time, such as johnny carson's ``tonight show'' and ``late night with david letterman.''
the effects on prime-time programs and feature films would be slight unless a strike was extended
the alliance of motion picture and television producers announced that it had agreed to the latest negotiations even before east coast writers finished voting on whether to reject the latest contract offer and authorize a strike
the strike sentiment was already clear, based on the mood of west coast members of the writers guild of america who voted tuesday night after union leaders unanimously recommended that the pact be rejected. the west coast unit represents about 6,500 of the union's 9,000 members
the last strike by writers was three years ago and lasted two weeks before writers voted to accept a contract that was essentially the same as the one they had rejected before that walkout
many minor issues were resolved in a 21-hour bargaining session that lasted until 7 a.m. tuesday. but the union and producers remained deadlocked on three items that each side considers vital:
a ``creative rights'' issue that would give original writers more more control over how their work is rewritten and ultimately presented; residual payments for foreign distribution; and a revision of residuals for domestic syndication of one-hour programs, a market that is drying up
producers have resisted union demands on the first two issues, insisting that a writer's control over the script after it is sold should be bargained individually, and that they can't afford to increase foreign residuals
the producers are seeking the syndication revision, which the union opposes the change as a roll-back in current benefits
under the producers' proposal, one-hour programs could be syndicated locally with writers receiving only 50 percent of their normal residuals. if the program is later syndicated nationally, they would receive an additional 100 percent of residuals
the median annual income for writers is $40,000, but about half of the wga's members are unemployed at any given time. the old pact expired tuesday. szerygn, throughout.</note>
virtuoso violinist henryk szeryng died today in west germany, where he was on a concert tour. he was 69
szeryng died in kassel, west germany, of a cerebral hemorrhage, according to herve corre, of his paris office
the polish-born mexican violinist was educated in west germany and then in france, at the paris conservatory, becoming one of the great international violinists after world war ii. he became a mexican citizen in 1946 but was based in europe
i wasn't coming here expecting a happy ending, but i was expecting my son to finally be home. this is almost too much to handle.'' _ malfada ditommaso of buffalo, n.y., who flew to hawaii to claim her son's remains from the vietnam war, only to learn the military was mistaken and they hadn't been returned
