they are political prisoners, branded ``enemies of the people'' under stalin. they have been banished to a ramshackle fishing village in the soviet north, where they live alongside, but apart from, villagers
their names are luzga and kopalych, and they are the heroes of a new soviet film that illustrates the country's confusion after the death of josef v. stalin in march 1953 and its continuing attempt to come to grips with the dictator's legacy
in ``the cold summer of '53,'' by producer alexander proshkin, the two exiles are the only village dwellers who do not submit when their settlement near the finnish border is seized by six common criminals who were freed in a prison amnesty that followed stalin's death
the others, including a mustachioed old captain whose cabin is decorated with a portrait of stalin, allow themselves to be put under lock and key, or even cross the line between obeying their armed captors and seeking to help them
luzga and kopalych resist, and kill off the criminals, one by one
the film, shown to moscow-based journalists wednesday night at the foreign ministry press center, seems an apt summary of the terrible paradoxes of the stalin era, when innocent people could be convicted of crimes, and those who committed injustices could be honored members of the community
cold summer'' is the latest soviet artistic work dealing with the stalinist legacy to emerge under communist party chief mikhail s. gorbachev's loosened restrictions on depicting the often troubled soviet past and stalin's 29-year reign
confession,'' a film by georgian director tengiz abuladze released in late 1986, portrays a pudgy, mustachioed communist party official that soviet audiences immediately recognized as lavrenti beria, the feared head of stalin's secret police
beria's image also makes a small appearance in ``cold summer,'' in a scene that shows the contradictory feelings soviets still have for stalin and his henchman
a policeman, who will become the first villager killed by the amnestied criminals, spies a portrait of beria in a publication lying in the captain's house
he starts to rip out the picture, but the captain stops him
by what instructions do you destroy portraits?'' asks the captain, ever the fearful bureaucrat
the policeman tosses beria's picture away, but it is picked up, carefully smoothed out and saved by one of the leading members of the small fishing community, a man who will later do more than anyone else to assist the criminals
luzga is a gaunt red army veteran with the drawn features and permanent 5-day-old whiskers of a soviet indiana jones. played by veteran actor valery priemykhov, lyzga is often lost in reverie, and scoffs at the suggestion that he might one day be able to return to his former life
were you ever in moscow?'' a blonde-haired village girl asks him at one point
i don't remember,'' he says with a blank look
the gray-haired, baggy-eyed kopalych is played by anatoly papanov, who died after filming his last scene in ``cold summer''in august. the film was completed in november
papanov's gruff voice is familiar to soviet children as the voice of a wolf in a popular cartoon series broadcast by state-run television
the plot of ``cold summer'' is reminiscent of countless cowboy movies where mild-mannered characters find the strength in themselves to resist injustice, and go on to slay the villains
many in the audience of journalists, foreign ministry officials and guests applauded when luzga killed one of the more odious criminals with a pistol shot to the head
he finished off the gang's fleeing ringleader by wading into the water and drowning him
proshkin, 47, who appeared at the screening to present his film and answer questions, acknowledged the movie's script was a ``pure western,'' when he got it, but said he had tried to made something more eclectic with a political edge
the average spectator today in the country is young,'' proshkin said. ``you need strong action to get across the moral and political point of view.''
proshkin was 13 when stalin died, and said he hopes his film will deliver a political message about the stalin era to the country's youth
i think the current generation is less politicized than mine was,'' he said. brush fire</head>
residents ignored evacuation orders and joined firefighters battling a wind-fueled brush fire that threatened dozens of homes in rural central florida near the ocala national forest
about 475 acres had burned by early today, but no homes were destroyed and no injuries were reported. police, state forestry firefighters and u.s. forest service workers battled flames sparked wednesday and fueled by gusty winds
the fire's under control,'' florida forestry division spokesman david bucher said this morning. fire crews would check today for flareups, he said
katherine henrie, 64, was among the residents of the remote lake kathryn heights neighborhood who stayed with their homes. as towering flames threatened to consume a nearby house, she sprayed her yard with a garden hose
they told me to leave but i got no place to go if i did,'' said mrs. henrie. ``i'll just lose everything i have. i got no insurance. they just told me to keep watering the best i could. i got the sprinkler going over there and three dogs waiting in the car.''
late winter and early spring are generally are the worst times for brush fires in central florida. pastures and woodlands become tinder-dry and frost often has killed grass to create hay in underbrush, which becomes fire fodder.   behind bars</head>
a man convicted of killing two police officers in 1963 must remain behind bars at least three more years, a parole board has ruled in revoking an earlier decision to release him
after two hours of closed-door discussions, the board voted 4-3 wednesday to cancel thomas trantino's march 15 release, set by two members in january. it was the second time trantino, who has spent nearly 25 years in prison, came within a hair of parole
trantino was convicted of shooting of two lodi police officers in 1963. he originally was sentenced to the electric chair, but the penalty was changed to life in prison when the death penalty law was struck down in 1972
the possibility of parole sparked a candlelight vigil, a petition drive and a letter-writing campaign in recent weeks. the day after a television show on the case, 1,000 people called the board to argue against parole
those opposed to trantino's release, including police and relatives of his victims, expressed relief at the board's decision
crime is on a runaway train in this country, and a crime of this type needs an appropriate punishment,'' said lodi police chief andrew voto, brother of one victim
in wednesday's decision, the board ruled that trantino must remain behind bars for more than three years, but it left open exactly when he will again be eligible for parole. parole board chairman louis nickolopoulos said the panel will decide that later
in 1980 the board said he could be released if he made restitution to relatives of his victims. after a court fight the panel decided in 1982 that he should remain in prison
nickolopoulos, asked about trantino's reaction, said: ``there was no comment. he was very calm. he was very courteous and polite throughout the hearing.''
trantino's wife, charlee, whom he married while on a prison furlough, said she her husband ``doesn't feel any bitterness toward anyone.''
trantino's lawyer, stuart f. pierson, who has criticized what he called undue pressure on the parole board by police and others, said he wasn't certain whether the denial will be appealed
nickolopoulos said he could not discuss the reasons for the panel's decision until trantino is notified in writing. the board has 21 days to inform the inmate, who then has 14 days to ask for a reconsideration. if he is denied again, he can appeal to the courts
trantino, 50, now in a medium-security prison in camden, was convicted for the murders of sgt. peter voto and patrolman gary tedesco
the two were investigating a report of a disturbance at tavern when they were surprised, partially stripped and shot dead by trantino and an accomplice. the accomplice was fatally shot the next day by police
a lawmaker in a black homeland where rival political groups are engaged in a bloody power struggle was shot to death at home as he and his children watched television, police said today
the 36-year-old legislator, petrus mbatha, was a member of inkatha, a zulu political organization that has been locked in the fierce feud in kwazulu homeland with backers of militant anti-apartheid groups
mbatha lived near camperdown on the fringe of the area around the natal province capital of pietermaritzburg, where more than 400 people have been killed in the feud since early last year
police said it was not known who killed mbatha late wednesday, but reported finding cartridges from soviet-made ak-47 automatic rifles. police regularly link these weapons to members and supporters of the outlawed african national congress, the main guerrilla group fighting to end white-minority domination
inkatha's prinicpal rival in the natal power struggle has been the united democratic front, south africa's largest anti-apartheid coalition
last week, the government banned the udf from political activity and barred several of its senior leaders from further involvement with the organization. several of these leaders had been involved in negotiations aimed at halting the inkatha-udf feud, and the government's action was widely viewed as undermining the peace process
mangosuthu buthelezi, leader of inkatha and chief minister of kwazulu, contends udf cooperates with the african national congress in a campaign to seize control of black townships and oust black moderates who oppose violence
udf leaders have criticized buthelezi for refusing to support militant anti-apartheid strategies such as boycotts and sanctions
this week, the government reinforced its security forces around peitermaritzburg with 300 so-called ``instant constables'' _ black policemen assigned to duty after relatively short training programs
the law and order ministry has declined to comment on allegations most of the new constables are inkatha members
buthelezi describes inkatha as a zulu cultural organization, although it functions as kwazulu's dominant political party
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
the leader of the extreme right-wing conservative party said today that victories in two special parliamentary elections show growing white support for his staunchly pro-apartheid policies
the conservatives won decisively wednesday in the rural transvaal province districts of standerton and schweizer-reneke despite an intensive campaign by president p.w. botha's national party
they had won the seats in may's national white elections, but the winners were forced to resign, one on a technicality, the other because of bankruptcy
in both contests, the conservatives substantially increased their margin of victory
conservative party leader andries treurnicht said the victories would ``have a snowball effect.''
botha called them ``temporary disappointments'' for the national party
foreign interference as well as actions by radical elements that break internal laws undoubtedly cause aversion to patriotic voters,'' he said without elaborating
the conservatives are favored to win another special election later this month and appear likely to cut into national party support in nationwide municipal elections in october
chris van den heever, the conservatives' chief spokesman in transvaal, predicted the 8-year-old party would take control of local councils throughout rural areas of transvaal. he said the party also expected to do well in coastal areas where many whites have protested the recent opening of beaches to blacks
van den heever said the national party, in an effort to preserve its support, would place increasing emphasis on security issues. he predicted the government would launch some type of law-and-order campaign
the independent pretoria news said in an editorial today: ``after being fed a diet of national party racism for decades, it is not surprising that the farmers ... voted for the old precepts of that party as espoused now by treurnicht.''
the conservative party seeks to reinstate all rescinded apartheid laws. it charges that botha is capitulating to the country's 26 million black majority through his limited reforms of recent years
botha maintains his reforms will not threaten ``white interests,'' which he promises will be protected through continued segregation of housing, schools and health services
the national party, which has been in power since 1948, advocates limited power-sharing, with blacks gaining a say in national politics, but whites maintaining power. it firmly controls the 178-member white chamber of parliament, with 133 seats to the conservatives' 22, though the conservatives won 26 percent of the votes nationwide last may
the anti-apartheid progressive federal party, which has 17 seats in the white chamber, did not field any candidates in wednesday's two by-elections
both the national and conservative parties rely largely on support from afrikaners, descendants of the 17th-century dutch settlers who comprise about 3 million of the 5 million whites
south africa's parliament has separate chambers for whites, asians and people of mixed-race. blacks are excluded
a u.s. official said the general assembly acted prematurely when it voted in emergency session to order the united states to submit to binding arbitration its plan to close the plo u.n. mission
the vote wednesday was 143-1. america's western allies joined the majority. israel cast the only dissenting vote. the united states did not vote
arab diplomats hinted the united nations might have to leave new york if the u.s. government insists on enforcing an anti-terrorism law that would close the palestine liberation organization mission by march 21
the u.s. deputy permanent representative, herbert s. okun, called the special session ``inappropriate and premature.''
although u.s. ambassador vernon a. walters was not present wednesday, he has said various branches of the government are discussing the issue and its legal implications
clovis maksoud, arab envoy, said america was opening ``a pandora's box of diplomatic, legal and political problems'' by trying to close the mission and putting u.s. domestic legislation above international treaty obligations
most diplomats, however, said a move from new york was undesirable and unlikely. the plo has non-voting, observer status at the united nations
maksoud, representative of the league of arab states, told a news conference congress should repeal the anti-terrorism law and said president reagan could exclude the plo u.n. mission from application of the law
maksoud said the issue is a problem between the united states and the united nations, not the plo
this demonstrates the level of embarrassment for the united states. it is opening a pandora's box of political, legal and diplomatic problems,'' he said
alexander m. belonogov, soviet ambassador, called the dispute a ``self-inflicted wound'' to u.s. prestige
the united nations and the state department say the u.s. law would violate international law and the headquarters agreement of 1947 that allows all u.n. missions to operate
the united states said it has not decided if it will implement the measure calling for closing of the plo mission
the assembly also voted 142-0 to ask the international court of justice in the hague to rule whether the united states has the right to refuse arbitration. the united states and israel did not vote
general assembly votes are considered expressions of international will and mainly carry moral authority. they are not legally binding and there is no enforcement mechanism. assembly resolutions are often ignored or defied
the assembly decided to reconvene and consider its next move if the united states goes ahead and orders the plo mission closed
the united states so far has rejected arbitration provided in the headquarters agreement for dispute settlement. it is the first time the clause has been invoked. the next step will be a justice department announcement on whether it will enforce the new law
the world court is also expected to submit an opinion on whether the united states has to submit disputes to binding arbitration
america and other nations have disregarded court rulings in the past
benjamin netanyahu, israeli ambassador, called the plo a terrorist organization whose commitment to armed struggle conflicts with the u.n. charter. he walked out when plo representative zehdi labib terzi said israel has disregarded ``norms of civilized behavior.'' tightens throughout.</note>
minority students who took over a hampshire college dormitory office for nine days to protest alleged campus racism headed back to class today, saying they were relieved the sit-in was over
i think everybody's pretty much exhausted,'' said anita fearman, a spokeswoman for the 40 black, hispanic and other minority students who ended the takeover wednesday with the signing of a 16-point agreement designed to encourage racial harmony at the private school, where about 100 of the 1,100 students are minorities
fearnab and 20 other protesters were among the 150 students who watched as college president adele simmons and two other administrators signed the document outside the office that had been occupied since feb. 23
the settlement provided for a dean of multicultural affairs, an adviser for the group that occupied the dakin house office and at least $4,500 in yearly funding for the group. the administration also agreed not to discipline the students, and to allow them to make up work missed during the takeover
i think the occupation strengthened the institution,'' said simmons. ``for the last several years we've been working to improve student life and this represents a finishing of the old agenda.''
fearman said the protesters were relieved to trade in their sleeping bags for dormitory beds, although ``a few are feeling that it will be hard not to have each other for support 24 hours a day.'' she said the protesters had begun returning to classes wednesday afternoon
the occupation began a week after the end of a takeover at nearby university of massachusetts that was sparked by campus racial violence. that takeover ended when chancellor joseph duffey agreed to increase funding of minority student programs and to other demands
hampshire protesters said racial violence is rare at their school, but the college had long ignored their concerns
college officials said the allegation was a surprise, given the school's aim to be a progressive alternative to the traditional liberal arts education offered at nearby amherst, mount holyoke and smith colleges. hampshire students design their own courses of study and must complete individual research projects and pass three divisional examinations to graduate
the protesters, however, said that the settlement and the sympathy shown them by the college community, which organized rallies and sent food to the protesters throughout the occupation, had changed their minds about warning minorities away from the school
i really would tell them to come here,'' said protester penny predmas
it was something unheard of among the mild and compliant commuter ranks in london, but it happened this week _ an underground revolt
the underground in this case was a subway train on the aging northern line of the london regional transport system
the riders were told tuesday night to get off their delay-plagued train five stops before their destination and wait for the next train. a signal failure was blamed
not a rare occurrence
what was rare was that they balked
transport spokesman david morris said the passengers, bound for high barnet at the end of the northern line, started filing off. that's what london subway riders always do. grumbling, maybe, but obeying orders
but then, according to the london evening standard newspaper, a ``mild-looking and well-dressed'' passenger declared: ``i've had enough. i'm staying put. if we all do it, they'll have to take the train on.''
he was among about a dozen passengers who got back into the train, the paper said. more passengers followed. after hurried consultations the staff gave in and waved the train on
london regional transport called the subway mutineers selfish
morris complained to the associated press. ``those passengers had only a narrow and selfish view and put their needs above others.''
but the standard newspaper hailed it as ``the great tube revolt'' _ the subway is known as the tube in britain _ and called the unidentified leader ``a superhero in the clark kent mold _ quiet, mild-mannered and unassuming.''
the paper quoted passenger sheila golding of high barnet as saying the rebels cheered and laughed, because ``we knew that if everyone did it _ and stayed put _ there wasn't anything they could do about it.''
it quoted passenger maria gama as saying: ``everybody was just totally fed up. the waiting room was freezing and nobody could tell us why the train was stopping where it did. but when everybody climbed back on, it was a marvelous moment.''
the northern line, which carries 700,000 passengers between south and north london, is sometimes called ``the misery line'' by newspapers and criticized for defective trains and equipment, last-minute schedule changes, signal failures and dirty stations
morris denied the line was worse than others
but none of that mattered
the meek, mild, patient, uncomplaining london subway riders had had their day
milovan djilas, yugoslavia's best known dissident and a former vice president, got a short story published in a regular literary magazine for the first time in 34 years
the story, titled ``the war,'' was published wednesday in the knjizevne novine periodical of belgrade. it deals with a summary execution of a young deserter in the presence of his parents during world war ii
in a note, the editors of the march 1-15 issue that reached news stands wednesday, stressed, ``we have no intention today ... to engage in assessing the political ideas, stands and programs of milovan djilas.''
it said that ``publishing the literary work of milovan djilas, a test of his artistic achievement by the literary public, will confirm ... the democratic strength of the principled attitude'' of the yugoslav leadership ``toward cultural creativity.''
we believe that freedom of art creations and autonomy of an artistic work are a major achievement of our policy and our culture,'' the editors said
djilas, a top partisan leader, emerged from the war as heir apparent to marshal josip broz tito, who became yugoslavia's first president
however, after he began writing articles displaying his disenchantment with communism in the early 1950s and then published his first book, ``the new class,'' djilas fell into disgrace and spent about nine years in jail
last september, a belgrade company said it was considering publishing djilas' book ``the revolutionary war,'' known in the west under the title ``war-time.''
no book or article by djilas, now 76, has been officially published in yugoslavia after his fall from favor
but djilas received a passport in january 1987 and has traveled widely since
knjizevne novine, in its 40th anniversary issue, put djilas' name on the front page listing its contributors
removing the silently perpetuated taboo (on publishing his work), now that administrative obstacles no longer exist, means permitting a potentially worthy work to establish itself in a place that belongs to it _ or to lose it, should it prove worthless,'' the editors' note said. charges</head>
county officials are searching for a hospice to care for a male prostitute acquitted of attempted poisoning charges after selling his aids-tainted blood
right now, it is hard to place a person like that,'' said eric rofes, executive director of the gay and lesbian community services center
joseph markowski, 29, was acquitted wednesday by a superior court jury on two counts of attempted poisoning. jurors decided he lacked the intent required under state law to kill or injure someone by selling his blood
what he did was inexcusable, but we had to follow the law,'' juror william e. ferguson said after the verdict was read. ``i hope they will come up with a law to prevent people from doing this in the future.''
we need legislation on this,'' said deputy district attorney antonio barreto jr., who prosecuted the case. ``he can go out and do this again today, as long as he said, `i just did it for the money.'''
markowski, who suffers from mental illness and carries the aids virus but has not developed the disease, could have faced up to seven years in prison if convicted
he had been accused of selling his tainted blood for $10 to plasma production associates on june 22 and of trying to do so again june 25
acquired immune deficiency syndrome can be spread is by transfusion of infected blood or blood products. aids cripples the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancers. there is no known cure
markowski originally was charged with attempted murder, but judge ronald s. coen dismissed those counts, saying the law required a specific intent to kill that was not present in the case
the homeless prostitute was arrested june 23 after screaming, ``kill me! kill me! i have aids!'' in a hollywood bank while attempting to grab a security guard's gun. police found his receipt from the plasma center
court-appointed defense attorney guy o'brien said markowski was happy to be acquitted but concerned about where he would make his home
i don't know what's going to happen to him,'' said dr. eugene kunzman of the mental health unit at county jail. ``all the agencies involved are attempting to do what is best for everyone involved.''
last year, los angeles county district attorney ira reiner lobbied for legislation making it a felony to knowingly sell or donate aids-contaminated blood. the state assembly failed to approve it
markowski allegedly admitted to police that he sold his blood because he needed money and didn't care about the public, but coen ruled the statement inadmissible because markowski had not been informed of his right to remain silent and wait for an attorney. sted grammies, in keyword line; this column normally moves in advance.</note>
until little richard took the grammy awards hostage for several minutes, the high point might have been michael jackson's pepsi commercial
but seriously, folks, perhaps because no one artist dominated the awards, wednesday night's was one of the best grammy shows in years
billy crystal was host of the three-hour cbs special, but new york _ more specifically radio city music hall _ was the star
the show seemed to have gotten a new soul infusion by returning from los angeles. it was broadcast live from the venerable old music hall, all decked out in a brilliantly glitzy art deco set design that was just made for cab calloway to strut across singing ``minnie the moocher'' and coaxing the tres cool audience into joining in on ``hidy, hidy, hidy ho.''
but it was little richard who stopped the show when he was supposed to announce the winner for best new artist. instead, he ran off with the envelope, insisting, ``the best new artist is _ me!'' a pain to the waiting nominees, but undeniably great television
richard had come out complaining that co-presenter buster poindexter had stolen his pompadour. ``everything i get, they take it from me,'' he said
his giggling outburst prompted a standing ovation from the audience, a fuming ``shut up!'' from poindexter _ but no grammy. maybe an emmy if they create a best supporting player on a self-congratulatory industry awards show
dion represented oldsters without causing trouble; he just came out and sang ``why must i be a teen-ager in love?'' and wrapped up the show with ``runaround sue.''
michael jackson didn't get any awards during the broadcast, but he turned in a stunning performance that concluded with an inspired james brown-esque gospel number complete with robed choir, even upstaging his pepsi trilogy
until jackson came out, some of the best musical moments were in the ads. it was a little hard to pay attention to jackie mason's mushy borscht-belt humor _ he was doing ed sullivan, for pete's sake _ after eric clapton's wailing guitar solo on behalf of michelob
when it came to acceptance speeches, the irish consciousness band u2 was in a class by itself. when it won for best performance by a duo or group, guitarist the edge thanked, ``martin luther king ... bob dylan for `tangled up in blue,' flannery o'connor, jimi hendrix, walt disney, john the baptist, george best, gregory peck ... dr. ruth, fawn hall, batman and robin ... the ymca, sumo wrestlers throughout the world, and of course ronald reagan.''
later, for best album, lead singer bono made a self-deprecating poke at the band's messiah image
it really is hard having the weight of the world on your shoulders,'' he said. ``but we enjoy our work.''
he also added, ``it's hard when there are 60 million people watching not to talk about south africa and what's happening there, ... but tonight is maybe is not the night to do that.'' he made his point
as usual, the show was a hodgepodge of american musical tastes, though the flamboyance level of the rock stars being what it is, everybody else looked like badly dressed tourists who wandered away from the bus. how about a segue from vladimir horowitz to george strait singing ``all my exes live in texas?''
crystal's humor depended largely on insider entertainment jokes _ who cares at this point that ``the wilton north report'' got canceled? he set up the tribute to the apple with his touching bit on an old, black jazz musician _ ``can you dig it? i knew that you could.'' unfortunately, the routine plays better in a dark club than on a glitter-drenched, island-sized stage
steve allen was funnier. (crystal later kept crediting allen with writing the hottest of the rock numbers.) allen presented the best comedy album award with steven wright. he led off by announcing the good news that ``they did find liza minelli's dress.''
steven asked me to read the list of nominees,'' he said, ``because he suffers from dyslexia. actually he doesn't suffer from it, he digs it.''
elsewhere in television:
bergen series _ movie star candice bergen has been signed to star in ``murphy brown,'' a pilot for a cbs half-hour comedy series. it's bergen's first venture into series television, though she starred earlier this season in the cbs movie ``mayflower madam.'' warner bros. television says she plays the title character, ``a tough, get-the-story interviewers who is ready to tackle anyone from david letterman to the president of the united states.'' and we all know how painful that can be
twelve months have passed since 193 people died aboard the herald of free enterprise. but time has not eased the pain of evelyn pinnells, who lost two daughters when the ferry capsized off belgium
for mrs. pinnells, it has been a year of depression, sleeping pills and anger that the owners of the ferry have gone unpunished. every day she goes to the little cemetery near her home in aylesbury. there her daughters, heidi, 14, and fiona, 20, and fiona's fiance, jonathan reynolds, are buried
they were among the victims when the herald of free enterprise capsized off the beglian port of zeebrugge on march 6, 1987. it was the worst peacetime disaster involving a british ship since the titanic sank in 1912
they say that time heals, but i don't think i'll ever get over it,'' said the divorcee, who survived with her two other children
as the salvaged ferry heads for a taiwan shipyard to be scrapped, its legacy lingers in shattered lives, police investigations, compensation disputes and possible charges against three crewmen and the owners
many survivors haven't been able to return to work
some who lost loved ones have had serious emotional problems. others started drinking heavily. many suffer nightmares and are afraid of the water. more than 200 policemen involved in the aftermath have received psychiatric counseling
it has ruined my life forever,'' said forklift operator chris leach, who rescued mrs. pinnells' 12-year-old son
the things i'd done before, i can't do now. i'm a fisherman but i can't go fishing. i have a boat but it's locked away on a farm and i can't even look at it,'' he said
leach says he is even frightened to drive his car through a carwash
martin hartley, a 9-year-old boy orphaned in the disaster, is living with an aunt and back at school. his story touched the hearts of britons and helped swell a relief fund that has raised $10.6 million for survivors and bereaved
for ferry owners townsend thoresen, it has been a year of change
taken over by p and o just before the disaster, the company has a new name _ p and o european ferries ltd. _ new senior management and new safety measures on its ships
but the threat of corporate prosecution exists, and debate rumbles on over the safety of the modern roll-on, roll-off ferries, which have doors on both ends instead of just one to allow faster loading and unloading of vehicles
the company faces a massive compensation bill
on jan. 22, the high court approved a test case compensation settlement of more than 165,000 pounds, or $292,000, for a family, including young children, who lost their father in the disaster
lawyers representing most claimants say that settlement was expected to become the model for settling more than 300 other claims
michael napier, chairman of a committee of lawyers for 300 survivors and relatives of victims, said wednesday that about 200 had accepted a compensation package from the vessel's owner. he would not disclose the amounts involved
the herald of free enterprise capsized after the sea rushed in through bow doors that were left open
the estimated 543 britons on board, mainly families returning from a day's outing in belgium, had no time to scramble into lifeboats. the lights went out, furniture flew, the water kept rising and in the screaming chaos only 350 made it to safety
it was over in less than five minutes
dave wilkinson, head of the herald assistance unit in dover, where the ferry was bound, said only three officers of the 42 crew members who survived have returned to sea
an official british inquiry blamed townsend thoresen and three crewmen for allowing the ferry to sail with its bow doors open. it said no laws were broken but found the company ``from top to bottom ... was infected with the disease of sloppiness.''
but in october, an inquest jury ruled that the victims were ``unlawfully killed,'' paving the way for possible criminal proceedings against the company's owners and those blamed for leaving the bow doors open: capt. david lewry, first officer leslie sabel and assistant boatswain mark stanley
lewry's certificate of competency was suspended for a year after the inquiry found him ``seriously negligent.'' sabel lost his certificate for two years. stanley, shattered by the tragedy, left the company on medical grounds
on nov. 13, kent police were ordered to start a new investigation, and belgian judge arthur d'hoest's separate investigation may also bring criminal charges
the herald families association, comprising about 150 survivors and relatives, says it will fund a private prosecution of the company for corporate manslaughter if britain's state prosecutor doesn't
there are strong feelings of injustice among the families _ very strong. their children are killed and nobody's doing anything about it,'' said association president maurice de rohan
de rohan, whose daughter and son-in-law were among the dead, said: ``it was just utter carelessness and indifference. i believe the company didn't understand what it was doing and didn't sufficiently care.''
but p and o chairman sir geoffrey sterling said responsibility rested on the shipboard staff. he said it was ``a bit far-fetched'' to prosecute those onshore
united in grief, hundreds of survivors and relatives will join together march 6 to mark the first anniversary
some will return to zeebrugge to drop a wreath in the water where the herald capsized. others will attend a service at st. mary the virgin church in dover and unveil a commemorative stained-glass window
new british regulations require indicator lights on the bridge to show that doors are closed, and ferry passengers must have boarding cards to avoid the kind of confusion over incomplete passenger lists that hampered the search for survivors in the zeebrugge disaster
a bill before parliament includes a two-year jail sentence for an owner or a master who sails with an unsafe ship
a soggy patch of grass alongside saint donaas parish church will be turned into a rose garden in remembrance of the people who died when the herald of free enterprise ferry capsized last year
but apart for the cars and trucks that lie crushed and rusting, there are few visible reminders of the maritime tragedy that pushed this drab port city into the headlines on march 6, 1987
can we keep running around with our hands in the air? do we have to be in sackcloth and ashes because of the disaster?'' asked wim catry, the priest of zeebrugge's saint donaas parish
the ferry, loaded with 543 people and tons of cars and trucks, capsized after leaving zeebrugge with its bow doors left open. it was bound for the british port of dover, across the english channel
it was tragic, but you forget,'' said andre pape, 57, captain of the tug boat sea horse, which was the first to reach the capsized vessel minutes after it sank just ouside the harbor walls. ``we are faced with the force of the sea every day. when one thing happens, you forget another.''
after the ship went down, authorities quickly set up a rescue operation involving ships, divers and helicopters
many lives were saved because of the swiftness and efficiency that won belgium international acclaim, but 193 people died
olivier vanneste, the provincial governor who led the rescue operations, was one of 31 people, including 13 belgians, decorated by queen elizabeth ii for their conduct in the disaster
it has been a tribute to the country and all people who participated in the operation,'' vanneste said. officials from sweden, norway, denmark and britain have since come here to study the rescue plan, he said
he remembers best the selflessness of people bringing in blankets and clothing for the rescued britons and never asking for reimbursement
the steady flow of ferries in and out of the port continues unabated. ``the boats just keep coming,'' said catry. ``they might be a little more careful now. but who can tell?''
lionel linder, editor and vice president of the detroit news since march 1983, has been named editor of the commercial appeal in memphis, tenn., newspaper officials said
linder, 56, assumes his new post today. the tennessee newspaper is owned by scripps howard publishing and has a circulation of 240,000 daily and 350,000 on sunday
linder had been a news employee since 1977
the new position is an opportunity for me to move on,'' linder said. ``i love the challenge to build and rebuild newspapers.''
before becoming editor at the news, linder was executive editor and managing editor with the paper. the news, owned by gannett co. inc., has a circulation of 678,720 daily and 839,319 on sundays, according to the audit bureau of circulations
a computer company has agreed to make refunds to about 100 consumers who bought memory expansion boards in response to exaggerated advertising claims, according to the federal trade commission
nec home electronics, a subsidiary of nec corp. of japan, agreed to pay $15,000 in consumer redress to settle charges that it had made deceptive claims for some of its computers, the ftc said tuesday
according to the commission, nec advertised its pc-8000 series of computers and accessories from 1981 to 1984, including the claim that the average person with no training could quadruple the device's memory by buying accessory equipment
the ftc said expanding the memory to that extent required a skilled programmer or access to a sophisticated operating system which was never made available in the united states
under the consent agreement, nec will refund the $150 purchase price to consumers who bought memory expansion boards for the computers, which it estimated at about 100 people
purchasers of the boards can contact the company about refunds by writing to nec at 1255 michael drive, wood dale, ill., 60191
attorney general edwin meese iii said today the justice department backs a new customs service decision to seize the passports of americans suspected of entering the country with illegal drugs
we're in favor of it and we're looking now at the legal aspects of it. i hope we will find legal ways to do that,'' meese siad in an interview on abc-tv's ``good morning america.''
there's no reason that drug traffickers should have freedom to travel around the world peddling their wares,'' he added
william von raab, the customs service commissioner, told the white house conference on a drug-free america on wednesday that his agency, on march 15, will begin taking the passports of americans who try to re-enter the country with illegal drugs. customs service spoksman edward kittredge said the passports would be seized as evidence of a crime and forwarded to the state department
meese also refuted reagan administration critics who say the military is not being used to stop the flow of drugs into the united states
we've been using the military in this country for six years against drugs,'' he said, adding, ``they help with the interdiction. they provide the surveillance, which is what they can do.''
addressing the conference wednesday, meese said recalcitrant bureaucrats and meddling members of congress are hampering the federal war on drugs
i am extremely concerned about the fragmentation that goes on in congress,'' he said
we have 32 different committees in the congress with cognizance over the drug problem so that too many of the leaders who are seated on the stage here are spending their time testifying in front of congressional committees instead of leading the forces that ought to be out in the field working on the drug problem.''
meese was among four cabinet members and five other top-ranking administration officials appearing together on a panel at the conference
von raab complained to the estimated 2,000 delegates that federal bureaucrats are too lax in pushing anti-drug efforts, a position subsequently embraced by meese
i have been flat out told by many bureaucrats that just because the president is supporting an effort it doesn't mean that money goes with it,'' von raab said. ``we don't need a bunch of bureaucrats that will deal with this war on drugs the way they dealt with the war in vietnam. we need heart in this effort. ..
there are still too many people who work for us _ in my organization as well _ who still have their noses too deeply buried in their old books.''
meese said later, ``i am worried about what mr. von raab talked about: some people in the trenches who do not have the message.''
the attorney general called on state and local officials to pour more money into anti-drug efforts
if state and local governments will increase their efforts threefold _ 300 percent _ as the federal government has in the last seven years _ i think we will have adequate funds to provide the necessary resources for all aspects, enforcement as well as treatment,'' he said
a 12-year-old boy whose body was found in a dishwasher may have tried to take a shower in it, his uncle said
i really believe he crawled in there thinking he could wash up and crawl back out,'' darold degrand said of his nephew, michael conard, of humboldt
the boy's nude body was discovered by his mother, jean, 33, when she returned home from work tuesday afternoon
it's a strange situation,'' brown county sheriff's commander david zasada said wednesday. ``right now we're not looking at this as foul play.''
the boy was 4 foot, 10 inches tall and weighed about 90 pounds
degrand said he was convinced the death was accidental
the portable dishwasher was found hooked up to the kitchen sink and running, zasada said, and the mother turned it off and found her son's body inside
the uncle said the dishwasher had no safety features to prevent such an accident. ``it was an older model where, once you shut the door, if the dial was set right, it kicked in. they bought it secondhand may years ago.''
zasada said investigators were trying to determine whether there was forced entry or sign of a struggle. there were no external injuries that might have indicated the boy was shoved into the dishwasher
i would certainly not at this time say there was a suicide,'' he said
an autopsy to determine the casue of death was inconclusive, zasada said, and further tests were planned
more than two hours after the nato summit ended today, president reagan said he hadn't read the final communique
i haven't seen it yet,'' reagan replied, when a reporter asked if he was pleased with the allied leaders' statement he had praised earlier
white house chief of staff howard baker quickly interjected, ``no, we saw it last night. no problems, and it's very good.''
taking his cue from baker, reagan said, ``yes, very good, no problems.''
the exchange took place during a photo session at the president's guest house, where he had a post-summit meeting with british prime minister margaret thatcher. he lived.</note>
virtuoso violinist henryk szeryng, a polish emigre and mexican citizen who gained fame after performing extensively for allied troops during world war ii, died today in west germany. he was 69
szeryng died at 4 a.m. in kassel, west germany, of a cerebral hemorrhage he suffered early wednesday, his paris and new york offices said
a recipient of numerous international awards, the violinist was to have played in brussels wednesday night with the orchestra of sarrebruck and begin a u.s. tour in a few weeks
real music lovers want emotion _ great moments _ which szeryng's playing gives them,'' arthur rubinstein, who died in 1982, once said
szeryng had a preference for resurrecting neglected works and bringing relatively unknown contemporary works to the public. in 1971, he reconstructed and gave the first performance in modern times of paganini's concerto no. 3
he made numerous recordings and authored several publications on technique and interpretation
szeryng was born in warsaw sept. 22, 1918 and educated in west germany, then in france, where he studied under gabriel bouillon and nadia boulanger at the paris conservatory. in 1937, he graduated with the coveted first prize
szeryng was firmly associated with the french school of violin playing, although the major musical force behind him was carl flesch
at the outbreak of world war ii, szeryng, who spoke eight languages, was appointed liaison officer and interpreter for gen. wladislaw sikorski, premier of the polish government-in-exile and commander of the free polish army
in 1941, he went with sikorski to latin america in search of a home for about 4,000 polish refugees. the refugees were accepted by mexico. moved by this humanitarian gesture, szeryng took on mexican citizenship in 1946
during the war, he performed more than 300 concerts for allied troops
he eventually became an adviser to the mexican government on cultural matters, but he maintained his base in europe. he lived in paris for about 20 years, but for the past five years he lived in monaco and went to mexico about twice a year
he was decorated by governments from italy to finland, including france, which gave him its illustrious legion of honor in 1984
szeryng made his american debut in carnegie hall in 1943 and went on to make numerous recordings, reaping a grammy award for one of them
in 1970, he was appointed special music advisor to mexico's unesco delegation in paris
encouraged by rubinstein to extend his musical activities worldwide, szeryng did so, increasing his reputation and making numerous recordings with rubinstein
funeral services are to be held in monte carlo, monaco, at a still unspecified date, his paris office said
a federal judge set a precedent when he struck down a florida law that would keep reporters at least 150 feet from polling places on election days, an attorney for three television networks said
u.s. district judge stanley marcus ruled that reporters have a constitutional right to speak to voters, but said they could be kept 50 feet away from polling places
i think judge marcus' decision is going to be cited in a lot of other states besides florida and will be a significant part of a body of law which is being formed striking down similar statutes elsewhere,'' said floyd abrams, attorney for the abc, cbs and nbc networks
the networks, along with the miami news, argued that reporters needed to be closer to polling places to conduct exit polls during next week's super tuesday voting
the decision will make it possible for more people to have more information more quickly about the super tuesday results in florida than would have otherwise been conceivable,'' abrams said
marcus' decision left intact a provision of the law allowing poll workers to keep the media, campaigners and petitioners 50 feet away from the polls. david kraslow, publisher of the news, said that restriction would not interfere with exit polling
the decision is the second florida ruling in a week against the 150-foot rule. u.s. district judge howell melton in jacksonville ruled friday that petitioners seeking to put a medical malpractice measure on future ballots could also approach up to a 50-foot limit
reporters ``have a constitutional right to engage in speech or other expressive activities'' near the polls, marcus said in his opinion wednesday. his decision followed similar rulings by federal judges in georgia and washington state
david leahy, dade county's elections supervisor and a defendant in the suit, said the decision left polling officials with difficult choices
since the jacksonville ruling applied only to medical malpractice petitioners and the miami decision only to the media, officials would be left in the uncomfortable decision of allowing some people up to 50 feet away while others had to stay 150 feet away
we are looking at abandoning any effort to enforce the 150-foot rule,'' leahy said
a high school senior who has taken to singing the national anthem aloud when it is played over the school intercom in the morning has been banished from homeroom for improper behavior
paul rennick, principal of north kingstown high school, said sara sprague is ``playing games'' by violating policy that requires silence when ``the star-spangled banner'' is played on the public address system each morning
but miss sprague, 17, says her patriotic expression is a ``spontaneous reaction to the music.''
nevertheless, she has spent the last three weeks in the school office each morning. katherine janis, her homeroom teacher, said the singing and humming was part of ``noisy and disruptive'' behavior on the student's part
it's not a matter of discipline, it's a matter of the right of a student to participate in singing the national anthem,'' said miss sprague, a member of the school's concert choir
her mother, jane sprague, said she backs her daughter
it's hard for me to believe that a school supported by local, state and federal taxes won't let students sing the national anthem if they want to,'' mrs. sprague said. ``i've never been anyplace where the anthem was played that singing it wasn't welcome.''
the controversy began last month when miss sprague began humming along with the anthem. she was reprimanded by ms. janis
the next day miss sprague sang, quietly she says, and quickly found herself in the assistant principle's office for a lecture on homeroom behavior
the issue went public when miss sprague wrote a letter to a local newspaper protesting her case
rebecca tougas, a member of the student council's executive board, said the council will take up the issue in a survey of the school's 1,600 students
this is a pretty patriotic school,'' rennick said. ``the flag is everywhere. george washington is on the walls. it's not a question of patriotism, it's a question of who's in charge.'' casualties, higher injury toll in hospital attack, other details. no pickup.</note>
iran and iraq said they fired more missiles into each other's capitals for the fourth straight day today. iraq said women and children were killed in baghdad and iran said 13 people were killed in tehran
iran also said 20 people were wounded when a missile hit a hospital in tehran
the missile exchange is the first time both belligerents have bombarded each other's capitals with missiles since the persian gulf war began in september 1980. it is also the worst escalation of the so-called ``war of the cities'' since it began in early 1985
iran has listed 30 killed and more than 130 wounded in tehran since the iraqi missiles began crashing into the capital monday afternoon. it said another five people were killed in an air raid on the northern town of rasht wednesday
iraq has given no official breakdown of its casualties since monday, when iran fired two missiles into baghdad, a city of 5 million people. the official iraqi news agency has reported only that ``many civilians'' have been killed or wounded, but given no figures
the news agency said iraq lobbed two surface-to-surface missiles into tehran soon after dawn. iraqi warplanes also bombed dezful in western iran and the southern city of shiraz
it said the iraqi pilots ``destroyed their targets, leaving them gutted by fire.'' it did not elaborate
tehran radio said the air strikes hit residential areas, killing 13 civilians and wounding 40
that raised to 24 the number of missiles the iraqis claim to have fired since tuesday into the iranian capital, which has a population of 6 million
the iraqi agency also said another missile was fired into the holy city of qom, the cradle of iran's islamic revolution and south of tehran, around daybreak, when moslems pray
the iraqis said they have fired three missiles into qom since wednesday morning. the iraqi agency was monitored in nicosia
tehran's official islamic republic news agency, also monitored in nicosia, said that revolutionary guards fired two missiles into baghdad early today
that brought the number of missiles iran says it has launched since monday to 10. iraq has so far acknowledged that eight hit baghdad
tehran radio quoted military communiques as saying the iranian missiles were aimed at iraq's intelligence headquarters and a center of the ruling baath socialist party
iraq said both missiles hit residential areas, killing or wounding ``a number of civilians, including women and children.''
the agency quoted a military spokesman in baghdad as saying iraq ``will make the rulers of iran taste real agony.''
baghdad's army daily, al-qadissiya, declared: ``whole iranian cities will be wiped off the map and our missile strikes will include other cities besides tehran
the number of missiles we have used so far is only a sample of what we have in store to deter the enemy once and for all.''
irna quoted kamal kharrazi, a member of iran's supreme defense council, as declaring in tehran that iran is ``quite capable of continuing the war of the cities'' until baghdad stops its ``inhuman attacks.''
until monday, iran had fired 37 missiles into baghdad, but the iraqis had not launched any in retaliation
western military analysts believe both sides are using soviet-made ss-1 missiles, known as scud-bs. western military analysts were unsure how many the two belligerents had before they began their long-distance dueling
the iraqis are believed to be firing scuds fitted with strap-on boosters to extend their normal 190-mile range to hit tehran, 290 miles from the iraqi border
iran does not have problems with range as baghdad is only 80 miles west of the battleground frontier
irna quoted a revolutionary guards communique as warning that iran's ``retaliatory operations, including missile and artillery attacks, on iraqi cities will continue powerfully and severely until the baghdad regime stops its vicious acts.''
the missile strikes were the first on qom, although iraqi warplanes bombed the city several times in january last year. qom, a city of 250,000 residents, is about as far from the border as tehran
here are some comments thursday by participants in the two-day nato summit
all of us understand the absolute necessity of maintaining the credibility of our deterrent. we will never trade that credibility away at the negotiating table and we won't give it away through neglect.''
we must not be naive, but we must show flexibility, which will enable dialogue, which will have an effect on (soviet leader mikhail s.) gorbachev's actions,'' mitterand was quoted as telling his fellow summiteers

