he said this was ``absolutely not the time to talk about modernization. it will not be necessary to do it before'' the early 1990s

prime minister rudd lubbers, netherlands:
(the communique) gives the flexibility to choose the moment and where and how to modernize.''

foreign minister giovanni andreotti, italy, on the nato communique:
the basis for the statement is political cohesion coupled with military readiness.''
michigan would return to a presidential primary election in 1992 under a bill unanimously approved by a legislative committee
the senate government operations committee voted 7-0 wednesday to replace the current caucus system of selecting presidential convention delegates with a primary election on the third tuesday in march four years from now
i'd rather have a system more open than we have'' under the bill, said sen. dick posthumus, r-alto, sponsor of the measure. but he noted that democratic objections to allowing ``crossover'' voting _ democrats voting in republican races and vice versa _ forced the party preference provision
however, unlike michigan's earlier presidential primary, voters would have to designate a party preference at least 30 days before the election in order to vote. the party preference would be in effect only for the presidential primary election, and not for other primaries or general elections
delegates
republican presidential candidate george bush picked up 24 delegates in new york this week by virtue of his opponents' failure to file delegate slates in eight of the state's congressional districts
and successful challenges to non-bush delegate slates in other districts, if upheld by the courts, could leave the vice president with at least two dozen other delegates running unopposed
the board of elections on tuesday wiped two slates of delegates supporting bob dole off the the april 19 primary ballot, one day after stripping the kansas senator's slate and one backing new york rep. jack kemp from the ballot
the petitions were rejected mainly because they did not contain the required 1,250 signatures of registered republicans, or were signed by republicans living outside the congressional district the petitions were filed for
at stake in new york are 102 delegates, three from each congressional district. the republican state committee will designate 34 other delegates after the primary
vice president george bush and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis emerged as the favorites in a quinnipiac college poll of connecticut voters taken before the iowa caucuses and new hampshire primary, the college said
the poll was based on telephone interviews between jan. 25 and feb. 2 with 818 registered voters and showed that a large portion was undecided on a favorite candidate for connecticut's march 29 primary
the poll, the first of the quinnipiac college polling institute sampled, 256 republicans, 316 democrats and 212 unaffiliated voters. it asked voters of each party which candidate they would pick among those running in their party. unaffiliated voters were given a choice among candidates of both parties
among the registered republicans surveyed, 43.4 percent favored bush. sen. bob dole of kansas was in second place with 20.5 percent, while rep. jack kemp of new york was third with 4.1 percent. the other republican candidates polled less than 2 percent, while undecided republicans totalled 25.4 percent
of the democrats polled, dukakis had 32.6 percent of the vote, followed by gary hart of colorado with 13.4 percent and jesse jackson of illinois with 10.3 percent. sen. paul simon of illinois had 4.8 percent, while none of the other candidates polled more than 1.4 percent. registered democrats who said they were undecided totalled 30.9 percent
the poll's margin of error was plus or minus five percentage points, the college said wednesday
