but state officials say that even if the draft-cuomo committee succeeds in collecting 22,500 verified signatures of california voters by the march 24 deadline, they still won't add his name to the ballot unless cuomo authorizes the petition drive
the law and party rules make no provisions for unauthorized slates (of delegates). even if they get their signatures, we can't place his name on the ballot,'' said secretary of state spokeswoman caren daniels-meade
you've got to have an official steering committee named by the candidate. he has to be at least partially a willing participant,'' daniels-meade added
our strategy all along has been to get the signatures and then take her (california secretary of state march fong eu) to court to obtain an order placing the governor's name on the ballot,'' said los angeles attorney steven polard, head of the california draft cuomo for president committee
four canadians and nine soviets set off today on an icy, 1,073-mile ski journey over the north pole, from the northernmost point of the soviet union to canada
the soviet news agency tass said the cross-country skiers waved goodbye to observers at cape arctic on the northern tip of severnaya zemlya and headed north in single file. the expedition is expected to take more than three months
led by dmitri shparo, the group planned to make its way from this northern extreme of the soviet archipelago, known simply as ``northern land,'' across the pole and to cape columbia in the canadian artic
the joint expedition was originally planned for 1980, but the canadians backed out when soviet troops intervened in afghanistan's civil war
shparo, 46, led a soviet polar ski trek in 1979, and the head of the canadian team, 28-year-old richard weber of old chesea, ontario, skied the cape columbia-north pole segment in 1986. this will be the first transcontinental ski trek
the most interesting part for me will be the social factor of being in a very small tent with a large number of people for a very long time,'' weber told reporters who visited the ski team's headquarters in dickson, the soviet arctic circle settlement that is the northernmost city in the world
canadian teammate laurie dexter, an anglican minister from fort smith, northwest territories, said the tent is about 15 feet square
there are inevitably frayed nerves and tensions, but all of us are experienced enough and mature enough to let those things pass and get on with the expedition,'' he said
shparo said his biggest fears about the journey are thin ice at the start and finish and encounters with open water caused by drifting ice floes
last time, vasily had to swim twice, and the second time the temperature was minus 30 degrees,'' shparo said, referring to vasily shishkarev, a member of the 1979 soviet expedition and a radio operator on this trek
the skiers will be equipped with rubber rafts, and the soviets will be carrying hunting rifles in case they run into dangerous wildife
they plan to maintain radio contact with three polar weather stations that can relay distress calls to dickson. should a medical emergency develop, or an accident occur, an aeroflot plane can be summoned, weather permitting, shparo said
the ski team includes two doctors, max buxton of calabogie, ontario, and mikhail malakhov of moscow
malakhov is responsible for carrying out medical experiments on his teammates to help doctors understand the effects of extreme weather conditions on the human body
yuri khmelevsky, the chief researcher on the expedition, is looking for a second magnetic pole
he explained in an interview at expedition headquarters that strong magnetic pulls have been recorded by ships and planes in a soviet region below the pole
if it exists, we will find it on this trip,'' khmelevsky said
the skiers will have supplies delivered to them by plane, but their packs and equipment weigh up to 95 pounds when fully loaded
the expedition itinerary envisions five drops of food and supplies
other team members include canadian scientist chris holloway, soviet cameraman vladimir ledenev, radio operator anatoli melnikov, equipment manager anatoly fedyakov, photographer alexander belyayev and artist anatoly fyodyakov
most of the skiers are using soviet-made wooden skis. statistic. pick up 8th pvs, `heroin smuggled...'</note>
well out of sight of tourists strolling along the spectacular royal mile between edinburgh's medieval castle and holyrood palace, the scottish capital is grappling with a double epidemic of drug abuse and aids
the graceful old city, whose arts festival draws 600,000 visitors each summer, is becoming stigmatized as a european center for drug-related aids
unlike the rest of britain, where drug addicts account for only 7 percent of aids carriers, needle-users make up 60 percent of the infected population in scotland and the majority live in edinburgh. the sharing of contaminated needles is one way that the aids virus is transmitted
the number of full-blown aids cases in scotland remains low _ 39 at the end of 1987 _ but 1,500 people in edinburgh alone are thought to be carrying the aids virus, an undetermined proportion of whom will eventually die. the city of 440,000 inhabitants has reported 824 confirmed aids carriers since mid-1983
thirty-nine babies born in edinburgh hospitals since 1985 had aids antibodies, indicating their mothers were infected. it is not known how many of the babies will develop aids
acquired immune deficiency syndrome destroys the body's natural immune system. throughout most of western europe and the united states, it has been confined largely to male homosexuals, although it also affects hemophiliacs and intravenous drug users. about 25 percent of u.s. aids victims are intravenous drug users
in edinburgh, aids is spread mainly through the sharing of needles
heroin smuggled through england's southern ports doubles in price by the time it reaches this northern city and is so adulterated that a dose becomes ineffective when inhaled or smoked
edinburgh addicts, therefore, tend to inject drugs
there's a peculiar sort of scottish characteristic here,'' explained chief inspector douglas kerr, edinburgh's drug squad chief. ``people didn't want to see themselves as being soft or lacking guts. so anyone who failed to use heroin by injecting was seen as copping out.''
also, needle-sharing ``is part of the scene in the same way that a reefer is passed around at a party,'' he said. ``it's the social thing.''
several specialists said a crackdown on drugs helped create a needle shortage and may have quickened the spread of aids by forcing more addicts to share
they're driving people, almost, into injecting,'' said ray de souza, head of simpson house, a drug rehabilitation center
but kerr said experts were jumping to conclusions for want of any other explanation for edinburgh's predicament
with an estimated 2,000 to 3,000 drug abusers in edinburgh, many of them prostitutes, health officials are worried that aids will spread into the general heterosexual population
it's the scale people are concerned about,'' said carol skidmore, a psychologist with the edinburgh drug addiction study, a research unit based at the west granton medical group. she said the infection rate among women due to sexual contact with male addicts was 13 percent to 14 percent
an 11-doctor group in muirhouse, a grim blue-collar district known as ``smack alley,'' has 300 drug abusers among its 18,000 patients. ms. skidmore said 56 percent of the addicts are infected with the aids virus _ and the clinic is having trouble coping with them
dr. george bath, aids coordinator for the lothian health board, which is responsible for an area of 745,000 people in edinburgh and lothian county, said the aids epidemic has created heavy demand for screening and counseling
but so far, there's been minimal pressure on hospitals because most of those carrying the virus are still well. ``the situation,'' he said in an interview, ``is the calm before the storm.''
drug abuse exploded in scotland's inner cities in the early 1980s amid rising unemployment, social deprivation and plentiful heroin. edinburgh was hardest hit, although the industrial cities of glasgow and dundee also experienced sharp rises in drug trafficking
while scottish officials cracked down on heroin, many addicts simply switched to prescribed drugs, mainly painkillers and tranquilizers, creating a new set of problems
we're finding that a lot of drug abusers are coming in to get prescriptions for drugs because they're not able to get heroin,'' ms. skidmore said in an interview
they always want more than we're prepared to give. ... really, it's like a bottomless pit. you could just keep throwing prescriptions at them and they would just keep using them.''
worse yet, she said, most addicts who switched from heroin were taking prescription drugs in liquid form and still injecting them despite the danger of aids
last year, the government set up 15 pilot centers in british cities, including edinburgh, glasgow and dundee, where addicts can swap old needles for new
scottish health minister michael forsyth said in an interview that he has extended government funding for the scottish projects through the end of march, but said preliminary results have been disappointing. the dundee clinic, for example, closed after only six weeks
a recovered alcoholic who was fired for missing 389 days of work in three years has successfully sued his federal employer for job discrimination because he didn't receive legally mandated counseling
a federal judge ruled that clarence ferguson, 48, should be allowed to re-apply for his job as a purchasing agent and ordered the government to give him more than $150,000 in back pay
ferguson said he didn't know he had a drinking problem until he began attending alcoholics anonymous meetings regularly in 1984 after his dismissal from the national wildlife fisheries service
a government worker for 20 years, ferguson said he used to drink a pint of gin daily. he doesn't drink now, he said
u.s. district judge elizabeth kovachevich, in a ruling tuesday, cited a federal law requiring all federal agencies to ``make reasonable accommodations'' for handicapped workers, including those who are alcoholics and drug addicts
this is a very specific federal mandate that says the federal government has to take certain steps that the private sector doesn't have to,'' said ferguson's lawyer, roger benson
attorneys for the government argued they couldn't offer ferguson counseling before firing him because he never told them he was an alcoholic. he never smelled of alcohol, never staggered and didn't sneak drinks, they said during a non-jury trial last month
but kovachevich ruled he was legally crippled by alcoholism and that his employers should have helped him get counseling before dismissing him. his absenteeism should have been a tipoff, she said
attorneys for the department of commerce, which controls the fisheries service, declined comment on whether they will appeal
the u.s. supreme court is scheduled to hear arguments that could legally define alcoholism as a disease and carry consequences for the private sector
the nation's highest court agreed last october to hear a challenge filed against the veterans administration for excluding alcoholism from a list of illnesses and disabilities that veterans can claim when seeking more time to apply for education benefits
the va policy defines alcoholism as ``willful misconduct.''
an 18-year-old man who shot and killed his best friend during an argument over a pet ferret was sentenced to four to five years in prison
michael l. james, sentenced wednesday in douglas county district court, said he would always regret the shooting of david klotz, 20
i'd like to say something to his parents that i haven't said,'' james said. ``really, i'm sorry.''
james shot klotz in the head sept. 6 at the apartment they shared. witnesses told police james threatened to kill a pet ferret because it had fleas. klotz protested and james shot him after a struggle, authorities said
judge jerry gitnick sentenced james to three to five years in prison for manslaughter and to one additional year for using a weapon in the commission of a felony
he originally was charged with second-degree murder but pleaded guilty to the manslaughter and weapon charges. mediator</head> contra comment. pick up 4th graf pvs: `nicaragua previously...' edits thereafter to conform and tighten.</note>
the government for the first time offered to hold peace talks with contra rebels inside nicaragua and recommended they be conducted without a go-between because past mediation produced no results
president daniel ortega said wednesday the talks should be held march 10-12 in the nicaraguan town of sapoa near the costa rican border. he also said his brother, defense minister humberto ortega, would lead the sandinista delegation
it was the first time the leftist sandinista government proposed negotiations in nicaraguan territory with the u.s.-backed rebels, and it would be the highest-level sandinista delegation to meet directly with the contras
in miami, the contras had no immediate response to the proposal, but a spokesman said today they viewed it with suspicion
we are following the situation closely and with concern,'' said jorge rosales, spokesman for the nicaraguan resistance, umbrella organization for rebel groups. ``we have to have first-hand information.''
the sandinistas have violated the peace accords and don't honor their own signature,'' he said
nicaragua previously demanded that the rebels accept a government amnesty as a condition for meeting inside nicaragua. until now, the highest-ranking sandinista negotiator has been a deputy foreign minister
ortega made the announcement after meeting for 20 minutes with cardinal miguel obando y bravo, who mediated two rounds of cease-fire talks with the contras
the last round of negotiations broke off feb. 19 in guatemala after the cardinal declared an impasse. the first meeting, in costa rica, was noted both for its cordial atmosphere and lack of progress
ortega said he decided ``to take the bull by the horns'' because obando y bravo's efforts to halt the 7-year-old war had produced no results
erick ramirez, leader of the opposition social christian party in managua, said the cardinal's dismissal ``will mean an increase in war and violence ... because the cardinal had the confidence of the people.''
i expressed to cardinal obando my concern over time passing by and that, as he himself had said, we must take the bull by the horns and that a direct contact at the highest level and here in nicaragua would be very important because it would make the job of the mediator unnecessary,'' ortega said
the peace talks are being conducted under a central american peace plan signed last august by the presidents of nicaragua, el salvador, costa rica, guatemala and honduras
ortega publicly thanked obando y bravo for his efforts, adding: ``we would not have reached this decisive moment where we will put to the test the will to work for a cease-fire if we had not had his contribution in this first phase when there was no direct contact with the counterrevolution and when the role of the mediator was necessary and indispensable.''
i hope they can find peace now, even if i am not there anymore as mediator,'' obando y bravo told the associated press a few hours later. ``i have often said that a mediator is necessary when both parties want him. i hope they find peace and put an end to the war, the suffering.''
we worked a lot. there were many problems at first. they (the government) refused to meet in central america first, then they did; then they had refused to meet in nicaragua, now they are proposing it,'' the cardinal said
ortega said: ``they (the contras) cannot have any excuse now. they themselves have requested the highest level talks possible and in nicaragua. this is a delegation of the highest level.''
before wednesday, ortega had insisted the contras seek a government amnesty forcing them to pledge to stop fightingbefore they would be allowed into the country to hold cease-fire talks
obando y bravo sent a letter to ortega earlier wednesday calling for a resumption in truce talks. ortega left him a letter in reply, outlining his decision proposing new negotiations without a mediator
the cardinal said he had read the letter to leaders of the nicaraguan resistance
the regional peace plan calls for cease-fires in civil wars in nicaragua, el salvador and guatemala; as well as amnesties, greater democracy, the end of using a country's territory to launch attacks on a neighbor and a halt to outside aid to insurgents in the region
a university dean has confirmed that a man accused of a slaying in his home is his former lover, but says he was not pressured into resigning because of the scandal over the killing
timothy j. lyons, dean of youngstown state university's college of fine and performing arts, on wednesday confirmed a police affidavit that identified the defendant as his former lover
brian scott blevins, 22, of boardman, is charged with murder in the feb. 12 death of kenmore b. drake. blevins is in jail in lieu of $250,000 bond
drake, 21, was staying at lyons' home while lyons was in california visiting his daughters. lyons said he and drake were friends, not lovers
it is essential to the police case to establish my homosexuality, that scott blevins and i lived as lovers,'' lyons, 43, told reporters wednesday. ``i don't resent that people know something is true. i have a problem with the way people react. ... my homosexuality is so damned irrelevant to my profession.''
youngstown state officials announced tuesday that lyons would leave his post monday because of ``difficulties'' resulting from drake's death. university officials have not commented on the situation, other than to issue lyons' resignation statement
drake, a youngstown state senior, was stabbed about 50 times with a pair of scissors, the mahoning county coroner's office says. blevins was not a university student
lyons said he persuaded the university's board of trustees to consider his resignation and that he wasn't pressured to quit
lyons said he's upset that people are allowing his homosexuality to overshadow the fact that ``a good man is dead.''
lyons said he planned to leave the area after his testimony if the case goes to trial. he said he didn't know if he would stay in academics
lyons is to be paid his salary, $59,000 a year, through dec. 31. he joined youngstown state as dean in 1985. 4th graf pvs, `the secretary...; minor editing to conform.</note>
secretary of state george p. shultz, resuming mideast peacemaking efforts, said today the reagan administration remains opposed to bringing the palestine liberation organization into negotiations
shultz arrived in london for two hours of talks with king hussein of jordan. before leaving nato headquarters in brussels, he told reporters, ``the current u.s. policy toward the plo is the same as it has been for years
we don't talk to the plo or deal with them as long as they do not ... basically state their readiness to deal with the state of israel as a fact of life that's going to be there,'' shultz said, ``and as long as they don't renounce terrorism and violence. those are the conditions.''
hussein has reportedly been in london for dental surgery
the secretary, who was to travel to jersualem after seeing hussein, said that any arab-israeli settlement must ``deal with the legitimate rights'' of the palestinians. shultz said he did not expect, during his return trip to the middle east, to meet with palestinian leaders in the israeli occupied lands
i don't see any way to do that, but of course i would like to do that as soon as possible,'' he said
president reagan announced wednesday that he was sending shultz on a new round of talks with mideast leaders in search of a formula for negotiations to end the 40-year arab-israeli dispute
on friday, in a fast-paced sequence, he will meet separately with israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir and foreign minister shimon peres, go to egypt and syria for talks with leaders there _ and immediately fly home
his hope is that he can narrow the differences over who should be at the negotiating table and over the outline of an eventual settlement
hussein and syrian president hafez assad are pushing hard for participation by the soviet union and the palestine liberation organization. shamir, meanwhile, is resisting the u.s. call on israel to exchange territory for peace with the arabs
reagan made the decision to recommit shultz and u.s. prestige to the so-far unsuccessful search for peace after shultz reported on his first, four-day meeting the arabs and israelis
it is clear all countries in the region believe it is useful for the united states to remain engaged in this process,'' reagan said. ``we will spare no effort in our search for a comprehensive peace settlement.''
shultz, interviewed on ``cbs morning news'' today, said that since he consulted here with reagan, ``i feel as though i have something to say that comes from the president, and my discussions with him, and i'll go around and say it.''
the idea _ which so far hussein and shamir have not accepted _ is to quickly defuse the disturbances on the west bank and in gaza with a two-step plan
first, arrangements would be made to transfer immediately to the 1.5 million palestinians in the israeli-held territories control over their daily affairs
then, by december, israelis, jordanians and palestinians would meet on an overall settlement of the middle east conflict
hussein is insisting on an active role by the soviet union in shaping a settlement and the direct participation of the plo, which is accused by israel and the united states of fomenting terrorism
he is also demanding the withdrawal of israel from all the land the arabs lost in the 1967 six-day war
shamir has offered autonomy for the palestinians and is trying to fence out the soviets, who do not have diplomatic ties with jerusalem. he has resisted yielding territory
shamir said in jerusalem on wednesday that shultz ``is making a laudable attempt to move the peace process forward and get negotiations started between us and jordan.''
but he told members of the conference of presidents of major american jewish organizations that israeli withdrawal from occupied lands would have ``disastrous consequences,'' arguing the ultimate goal of arab leaders was to destroy israel
a u.s. official, who demanded anonymity, said hussein did not ``throw cold water'' on the u.s. initiative but also did not endorse it
if i had to describe the situation, i would say that nobody has signed up to our proposals, but everybody wants us to keep working,'' shultz said tuesday in tel aviv
asked during the cbs interview about palestinian participation in any peace talks, shultz said that hussein has said that palestinians must be present ``so they can speak'' and said the israelis ``fully agree with this.''
shultz said ``the king's idea is that they be part of a jordanian-palestinian delegations.''    admits lying</head>
a mistrial was declared in a reverse discrimination case of four white police officers after chicago's former head of police admitted he lied under oath
u.s. district judge paul e. plunkett declared the mistrial wednesday in the $12 million lawsuit, in which four officers say they were demoted because of their race and for political reasons. the judge said former police superintendent fred rice's admission and reasons he cited for lying tainted the jury and undercut the case
matthew piers, an assistant corporation counsel for the city who represented rice, said it was ``ridiculous'' when asked if rice could face perjury charges. ``it is not a possibility at all,'' piers said
u.s. attorney anton valukas would not comment
piers had argued against a mistrial, telling the judge that rice's admission harmed no one but himself. ``a mistrial is a gross injustice to the defendant's case,'' he said
but plunkett did not agree. he said he would rule april 13 on a request for a default judgment in favor of the four officers
a few months after the 1983 election of harold washington, the city's first black mayor, rice was named as the first black police superintendent, and 25 white officers were demoted
four officers are seeking $12 million from the city, maintaining they were demoted because they are white and because they supported washington's democratic primary opponent, former mayor jane byrne
rice said politics had no part in any reassignments during his years as police superintendent
in court tuesday, rice said he concealed his real reasons for demoting a number of ranking white officers to protect their reputations and preserve police morale. he said ``negative information'' was a factor in the demotions
rice, 61, said he lied in depositions taken in october 1984 and august 1985 when he was still superintendent. he retired last year
rice's unexpected admission brought an angry response from edward theobald, attorney for the plaintiffs, one current and three former officers
you know it's a felony crime, and you deliberately lied when you were sworn to tell the truth,'' theobald contended
that's right,'' said rice, who said ``there were extenuating circumstances that caused me to say the things i did.''
i tried to be as considerate to those people as possible,'' the former police chief said. ``i felt i was protecting the reputation of all the people i reduced.''
theobald requested the mistrial and asked plunkett for a default judgment
in a telephone interview late wednesday, theobald said that if the judge rules in the officers' favor, a jury would be chosen to set damages. if plunkett denies the default judgment, a new trial would begin
lt. col. william higgins, the american marine kidnapped in lebanon two weeks ago, has been selected for promotion to the rank of colonel
higgins, a military aide to former defense secretary caspar w. weinberger before assuming a temporary assignment as the head of a united nations observer detachment last summer, was listed today along with 78 other lieutenant colonels selected by a promotion board for advancement
higgins is no. 28 on the list of 79 and would not actually receive the new rank for another year at the earliest. the marine promotion board was formed early this year to screen a field of 165 men and women. higgins was kidnapped on feb. 17
higgins, 43, was in lebanon because he had been assigned to temporary duty with the united nations heading a group of observers attached to the u.n. truce supervision organization
a decorated vietnam combat veteran, higgins served as the junior military assistant to weinberger for two years, from june 1985 to june 1987
