we assume that she was driving around and got disoriented,'' andy fisher, an aide to the indiana republican, said from washington
bertha lugar caldwell, 81, may have gotten disoriented while driving late wednesday in indianapolis, which is about 70 miles from the illinois state line, fisher said
fisher would not specify where mrs. caldwell was but said she was ok and at a hotel. relatives were en route
there was no foul play involved,'' said wendy snitko of the indianapolis police department
fisher said a doctor probably would examine mrs. caldwell in indianapolis but that her health ``has been fine all along.''
it is one of these things that happens from time to time with older people. she may have gotten disoriented.''
mrs. caldwell was reported missing about 1:30 a.m. today by her stepdaughter, lynn caldwell
she had last been seen wednesday night driving in the city's northside
sally lugar, wife of the senator's brother thomas, said she received a call late wednesday from a friend who said she had seen mrs. caldwell driving her car at the christian theological seminary
with the weather, we were a little concerned,'' mrs. lugar said. ``i called at her home. when i didn't get an answer, i went over. it's been a long night.''
there was rain, freezing rain and sleet in the area during the night
wrapped in a clear plastic sheet to ward off drizzle, jacqueline smith today sat on a sidewalk and protested plans to make a civil rights museum out of the small motel where martin luther king jr. was killed
ms. smith, who was forcibly evicted wednesday from the lorraine motel, said she would stay in front of the motel as long as she could
i don't mind being a little uncomfortable,'' she said. ``i'll try to sit here as long as my body allows.''
ms. smith said several friends dropped by during the night to offer food and encouragement and two supporters took turns sitting with her until daybreak
she was carried from the motel by shelby county sheriff's deputies who deposited her just outside an 8-foot chain-link surrounding the lorraine, which was closed last month to make way for an $8.8 million museum
you people are making a mistake. you people are making a mistake,'' ms. smith sobbed as the deputies evicted her
the lorraine was closed jan. 11, but ms. smith ignored repeated requests to move from her room, about 25 feet from where king was felled by an assassin's rifle slug
ms. smith, who has lived and worked at the lorraine for 11 years, argued that the motel should be turned into shelter for the homeless, not a museum. she argued a museum will speed efforts to gentrify her low-income neighborhood
the lorraine, which has fallen into disrepair over the years, was bought at a foreclosure auction in 1982 by a group pushing plans for a museum
the state has appropriated $4.4 million for the project and city and county governments have agreed to match that. the state has title to the property and will build and operate the museum, scheduled to open in 1991
