west german hostage ralph rudolf schray was freed by his pro-iranian shiite moslem kidnappers in beirut today and turned over to the west german embassy in damascus, officials said
an embassy employee in damascus, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he saw schray being escorted into the embassy at around noon. the 30-year-old industrial engineer was kidnapped jan. 27 and released before dawn
he is still inside, resting and waiting for his wife,'' the employee said. ``a car has been sent to beirut to bring her.''
a military source at the syrian command in beirut, also speaking on condition of anonymity, told the associated press that schray was driven to the syrian capital, 56 miles east of beirut, under heavy syrian escort
in a statement issued in bonn, foreign minister hans-dietrich genscher thanked the syrian government for its help. a ministry statement said schray was in good physical condition
schray, a lebanese-born west german, was seized in moslem west beirut. a shiite faction, holy warriors for freedom, on wednesday claimed responsibility for his abduction
the group also claimed responsibility for kidnapping two other west germans in beirut in january 1987. it is believed headed by the brother of two lebanese shiite moslems who are being held in west germany on terrorism and kidnapping charges
schray's mother, fahima schray, called her son's captivity ``the most terrible days of my life. it was so difficult.'' mrs. schray was interviewed in fort myers, fla
i couldn't sleep last night one minute. this morning, everything has changed completely, as if i'm a new woman,'' she said
schray's lebanese wife of six months, rana mounla, and his uncle, george abu nassar, left by car for damascus carrying a suitcase of clothes for the freed german
i'm going to see him,'' a beaming mrs. schray told reporters. ``i'm taking clothes for him.''
she indicated that she planned to return to beirut with her husband from damascus. ``when we're back together in beirut tomorrow we'll both talk to you,'' she said. she declined to elaborate
abu nassar, a wealthy lebanese businessman of palestinian descent, refused to talk to reporters
there are still 22 foreigners missing after being kidnapped in lebanon. they include nine americans, four frenchmen, three britons, a west german, an italian, an irishman, an indian and two unidentified men
longest held is american terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press. he was kidnapped march 16, 1985
the holy warriors for freedom made its claim in a typewritten arabic statement released to the reuters news agency in beirut. it was accompanied by a recent snapshot of schray
the statement said schray could be released within hours as a result of mediation by syrian president hafez assad
abdul-hadi hamadi is reputed to lead the holy warriors for freedom, and he also heads the security apparatus of the pro-iranian hezbollah, or party of god
hamadi's brother, abbas hamadi, is on trial in west germany on charges of kidnapping west germans rudolf cordes and alfred schmidt in january 1987 in beirut
those kidnappings allegedly were to pressure the bonn government into releasing a third hamadi brother, mohammed, who is being held in frankfurt on terrorism charges
in their statement wednesday, the kidnappers said that while they were negotiating with the west germans over schray, ``a mediation team from the brothers in syria, led by president assad, gave a chance for a new round of commitments that made the case of the german schray head for a solution within the coming hours.''
the hamadi brothers are still in germany. the release (of schray) is goodwill gesture no. 2,'' it added
schmidt, 47, was released sept. 7 as a goodwill gesture. cordes, 53, is still in captivity
mohammed hamadi has been indicted in the united states on murder and air piracy charges in connection with the june 1985 hijacking of a twa jetliner in which 39 americans were held hostage and a u.s. navy diver was killed
he was arrested jan. 13, 1987 when he arrived at frankfurt airport carrying explosives. the bonn government last year turned down a u.s. request for his extradition, saying he will be tried in west germany on similar charges
cordes was kidnapped in beirut on jan. 17, 1987, and schmidt seven days later, on jan. 21, 1987
abbas hamadi was arrested also upon arriving at frankfurt airport jan. 26, five days after schmidt was abducted.  
the mother of a west german industrial engineer freed early today after being kidnapped in lebanon five weeks ago said the news ended the ``most terrible days of my life.''
farina schray said she was waiting for word from her only child, 30-year-old ralph rudolf schray, who was abducted jan. 27 in moslem west beirut
schray was freed unharmed before dawn today by shiite moslem kidnappers and taken to damascus. he was reported in good physical condition
it was so difficult,'' said ms. schray, who is visiting her son's uncle. ``we were praying all the time. ... it was the most terrible days of my life.''
ms. schray said that during the ordeal she has maintained contact with her son's wife of six months, rana mounla
ms. schray said she wasn't sure how long she will stay in florida or if her son will come here. if he doesn't, she will probably return to her beirut home in a week or so, she said
the syrian government was credited with mediating the release of schray, a lebanese-born west german. since march 1985, 22 foreigners have been kidnapped in lebanon, including nine americans, four frenchmen, three britons, a west german, an italian, an irishman and indian and two unidentified men
longest held is american terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press. he was kidnapped march 16, 1985
a meteorologist says it would have made ``all the difference in the world'' if national weather service forecasters had passed along information about a thunderstorm that downed delta airlines flight 191
william haggard also criticized a weather service meteorologist assigned to monitor weather near dallas-fort worth international airport for going to dinner 40 minutes before the crash
flight 191 crashed aug. 2, 1985, while attempting to land at dallas-fort worth during a severe thunderstorm, killing 137 people and injuring 25 others
delta is suing the government, claiming the failure of weather service employees and air traffic controllers to warn the flight crew of the storm was a primary cause of the crash
the national transportation safety board concluded that the crash was caused in part by the pilot's decision to fly into an area of potential wind shear, a violent downdraft of air beneath thunderstorms
the l-1011 widebody jet was hit by such a downdraft while approaching the runway, and slammed into airport water tanks and exploded into flames
haggard, who owns a private meteorological consulting firm in north carolina, said wednesday that government meteorologist richard douglass should not have left his post for more than 10 minutes on the evening of the crash because conditions suggested dangerous weather might be ahead
i think all the difference in the world would have been made if he (douglass) had been there and been alert,'' haggard said. ``he would have had the opportunity to call the (control) tower and warn them.''
justice department attorney kathlynn fadely has argued that the delta flight crew knew of the thunderstorm in its landing path when co-pilot rudolph price spotted lightning about 1{ minutes before the crash
haggard testified that while douglass was at dinner, a second forecaster stationed at stephenville, southwest of fort worth, spotted signs of a storm but telephoned his warning to the weather service in fort worth instead of the airport control tower. he said weather service officials failed to relay that warning in the minutes before the crash
the non-jury trial will determine whether the government must pay part of $91.2 million in claims that delta's insurers have paid so far in connection with the crash
the senate voted overwhelmingly today to prohibit most employers from using lie detectors to screen job applicants and randomly test the honesty of employees
on a 69-27 vote, the senate passed a bill by senators edward m. kennedy, d-mass., and orrin hatch, r-utah _ normally adversaries on labor-management issues _ over the objections of a small group of conservative republicans
a similar but more stringent ban was approved last november by the house. differences between the two versions must be resolved and a compromise passed by both houses
sen. dan quayle, r-ind., a leader of the opposition, predicted that president reagan would sign a polygraph bill despite a vow by administration officials last year that they would encourage him to veto it
the administration does not have the backbone at this time to veto this bill,'' quayle complained. ``they have folded up shop, caving like a house of cards.''
sen. thad cochran, r-miss., another opponent, predicted that denying employers the opportunity to screen job applicants using polygraph examinations will raise consumer costs through increased thefts on the job
kennedy and hatch, however, said no one has presented any statistics in states where use of the test already is prohibited to demonstrate a higher incidence of theft or embezzlement
hatch called the softening of the administration's opposition ``encouraging.''
some 320,000 honest americans are branded as liars every single year because of these devices,'' he said. ``that's a stigma they are going to have to wear every day the rest of their lives and careers.''
kenneday said the polygraph has become ``to the 20th century what witchcraft was two centuries ago.''
we're going to see the day where the average worker is going to be able to walk into the workplace with dignity and self-respect,'' he said. ``these devices are no longer going to scar people in ways that they and their families can never forget.''
the senate voted after quayle, cochran and sen. phil gramm, r-texas, dropped plans to introduce three more amendments aimed at weakening the ban
the house version would ban all use of polygraph examinations in private industry except for security personnel and pharmaceutical companies
while imposing the same prohibitions on lie detectors to screen job applicants, the senate measure would allow their use to investigate incidents of ``economic loss or injury'' such as alleged thefts or other criminal acts, but only under strict regulations to be enforced by the labor department
hatch said the compromise acceptable to many retailers and other companies plagued by thefts was formulated primarily by leaders of the 1-million-member united food and commercial workers union
honest people each year are branded as liars,'' hatch said, because of false results from polygraph tests often administered in 15 minutes and in ways that minimize their accuracy
conversely,'' he said, ``it is a regrettable fact that employees steal. this bill addresses both concerns by barring use of polygraphs where they are most likely to make a false identification but permitting the use of these tests where they are likely to be most accurate ... in conjunction with the investigation of a specific incident.''
before any test, employers would first have to file a police report, insurance claim or report to a regulatory agency _ or sign a statement detailing their reasons for testing a specific worker
and the tests would have to be administered under strict guidelines to be developed by the labor department requiring at least 90 minutes for each exam
violations could result in fines of up to $10,000 each, and employees or job applicants would have the right to file civil suits against offenders
disciplining or firing employees for refusing to take the test or for failing it without additional supporting evidence of wrongdoing would be prohibited
administration officials have said they would urge president reagan to veto the house version as an unwarranted federal intrusion into labor-management relations and pre-emption of state regulations
the administration also has gone on record opposing the senate measure but not in as strong terms
kennedy, citing reports from the congressional office of technology assessment and the american medical association that the tests give false results 15 percent to 50 percent of the time, called lie detectors ``inaccurate instruments of intimidation.''
we know that in most applications, the devices cannot be trusted,'' he said. ``it is time to put an end to their unacceptable misuse that unfairly places so many workers' jobs in jeopardy.''
the legislation was prompted by an explosive growth _ ``like wildfire,'' according to kennedy _ in the use of lie detector tests by employers over the past eight years
an estimated 2 million people are now subjected to the tests each year, double the number just three years ago, according to kennedy. he and hatch estimated their bill would outlaw about 85 percent of those tests
like the house, the senate voted wednesday to also exempt security guards, armored car companies and firms that install and service security alarms from the prohibition
and it extended the house exemption to include workers at nuclear power plants and contract employees hired by the government with access to classified information
however, it rejected several other amendments aimed at weakening the ban, such as allowing the tests if employees request them and exemptions for airline, railroad and other employees in the transportation industry
a woman located through income tax errors has pleaded guilty to escaping from a federal women's prison 10 years ago, but even a prosecutor cites her good behavior since then
mary hughey cantrell, who failed to return from a 1977 christmas furlough, pleaded guilty wednesday in federal court in beckley to a charge of escape from the alderson federal correctional institution. she was returned to the prison to await her april 22 sentencing
the charge carries a maximum five-year sentence and a $5,000 fine
federal public defender ira kirkendoll said cantrell, 40, originally from north carolina, moved to arizona shortly after her escape and apparently remained law-abiding while working for several years as a maid in private homes and resorts
it's pretty unusual, the length of time,'' kirkendoll said. ``apparently she has reformed to some degree.''
even assistant u.s. attorney kirk brandfass said the woman's decade of crime-free living, aside from maintaining a false identity, should be considered at sentencing
my heavens, that ought to count for something,'' brandfass said outside court
u.s. marshals wouldn't allow an interview with cantrell, who had been sentenced to three years after a 1975 conviction for passing counterfeit money
she was paroled in may 1976 but was returned to the alderson prison in early 1977 after a parole violation, and has about 470 days left to serve on her original sentence
she was arrested jan. 5 in phoenix, ariz
during her 10 years of freedom, cantrell acquired an acquaintance's identification cards. she was discovered after the internal revenue service spotted a discrepancy in income tax returns for a woman who had never worked in arizona
then it was a matter of running the paychecks back to where they were earned,'' brandfass said. ``and it zeroed in at phoenix, ariz. i'm told she was pretty stunned when the marshals showed up to get her.''
education secretary william j. bennett today renewed his call for sexual abstinence among teen-agers as their best defense against aids, and said he and surgeon general c. everett koop are not as far apart on the issue as perceived
bennett was responding to a statement by retired adm. james d. watkins, chairman of president reagan's aids commission, that one of the panel's main tasks is to resolve seemingly differing opinions in making its recommendations this summer
commenting on publicized differences between bennett and koop over what emphasis to place on urging sexually active people to use condoms, watkins said, ``whether it is real or non-substantive, it is a real perception out there.''
watkins said many witnesses have told the commission they fear top federal officials are sending ``equivocal messages'' to the nation on aids prevention and that it is important for the federal government to speak with one voice on the issue
dr. koop and i are very close, extremely close,'' said bennett. `'i think koop and i agree 95 percent of the way. it's all right for the surgeon general and the secretary of education to speak a little differently about these things.''
he compared it to a young woman or man who might discuss ``what he or she is doing'' with a doctor with a counselor
the doctor's advice would probably emphasize the medical aspects, as it should,'' said bennett. ``the teacher or counselor's advice might emphasize other things. some shading of difference is ok. some measure of disagreement is ok.''
when the american people ask for leadership, they are not saying, `we're a bunch of dummies, tell us what to think','' said bennett, ``they want to know our best thinking. and if our best thinking diverges on some points, they can handle it.''
although saying he agrees that people, including teen-agers, need to know that condom and spermicide use offers the only protection against contracting aids sexually, bennett said it was a matter of emphasis
what he fears, he said, is teachers going through ``a kind of incantation'' on abstinence and sexual monogamy in aids prevention classes, ``then proceeding for the rest of the class to talk (to teen-agers) about how to protect themselves.''
it's like saying, don't smoke, but if you do, smoke low tar. don't drink, but if you do, keep it to 70 proof. i think these are equivocal messages.''
koop told the white house aids commission earlier in the week that while it is important to recommend abstinence, ``i think it is also realistic to understand that sexually active teen-agers are unlikely to reverse their pattern and go backward, and therefore prevention for them has to be our third line of defense. ... we have to teach them about the protection of themselves and others through the use of condoms and spermicides.''
a former football star who now is a college athletic director has been charged with first-degree murder in the 31-year-old slaying of a reputed whiskey runner, police said
bobby hoppe, 53, of ringgold, ga., and athletic director at chattanooga state technical community college, was arrested wednesday after a hamilton county grand jury indicted him for the 1957 shotgun death of teddy donald hudson in north chattanooga
hoppe's arrest followed a 14-month investigation by two chattanooga detectives who interviewed at least 45 witnesses after reopening the case, police said
hoppe was a suspect in the original 1957 investigation, said police spokesman freeman cooper
allegations were made during that investigation that hoppe had shot hudson over his (hoppe's) sister, whom hudson was dating at the time,'' cooper read from a statement. ``however, police could not develop enough evidence to arrest him.''
after hudson, 24, was shot to death in a car near his home, police investigated the possibility that the slaying was related to the moonshine liquor business, for which hudson had served time previously
the investigation was reopened after hudson's mother, georgia, talked with detectives following a meeting of families and friends of murder victims, a support and counseling group
at the time of the slaying, hoppe was a starter on the alabama polytechnic institute, now auburn university, football team that went on to win a national championship. before that, he was an all-state player at chattanooga's central high school
hoppe, who was released after posting $7,000 bond, said wednesday: ``my attorney has told me not to make a statement. ... i am not going to answer more questions.'' builds</head> from reagan, other details. no pickup</note>
many shuttered stores reopened today and opponents of the regime of gen. manuel antonio noriega pondered their next move as a general strike wound down
president reagan indicated today he believes noriega must go. secretary of state george p. shultz said economic sanctions against noriega's government were being ``considered carefully.''
local banks, closed since the strike began monday, were to reopen at midday. at least two factories in the city's main industrial park _ a ghost town for the past three days _ resumed work this morning, with others preparing to do so
anti-riot police made a show of force early today along calle 50, the scene of disturbances tuesday and wednesday. at least three truckloads of the troopers _ whose corps is called the ``dobermans'' _ took up positions at strategic intersections
leaders of the national civic crusade said they would decide tonight whether to call off the strike, which has lasted longer than any of the five shutdowns staged last year by the opposition coalition
a member of the joint chiefs of staff, meanwhile, was quoted by a panama city newspaper as denying reports that noriega was purging his armed forces
national assemblyman guillermo cochez, of the opposition christian democratic party, said wednesday at a news conference that noriega had ordered the early retirements of two colonels and two majors he suspected of wavering loyalty
but joint chiefs member col. leonidas macias told the pro-government newspaper ``la estrella'' that ``here everything is normal and no one has been retired or dismissed.''
on wednesday, organizers called the strike their most successful yet. the united states also stepped up economic pressure on panama's military strongman
doctors on wednesday joined businesses in the strike. organizers said they would increase street demonstrations that have brought scattered violence to the capital
reagan was asked in brussels, where he attended a nato summit, if he thought noriega should relinquish power
yes,'' the president responded. he did not elaborate
shultz called noriega ``bad news'' but said that no decision had been made on sanctions
noriega, chief of the 15,000-strong defense forces, has run the country since 1983. he was indicted in the united states last month on charges of trafficking in cocaine
in june, his former second-in-command went public with charges that noriega was involved in election fraud, corruption and political assassinations. noriega has denied those accusations
in washington, u.s. officials confirmed wednesday that they will ask u.s. banks to freeze panamanian government assets and delay payment of panama canal tolls to the military-dominated government
panama is thought to have up to $50 million on deposit in seven u.s. banks and its share of canal fees comes to about $7 million a month
the sanctions were recommended by william d. rogers, whose washington law firm represents panama's deposed president, eric arturo delvalle
the u.s. officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the state department was acting on the rogers recommendations because it recognizes delvalle as panama's lawful head of state
elliott abrams, assistant secretary of state for latin american affairs, told cable news network in washington that the state department would advise american bankers to withhold funds from the panamanian government
delvalle is president of panama. and noriega has been fired and he does not have legitimate authority here,'' he said
manuel solis palma, installed as panama's new chief of state, said wednesday that he had no official knowledge of the u.s. plan
delvalle attempted to fire noriega last week, prompting the noriega-controlled national assembly to remove him. delvalle went into hiding, apparently in panama
strike organizers claimed ship traffic through the panama canal was halted for an hour wednesday by panamanian workers
the panama canal commission said traffic was normal. the commission also said it received two phony bomb threats wednesday and tuesday, adding that they had not disrupted operation of the waterway. agreement. pick up 4th graf pvs: `soviet leader...' edits thereafter to conform and trim.</note>
negotiators in the u.n.-sponsored afghanistan peace talks agreed today that the soviet union should withdraw its 115,000 soldiers from the country within nine months
afghan foreign minister abdul wakil announced the agreement and told reporters that half the troops would leave within the first three months
wakil said the accord was reached during 2{ hours of meetings that u.n. mediator diego cordovez conducted separately today with afghan and pakistani representatives
nothing important stands in the way of concluding a settlement,'' wakil said. the accord on the timetable had been expected after the gap between the two sides' positions had narrowed from an original 43 months to two months in almost six years of negotiations
soviet leader mikhail gorbachev last month had said moscow would bring home its troops within 10 months starting may 15 provided a settlement is signed in geneva by march 15
cordovez planned to brief u.s. and soviet officials later, including deputy u.s. secretary of state robert peck, sources said
soviet troops entered afghanistan in 1979 and replaced the communist government with another communist regime. they have been helping the government fight anti-communist moslem guerrillas
a new u.n. report said success at the geneva talks may leave a primary problem unresolved: the return of more than 5 million afghan refugees who fled the war to neighboring pakistan and iran
the head of the pakistani delegation, acting foreign minister zain noorani, told reporters that islamabad wants a broad-based transitional government to be set up, but would not specify when that should be done
we are firmly convinced that a settlement without creating circumstances of peace and stability in afghanistan will not pursuade 5 million afghan refugees ...to return,'' he said
asked when such a government should take office, he said the timing depends ``on when efforts to bring about a settlement among the afghans can be visibly seen and when we are able to pursuade all parties concerned '' to establish it
before the new round got under way wednesday, cordovez reaffirmed that the future makeup of the kabul government is outside the scope of negotiations
the soviets also have said they are not interested in influencing its composition
the u.n. report, prepared for the 43-nation u.n. human rights commission, warned that most refugees were unlikely to return unless the afghan government is replaced by one that includes opposition and refugee representation
the report also says the human rights situation in afghanistan has improved, though there is evidence political prisoners are still being tortured and killed
the regime of president najib is backed by little more than the 115,000 red army troops
the ``national reconciliation'' policy najib proclaimed more than a year ago has failed, austrian jurist felix ermacora, special investigator for the 43-nation u.n. human rights commission, says in the 29-page report
ermacora visited refugees in pakistan and government-controlled areas of afghanistan in january
he says in the report that most refugees he spoke with said they would return only when ``the foreign troops had withdrawn and a government in which they had confidence had been established.''
government sources were quoted in the report as saying there were 3,147 political prisoners in january, though more than 7,000 had been released under amnesty decrees
but the report cites ``reliable reports'' that political prisoners had recently been killed in the kabul area and that there had been torture in ghazni province
it says the new afghan constitution makes no provision ``for free, secret and universal elections to the national assembly'' in balloting to be held by june. ermacora says he doubts the najib regime will allow multi-party participation
the united states last year gave an estimated $700 million worth of military assistance to the 200,000 guerrillas. up 4th graf, `if they;'' deletes last 6 grafs to shorten.</note>
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis accused rival democratic presidential candidate richard gephardt today of trying to impose ``a $50 billion burden on the nation's economy'' with an oil import fee and ``duck-and-hide'' trade barriers
dukakis, barnstorming across texas in quest of the biggest super tuesday primary prize of 183 delegates, defended his own opposition to an oil import fee, which many in the ailing texas oil industry have hoped for
on a visit to mp industries, a successful small business that makes rubber parts for oil field drills, dukakis said the missouri congressman wants to return the united states to ``policies that almost destroyed us 50 years ago.''
if we adopt congressman gephardt's policies, we'll have a trade war, and nobody benefits from a trade war,'' said dukakis
there's always somebody around who suggests that: throw up the walls, hunker down,'' he said. dukakis claimed his administration would foster ``a competitive america, one that doesn't duck and hide but stands up and competes with the best of them.''
an oil import fee ``will put a $50 billion burden on this nation's economy. we don't need that,'' said the governor, who favors creating incentives for small oil producers to start drilling again, repealing of the oil windfall tax, filling the strategic petroleum reserve, and increasing natural gas production
dukakis was traveling across texas today, from east texas to corpus christi to border towns to houston and on to west texas in his campaign for votes in next tuesday's primaries in 20 states
on wednesday, dukakis promised to fight to make all american workers eligible for basic health insurance on the job. he told uninsured workers at a free clinic in tampa, fla., ``it is very disturbing to meet american families who literally don't have a dime of basic health insurance
if they or their youngsters have to go to the hospital, they don't know how they're going to pay those bills. ... '' he said. ``it's just unconscionable.''
back home, the massachusetts house passed a dukakis plan to force employers with six or more workers to provide health insurance. the state senate is expected to follow suit within two weeks
dukakis predicted massachusetts' example will pave the way for a similar federal breakthrough, four decades after harry truman proposed national health insurance
thirty-seven million americans are uninsured, he said. ``it's time we decided in this country that one of the things you get along with your wages is basic health insurance.''
he claimed it could be done without ``creating a big new bureaucratic program. ... this will not cost the federal treasury a dime.''
asked how small businesses could afford it, dukakis said most businesses already provide insurance, and indirectly pay ``a hidden surcharge'' to cover hospitals' costs of treating the uninsured
richard posada, 32, a tampa carpet installer who makes $18,000 a year, told dukakis he went without insurance when he found it would cost him $240 a month
it's a gamble,'' said posada. then he found the judeo christian health clinic here, where care for his wife and two toddlers is free. ``they've treated us real nice here,'' the carpet layer said
dale smith, a lawn worker with high blood pressure and no insurance, told the candidate, ``this place has been a real blessing to me.''
dukakis said if all workers had insurance, ``we'd have clinics like this springing up all over the place.''
the massachusetts bill will cost the state $100 million, including aid for hospitals hit by big debts for indigent care
meanwhile, the massachusetts governor began airing a new television commercial attacking rival rep. richard gephardt and mocking gephardt's populist slogan, ``it's your fight too.''
the advertisement says gephardt is taking campaign contributions from ``big establishment power brokers'' and adds: ``kinda makes you wonder, is dick gephardt fighting your fight or theirs?''
in miami, where he was endorsed by the president of the embattled machinists' union at ailing eastern airlines, dukakis said, ``i hope i'll be the candidate who emerges from super tuesday with the largest number of cumulative delegate votes
if we can do that, then i think we're going to be steaming into illinois and we're going to be on our way to the nomination,'' said dukakis
dukakis did wednesday what a lot of visitors to florida do this time of year: visit a baseball spring training camp
but unlike ordinary tourists, dukakis actually got to stand in the boston red sox batting cage in winter haven for a turn at bat. in 10 swings against a batting practice pitcher, the onetime catcher on the brookline, mass., high school freshman team hit three foul balls, a pop into the cage and five grounders; and fanned once
tamil rebels disguised as soldiers attacked a village with submachine guns and automatic rifles and killed 16 people, a military official said today. most of the victims were woman and children
in a separate incident today, three rebels were killed in a gun battle with police manning a roadblock in the southeast
police chief s. wijesinghe of the ampara district said there were no police casualties. police seized a chinese-made t-56 rifle and a submachine gun from the slain rebels, he said
the military official said the 16 were killed wednesday at morawewa village, 27 miles west of trincomalee port on the eastern coast of sri lanka. he spoke on condition of anonymity according to regulations
the victims included nine children, four women and three men, he said. all were sinhalese except for one tamil. three people were injured
the official blamed the attack on members of the liberation tigers of tamil eelam, the largest rebel group. the tigers have been at the forefront of a four-year war for a separate tamil homeland and have targeted attacks on the majority sinhalese community
the tigers were blamed for the killings of more than 200 sinhalese in october last year soon after they renounced a peace accord aimed at ending the separatist war
more than 8,000 people have been killed in the tamil conflict since 1983. tamils, who form 18 percent of the country's 16 million people, claim that they are discriminated against by the majority sinhalese, who form 75 percent of the population. 03-03 0482</first> disease</head> doctors...' to update with ross news conference today. adds byline.</note>
a victim of degenerative huntington's disease underwent experimental surgery in which doctors removed an adrenal gland and grafted the tissue onto the man's brain
it was the first time a patient with huntington's, a fatal disease marked by mental deterioration and uncontrollable movements, underwent a procedure that has shown promise in relieving symptoms of parkinson's disease, surgeons at vanderbilt university medical center said wednesday
it will be several months before we know if it works,'' said dr. george s. allen, chairman of the department of neurosurgery and director of vanderbilt's neurotransplant program
the 41-year-old patient was in critical but stable condition this morning, said john houser, a medical center spokesman
our hope is that this (surgery) is something that would dramatically affect this disease,'' dr. j.c. ross, associate vice chancellor for health affairs at vanderbilt, said at a news conference today. ``it is not a cure. our hope is that it might slow down the illness.''
surgeons said the procedure tuesday is similar to surgery performed at vanderbilt last year on 18 patients with parkinson's disease, a brain disorder characterized by rigidity and tremors
we aren't as likely to see improvement in symptoms as with the parkinson's surgery, but we hope this procedure will slow down or stop the progress of huntington's disease,'' said dr. noel tulipan, principal investigator on the project
vanderbilt doctors decided to apply the procedure to huntington's patients based on experiments on rats
the team hopes to perform more of the operations, depending on how many volunteers there are, ross said today
vanderbilt is searching for identical twins suffering from huntington's who might participate in the pilot study, he said. because twins' genetic makeup would be exactly alike, researchers could study the effects of the surgery by performing the operation on one twin and allowing the disease to progress naturally in the other, he said
houser said there is evidence that a naturally occurring chemical in the brain, quinolinic acid, may cause the degeneration seen in huntington's
experiments demonstrated that the adrenal tissue transplant could protect against the damage caused by the acid, he said
in huntington's disease, as nerve cells in the brain die, patients experience involuntary spasms of the face and body, slurred speech and trouble walking
the patient, whose name was withheld at his family's request, was diagnosed as having huntington's five years ago. the disease has caused him trouble talking and performing ordinary tasks, forcing him to quit working three years ago. he has a wife but no children
between 10,000 and 20,000 americans have huntington's disease, and 500 to 1,000 new cases occur each year
a judge who feared a key witness would not show up for the trial of two people charged in the drug overdose of their baby has ordered the witness jailed, while the parents are free on bail
this is obscene,'' attorney patrick mcneal said of his client, bruce chavez, who was ordered jailed wednesday as a material witness by orange county superior court judge francisco briseno
this is the worst miscarriage of justice that i've seen in recent years. it's ludicrous.''
gilbert delgado, 24, and his wife, debbie, 22, are charged with murder, child endangerment and drug possession in the september 1986 death of their 2-month-old daughter, stephanie. delgado was free on $100,000 bail and his wife was free on $50,000 bail
the trial of the costa mesa couple is scheduled june 20. chavez, mrs. delgado's brother, could be held until he testifies or posts $100,000 bail
chavez had told police that his sister and brother-in-law used cocaine regularly and that he had seen the drug and paraphernalia near baby bottles and bottle nipples
but when he was subpoenaed to appear at a preliminary hearing, he took extreme measures to avoid an appearance, said deputy district attorney rick king. the measures included sleeping in his truck or in parks, refusing to go home and changing his appearance
it wasn't until more than a year after the baby's death that the delgados were arrested because initial coroner's reports attributed the death to infant death syndrome, police said. three months later, tests revealed she died from cocaine overdose and the delgados were arrested last october
a woman has been reunited with her kidnapped child 10 months after the state took custody of the baby without realizing his identity
alisha wetselline-rodriguez held her son for the first time in more than 14 months wednesday and was so excited she could barely speak
i understand he has to get used to me,'' ms. wetselline-rodriguez said as she cradled her son at the home of the boy's foster parents, john and diane noster, in mesquite
family court judge harold gaither jr. returned the boy, eric, to ms. wetselline-rodriguez's custody wednesday after reviewing evidence from blood tests and testimony by a department of human services caseworker
eric was only 18 days old when he was taken from his home in dallas on dec. 9, 1986
last may, edica flores of east dallas took him to st. matthews cathedral. she told a priest that a woman she met in a park nine days earlier had asked her to take care of the child for a week while the woman went to houston to seek work
the woman never returned and dallas county assistant district attorney beverly storey said efforts to find her have failed
the state took custody of the boy may 4, and it wasn't until christmas eve that a caseworker's casual glance at a mass-mailed missing children's flyer led to the discovery of the child's identity
the parents of a groom in a drought-stricken indian state demanded that the bride's family give them an unusual dowry: water
two barrels of water have been delivered every day to the house of the groom, prashant pandeya, since his recent marriage, the united news of india reported thursday
under the dowry pact, the bride's parents, who have a steady source of underground water, must keep up the supply until the next monsoon, the news agency reported
gujarat and 15 other states have been hit by drought, the worst in india in a century
the parents of a bride normally give clothes, jewelry, cash, furniture or electronic goods as dowry to the groom and his family. although outlawed in 1961, dowry still persists
a japan railways labor union leader was clubbed to death early thursday by a group of men who broke into his home in an attack believed linked to fighting among radical groups, a police official said
masaru matsushita, chairman of the regional headquarters of the jr east japan workers union, was attacked by seven or eight masked men while alseep in his home in takasaki, about 70 miles north of tokyo, the police official said
he was the sixth labor union official killed since september 1986 in attacks believed linked to feuding among rival radical groups over union cooperation in the conversion of the government-owned japanese national railways into a private corporation in april
matsushita, 45, died later at a hospital. his wife and three children were uninjured, said the official, speaking on condition of anonymity
police were searching for the attackers, who fled in a car after scattering needles on the road in front of matsushita's house
