republican pat robertson, meanwhile, sought to score some political points by repeatedly invoking jackson's name
i see some signs here of my friend jesse jackson,'' the former television evangelist told a predominantly black crowd at the orangeburg campus of south carolina state college. ``what jesse has been saying is what i'm saying to you.'' chips</head>
president reagan's sanctions against japanese electronics imports have halted computer chip ``dumping'' but have failed to boost sales of u.s. chips in japan, an industry group said thursday
the semiconductor industry association said that by the end of 1987, the u.s. share of the japanese chip market was only 10 percent, the historical level and up only slightly from the 9 percent share that existed when the sanctions were announced last april
the association urged the reagan administration to leave in place $165 million in remaining sanctions on japanese electronics imports and said ``other measures,'' including additional sanctions, might be sought
it also requested new high-level consultations with government officials on the subject of computer component trade
in a joint statement, the semiconductor association, representing chip makers, and the american electronics association, representing users, called on the government to help open japanese markets further and to insure a ``fair allocation'' of chips to the u.s. market
the issue of access to the japanese market remains problematic,'' the semiconductor group said in a review of compliance with a 1986 agreement between the united states and japan on semiconductors
under that agreement, ``the foreign market share expected in japan by the end of 1987 was 12.3 percent,'' the report said
the 1986 agreement called for japanese companies to stop marketing computer chips in the united states and other markets at artifically low prices, a practice known as dumping. u.s. chip makers claimed the japanse pricing pratices were driving them out of business
another part of the agreement called for japanese companies to buy more u.s.-made chips, with foreign-based industries' share in japan to rise to a level slightly above 20 percent by 1991
japan's alleged failure to comply with terms of the agreement caused reagan to impose $300 million in sanctions on imports of japanese televisions, computers and power tools last april
the administration, in two installments, lifted $135 million of those penalties, citing progress by japan in halting the dumping. but it left $165 million in place, claiming lack of progress in the ``market access'' area
thursday's assessment by the semiconductor association backed up government claims that all dumping had ceased in the aftermath of the sanctions, both in the united states and in foreign markets
computer chips, or semiconductors, are the tiny electrical circuits that are the building blocks of computers and many other electronic devices
they are called semiconductors because the material from which they are made _ usually silicon _ is a poor conductor of electricity in its normal state but allows electricity to pass freely with the application of small amounts of light, heat or voltage
as a result of the battering american companies took from low-cost japanese imports, many u.s. companies stopped manufacturing basic categories of computer chips altogther, leading to a shortage currently. today's testimony, and deletes now redundant last graf.</note>
pizzerias and pep rallies, the normal elements of teen life, are part of a bizarre murder case in which the defendant allegedly killed a classmate for a thrill, then showed the corpse to friends who stayed mum for weeks about the macabre secret in the snowy woods
the case, which began unfolding wednesday in norfolk superior court, features accusations that a 14-year-old plotted the crime for nearly a month, sorting through a list of possible victims
it includes young friends, now his chief accusers, who told a shocked courtroom of viewing a dead classmate only hours after a pre-thanksgiving pep rally, then going with the alleged killer for a snack at a shopping mall pizza parlor
he said he wanted to know what it was like to kill somebody,'' robbie peterson, 16, testified about defendant rod matthews
matthews, now 15, is being tried as an adult for the nov. 20, 1986, bludgeoning of 14-year-old shaun ouillette. according to the prosecutor, the thin, bespectacled defendant coldly killed his victim with a baseball bat, then calmly lied to police about his victim's whereabouts
he was deliberate in the plan and put it into effect efficiently and effectively,'' said assistant district attorney peter casey
matthews' defense attorney painted another picture of the youth, that of a mentally ill child from a troubled home whose use of the prescribed stimulant ritalin contributed to his murderous actions
in this case is the insidious element of mental illness with the overlying thread of ritalin,'' attorney john philip white told the jury
under cross-examination today by white, 16-year-old jonathan cash said matthews was known for volatile behavior and was fascinated by fire
cash, in his second day on the stand, also testified that he sent an anonymous letter to police about ouillette's body in december 1986 after going to see the body by himself late at night and suffering several nights of troubled sleep
according to the prosecutor and testimony by peterson and cash, matthews began talking about killing someone about halloween of 1986. they said he eventually decided to lure a victim to a wooded area known as ``the pits,'' then beat him with a baseball bat. peterson said matthews also planned to cut off his victim's legs ``and toss them.''
i said why? ... he said, `just for the heck of it,''' peterson testified
the teen-ager, testifying in a barely audible voice, told how matthews named several potential victims before settling on ouillette, an overweight high school freshman who had moved to the community south of boston a year earlier
he said he (ouillette) would be the least missed, that he didn't have that many friends,'' peterson testified
peterson said he had warned other potential victims not to go to matthews' home, but although he knew matthews planned to lure ouillette into the woods with the promise of fireworks, peterson said he only told ouillette, on the day he died, to have matthews bring the fireworks to school
after school that day, peterson said he was playing with a radio-controlled car when he saw matthews walking down the street with a baseball bat. when he asked if matthews had killed ouillette, peterson said the defendant hesitated before admitting to the killing. the talk of murder was interrupted for a snowball fight with neighborhood children, peterson testified
peterson said matthews then agreed to take him to the murder scene
the teen-ager testified that matthews explained how he walked in ouillette's footsteps in the snow, then clubbed him in the head with a bat as the victim set off bottle rockets
he said shaun fell down and said `help me' and rod hit him again.'' peterson said matthews told him how he cleaned the bloody bat in the snow
ouillette's mother, jeanne quinn, sobbed as she heard the description of her son's murder. matthews stared at the wooden table without expression while his mother, janice, bowed her head
under cross examination, peterson said he would have gone for help if he thought ouillette was still alive. he also acknowledged telling authorities early in the investigation that matthews told him ``everything just went blank and he went after shaun.''
peterson testified that a week later, he and cash viewed the body again with matthews after the school rally. as the three rode their bicycles from the murder site to the mall, matthews warned his friends not to talk
rod said not to say anything,'' peterson said. ``he said it could happen to us. he said, `you never know.'''  picks up 6th graf pvs, `presiding judge...' ^by laurie asseo</note>
gov. evan mecham drew criticism at his senate impeachment trial for sending all 30 senators a statement pleading his case, but gained promises of $100,000 in defense funds at a raucous rally
several senators said wednesday it was inappropriate for the first-term republican governor to contact them because they are serving as his judges and jury. mecham attorney thomas crowe contended there was nothing wrong with the governor's action
the trial resumed today with testimony by department of public safety lt. col. james chilcoat on an allegation that mecham tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official
chilcoat told about meetings that occurred before mecham was told about the alleged threat on nov. 13, 1987. ``it appeared to me that somebody was attempting to threaten a potential witness before a statewide grand jury,'' chilcoat testified
the senate today also threw out a subpoena of state grand jury records in connection with the alleged threat
in television interviews this morning, mecham said he hasn't broken any laws and will be found innocent if the senators listen to their constituents
the senate also was expected to consider whether to allow testimony intended to discredit dps director ralph milstead, the key witness on the death threat allegation
presiding judge frank x. gordon jr. said wednesday he would not allow testimony on allegations about milstead's sex life, but the senate could decide to overrule his decision. milstead has dismissed as ridiculous the allegation that he had an affair with an employee in 1982
mecham is accused of ordering milstead not to cooperate with the attorney general's investigation of the alleged threat
mecham's former chief bodyguard, dps lt. beau johnson, testified he considered the alleged threat to be a possible felony and that he fully informed mecham of the seriousness of the matter
in cross-examination, defense lawyer fred craft suggested the alleged threat by then-state official lee watkins against former top mecham aide donna carlson was a ``political matter,'' not a crime. but johnson testified, ``i did not really think of it in the political sense.''
at the time of the alleged threat, ms. carlson was scheduled to testify before a grand jury on a $350,000 campaign loan mecham is accused of concealing. watkins has denied he told state official peggy griffith that if her friend ms. carlson did not keep her mouth shut she might ``go on a long boat ride.''
craft might become a grand jury witness himself, some senators said, because he attended the meeting at which johnson has testified that he told mecham of the alleged threat. minority leader alan stephens, a democrat, said he believes senate rules allow a senator to ask that craft be called as a witness
stephens also said many senators were questioning whether it was appropriate that mecham sent senators a copy of a public statement he made saturday arguing that the senate trial be delayed until after his march 22 criminal trial on charges of concealing the $350,000 loan
democratic sen. jesus higuera displayed the statement on the senate floor and urged fellow lawmakers not to read it
i hope governor mecham understands the oath we have taken,'' higuera said. ``it's inappropriate to attempt to communicate with us.''
but crowe said, ``it's a political proceeding. ... the senators have received communications from many people pro and con. i don't see why the governor should be any different.''
mecham, who also faces a may 17 recall election, received a $50,000 check from supporters at a $20-a-person rally wednesday night in tempe. the rally by 4,000 people would raise more than $100,000 after expenses, said organizer john thomas
this morning, on nbc's ``today'' program, mecham said there is a ``groundswell'' of support for him because ``people are now seeing what's happened, that this is an attempt at a railroad job.''
mecham told abc's ``good morning america'' that now that the trial is being televised ``there's great reaction from the people.''
the governor also told ``cbs this morning'' that he wasn't attending the impeachment trial because he expected to return to office and ``was keeping track of some things. .... i don't want everything to get clear out of hand.''
among those in the wildly cheering crowd wednesday was a man in a train engineer's cap, signifying the ``railroading'' of the governor, and a woman in a kangaroo costume, symbolizing a ``kangaroo court.''
mecham, 63, was forced to step down pending the trial after the house impeached him feb. 5. in addition to the death threat and loan allegations, he is accused of misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by lending it to his auto dealership
a two-thirds senate vote is required to convict mecham, the first u.s. governor in nearly 60 years to face an impeachment trial
meanwhile, acting gov. rose mofford, a democrat, fired one of mecham's top aides, max hawkins, saying he had ``engaged in a number of personal attacks on state elected officials.'' hawkins said he was fired because he is a whistle-blower
hawkins has accused rep. jim skelly, chairman of the house impeachment committee, of interfering on a friend's behalf in a state racing commission investigation. skelly responded wednesday on the house floor that hawkins is ``a pathological liar, and it's not surprising because he works for governor mecham, and governor mecham wouldn't know the truth if it bit him in the nose.''
crowds thronged to holiday festivals across the country and 25 people were trampled to death during celebrations in two cities, it was reported thursday
at least 220 people were injured during the celebrations wednesday of the lantern festival, which falls 15 days after the lunar new year
eighteen people were crushed to death and 113 were injured in xining, capital of qinghai province, when 100,000 people who turned out to watch a lantern procession panicked, the official xinhua news agency said
seven people were trampled to death and another seven injured in lankao county, henan province, as a crowd of 20,000 dispersed after watching a fireworks show, xinhua said
the ministry of public security issued an emergency circular thursday calling attention to the problem of crowd control and safety
the lantern festival traditionally closes two weeks of celebrations that draw big crowds to admire the colorful and elaborate lanterns on display
american requests to europe to spend more for nato's defense will fail if the appeals are based on u.s. budget deficits, defense secretary frank carlucci said thursday
instead, the united states must convince the other 15 members of the north atlantic treaty organization to increase nato's budget because it is in the best interests of the alliance, carlucci said
as carlucci was speaking, president reagan and other nato leaders were winding up a two-day meeting of alliance leaders, their first such session since 1982
carlucci, speaking to the senate budget committee, echoed reagan's call for nato to go ahead with its previous plans to build a new generation of non-nuclear weapons to defend against a soviet attack
criticism of nato has long been popular on capitol hill among legislators of both parties, who complain that western european nations don't pay enough of the common defense bill
that criticism has increased in recent months, particularly because rising u.s. budget deficits have led congress to target the pentagon as a chief method of cutting federal spending
i think we need to approach a burden-sharing undertaking as an effort to strengthen the alliance, not as effort to solve our budget problems,'' said carlucci
if we go to the allies and say we've been obliged to cut our budget, therefore you have to make up the difference, i predict a lack of success,'' he said
on the other hand, if we're able to exercise leadership,'' nato may go along with previous plans to improve weapons, despite political opposition in europe, carlucci said
sen. lawton chiles, d-fla., chairman of the committee, noted that ``the lion's share of the load (borne by nato) has been carried by the united states.''
while u.s. wealth is less compared to the years after world war ii, he said ``the contribution we make to our alliances remains very high.''
and so it seems reasonable to ask how those with new wealth _ acquired in a world made more stable by american sacrifice _ might carry more of freedom's burden,'' he said
sen. james exon, d-neb., suggested that public criticism is the not the best way to win increased defense budgets in europe and suggested that ``quiet diplomacy'' be used
nato-bashing at this time is not the way to solve the problem,'' exon told the committee
the united states is becoming more and more reliant on its partners in nato, said adm. william crowe jr., chairman of the joint chiefs of staff
with respect to risks, the 1989 budget recognizes that a coalition strategy has become more _ not less _ important to the united states,'' he said
similarly, it (the budget) was structured to preserve and optimize u.s. contributions to the collective security of nato europe and our allies in asia,'' crowe said
we are not well positioned, however, to fill the gaps if, for one reason or another, some of the allies decide to reduce defense spending levels, shed defense commitments, or trim back on conventional force improvements,'' he said
the transportation department today proposed widespread drug testing covering tens of thousands of airline employees and said such tests are needed to ``maintain public confidence'' in the aviation system
the proposal, due to take effect in several months, would cover pilots, flight attendants and other workers involved with safety or security
aviation unions have strongly opposed widespread testing, agruing that no evidence has been produced showing drug use to be a significant problem among the nation's airlines
but transportation secretary jim burnley said that the tests are needed because ``all it takes is one person on drugs in one of these sensitive airline jobs to endanger the lives of hundreds of innocent people.''
the regulation, when it takes affect after a period of public comment, would require a broad range of testing including pre-employment tests, random tests and post-accident tests
employees covered by the proposal would include all flight crew members as well as aircraft dispatchers, mechanics and security workers at airport screening checkpoints
i firmly believe that drug testing, especially random testing, is absolutely critical in our efforts to create a drug-free aviation system for the american people,'' burnley told a news coinference
allan mcartor, administrator of the federal aviation administration, which will enforce the new regulations, said that the testing program, although controversial, is ``essential to maintaining public confidence in flying (by) ... insuring a drug-free aviation workforce.''
the airline pilots association and unions representing flight attendants have strongly opposed plans for widespread testing, arguing it is an invasion of privacy when no safety threat has been shown
congress has been debating legislation that would require drug testing in various forms of transportation, including aviation and railroads, but no legislation has been approved, partly because of strong labor opposition
for thousands of people fleeing communist vietnam, the fishing towns and beaches of thailand's east coast were once steppingstones to the west, easy to reach by boat
but with nearly 12,000 new arrivals last year, thailand has cracked down on the refugees. marine police and navy boats intercept and turn away the ``boat people,'' over protests by the united states, the united nations and western aid agencies
western officials are concerned at what they see as an erosion of the principle of ``first asylum,'' or temporary haven for refugees from indochina
authorities have quietly turned away some boat people for years. but in january, bangkok declared for the first time that its policy includes expulsions, and mounted a blockade of waters bordering cambodia. most of the vietnamese pay for passage on smugglers' boats from cambodia
the thais say the vietnamese are not fleeing political persecution, but are seeking better economic conditions. they said the migrants add to the country's already sizable burden of illegal aliens and threaten national security
most are not refugees. the war ended 13 years ago,'' said somporn klinpongsa, the deputy permanent secretary of the interior ministry. he referred to the 1975 communist victory over the u.s.-backed south vietnam government
before they came in on small boats. now we try to stop them,'' somporn said as he pointed to waters off this district in trat province where many vietnamese attempt to land. he was guiding foreign diplomats on a recent marine police boat tour of the coast
somporn claimed 30,000 ``economic migrants'' were waiting at cambodia's major seaport, kompongsom, to take boats into thailand
u.s. ambassador to thailand william a. brown told a congressional hearing in washington last week that a thai fishing vessel reportedly rammed a boat carrying vietnamese, resulting in drownings
western aid officials said a number of vietnamese drowned when smugglers trying to evade the blockade forced them to swim to islands off trat. at least two people died of illness as more than 500 vietnamese on the islands for a while had no regular source of food, water and medical care. there is concern that others may be stranded, unknown to authorities
nearly a million indochinese have fled to thailand since the communist takeovers in 1975, and in recent years the thais have bitterly complained that the west has reneged on pledges to resettle them
according to the office of the united nations high commissioner for refugees, about 117,000 vietnamese, laotians and cambodians remained in thai refugee camps at the end of may 1987
as of january, there were 16,040 vietnamese in camps in thailand
western nations, meanwhile, resettled 5,275 vietnamese in 1987. the numbers dropped from a high of 26,574 in 1981 to a low of 3,391 in 1982, the office said
the overall number of indochinese resettled in 1986 was 26,804, about 4,400 fewer than in 1985
the thai government toughened policies on laotian and cambodian migrants last year
it clamped down on the vietnamese after almost 12,000 arrived in 1987, triple the number the previous year, and reports surfaced that local officials in trat were involved in the smuggling. the governor and provincial police superintendant were among those who have since been transferred
most vietnamese refugees travel overland to cambodia. there, with the help of a network of smugglers, they board chartered fishing boats that try to slip into trat at night. the route is much shorter and safer than the traditional passage across the gulf of thailand to the southern coast
electronics, vehicle spare parts and strategic contraband regularly are smuggled to cambodia and vietnam aboard the boats
somporn said boats that are intercepted are given fuel, food and medicine and told to turn back out to sea
at first, authorities also towed back out to sea hundreds of vietnamese who had already made it to shore. somporn said such people now can stay, but will no longer be sent to phanat nikhom, a camp near bangkok where western countries interview indochinese for resettlement
instead, they go to camps near the cambodian border where chances of resettlement are slight and they risk danger from the war between cambodian guerrillas and vietnamese troops occupying the country
although somporn claims most of the refugees fled for economic reasons, 66 percent of the vietnamese who arrived in thailand last year told international aid workers they were persecuted because they were ethnic chinese or had spent time in political ``re-education'' camps
less than 2 percent cited economic reasons for leaving their homeland. many vietnamese detained at the khlong yai police station said they fled to rejoin relatives in the united states
reporters were able to interview them briefly only during the diplomats' visit. authorities have limited access to the vietnamese by journalists and aid workers
authorities charged a 21-year-old man today in the shooting of four teen-agers fired on after a high school basketball game
nathan ward of north chicago was charged with aggravated battery and armed violence, deputy police chief terry house said
the shooting occurred late wednesday outside waukegan east high school after a regional semifinal basketball game between waukegan east and north chicago high school. waukegan east won, 77-56
investigators had not established a motive for the shooting, but had ruled out involvement with drugs, gangs and the game, house said
investigators recovered a .38-caliber handgun, he said, and a second person was being sought for questioning
two teen-agers injured in the shooting were in satisfactory condition at victory memorial hospital with arm wounds. two others were treated at the scene and sent home, police said
frank young, principal of waukegan east, said the shooting occurred 30 minutes after the game, and most of the estimated 2,000 fans had left
larry tenpas, a waukegan alderman and teacher at waukegan east, said he saw a man fire shots at the students who were milling around the school. vote. may stand; a vote is unlikely before 5 p.m. est, and that timetable could slip.</note>
house speaker jim wright said today a democratic plan for giving purely ``humanitarian'' aid to nicaragua's contra rebels represents a chance for the united states to take a positive role in its relations with central america
it's a battle for peace in nicaragua and for a constructive role for the united states in central america, as opposed to a destructive role,'' wright, d-texas, said of a showdown vote over rival democratic and republican aid plans set for later in the day
but president reagan, in a letter to house republicans sent while he was attending a meeting of western allies in brussels, belgium, said wright's plan ``does not meet the essential criteria'' of keeping the contras alive as a fighting force capable of putting military pressure on the leftist sandinista regime
today could represent a watershed in our policies toward central america,'' reagan wrote. ``one avenue will lead to rapid debilitation of the resistance and further encouragement of sandinista intransigence. the other could keep alive prospects for democracy and meaningful talks toward peace
as with virtually all past votes on u.s. aid for the contras, the showdown late today promised to be close. but democratic vote-counters said they believed they would win with at least as wide a margin as a month ago, when the house defeated a reagan aid package 219 to 211
on an early procedural vote to adopt rules for floor debate, democrats prevailed, 225 to 187. but leaders cautioned that the ballot was not a true test of whether the democratic aid package would pass
they also said they believed a move by nicaraguan president daniel ortega to dismiss cardinal miguel obando y bravo as mediator in cease-fire talks with the contras and propose direct talks in nicaragua would have little effect on the outcome
in brussels, reagan said during a picture-taking session that ``we have always believed there should be direct talks between the people of nicaragua who want freedom and have been called contras because of that, and the present government.''
but of the move to dismiss the cardinal as an intermediary, reagan said: ``i don't understand that at all.''
house republicans, angry over what they considered an unfair procedure under which the bill was being brought up, vowed not to go away quietly
we're going to fight them on everything,'' said rep. mickey edwards, r-okla., who has led the fight for contra aid in the house. ``it's gotten a lot of republicans mad.''
the $30.5 million democratic proposal called for about $16 million in food, clothing, medicine and shelter for the anti-sandinista rebels, and another $14 million to set up a fund to help children injured in the seven-year nicaraguan civil war
democrats were working to keep the support of moderate party members who helped design the package, and keep to a minimum defections by members of the party's left wing, most of whom never have voted for aid to the rebels in any form
party leaders argued that passage of this purely ``humanitarian'' aid bill would lessen chances that the administration could come back to congress soon with a request for weapons and ammunition to sustain the guerrilla war
a republican alternative contained more money _ about $36 million _ and placed fewer restrictions on the way the contras could use the aid. but it appeared unlikely the gop version would come to a vote because of democratic-designed rules that called for their package to come up first
edwards said the key difference between the two bills was that the democrats' version offered no guarantees of quick consideration of a future reagan administration request for military aid for the rebels. the gop package would permit reagan to ask for such aid any time after april 15, and would require expedited congressional action
unless we put expedited procedures in the bill, the contras get nothing and the sandinistas get no threat. that really is the bottom-line issue,'' he said
and edwards noted that the democratic bill would turn over responsibility for delivery of the ``humanitarian'' supplies to the pentagon, rather than the existing cia-run supply network. even if the pentagon retained the private contractors now used by the cia to make supply flights, u.s. military personnel would have to be present in the region to oversee them, he said
the republican alternative would leave the delivery of supplies in the hands of the cia
wright on wednesday defended the procedure under which the two bills were being brought to the floor, saying the republicans had had their chance for a vote a month ago, when the house defeated reagan's last aid request
if ours were not offered (under the democrats' procedure), many of our members argued we might never get to vote on our plan,'' wright said. ``i don't think it's unfair to them.''
at least 11 people were reported killed and hundreds injured thursday in violence related to parliamentary elections, which the opposition denounced as fraudulent and a failure
early results showed president hussain muhammad ershad's jatiya party with the lead in 53 of the 282 constituencies where ballots were cast. eighteen of his candidates had already been declared elected to parliament for lack of opposition candidates
initial returns from nine other constituencies showed minor opposition parties leading. major opposition parties boycotted the vote
newspapers, quoting reliable sources, said 11 people were killed in confrontations during the day between supporters of rival candidates
home minister abdul matin said only five people died _ four in dhaka and one in nearby manikganj. he said 80 were injured and 55 were hospitalized
the opposition's call for a general strike shut down most of the capital
there was no turnout, there was no election,'' said sheik hasina, leader of the main opposition awami league. ``perhaps the so-called candidates voted.''
but matin told reporters that on the basis of 12 voting centers he visited in dhaka, he estimated voter to be 50 percent of the 47.8 million eligible to cast ballots
reporters who went to a dozen polling stations in and around the capital said a reasonable turnout was apparent at only three. two had been shut down by violence by midmorning
at several stations, election officials and even workers for ershad's jatiya party admitted that ballot boxes were stuffed and voter turnout exaggerated
ms. hasina vowed the opposition camp of 21 parties would keep up the campaign it began in november to oust ershad as president
ershad scheduled thursday's elections after he dissolved parliament last december, 3{ years ahead of schedule. the move was aimed at working out a compromise with his foes, but they demanded instead that ershad step down and said elections held under him wouldn't be fair
the governing jatiya party won 152 seats in the last parliamentary elections in 1986, and the awami league won 102 of the 330 seats. small parties held the rest
ershad, speaking to reporters after casting his ballot in dhaka, said he thought this election would end the violence
after this, things certainly will improve,'' he said
ershad said he had no plans for another election soon. ``the parliament is elected for five years by the people ... i expect it to serve for five years.''
ms. hasina maintained that bangladeshis had rejected the election
the whole nation has sided with us,'' hasina said. ``that is our achievement.''
at savar, 12 miles north of dhaka, a jatiya worker named khalil mahmood said ballots were fraudulently stamped for jatiya and also for other parties to make the rigging less obvious
we finished by 11 a.m. and we even gave some votes to other candidates,'' he said
matin said he had no reports of vote rigging. he said voting was suspended at 170 of the 22,393 polling booths because of violence or election officials' failure to arrive to man the stations
matin noted that there had been 21 deaths in the 1986 parliamentary election and said of thursday's vote: ``it's a successful and peaceful election.''
in chittagong, bangladesh's second largest city, reporters quoted police and hospital sources as saying more than 100 people were injured in violence
bob dole is looking beyond next week's big round of southern primaries and hoping his candidacy can get beyond it too
when all is said and done,'' the republican presidential hopeful said at a florida rally, ``this is probably going to go all the way to california now.''
if the race for the republican presidential nomination doesn't prove as long as he suggests, going on until the last round of primaries in early june, dole probably won't be the nominee
the southern primaries _ south carolina on saturday and the rest of the region on super tuesday _ aren't going to get him there. george bush leads dole by as much as 3-to-1 in polls of the south
while dole figures to run better than that in the popular vote, the republicans' delegate allotment system means the real score in delegates may be that bad or worse. and pat robertson is a gop wild card that could siphone off more delegates
it's a struggle,'' said dole press secretary dale tate. ``but i don't think anybody here thinks we won't survive. it's going to be a long time to new orleans'' and the republican convention
but with 712 gop delegates at stake that day, bush has the potential to go a long way toward the 1,139 delegates needed to nominate
dole's problem is how to keep bush from running up such a collection of victories on tuesday that he is unstoppable when the race turns to the next round of big industrial states
the grim potential of super tuesday for dole heightens the importance of the next primary, illinois on march 15
dole forces figure they must be able to bounce back there
i think if dole doesn't win illinois, it's just about over,'' said one dole campaign official, speaking only on condition of anonymity
facing that reality, dole is attacking bush with a broad brush as a man with no more of a record than the embarrassment of involvement in the sale of arms to iran for hostages
but he also is carefully choosing his spots in the states and congressional districts where he has a chance of success
we're going to win some states here,'' dole pollster richard wirthlin said in atlanta last weekend. ``we're doing well in areas that can be typified as the new south
we're going to be very competitive in four or five states,'' wirthlin said
dole forces see their best chances among the 14 southern and border states voting tuesday to be in missouri, with 47 delegates at stake, oklahoma, with 36, and north carolina, with 54
they would like to score some surprises in alabama, arkansas, and in certain portions of florida and georgia
among the states outside the south voting on tuesday, they are focusing on rhode island, with 21 delegates, and washington state, where the 41 delegates aren't allocated by the primary but where a victory would give dole something to talk about
north carolina is the state where dole's wife elizabeth is from and where together they have appeared often over the years. it is also a state where textiles is a major industry, and dole has been attacking the vice president's opposition to limits on foreign textile imports
dole is also on the air in south carolina, missouri, oklahoma and arkansas, and has small amounts of tv commercials on in rhode island and florida
doe has injected anew the iran-contra affair into the campaign with another ad that says: ``dole opposed selling arms to iran. bush supported the arms for hostages deal.''
part of dole's frustration is that bush has been able to appear the rightful heir to president reagan's conservative legacy in the south, where reagan has always been strong. dole seeks to tarnish bush, while straining to avoid seeming to attack reagan, which he knows would backfire
and he has been frustrated that bush's support in the region, often described as broad but thin, has not proven brittle
we know bush has a big lead in the south,'' dole said. ``for some reason, his people believe he's from the south or something.''
political scorekeepers face a complex challenge next tuesday as they try to track who wins roughly one-third of the delegates to the democratic and republican national conventions
super tuesday's chain of events, stretching from the u.s. atlantic coast almost to the international date line in the pacific ocean, relies on dozens of complicated and often confusing rules
in some cases, the process is so tangled that it's hard to agree even on how many delegates are involved
for example, the republicans are holding 16 or 17 events on super tuesday, and 712, 753 or 803 delegates are involved. all of those figures are correct, depending on how the question is phrased
the reason for the discrepancies is some of the gop events count, some don't and others can't be sorted out until later
sixteen of the republican events will have some effect on how national convention delegates will be divided, but only fifteen of those yield results that can be calculated immediately into national delegate totals. that leaves the grand totals at 16 states yielding 712 national convention delegates
the democrats aren't a lot easier to figure out. the 21 states and territories holding super tuesday events have 1,455 delegates. but 148 of them are a special type of delegate not affected by what happens in the primaries or caucuses. that leaves 1,307 democratic delegates at stake on march 8
to complicate matters further, minnesota's democrats, who held their caucuses on feb. 23, are releasing the results on march 8. this is an outgrowth of a convoluted compromise between the state and national parties to allow minnesota to hold caucuses two weeks earlier than allowed by the rules without breaking the rules. these results will govern who wins 78 of the state's national convention delegates
in both parties, a state's national convention delegates are chosen both on the basis of how much support a presidential candidate has in each congressional district and how much support the candidate commands statewide
democrats require that a presidential candidate reaches a certain level of support to be eligible for winning delegates. each candidate must receive at least 15 percent of the vote in any given congressional district or statewide
the corresponding republican requirements vary from state to state
here is a state-by-state breakdown of how the delegates will be calculated from super tuesday's events:
_ alabama: people running for 37 seats as delegates to the democratic national convention will be listed on the ballot in the primary along with the presidential candidate they support. another 19 democratic delegates will be picked later, but the results of the primary govern how they will be awarded to presidential candidates. the republicans, too, list their delegates on the ballot _ three in each of seven congressional district and 17 statewide. these are awarded on a winner-take-all basis in each district and statewide. total: 56 democrats, 38 republicans
_ american samoa: the democrats gather in one spot and pick six people who will each cast one-half vote at the national convention. the republican party does not provide for a delegation from american samoa. super tuesday total: 3 democrats, 0 republicans
_ arkansas: the democrats vote in the primary for presidential candidates, and delegates will be awarded in proportion to these results. the republicans, too, award their national convention delegates in proportion to the primary results. super tuesday total: 38 democrats, 27 republicans
_ florida: in each of the state's 19 congressional districts, the presidential candidate receiving the most votes in the primary gets one delegate as a bonus, while the remaining delegates are divided in proportion to the vote. statewide, another 47 delegates will be awarded in prortion to the overall vote. the republicans use a somewhat simpler method: the winner in each congressional district gets all of the delegates from that district, and the winner statewide receives all 18 of the at-large delegates. super tuesday total: 136 democrats, 82 republicans
_ georgia: the democrats use rules similar to those in florida: a ``bonus delegate'' awarded to the winner in each congressional district, the rest allocated proportionally. the republicans also use the same kind of rules as the florida gop: winner-take-all by congressional district and statewide. super tuesday total: 77 democrats, 48 republicans
_ hawaii: the democrats hold precinct caucuses to elect delegates to the state convention. the people attending the caucuses will register their presidential preference, and the national convention delegates will be awarded to presidential candidates in proportion to those results. hawaii's republicans held their precinct caucuses last month. however, in this as well as other gop caucus systems, the presidential preferences of the people at the first step of the process do not in any formal way bind those who attend the following steps. in addition, the conventions and caucuses later in the process need not follow any uniform set of rules. thus, the number of national convention delegates won by each presidential candidate cannot be figured with precision based only on the results of the first step. super tuesday total: 20 democrats, 0 republicans
_ idaho: the democrats hold caucuses similar to those in hawaii, picking delegates to the state convention in june, when the national convention delegates will finally be selected. the allocation of those delegates among the presidential candidates will be governed by the support registered by those attending the march 8 caucuses. idaho republicans hold a primary on may 24. super tuesday total: 18 democrats, 0 republicans
_ kentucky: both the democrats and republicans divide their national convention delegates among the presidential candidates in proportion to the results of the primary. super tuesday total: 55 democrats, 38 republicans
_ louisiana: the democrats divide their delegates in proportion to the results of the primary. the republicans award 24 of their delegates on a winner-take-all basis in each of the state's eight congressional districts. the remaining 17 gop delegates from louisiana are awarded in proportion to the results of the primary statewide. super tuesday total: 63 democrats, 41 republicans
_ maryland: the democrats elect 44 delegates listed on the ballot by congressional districts and award another 23 delegates in proportion to the statewide results of the primary. the republicans award their delegates on a winner-take-all basis by congressional district and statewide. super tuesday total: 67 democrats, 41 republicans
_ massachusetts: the democrats use a system similar to that of georgia and florida, awarding a ``bonus delegate'' to the presidential candidate who wins in each congressional district and dividing the rest proportionally. the republicans award their delegates in proportion to the results of the primary. super tuesday total: 98 democrats, 52 republicans
_ mississippi: the democrats award their delegates in proportion to the results of the primary, both by congressional district and statewide. the republicans divide their statewide delegates proportionally, while those from congressional districts are awarded on a winner-take-all basis. super tuesday total: 40 democrats, 31 republicans
_ missouri: the democrats award their national convention delegates in proportion to the results of the primary, with a ``bonus delegate'' given in each of the state's nine congressional districts to the presidential candidate carrying that district. gop presidential candidates win delegates in proportion to the results of the primary. super tuesday total: 77 democrats, 47 republicans
_ nevada: democrats meet in precinct caucuses to choose delegates to the county conventions to pick delegates to the state convention where the delegates to the national convention will be selected
participants at each level of the process are required to declare whom they support for president, and this governs how the national convention delegates are to be divided among the presidential candidates. the republicans had their precinct caucuses last month, but the final outcome will not be known until the national convention delegates are chosen in april. super tuesday total: 16 democrats, 0 republicans
_ north carolina: democrats use a ``bonus delegate'' system in the congressional districts and award the 29 at-large delegates in proportion to the statewide primary vote. the republican delegates are awarded to presidential candidates in proportion to the primary vote. super tuesday total: 82 democrats, 54 republicans
_ oklahoma: the democrats allocate their delegates in proportion to the results of the primary. the republicans award their delegates, winner-take-all, by congressional district and statewide. super tuesday total: 46 democrats, 36 republicans
_ rhode island: democratic and republican presidential candidates win delegates in proportion to how well they do in the primary. super tuesday total: 22 democrats, 21 republicans
_ tennessee: the democrats divide their delegates proportionally based on the results of the primary. the republicans elect 33 of their delegates directly from the ballot by congressional district and award another dozen based on the statewide vote. super tuesday total: 70 democrats, 45 republicans
_ texas: the results of the primary by congressional district govern the proportional allocation of 119 of the democratic delegates from texas, but there's a twist in how the remaining 64 delegates statewide are picked. in texas, democrats who vote in the primary can also take part in precinct party caucuses held after the polls close. in many cases, this would require people to make two trips to the polls in one day. the at-large delegates will be awarded to presidential candidates based on the preferences of the people attending the caucuses. the republicans award their delegates on a winner-take-all basis by congressional district and statewide. super tuesday total: 183 democrats, 111 republicans
_ virginia: democrats award their delegates in proportion to the results of the primary. republicans also are holding a primary, but its results have no effect at all on who eventually wins the delegates. that will be handled through a system of caucuses and conventions concluding in may and june. super tuesday total: 75 democrats, 0 republicans
_ washington: the democrats hold precinct caucuses similar to those in nevada, and allocation of national convention delegates will reflect the presidential preferences of the participants. republicans also are holding precinct caucuses and will cast votes for presidential candidates in a non-binding straw poll. however, just as in other gop caucus states the delegate allocation cannot be calculated until the delegates themselves are chosen later in the season. super tuesday total: 65 democrats, 0 republicans. to third organization.</note>
leaders of the assemblies of god, who are at odds with their louisiana district over the discipline of evangelist jimmy swaggart, said today the denomination's policy-making body will have the final say
a statement from the headquarters of the pentecostal denomination said the executive presbytery of the church's general council has called a special meeting of the general presbytery for march 28 ``to make decisions regarding matters relating to evangelist jimmy swaggart.''
the 250-member general presbytery is the policy-making body for the church when the general council is not in session, and serves as a court of appeals in matters relating to ministerial credentials,'' the statement said. ``its decisions are final.''
the next regularly scheduled meeting of the 13-member executive presbytery is march 29
swaggart, in a tearful admission at his headquarters in baton rouge, la., a week ago sunday, acknowledged he was guilty of unspecified sin, begging forgiveness. he was reportedly caught with a prostitute at a new orleans area motel by rival evangelist marvin gorman last october
swaggart heads a ministry based in baton rouge that takes in nearly $150 million a year to support broadcasts in almost 150 countries and a bible college
the louisiana district presbyters of the assemblies of god, the nation's largest pentecostal denomination, recommended that swaggart be suspended from the pulpit for three months. but after complaints that that was too lenient, the executive presbyters of the springfield-based church referred the matter back to the district level for reconsideration
on monday, the district leaders decided to stand by their recommendation
the rev. gerald lewis, a member of the church's louisiana district council, was quoted by the news-leader in springfield today as saying the council decided monday to stand by its original recommendation to suspend swaggart from the pulpit for three months after ``there was an interpretation'' of a message received in tongues
pentecostals believe in tangible manifestations of the holy spirit such as speaking in ``unknown tongues.''
i don't think there was a person on the board that was not weeping,'' said lewis, a cousin of swaggart, referring to the nine-hour council meeting
juleen turnage, spokeswoman for the assemblies of god, said today that the church would have no further statements on swaggart until after the general presbytery meets
in new orleans later today, a $90 million lawsuit filed against swaggart and others by gorman, who claims swaggart defamed him with charges of adultery, is scheduled for a hearing on gorman's appeal of the dismissal of the suit
swaggart has been unavailable for comment this week, and there was no indication he would appear in public for the court hearing
a state judge threw out gorman's suit last summer, saying it was a religious dispute. gorman turned to a state appeals court, which agreed to hear arguments
gorman admitted ``an immoral act'' with a woman in 1979, but denied other affairs as claimed by swaggart. gorman resigned as minister of the first assembly of god church of new orleans. he continues to lead marvin gorman ministries at his television studio
he pronounces y'all as two distinct words, but george bush speaks the language of the south in a way that overcomes his new england accent. it can be summed up in two other words: ronald reagan
with the super tuesday primaries and caucuses offering 712 delegates, a majority of them in the south, polls indicate bush could end the day with a big lead in the race for the republican presidential nomination
and during a hectic campaign schedule this week, including 10 stops in five southern states tuesday and wednesday, bush exuded confidence as he predicted tuesday's winner will be the next president
he's in a very upbeat mood,'' said bush spokesman peter teeley. ``when you consider what we went through the last four or five days of new hampshire. ...''
teeley meant a period when it seemed sen. bob dole might follow his iowa victory by beating bush in the new hampshire primary. bush's feb. 16 victory changed all that, giving him momentum to go with his strong organization as he headed south
and he hoped to benefit from the president's popularity
throughout his southern swing this week, bush referred to ``the reagan-bush administration'' and said he was the man who could build upon ``the superb foundation of the reagan revolution.'' he criticized other candidates for differing with the president on some issues and for criticizing bush as a yes man
if the price of winning this nomination is to turn my back in some way on ronald reagan, then i'm not willing to pay that price,'' bush said in tampa
you mississippians also know that loyalty is a strength,'' bush told shipyard workers in pascagoula, miss
lanny griffith, bush's southern campaign coordinator from corinth, miss., said rivals' attacks on bush were unlikely to succeed in the south
people here think of george bush as reagan's partner, a war hero, the former cia director, and as a texan,'' griffith said. ``they don't pay attention to that d.c.-new york type of stuff. `doonesbury' does not shape the conventional wisdom here.''
bush has important advantages in the two largest super tuesday states, texas and florida. he made his mark in the texas oil business and entered politics there
in florida, he has the support of gov. bob martinez, who appointed bush's son, jeb, as florida's secretary of commerce. the younger bush formerly headed the dade county republican party. bush's mother lives in palm beach, and the vice president has visited florida often, both for personal reasons and on such official business as his role heading the south florida task force on drugs
as he campaigned energetically this week, bush said dole-leaning new hampshire polls preceding bush's victory there had taught him a lesson
you have to continue to fight like you're behind,'' bush said. ``so you don't let up, you don't go home, and you stay out of the mud.''
bush said he was waging a positive campaign on a ``higher plain,'' while making indirect jabs at his opponents by calling himself the most stable and most mature candidate
the bush campaign's officials said they had been outspent in much of the south but were ready for a final television blitz
i believe that you should hold back everything you can to spend as late as possible,'' said southern coordinator griffith
bush's late campaigning was concentrated on pockets in the south where it seemed former television evangelist pat robertson had strong grass-roots support or where dole was most active
in the deep south states, bush expected to capitalize on the administration's stand for strong defense and tough foreign policy
he often sprinkled in references to his navy world war ii combat experience. in case anyone missed them, he was greeted upon arrival in tampa with a grumman avenger plane, like the one he flew. bush put on a flight jacket and climbed into the cockpit for the cameras
his strong organization and the advantage of secret service-aided logistics helped allow bush to pack many appearances into his swing _ driving a paving machine at a north miami beach construction site, playing shuffleboard with retirees in boca raton, fla., serving catfish in biloxi and jambalaya in baton rouge, la
the dean of american conservatives, 1964 presidential nominee barry goldwater, campaigned with him in florida and filmed an endorsement commercial. former navy secretary john lehman also campaigned with bush in the south. activities today. picks up 5th graf, `sarah wore...</note>
the duke and duchess of york spent a jovial day among the arts and artists, joking with conductor andre previn following a concert by the los angeles philharmonic orchestra and laughing with artist david hockney
prince andrew and his wife, sarah, spent wednesday evening at the music center listening to the two-hour concert that included a work by their countryman, ralph vaughan williams
the duke and duchess, both 28, were scheduled to visit the aircraft carrier uss nimitz today, the seventh day of their 10-day visit as patrons of the uk@la '88 arts festival
the nuclear-powered aircraft carrier sailed from san diego at 7 a.m. for the noon rendezvous
the navy planned a fly-by of a-7 jets breaking the sound barrier, demonstrations of catapault launches and recovery of aircraft and a lunch that included asparagus soup, marinated mushrooms, chicken salad and cherries jubilee
the prince, who is a royal navy officer and helicopter pilot who saw action in britain's falkland islands war, was to be catapaulted from the carrier's deck aboard an s-3a viking anti-submarine warfare jet
on wednesday, the duchess, who is expecting her first child in august, was given a bouquet of lavendar roses sporting a white stork and balloon that read ``special delivery'' when she arrived for the concert
sarah wore a calf-length jade-green gown, contrasting with her red hair pulled to the side with a flower hair ornament
afterward, the royal couple chatted with previn and his wife, heather. the conversation ended in laughter, as they joked about the fierce facial expressions conductors sometimes wear
so far, the couple known popularly as andy and fergie have hobnobbed with hollywood celebrities and local business and political leaders and taken a backstage look at a movie special-effects studio
earlier in the day, andrew greeted american investors for a five-hour cruise aboard her majesty's yacht britannia by quipping, ``please don't sink her when you go to sea. bon voyage.''
andrew also expressed his appreciation for wednesday's sunny skies, which followed days of rain during their visit
we thank you for the weather, for as you know, when the queen and the royal family comes to pay a visit the weather gets dreadful,'' andrew said
to the delight of americans, the duchess dropped her regal composure a few hours later outside the los angeles county museum of art
check these out!'' she called out, flouncing about to show the crowds her hair tied in a loose ponytail and held by clips shaped like the union jack and the stars and stripes
sarah wore a purple knee-length skirt and matching blazer with tan shoes to wednesday's museum visit. the prince wore a gray suit, pale green shirt and dark green tie
at the museum, hockney met them beneath two of his works, the giant paintings ``les mamille,'' a depiction of a harbor done for an opera set, and ``a walk around the courtyard, acatlan.''
hockney and museum officials led the couple through the retrospective show, which includes 150 paintings, 60 drawings and 30 photographs
gunmen burst into the home of a security guard and his wife, then used them as hostages in a ``meticulously planned raid'' to steal up to $1.7 million from an armored van, according to scotland yard and a published report
the robbery began tuesday night when two men with pistols took a security express guard and his wife hostage at their southeastern london home, said a scotland yard spokeswoman
a third man arrived at the house wednesday morning and drove the woman away, she said, speaking anonymously in keeping with british custom
the two remaining robbers drove the guard to work in his own car and ordered him to drive his money-laden van to a south london location, the spokeswoman said
the guard explained his predicament to two other guards in the van and they drove to the prearranged meeting point, she said
two men on motorcycles met the van and ordered the guards to drive to a nearby soccer field, she said. the guards were ordered to lie beneath stands in the stadium along with three gardeners who had seen one of the robbers, she said
minutes later they were joined by the guard's wife and held at gunpoint until the van's cash was loaded onto another vehicle and the robbers escaped, the spokeswoman said
this was a very meticulously planned raid. the raiders had obviously been following the movements of the guard for many days and knew where to find him,'' one of her male colleagues at scotland yard added later
police refused to say how much cash was taken, but the times of london on thursday quoted unidentified police sources as saying the gang got away with between $1.32 million and $1.76 million
the reagan administration's decision not to adjust the 1990 national census to allow for people who are overlooked was ``shameful'' and blatantly political, a new york congressman charged thursday
the action was not based ``on fairminded concern about accurate statistics; it's a raw exercise of partisan politics,'' rep. charles e. schumer charged at a hearing of the house post office and civil service census subcommittee
schumer and reps. mervyn m. dymally of california and robert garcia of new york all raised concern about the decision not to adjust, which was announced last october by the commerce department, parent agency of the census. all three are democrats
commerce undersecretary robert ortner denied that it was a political decision, however, contending that statisticians disagree on whether there is an accurate method of making adjustments
i don't think it would make the problem any better if we were to devise an elaborate mathematical system to make up new numbers,'' ortner commented
the focus of the problem is the fact that all 435 seats in the house of representatives and billions of dollars in state and federal money are distributed on the basis of the figures collected every 10 years by the census bureau
no head count can be perfect in a nation the size of the united states, with the current population estimated at more than 244 million people. but concern centers on studies that show that the number of people missed is much higher among minorities
that results in such groups as blacks and hispanics getting less economic and political clout, and has led to calls for an adjustment of census figures to compensate for this problem
census statisticians have been working on finding a way to adjust the figures, but disagreement exists as to whether this can be done in an accurate fashion
thus, ortner announced last fall that no adjustment would be made in 1990, stating that the time for experimenting was over and the agency had go get on with the task of taking the census
that drew a barrage of criticism, however, from groups contending that those most often missed are urban minorities, usually democrats, and that the decision not to adjust was a political action to boost the power of conservatives and republicans
the administration's position is shameful. it's shameful because the administration's problem with adjusting census figures is not statisatical, it's political,'' schumer said
that's absolutely untrue,'' responded ortner. he said the department simply wanted to go out and conduct the best actual count possible, adding that cuts in post-census surveys which might have been used to make later adjustments were designed to save money
dymally commented that he found it interesting that the decision not to make an adjustment was made by commerce department officials just 10 days after he proposed a bill to require an adjustment
the decision should have been left up to xensus statisticians rather than being made by commerce officials, he added
schumer pointed out that barbara bailar, a census official who had been in charge of developing adjustment methods, resigned from the agency charging that the decision was political rather than technical
bailar said in her prepared testimony that while opinion was divided in the bureau, she believed that the census figures could be accurately adjusted using a survey of residents on specific areas to estimate the undercount
but ortner reiterated that statisticians continue to disagree on the matter and presented a letter from about a dozen academic popualation experts opposed to making adjustments in the census counts
the democratic-controlled house labor standards subcommittee voted along party lines thursday to increase the minimum wage from $3.35 to $4.65 an hour over the next three years
the 6-3 vote came after democrats defeated republican amendments designed to either water down or kill the measure, which would raise the minimum wage 50 cents an hour on jan. 1, 1989 and 40 cents an hour each of the following years
however, the subcommittee refused, 7-2, to tie future increases to inflation, a proposal once wanted by organized labor but which it abandoned in an effort to preserve the $4.65-an-hour figure
rep. timothy j. penny, d-minn., who proposed the elimination of the indexing of future increases, said he was ``concerned about something like this being on automatic pilot. congress should review an future increases.'' he also said automatic increases in the minimum wage would could drive up salaries of workers who make higher than the minimum, leading to inflation
rep. augustus f. hawkins, d-calif., chairman of the full house labor and education committee, voted against the penny amendment, saying it ``is ill-timed, unwarranted and not justified by the facts. there is no indication that it leads to inflation. wages lag behind inflation and will always do as long as they are based on past experience.''
hawkins said the full committee would take up the measure next thursday
a similar bill has been introduced in the senate by sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., chairman of the labor and human resources committee. that panel has held hearings on the proposal but has not scheduled further action on it
the house subcommittee rejected, 6-3, a substitute measure proposed by rep. thomas e. petri, r-wis., that would have raised the minimum wage to $4 an hour over the next three years
rep. james m. jeffords, r-vt., offered an amendment to increase the ``tip credit'' for restaurant workers, it also lost, 6-3, after rep. tommy f. robinson, d-ark., said he planned to introduce a similar bill when the full committee meets next week and had worked out a deal with hawkins to do so
the restaurant industry wants to be able to count a waiter's tips as a credit toward half the minimum wage requirement. labor and hawkins are opposed to the proposal, but robinson said he believed he had enough votes in the full committee to pass it
the panel also defeated, 6-3, an amendment by steve bartlett, r-texas, to create what he called training wage of $3.35 an hour for a 180-day period during which an employer can teach a new worker
hawkins said the proposal was nothing more than a ``subminimum wage'' that had been rejected by congress many times in the past. ``how long does it take a youngster to learn how to flip a hamburger?'' he asked
voting for the minimum wage increase were reps. hawkins, penny, robinson, subcommittee chairman austin j. murphy, d-pa.; pat williams, d-mont., and robert e. wise jr., d-w.va. voting against it were petri, jeffords and bartlett
the minimum wage was raised to $3.35 an hour in 1981 from $3.10
the estate of the late rep. larry mcdonald, who died in 1983 when a korean air lines plane was shot down by a soviet fighter jet, is challenging an irs claim for $6.1 million in taxes
the key dispute is the contention by the internal revenue service that the value of the estate should include $10 million in punitive damages and $2 million for pain and suffering that are being sought in litigation against the airline. no damages have been awarded
the georgia democrat's widow, kathryn j. mcdonald, the administrator of the estate, filed suit in u.s. tax court to protest the irs claim
her petition says that because the damage suit against the airline is controlled by international law, no punitive damages are possible
no recovery has been made for any damages relating to the decedent's pain and suffering, and ultimate recovery is doubtful,'' said the peition, which was filed jan. 21
mcdonald was among 269 people who died when the kal jumbo jet was shot down after passing through soviet airspace on sept. 1, 1983, while flying from anchorage, alaska, to seoul
eddie ``the eagle'' edwards, the scrappy ski-jumper who became the superstar loser at the winter olympics, came home thursday in a white rolls-royce to the cheers of crowds
about 3,000 townsfolk waving ``welcome home eddie'' flags lined downtown streets for more than an hour to catch a glimpse of the 24-year-old who left home an unknown plasterer and returned a celebrity
it's great to be back home and i'm just staggered by everyone turning out to welcome me in the town,'' said edwards. he finished last in his two events but won over olympic crowds with his ever-ready smile and often-bumbling antics
he flew back from calgary on tuesday but spent two days in london saying he had to sort out offers from manufacturers, movie moguls, publishers and a vodka distiller
his parents, sister and brother greeted him wearing ``i love eddie'' sweaters knitted by his 80-year-old grandmother
after all the fuss he has had around the world, he is still a home-loving boy,'' said his mother, janette. ``he's coping well with it all.''
the mother of u.s. sen. richard g. lugar, reported missing early thursday by relatives, was found unharmed at a hotel in neighboring illinois, a spokesman for lugar said
bertha lugar caldwell, 81, was last seen driving her car late wednesday in indianapolis, about 70 miles from the illinois state line, andy fisher, an aide to the indiana republican, said from washington
we assume that she was driving around and got disoriented,'' said fisher
fisher said a doctor probably would examine mrs. caldwell in indianapolis but that her health ``has been fine all along.''
rain, freezing rain and sleet pelted the area during the night
more than 21,000 rock fans have signed their names to a pink cadillac in an unusual petition drive to get bruce springsteen to schedule a stop here on his ``tunnel of love'' tour
but berry bell of premier talent, springsteen's new york booking agency, said rockford's 10,000-seat metro centre couldn't hold such a concert
your building is too small. ... besides, he's booked through the end of may,'' bell said
radio station wzok bought the 1968 car and had it painted pink in honor of ``pink cadillac,'' an early springsteen hit
mark mcclure, operations manager at the station, said springsteen's tour, which began last week in worcester, mass., will stop in suburban chicago on march 16-17 and won't resume until march 22 in atlanta
he's got a five-day window between chicago and atlanta,'' he said. ``but we say, `come anytime you want.'''
mcclure plans to drive to philadelphia on monday when springsteen performs at the spectrum there and park the signature-decorated car near the back stage door. a similar promotion, he said, persuaded the rolling stones to play rockford in 1981
first graders at del obispo elementary school ate green eggs and ham this week in honor of the 84th birthday of theodor seuss geissel, known to readers of his children's books as dr. seuss
from his home in la jolla wednesday, dr. seuss said the tribute was flattering but joked he was ``terrified'' to think the youngsters actually ate green food
are you calling from a hospital?'' he quipped
the 120 youngsters used food coloring to create the culinary tribute to one of dr. seuss' most famous nonsensical works _ ``green eggs and ham.''
bill bradley admits that his speeches as a rookie u.s. senator were boring, according to an interview published thursday
there was a strong sense that i was competing with sominex,'' the new jersey democrat told parade magazine, which said his skills have greatly improved since he first announced a senate bid in 1977
despite continuing speculation of a presidential draft, bradley maintained he has a lot more to learn and do in the senate. running for president, he sasid, would mean he no longer could enjoy the freedom to make mistakes
you can no longer quietly and anonymously visit with and listen to ordinary americans in their homes,'' he said. ``you start to exist tarmac to tarmac.''   
the newly crowned miss usa said thursday that the ``astronomical'' odds she faced in her bid to become the fourth straight miss texas to win the title provided the extra push she needed
at a manhattan news conference, courtney gibbs said of her beauty pageant win, ``i've been extremely overwhelmed, very numb. it's just starting to settle in as i open up newspapers or turn on the television.''
the 21-year-old college student and model was crowned tuesday in the nationally televised event staged in el paso, texas
miss gibbs' win marked the fourth year in a row that a texas woman has won the event, prompting a stunned pageant spokeswoman, stacy sacco, to assure reporters that the contest was not rigged
on thursday, miss gibbs, a junior at texas christian university, said that going into the pageant the computer-generated odds were ``something astronomical'' against another texas woman winning
i think just that little bit of challenge, that little bit of extra `you can't' really gave me the push to think that i could.''
miss gibbs, an aspiring actress, will represent the united states in the miss universe pageant may 23 in taipei, taiwan
moslem guerrilla commanders have banned smoking by their forces in northern afghanistan
the jamiat-i-islami, one of the major moslem parties fighting to overthrow kabul's marxist government and the soviet forces who back it up, announced the decision by commanders of the panshir valley in a newsletter distributed thursday
it said the use and sale of tobacco and snuff was banned ``in accordance with the tenets of islam which forbid using things that make people unhealthy.''
economic considerations also had an important role in the decision,'' the newsletter said
afghanistan's panjshir valley is a key soviet supply route between kabul and the soviet border to the north
it used to be easy to handicap the grammys. but as the music industry awards moved into their third decade, they proved they can pack some surprises
take michael jackson, for example
four years ago, he nabbed a record eight grammys with his ``thriller'' lp. at the 30th annual grammy awards on wednesday night, he was a big loser. he was nominated for four grammys and he didn't win any, though his engineers won for their work on his album, ``bad.''
the irish quartet u2, with their introspective songs of humanity, were expected to sweep the national academy of recording arts &amp; sciences awards for their 12 million-seller lp, ``the joshua tree.''
the group was nominated for four grammys and won two, including album of the year. ``i still haven't found what i'm looking for'' lost song of the year honors to ``somewhere out there,'' a sweet song from an animated mouse movie, and lost record of the year to paul simon's title track from last year's grammy-winning ``graceland'' lp
the ``graceland'' single was released within the oct. 1, 1986 to sept. 30, 1987 eligibility year to qualify for this year's awards
simon wasn't at radio city music hall to collect his trophy, nor to see ladysmith black mambazo, his collaborators on the south african-inspired ``graceland'' album, win a grammy for their own ``shaka zulu'' collection, which simon produced
robert shaw and the atlanta symphony chorus and orchestra won more grammys than the rock and pop stars who usually make the headlines. their recording of requiems by gabriel faure and maurice durufle won awards for best engineered classical recording and for producer robert woods. the atlanta group's recording of paul hindemith's ``when lilacs last in the dooryard bloom'd'' won as best choral performance
there were more surprises: sting beat jackson and bruce springsteen as best male pop vocalist for his album ``bring on the night''; veteran rocker frank zappa zapped springsteen and stevie ray vaughan as best rock instrumentalist for his lp ``jazz from hell''; smokey robinson topped jackson and stevie wonder as best rhythm 'n' blues male vocalist for his single, ``just to see her.''
and suzanne vega, whose soliloquy of an abused child touched listeners throughout the world, won nothing for the song ``luka.'' she had three nominations, including song and record of the year
i was hoping it would win, but i was prepared for anything to happen,'' she said backstage. ``i'm a little disappointed i guess.''
it wasn't surprising that whitney houston was chosen best female pop vocalist for her single ``i wanna dance with somebody (who loves me)'' or that springsteen was chosen best rock vocalist for his album, ``tunnel of love.''
but one of the evening's biggest surprises and best moments came from a presenter _ the strutting, screaming and outrageous little richard. he stole the show and held it captive for a few hilarious minutes when he declared he had won the prize for best new artist. the award really went to jody watley
i have never received nuthin'. y'all ain't never gave me no grammys, and i've been singing for 30 years,'' declared the man who sang ``tutti frutti'' and ``good golly, miss molly.''
i am the architect of rock 'n' roll,'' he shouted, and the crowd jumped to its feet and roared approval
bill medley, who never won a grammy with bobby hatfield as the righteous brothers and said he'd ``been waiting 26 years for one of these suckers,'' won with jennifer warnes. their duet, ``(i've had) the time of my life,'' from the ``dirty dancing'' soundtrack, was named best pop vocal performance by a duo or group
aretha franklin became the woman who owns the most grammys, moving ahead of leontyne price and ella fitzgerald, by winning two this year for a total of 14. she won as best female rhythm 'n' blues vocalist for her album ``aretha,'' and with george michael as best rhythm 'n' blues duo or group for ``i knew you were waiting (for me),'' a track from ``aretha.''
diane schuur won over jazz veterans carmen mcrae, sarah vaughan and ella fitzgerald, and manhattan transfer's janis siegel, named best female jazz vocalist with her critically acclaimed lp, ``diane schuur and the count basie orchestra.''
the late duke ellington was represented by ``digital duke,'' the ellington band conducted by mercer ellington
i felt pop over my shoulder the whole time in the studio,'' mercer ellington said backstage
posthumous albums won in two categories. ``unfinished business'' by steve goodman, who died of leukemia, won as best contemporary folk record. peter tosh, slain in his jamaica home last year during a robbery, had recorded ``no nuclear war,'' which won in the reggae category
in classical categories, the chicago symphony's music director, sir georg solti, winner of more grammys than anybody, added another to his collection of 25, when ``beethoven: symphony no. 9'' was named best orchestral recording
pianist vladimir horowitz, who had been tied for second place with henry mancini with 20 grammys, pulled ahead. he picked up the best classical album grammy for ``horowitz in moscow.'' the record was also named best classical instrumental solo performance without orchestra
violinist itzhak perlman received two grammys, for best solo instrumental with orchestra, for ``mozart: violin concertos 2 and 4'' and, with cellist lynn harrell and pianist vladimir ashkenazy, for best chamber performance, for ``beethoven: the complete piano trios.''
soprano kathleen battle also received two. her ``kathleen battle _ salzburg recital'' won as best vocal solo performance and she was a principal soloist on strauss' ``ariadne auf naxos,'' which won as best opera recording. miss battle was a featured soloist on four of the five opera recordings that were nominated
a film about an american adventurer who took over nicaragua more than 100 years ago was a box-office flop in the united states, but it has been drawing long lines in managua
a downtown movie house has been packed since the film ``walker'' opened feb. 25. that's an unusual occurrence because the $5 tickets cost more than many workers earn in a day
moviegoers said they were curious and eager to see the scenes of granada, the central colonial city on the shores of lake nicaragua where most of the film was shot last year
the movie, directed by briton alex cox for universal pictures, is about william walker, a 19th century american adventurer who is little-known in the united states but featured in every child's history book in nicaragua. the satirical film stars ed harris as walker nd academy award-winner marlee matlin as his hearing-impaired wife
walker is seen here as the first invader from the united states, the man who started more than 100 years of u.s. intervention and a symbol of yankee imperialism
walker came to nicaragua in 1855 and after capturing granada, named himself president the following year. he offered an uneasy warning of today's friction between nicaragua and the united states by saying, ``we'll be back, time and time again.''
walker surrendered to the u.s. navy in 1857, tried to conquer central american in 1860 and was finally turned over to honduras. he was executed by firing squad in 1860
reviews so far have been mixed
roberto fonseca wrote in the culture magazine ventana that the film was ``a joke in bad taste.''
it's a shame that we lost the opportunity to make a film, a work with instructive and political ends,'' fonseca wrote
he noted that the film contained unnecessary violence and was ``extemely weak not only because of its ommissions but _ voluntary or not _ for its misrepresentations.''
the movie starts out by saying that ``this is a true story.''
but reviewers find scores of factual errors, including the wrong presidents at the time in nicaragua and the united states
the 20th century props used in the film amused the crowd in the teatro gonzalez movie house and they broke into laughter when scenes showed contemporary news magazines, a recent model car and a soviet-made troop helicopter that was supposed to be carrying u.s. government officials
but fonseca, in his review, said: ``personally, the misrepresentations don't make me laugh.''
the pro-government newspaper nuevo diario quoted roberto cruz, described as a movie enthusiast, as saying the ``satire covered up what walker means in nicaragua.''
most of the people at the theater hurried out, chatting among themselves about the film
i liked it,'' one woman said, pulling the hand of a youngster. ``why? well, i like the scenes.''
a young man, who said he didn't want to give his name, said: ``i thought it was funny.''
but another spectator, also declining to give his name, said simply, ``it was silly.'' book</head>
presidental candidate michael dukakis has joined the literary campaign trail by co-authoring a book that chronicles development in massachusetts under his governorship
dukakis wrote only two chapters of ``creating the future,'' but his name is listed ahead of co-author rosabeth moss kanter of the harvard business school on the new $17.95 hardcover book that explains the secrets of massachusett's economic success
the book may instruct students of economic development policy. but the average reader could come away thinking that political campaign books are to books what political campaign food is to food
several other presidential candidates have published books, ranging from democrat gary hart's novel, ``the double man,'' co-authored with sen. william cohen, r-maine, to kansas sen. bob dole's ``unlimited partners,'' written with his wife, former transportation secretary elizabeth dole, and richard norton smith
dukakis' book is neither a novel nor a biography. it has no plot, poetry or photos. but it is full of recipes _ economic recipes
resolutely serious, the book focuses on the reversal of massachusetts' economic fortunes since dukakis began his first term as governor in 1975, when the state's unemployment rate was 12 percent and the state treasury was more than $500 million in the red. he lost in 1978 but won two more terms, in 1982 and 1986
dukakis walks a fine line between praising himself and praising others for what he calls ``the massachusetts comeback'' or the ``massachusetts miracle.''
there is a lesson for america in the massachusetts success story. it is not that every specific program we tried here will work everywhere else,'' dukakis writes
rather, the lesson is in the idea of hands-on economic development and the approach we've used to get it done,'' he says. the key ingredients were fiscal reform, investments in public infrastructure, worker training and capital formation, and the creation of public-private partnerships to encourage innovation
in the early stages of his presidential campaign last year, dukakis stressed his role in the turnaround that brought lower taxes, rising personal income and the lowest unemployment rate of any industrial state
dukakis uses the book to lecture his critics who claim that massachusetts has benefited from the reagan defense build-up
the world may identify massachusetts with high technology, and high technology with defense, but the facts are otherwise,'' dukakis writes. he maintains that only about 4 percent of massachusetts employment depends on defense spending
dukakis is credited as the author of chapters on the state's comeback and on his now-familiar prescriptions for a national economic development strategy
the bulk of the book was written by kanter, an expert on entrepreneurship and an ally of the dukakis administration. kanter said the book grew out of discussions she had with dukakis in 1986, well before he decided to run for president
it might have been me first saying, there's a great story here. then his staff picked up on it,'' kanter said in an interview
in february (1987) we met and decided a book was a good idea. that was at his inititative,'' she said
according to kanter, the chapters attributed to dukakis were based on speeches and policy statements he had made before, but she insisted that dukakis was actively involved in updating, editing and rewriting them
he had somewhat less time than we were expecting,'' kanter said
john devillars, the governor's deputy chief of staff, said dukakis worked on the book while flying from one campaign stop to another. ``he probably, in writing the book, traveled 15,000 miles,'' devillars said
the publisher, simon and schuster, refused to divulge any figures about sales or orders. but if the book makes any money, dukakis and kanter have decided to donate any proceeds to the state's adult literacy corps. counseling</head>
a federal judge today blocked implementation of new reagan administration regulations designed to cut off federal funds to family planning clinics which perform abortions or offer abortion counseling
the new regulation, which were scheduled to take effect today, would have had no immediate impact on the estimated 4,000 family planning clinics around the nation operated with federal funds because the rules apply only to new grants
u.s. district judge walter jay skinner issued a permanent injunction against the department of health and human services regulations
skinner said in a 28-page order that the regulations issued last month by the department ``as a whole violate both congressional intent and rights protected by the constitution.''
it was not immediately clear if the ruling had effect outside massachusetts. federal judges in denver and new york city earlier had issued temporary injunctions against implementation of the rules
in my opinion, a governmentally imposed block on the flow of neutral information bearing on abortion is an impermissible burden on the presently recognized rights of a pregnant client'' of a family planning clinic
skinner also said the regulations violate first amendment protections of free speech for those who advocate abortion
the injunction was requested last month by the state of massachusetts, the national family planning and reproductive health association and 13 other local and national family planning groups
the new rules would prohibit federally funded family planning programs from providing abortion counseling, referring women to abortion providers and engaging in lobbying or legal action to increase availability of abortion
if the facility also performs abortions, to keep federal funding for its other programs the clinic must maintain separate personnel, separate accounting procedures, and provide different and clearly defined waiting and treatment rooms for each type of patient
about 4,000 family planning clinics nationwide would be affected by the regulations
in requesting the injunction, the state and the family planning association told skinner at a feb. 17 hearing that the new regulations were contrary to the intent of congress when it established the family planning program under title x of the public health service act in 1970
the title x budget for fiscal 1988 is $137 million, down from $142 million in fiscal 1987. an estimated 5 million poor women receive services from the program
in massachusetts, there are 84 clinics serving 87,000 recipients with the help of a $2.9 million title x appropriation
a government spokesman said thursday some people were killed in the southern city of sumgait during weekend riots, which he said were provoked by ``hooligans'' reacting to rumors of ethnic confrontation
foreign ministry spokesman gennady gerasimov gave the first official confirmation of deaths during the riots in the caucasian republic of azerbaijan, but would not say how many people were killed
even one single life lost is already much too much,'' gerasimov said when asked at a news briefing about a claim by armenian dissidents that 17 people were killed at sumgait, an industrial city of more than 160,000
trouble between ethnic azerbaijanis and ethnic armenians began early last month with a dispute over nagorno-karabakh, a region just north of iran and east of turkey. more than three-quarters of the population is armenian but it was made part of neighboring azerbaijan in 1923
protesters in nagorno-karabakh demanded that it be joined to armenia and peaceful protests spread to yerevan, capital of soviet armenia
riots were reported sunday in sumgait, 150 miles from nagorno-karabakh
a group of mutineers, of hooligans, provoked disorders,'' gerasimov said. ``these riots involved people who fell for provocative rumors and instigations with respect to what happened in nagorno-karabakh
using the situation of spontaneity, the instigators of violence participated in actions which led to casualties.''
he referred at other times in the briefing to loss of life, indicating the casualties were deaths
on wednesday, an employee of the television station in baku, capital of azerbaijan, said one or two people had been killed in sumgait. he spoke in a telephone interview on condition of anonymity
gerasimov acknowledged that problems also developed in kirovabad, another city in azerbaijan. ``the situation in kirovabad is normal, although over there some things might have happened too,'' he said, but refused to elaborate
the television worker said 50-60 young ethnic azerbaijanis who live in armenia traveled to sumgait last weekend and told relatives and friends about ethnic confrontations. he said ``young hooligans'' then went on a rampage and killed people
on thursday, gerasimov said people were arrested and prosecutors were investigating. he said order had been restored in sumgait, businesses and stores were running normally and the curfew had been lifted
he said two ranking soviet officials were in sumgait ``investigating these anti-social manifestations.'' he identified them as pyotr n. demichev, a non-voting member of the national communist party politburo, and kyamran bagirov, first secretary of the azerbaijan central committee
some ethnic azerbaijanis had fled their homes, he said
influenced by such provocative rumors and rumor-mongering, a small number of azerbaijani families left azerbaijan,'' gerasimobv told the journalists. ``they went to their relatives regularly,'' he said, but did not say where they settled
the only other confirmed report of deaths in the armenian-azerbaijan unrest was a soviet prosecutor's comment saturday that two people in agdamsky, a district of azerbaijan bordering nagorno-karabakh, had been murdered in disorders linked to the territorial dispute
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev appealed feb. 26 for calm in armenia and azerbaijan, and said the communist party central committee would review the dispute
new regulations to deny federal funds to family-planning organizations that counsel abortion technically go into effect today, but three court challenges have left the picture murky
even if the new rules weren't in legal limbo, there would be no immediate practical impact on the estimated 4,000 family planning clinics around the nation operated with federal funds
that is because the new regulations apply only to new grants
all the clinics that might eventually be affected are now operating with money approved under the old regulations. no new grant applications are in the final approval stage
federal judges in denver and new york city have issued temporary injunctions against implementation of the new rules, but it is not clear whether they have full nationwide force
in boston today, a third federal judge, walter jay skinner, issued a permament injunction against the department of health and human services blocking implementation of the rules
skinner said the regulations violate congress' intent and rights protected by the constitution
in my opinion, a governmentally imposed block on the flow of neutral information bearing on abortion is an impermissible burden on the presently recognized rights of a pregnant client'' of a family planning clinic, the judge said. replacements</head>
the united states is forging ahead with plans for better nuclear shells and short-range air-to-surface missiles, but is moving less rapidly to replace 88 aged ground-launched rockets, partly out of deference to west germany, u.s. officials said thursday
the shells are in development and the air-to-surface missile is close to that stage, the officials said
the officials, speaking on condition of anonymity in washington as nato leaders in brussels ended their two-day summit, said major decisions remain, however, on how to replace the 75-mile-range, ground-launched lance missile
deployment of a replacement for the lance could come as late as 1995, if ever, they said
nato is still committed to the modernization, but there isn't any decision facing the alliance now on lance replacement,'' one official said
what to do about short-range systems has become a bigger issue in nato, now that a u.s.-soviet treaty would eliminate missiles capable of hitting targets 300 to 3,120 miles away. the short-range arms would be the only nuclear weapons left in western europe
as promised at a defense ministers' meeting in montebello, canada, in 1983, nato already has reduced the number of short-range systems below a 4,600 ceiling. the other half of the montebello decision is pending. it calls for:
_ new, more accurate and reliable artillery shells, notably for 155-millimeter howitzers, capable of hitting targets 10-15 miles away. research is finished and that weapon is in the early development stage
_ a new air-to-surface missile with a range of about 350 miles. the could be in the development stage shortly, especially if a final decision is reached to simply modify existing air-launched cruise missiles. the weapons would be deployed on u.s. f-16s, f-111s, west german torndados and other fighter-bombers
_ a replacement for lance missile, a 1960s generation weapon deployed in 1972. there are 88 lance launchers in western europe and nato envisions replacing them with equipment capable of firing a missile about 130 miles. the replacement is in the early design stage
in a summit-ending communique, president reagan and the other 15 leaders said ``we are determined to sustain the requisite efforts to ensure the continued viability, credibility and effectiveness of our conventional and nuclear forces, including the nuclear forces in europe which together provide the guarantee of our common security.''
the final summit communique avoided use of the word modernization, to which west germany objects. instead, the document said nato will maintain ``an appropriate mix of adequate and effective nuclear and conventional forces which will continue to be kept up to date where necessary.''
of the nato allies, west germany is the most concerned about the pace of modernization. many political figures there would prefer less talk about nuclear improvements and more talk about negotiations with the soviets to reduce the number of short-range weapons on both sides
in deference to west germany, officials before and after the summit took pains to stress the fact that the lance replacement, the most powerful of the weapons, has not even been built, much less set for deployment
nato secretary general lord carrington said the allies were concerned that some people might think ``modernization'' might signal introduction of new, more destructive weapons. ``modernization actually means weapons that are more accurate and possibly less destructive,'' he said
frank gaffney, a former deputy assistant secretary of defense and advocate of rapid-as-possible improvements in the short-range systems, said thursday deployment of the new weapons would enhance the chances of getting an agreement at future arms talks with the soviets
the pentagon's 1987 report on soviet military power said east bloc forces have ``a substantial numerical superiority'' in short-range nuclear forces
the body of a 9-year-old boy, handcuffed and naked, was found inside the family's clothes dryer, authorities said thursday
the death of the boy, james l. keller, appears to have been accidental but the investigation was incomplete, said deputy police chief robert pepin
he said police were called to the home wednesday night and officers found the parents trying to revive the boy
as near as we can tell,'' said pepin, ``he had been playing with a couple of siblings and somehow or other ended up in the dryer.''
kankakee county coroner james orrison said there were some burns on the body, indicating the dryer had been turned on, but that he had not determined the cause of death
police do not know why the boy was naked and his hands cuffed. pepin said the accident happened in the basement while the father was sleeping and the mother was out of the house
earlier this week, the body of a 12-year-old humboldt, wis., boy was found nude in a portable dishwasher that had been turned on. police said the death was apparently accidental but they were continuing to investigate
doctors have isolated the aids virus from the cervixes of aids-infected women, a discovery that sheds some light on how the disease is transmitted
it may explain how a woman passes on the disease to babies during birth and to her sex partners, researchers say
doctors at massachusetts general hospital isolated the virus from the cervixes of three of four aids-infected women
these findings indicate that there is actually virus within the cervix tissue itself, and the virus can be secreted'' into the genital fluids, said dr. martin s. hirsch, senior author of the report. ``these might be a source of subsequent infection to others.''
experts had known before that infected women can have aids virus in their genital regions, although it was unclear where it came from
this shows pretty clearly that the source of the virus within the genital secretions is actually cells within the cervix,'' hirsch said in an interview
he said the cervix might also be infected directly during intercourse from contact with virus-laden sperm, although the study doesn't prove the aids virus actually gets into women's bodies this way
the study, directed by dr. roger j. pomerantz, was published in the march issue of the annals of internal medicine
the researchers found the virus in endothelial cells that line blood vessels in the inner layer of the cervix, as well as in germ-eating macrophages and other blood cells within the cervical tissue
it's interesting and raises possibilities that perhaps the cervix could be infected directly by the virus, rather than get there through the blood,'' said dr. jay a. levy of the university of california, san francisco
the new research adds one more site to the growing list of targets of the aids virus, known as hiv
the virus kills by destroying helper t-cells, blood cells that orchestrate the body's immune defenses against all kinds of microscopic invaders, among them the aids virus itself. however, experts have learned that the virus also infects other types of blood cells as well as other parts of the body, including the eyes and the brain
last month, levy and others published a report showing that the aids virus also infects the rectum and colon. that could explain one way that the disease is spread during anal intercourse
many experts have assumed that for an aids infection to occur, the virus must enter the bloodstream through a tear in the body's tissues. the discovery of infected rectal and cervical tissue, however, suggests this might not always be necessary. instead, infection might occur by direct viral contact with the rectum and the female sex organs
a local infection of susceptible cervical cells from infected semen may preceed systemic spread of hiv,'' the researchers wrote
hirsch said he believes, though cannot prove, that the aids virus can penetrate intact cervical tissue, but infection might occur more readily if the cervix is inflamed by venereal disease
about 40 percent of babies born to infected women catch the virus themselves, either before or during birth. the study raised the possiblity that delivery by caesarean section might lower the risk to the newborn but says there is no proof for this
the women tested in the study were all heroin users who likely got infected from contaminated needles
it may not be the great train robbery, but it could be the great rail theft _ every inch of a 2,000-foot stretch of city-owned railroad track in great falls has disappeared
they did a good job, too,'' said city engineer stu pearson. ``they took the railroad, the ties and the gravel.''
time of the theft is a bit uncertain _ sometime between august 1984 and last week. value of the stolen track was estimated at $80,000
pearson said he learned last week the track was missing. he was notified by the manager of the construction company that laid the track for the city
i had to sit down and catch my breath,'' pearson said. ``i couldn't believe it was gone. but sure enough, you go up there and there's not a lick of rail.''
he has since done some investigating. ``everybody that i've talked to ... can remember work going on, but they can't remember who did it,'' he said
the track spur, installed in 1978, extended from the burlington northern railroad's main line into an industrial park that is now partially occupied
the problem is serious, pearson said, because rail service is an important factor in selling lots in the industrial park. although the spur obviously had not been used much in the last few years, it may be needed when the economy improves, he said
pearson said he has asked officials from the bn and milwaukee road railroads to check records to determine whether their workers removed the track by mistake. he has yet to receive a response
the cost to replace the track would be about $160,000, he estimated, but the city has no plans to do so yet
early immigrants to the united states will be honored at a special stamp ceremony involving sweden and finland on march 29, the u.s. postal service said thursday
the occasion is the settlement 350 years ago of new sweden _ in what is now delaware _ by immigrants from those northern european nations
a stamp dedication ceremony will be held in the grand opera house in wilmington, del., where the issuance of a 44-cent u.s. airmail stamp will be marked
at the same time, stamps commemorating the same settlement will also be issued in helsinki, finland, and vaxjo, sweden
a hunch by a caseworker led to a tearful reunion of a mother with her 15-month-old son who was kidnapped when he was 18 days old
alisha wetselline-rodriguez held her son, eric, on wednesday and was so excited she could barely speak
i understand he has to get used to me,'' ms. wetselline-rodriguez said as she cradled the boy, dressed in red overalls and a striped shirt, during a visit to the home where he has been cared for
for months after eric was kidnapped from his home on dec. 9, 1986, ms. wetselline-rodriguez called police and got the same message: nothing yet
she then resorted to a nationwide search using fliers and getting in touch with child-welfare agencies
on christmas eve last year, texas department of human services worker mary forrester noticed a striking similarity between a picture of eric on a missing-children flier and the picture of an abandoned child who had been turned over to the agency
the identification process began then; the boy's mother was officially notified monday night that her son had been found
it was a one-in-a-million case,'' said ms. forrester. ``i wasn't even supposed to get the case, but another worker was overloaded. and when i first saw the flier, i threw it away. something made me go back and look at it.''
family court judge harold gaither jr. on wednesday returned the boy to ms. wetselline-rodriguez's custody after reviewing evidence from blood tests and testimony by officials
a few months after his kidnapping, a dallas woman took eric to a local catholic church and told a priest that a woman she met in a park had asked her to care for the child for a week while the woman went to houston to seek work
the church turned the child over to the state last may
the woman never returned, and efforts to find her have failed, according to dallas county assistant district attorney beverly storey
ms. forrester said the boy would have been eligible for adoption in november, but she postponed that process because she had a feeling about the case
john and diane noster, who have nurtured the boy for 10 months and have celebrated his first steps and first birthday, will keep the boy for another week, giving him a chance to grow accustomed to his mother
i've waited this long, what's another week?'' said ms. wetselline-rodriguez, who turned 22 on dec. 29. ``this is the best christmas and birthday present i've ever had.'' fever</head>
u.s. health officials warned thursday that new prevention and control programs are needed to prevent western hemisphere epidemics of dengue fever, a tropical disease carried by mosquitoes
the incidence of dengue in most countries of the (americas) region has continued to increase in recent years,'' the u.s. centers for disease control reported
in brazil alone, 47,370 cases of dengue were officially reported in 1986, and health authorities there estimate that between 300,000 and 500,000 cases may have actually occurred. in mexico, 21,975 cases were officially reported
dengue fever is caused by infection with a dengue virus and can prompt fever, pains in the joints, and even death
thirty-three cases of dengue fever were reported in the united states in 1986
the cdc noted that the disease is transmitted by mosquitoes, including the aedes albopictus, or ``tiger mosquito,'' which is increasingly prevalent in the united states. the species has now spread to 17 states, mostly in the south, east and midwest
while the ultimate significance of the presence of (the tiger mosquito) is not known, it is likely to increase the efficiency of virus maintenance in infested areas,'' the cdc said in its weekly report
the cdc also blamed the increase in dengue infections in the americas on the simultaneous circulation of several different types of dengue virus
a 73-year-old man described as a dangerous repeat offender was sentenced to 6 to 25 years in prison thursday after he pleaded guilty to stealing limburger cheese and other food from a grocery store
hairm richardson entered the plea to a single count of aggravated robbery just before he was to go on trial on charges of aggravated robbery, felonious assault and possessing criminal tools. warren county prosecutors agreed to drop the other charges in exchange for the guilty plea
richardson, of miamisburg, was accused of shoplifting two pounds of bacon, a sausage and a jar of limburger cheese from a franklin grocery store last october and then pulling a knife on a store employee who tried to stop him
prosecutors said richardson's ``criminal tool'' was a large coat with extra pockets sewn inside, allegedly for the purpose of hiding shoplifted food
james beaton, an assistant county prosecutor, said he was satisfied with the sentence and said richardson will probably spend the rest of his life behind bars
i don't think he'll see the light of day,'' beaton said
in 1942, richardson and three brothers were convicted of first-degree murder in the slaying of a man who tried to stop a robbery in a bar and all four were sentenced to life. richardson was paroled in july 1964 after then-gov. james rhodes commuted his conviction to second-degree murder
in 1981, richardson was convicted of misdemeanor theft in miamisburg and was sentenced to 30 days in jail and fined $250, police said. in 1982, franklin police charged him with drug abuse and trafficking in marijuana; he served less than 10 months of a 1-to 5-year sentence before being paroled in may 1983, officials said
we have to take a hard line on it. the guy's dangerous,'' beaton said in an interview. ``this guy is not your average 73-year-old man, not by a long shot.''
he's as strong as an ox and in perfect health,'' franklin police detective rick thacker said
if convicted of the original charges, richardson could have received a 10- to 25-year term for aggravated robbery and 8 to 15 years for each of the two felonious assault charges
an apartment cooperative that requires new owners and renters to speak english has sparked threats of picketing among hispanics, who claim the rule is discriminatory
the language requirement was imposed at the paradise towers apartment building after communications problems arose with a colombian couple who could not speak english. other residents complained they could not make the couple understand that their grandchildren were wandering too close to a dangerous seawall, the president of the condominium's board of directors said
the bylaw, which went into effect more than year ago, was publicized recently by a story in the miami herald
hispanics, angered at what they call a discriminatory policy, plan to picket outside the 70-unit cooperative later this week
this is a blatant violation and we will do whatever has to be done to get this changed,'' said mike morales, a south broward hispanic leader. ``so long as people have the money to pay, be it from spain, europe or any other part of the world, they should be able to live where they want.''
according to the fair housing act of 1968, discrimination in housing is prohibited on the basis of race, religion, sex, color and national origin. representatives of the u.s. justice department say the cooperative's bylaw could violate the act
under the bylaw, no apartment can be sold or leased unless at least one member of the new household can read, understand and speak english
it's sad that in a place like south florida, which depends a lot on economic relations with south america for its livelihood, that something like this could happen,'' said attorney osvaldo soto, chairman of the spanish american league against discrimination in miami
but residents of the cooperative, which screens all prospective owners and renters, say the rule is necessary to maintain safety and the building's private club atmosphere
we screen everyone for the protection of our tenants. we don't want undesirables living here,'' said charles levy, retired lawyer and president of paradise towers' board of directors. ``and if we can't communicate with people, it creates a real burden.''
the colombian couple moved out of the condominium in october 1986, and the bylaw was passed overwhelmingly in january 1987 by board members and residents. if the couple had stayed, they would have been exempt from the new bylaw, levy said
no one has yet been turned away or kicked out because of the rule, he said
despite the ruckus, board members said the cooperative has no plans of amending the bylaw unless residents demand it
some 450,000 tyrolia ski bindings are being recalled because of heel and toe lug breakage which could lead to serious injury, the consumer product safety commission said thursday
the voluntary recall was announced by tyrolia freizeitgerate of austria, which said consumers should cease using the affected bindings
if the lugs holding the ski bindings to the ski should fail during use, serious injury could occur because of loss of control by the skier, the commission said
generally, should breakage occur, it happens when the boot is being inserted into the binding. but five injuries have been reported that may have been related to lug failure, the agency said
the affected bindings can be identified by the color of the toe lug and the production code stamped on the right side of the base of the heel plate
bindings being recalled are:
_grey toe lugs: models 480, 230 and 177 with production codes starting with h; model 190 with production codes starting with g or h
_blue toe lugs: model 290 with production codes starting with f
_white toe lugs: model 290 with production codes starting with f; model 280 with codes starting with g; models 220 and 170 with codes starting with f or g or ending with 4; model 180 with codes starting with g; model 90 junior with codes ending with 4
_black toe lugs: model 80 junior with codes ending with 4 or 2
ski bindings with red lugs are not being recalled
tyrolia said consumers who bring their ski bindings to the shop where they were purchased or to their nearest tyrolia dealer by april 30 will be given new replacement bindings at no charge
after april 30 consumers will be given a choice of reconditioned bindings at no charge or new replacement bindings at a charge of between $18 and $21
consumers with questions can contact tyrolia at 1-800-343-5999 in the united states or 1-800-265-7252 in canada. the commission can be reached at 1-800-638-2772. issue</head> to bush.</note>
sen. bob dole pocketed an endorsement from conservative former u.n. ambassador jeane kirkpatrick on thursday and urged a federal death penalty for drug ``overlords and kingpins'' as he sought to invigorate a faltering super tuesday campaign
dole also stepped gingerly around the issue of whether gop presidential campaign rival george bush was involved in possible cia payments to panamanian strongman manuel noriega. bush has refused to discuss anything he did as cia director that might affect national security and criticized dole for talking about cia matters
on thursday, dole cited news reports saying noriega may have gotten millions of dollars from the cia but did not speak directly of bush the way he did when the kansas senator first raised the subject on wednesday
dole's aides hoped to use the endorsement from kirkpatrick, a former democrat, to attract conservative support in several of the southern states holding primaries and caucuses next tuesday. ms. kirkpatrick, who declined some moves to get her to run for the gop presidential nomination, is popular among conservatives for her hard-line foreign policy views
michael murphy, whose firm produces campaign commercials for dole, said ms. kirkpatrick's endorsement statement had been taped, and advertisements would be ready by the end of the day in case senior officials decide to use them in the super tuesday campaign
dole's aides concede he is running behind bush in most of the 17 states holding primaries and caucuses next tuesday, many of them in the south. the senator said his goal for those primaries is ``to get our share of delegate'' at stake, and insisted it was not possible for bush to strike a knockout blow on that day
but he offered no prediction on how many of the 712 available delegates he hopes for
he also conceded he is running behind bush in south carolina, which holds its primary on saturday _ and talked instead of same-day caucuses in his home state of kansas and in wyoming, two states where he said ``we look particulary good.''
ms. kirkpatrick, who left the democratic party after joining the reagan administration, praised dole warmly as a candidate who is ``serious and strong and smart and honorable and can be elected.''
i know george bush and bob dole,'' she told a news conference. ``i've worked with both of them on foreign policy problems, and i have more confidence that dole can produce the flexibility and the strength'' to deal with the country's problems and sit across from soviet leader mikhail gorbachev
dole called ms. kirkpatrick the ``heart and soul of the reagan revolution.''
earlier, in a speech to a white house conference on drug abuse, dole said it was wrong to give clean needles to drug addicts, as is being done in new york. ``giving clean needles to addicts may be intended to prevent disease, but it also endorses addiction,'' he said
he added that he favors imposition of a death penalty for ``the drug overlords and the kingpins'' of the international drug trade
dole used his speech to take a slap at noriega, who has been indicted on drug charges in this country, saying, ``we don't need him around either.''
but he seemed to back off slightly from comments he made while campaigning in louisiana on wednesday
at the time, he said there were ``some who say he's (noriega) been on the (cia) payroll since 1966.''
speaking of bush, who served as cia director from 1976 to 1977, he said, ``he made all those decisions in the cia. what were they? was noriega on the payroll when he was cia director? the cia payroll?''
asked to explain his comments at a news conference at which he won ms. kirkpatrick's endorsement, dole cited published reports saying that ``for many years noriega was on the cia payroll, maybe got millions of dollars from the cia
that's all i've suggested. there are a lot of cia directors over the past 20 years. i'm also suggesting that it shouldn't come as any surprise to anyone that noriega and others in panama have been involved in the drug business.''
virtuoso violinist and cultural ambassador henryk szeryng, known for his refreshing and moving renditions of bach and brahms, died thursday of a cerebral hemorrhage. he was 69
szeryng died in kassel, west germany, according to herve corre of the musician's paris office. he had suffered a cerebral hemorrhage early wednesday, then died after 24 hours in a coma
renowned worldwide for a vast repertoire which he executed with great skill and feeling during a career that spanned more than 50 years, szeryng was to have performed wednesday in brussels at a concert to benefit aids research
the polish-born musician, who traveled on a diplomatic passport as mexico's official cultural ambassador, also was known for his special preference for resurrecting neglected or lost works for the violin
last fall he delighted concert-goers in atlanta with a performance of a previously lost violin concerto by reynaldo hahn
szeryng also prided himself on introducing relatively unknown contemporary works to audiences worldwide
a tonalist and colorist with the technical command of a master, he thrilled audiences with what critics called ``his obvious delight in playing.'' instead of wrinkling his brow with the pained look of many of his colleagues, he appeared enraptured, smiling happily as he played favorite passages
arthur rubinstein, the polish-born pianist who died in 1982, once called him ``a musician's musician ... who gave real music lovers what they wanted: great moments of emotion.''
szeryng was born on sept. 22, 1918, in zelazowa-wola, poland, which was frederic chopin's birthplace. his father was a wealthy iron and lumber magnate and his mother was a professional pianist who taught the young henryk the piano and harmony when he was only five. his elder brother played the violin and szeryng, fascinated by the instrument, took it up at seven
it was totally beyond my comprehension,'' he said in a 1983 interview. ``how could one find the right notes and the right intervals on a fingerboard which is totally blank? piano playing was much simpler. you had white keys and black keys.''
polish violinst bronislaw huberman, a family friend, encouraged szeryng to pursue his violin studies and persuaded his parents to send him to berlin where he studied with carl flesch. huberman's political ideas also influenced szeryng's lifelong commitment to peace
in 1936, he studied at the paris conservatory, winning the coveted first prize only nine months after entering. he studied composition with the legendary nadia boulanger and gabriel bouillon and became friends with jean cocteau, pablo picasso and igor stravinsky
at the outbreak of world war ii, szeryng, who spoke seven languages fluently, was made polish prime minister wladislav sikorski's official translator and later became a personal goverment liaison officer. but he never abandonded his music, giving more than 300 concerts at allied hospitals and bases, even during air raids in britain
in 1941, he accompanied the exiled prime minister to latin america in search of a home for about 4,000 polish refugees displaced by the war. they were accepted by mexico. moved by this humanitarian gesture, szeryng took mexican citizenship in 1946
in 1970, he was appointed special music adviser to mexico's unesco delegation in paris and became the first musician to enjoy diplomatic status
although he once called bach his ``bible'' and chopin his ``first musical food,'' szeryng also had a passion for contemporary music. he said it gave him ``an extra portion of spontaneity and freshness.''
funeral services are to be held in monte carlo, monaco, his european home for many years, at a date to be announced. election</head>
the commission created to recommend solutions to the government's debt woes is apparently embroiled in a dispute with the reagan administration even before it begins meeting
house budget committee chairman william gray iii complained thursday that the administration was trying to dictate how the national economic commission would conduct its work in an effort to keep the panel's deliberations secret during the presidential election campaign
i don't think this commission should start off being dictated to by the white house,'' gray, who is a member of the commission, told reporters. ``someone is suggesting that we meet in a cave and roll a stone over the opening.''
gray took issue with a suggestion made by treasury secretary james a. baker iii that the 14-member bipartisan commission, which was created by congress last year, should hold its deliberations in secret and not release any reports before the november presidential election
while saying that the administration wanted the commission ``to go to work,'' baker suggested in an apperarance before the senate appropriations committee on tuesday that the commission's findings would carry more weight if the panel did not become embroiled in the presidential election campaign
the commission, which includes former democratic party leader robert strauss and chyrsler corp. chairman lee iacocca, is scheduled to hold its first meeting on friday in washington
gray said the first session would be a get-acquainted luncheon, but he said the panel would need to quickly make decisions on setting up a schedule of meetings and deciding how it would operate
however, the disagreement over such a fundamental issue as whether to hold open hearings suggests that the panel may have trouble operating, particularly if the members split along party lines. six members have been appointed by republicans and six by democrats
gray suggested that republicans were trying to keep the commission under wraps so that it would not become a forum for airing reagan's biggest economic failure, the string of record federal budget deficits
i don't think it is appropriate for the white house to say there should be nothing said or done until they get out of town,'' gray said. ``that is like the guilty party saying don't hand down sentence until we leave town.''
the commission is considered by many to be the best hope the next president will have to reach a quick consensus with congress on significant ways to reduce the budget deficit, which is expected to exceed $150 billion this year
the commission is scheduled to issue its final report on march 1, early in the next administration and presumably when a new president would have the most leverage to get his proposals through congress
the commission eventually will have 14 members. president reagan has already named as his choices former defense secretary caspar w. weinberger and former transportation secretary drew lewis, who is now chairman of union pacific corp
republican and democratic congressional leaders have named 10 other members and the new president-elect will name the final two members after the november election
gray's comments came following a budget committee hearing in which federal reserve chairman alan greenspan repeated his suggestion that a 15-cent-a-gallon increase in the federal gasoline tax would be a good way to help shrink the budget deficit. the gasoline tax is currently at nine cents a gallon
greenspan had voiced the same suggestion in testimony wednesday before the senate budget committee
in some unusually specific suggestions to congress, greenspan said thursday that an increase in the gasoline tax of 15 cents would raise $15 billion annually in new revenues while leaving retail gasoline prices still well below the levels of the early 1980s
responding to questions, greenspan said he favored a gasoline tax over an oil import fee, which is favored by the domestic oil industry, because an oil import fee would raise energy costs for american manufacturers, thus reducing their competitiveness with foreign producers
the u.s. marine officer kidnapped in lebanon two weeks ago has been selected for promotion to the rank of colonel, the corps said thursday
lt. col. william ``rich'' higgins, until last summer a military aide to former defense secretary caspar w. weinberger, was selected by a promotion board along with 78 other lieutenant colonels for advancement
the promotion list was published thursday. higgins is no. 55 on the list of 79 and would not actually receive the new rank for another year at the earliest
the marine promotion board was formed early this year to screen a field of 165 men and women, long before higgins' kidnapping on feb. 17
the 43-year-old officer was in lebanon because he had been assigned to temporary duty with the united nations, heading a group of observers in lebanon attached to the u.n. truce supervision organization
a decorated vietnam combat veteran, higgins served as the junior military assistant to weinberger for two years _ from june 1985 to june 1987. budget cuts</head>
budget cuts imposed by congress will lead to a slowdown in the air force's space launch operations this year and layoffs of as many as 500 contractor employees, the service said thursday
the roughly 28,000 civilian employees who work directly for the air force systems command, however, should not have to endure any unpaid furloughs, the service added
the air force said the head of the systems command sent a message to his field commanders thursday informing them of a variety of steps aimed at coping with a $281 million cut in his operations and maintenance fund
gen. bernard p. randolph has ordered a slowdown in operations at vandenberg air force base, calif., and cape canaveral air force station, fla., the service said. that move will force the contractors who operate the two space launch facilities to trim their work forces and delay some scheduled space launches, the air force said
the command also is offering early retirement to employees; cutting spending on travel, supplies and maintenance; and enforcing a hiring freeze
based on your planned and very difficult reductions in mission support, the command can still meet its critical mission without a furlough at this time,'' randolph wrote
but we have almost no room for error.''
the air force systems command, headquartered at andrews air force base, md., outside washington, is the arm of the service responsible for developing and procuring new aircraft and weapons. it is also the parent, however, of the air force's space division
the air force uses facilities at vandenberg and cape canaveral to launch military satellites into space
to save money, the air force said the contractors at the two facilities have been told to cut back to one shift per day, five days a week. currently, the contractors _ pan american world services inc. at cape canaveral and the federal electric corp. at vandenberg _ employ a total of about 5,000 workers
lt. col. doug kennett, a spokesman, said it would be up to the contractors to decide how many employees to lay off but ``it could get as high as 10 percent.''
the reduction in shifts ``will increase processing time to prepare for launches by at least 30 days,'' the service added
some test launches will have to be delayed and maintenance of existing facilities will be deferred.''
kennett declined to say how many launches might be delayed or which satellites would be affected
the move to avoid furloughs within the systems command follows a congressional outcry over plans by the air force logistics command to furlough its 84,000 civilian workers up to 10 days this year because of budget cuts
the operations and maintenance account for the systems command was reduced this year to $1.65 billion from $1.935 billion in fiscal 1987. of that fiscal 1988 total, about $231 million is earmarked for the operation of the two space centers _ down $22 million from fiscal 1987
the cuts stem from a reduction in the pentagon's budget under the terms of a deficit reduction compromise that was negotiated by the white house and congress last november
missiles fell on tehran and baghdad for a fourth day thursday and iraq said it had ``abundant'' supplies for continuing the deadly exchange
iraq's official news agency also said warplanes bombed dezful in western iran and the southern city of shiraz in the latest round of the ``war of the cities,'' whcih has taken thousands of lives in the 7{-year-old conflict
the soviet union denied supplying the rockets to either side. both are believed to use soviet-made scud-b surface-to-surface missiles
dispatches from the official news agencies said iraq fired two missiles into tehran and one into qom, the holy city of iran's shiite moslem hierarchy, and iran hit baghdad three times
that brought the total in four days to 27 iraqi missiles _ 24 fired at tehran and three at qom _ and 11 launched at baghdad by iran
iran said 13 people were killed and 40 wounded thursday in the air raids on dezful and shiraz, and 20 wounded by a missile strike on a tehran hospital. iraq said women and children were killed in baghdad, and houses and shops destroyed
since the missiles began flying monday afternoon, iran has listed 30 people killed and more than 130 wounded in tehran and said there were no casualties in qom. iraq has not given specific figures
an editorial in al-thawra, organ of iraq's ruling baath party, said the nation ``has highly abundant quantities of `al hussein' missiles that are ready to pound the (iranian) charlatans.''
al-qadissiya, the army daily, declared: ``the number of missiles we have used so far is only a sample of what we have in store to deter the enemy once and for all.''
the missiles are named for a saint of shiite moslems, who make up slightly more than half of iraq's 16 million people and the overwhelming majority of iran's 50 million
iran's official news agency quoted kamal kharrazi, a member of the supreme defense council, as saying iran is ``quite capable of continuing the war of the cities'' until baghdad stops its ``inhuman attacks.''
although iraq said it developed its own missiles, western military analysts believe they are scud-bs with strap-on boosters enabling them to reach tehran and qom, both about 290 miles from the iraqi border
iran also uses scud-bs, supplied by its arab allies syria and libya, but does not need boosters because baghdad is only 80 miles from the frontier
earlier this week, iran protested to the soviet ambassador about what it described as soviet-made missiles used by iraq. iran also said it knew what country shipped the weapons to iraq, but did not give the name
in moscow, foreign ministry spokesman gennady gerasimov said thursday: ``attempts are being made to present things in such a way as if the soviet union had something to do with'' the missile battle
claims of this kind are absolutely unfounded,'' he said. ``the u.s.s.r. has not supplied either of the sides with weapons for launching such strikes and in no way sanctioned them.''
tehran radio quoted military communiques as saying the missiles fired thursday were aimed at iraq's intelligence headquarters in baghdad and a baath party center. iraq said they hit residential areas
military experts say the scud-b is not accurate enough at the ranges involved to hit specific targets
filmmakers steven spielberg and george lucas asked a skeptical senate panel thursday to give artists final rights over their works, including the unapproved coloring of classic motion pictures
the destruction of our film heritage is only the tip of the iceberg,'' lucas testified
american law does not protect our painters, sculptors, recording artists, authors or filmmakers from having their lifework distorted, and their reputation distorted,'' said lucas, who directed the hit movies ``star wars'' and ``american grafitti.''
spielberg and lucas, makers of eight of the 10 biggest moneymaking movies ever, were the latest emissaries from hollywood asking that the united states adopt international copyright standards that give creators _ not those who put up the money _ so-called ``moral rights'' over their work
we're here representing the 95 to 97 percent of directors who don't have the clout we have,'' spielberg told the senate judiciary subcommittee on patents, copyrights and trademarks
those testifying in opposition to the directors' request included producer david brown, who backed ``jaws,'' spielberg's first major hit. ``producers and production companies are part of the creative process,'' said brown, asking that congress leave arguments over rights to individual negotiations
the ``moral rights'' provision would prevent changes being made in a motion picture without the consent of the screenwriter and director once the movie has been released theatrically
i've seen my first film, `sugarland express,' cut down to 76 minutes to fit into a television time slot. right now, i have no right to protest this,'' said spielberg
the issue has become more heated since media magnate ted turner began buying the rights to old movies like ``casablanca'' and ``yankee doodle dandy'' and began releasing new versions with color added by computer
publishers and the creators of computer programs testified that adherence to the berne convention on international copyright would make it easier to protect american products against ``piracy'' abroad
bills in the house and senate would add the united states to the 76 nations that are now part of the berne convention agreement, but none would give artists guaranteed rights to their work over the economic rights of the financier
outrageous acts will be committed'' if the law is not changed, lucas said. ``as new technologies come on, you're going to find them fouling up what we know as copyright and art.''
but the five senators on the subcommittee said they would support only a limited expansion of the copyright standards
the issue of `moral rights' is one that may have to wait for another day,'' said subcommittee chairman sen. dennis deconcini, d-ariz
spielberg said afterward, ``i don't think they sounded negative in there. they sounded practical.'' ``botha must ...''</note>
president p.w. botha said thursday his party's election losses to the far right were ``temporary disappointments,'' but they will force tough choices about his cautious reform of racial policy
leaders of the conservative party were jubilant about the decisive victory over the national party in two parliamentary by-elections wednesday. they said it shows increasing numbers of whites want apartheid strengthened and oppose even a token role for the black majority in national politics
botha must decide whether to appease those voters or move ahead with reforms in spite of them. the far right sees his goal of limited power-sharing as surrender. most black leaders and white liberals reject it as inadequate
one of the few black leaders showing any sympathy for botha was kenneth mopeli, chief minister of the qwaqwa tribal homeland, who said the election results ``spell disaster for the country.''
they not only signify a triumph for the policy of partition and fragmentation of the country, but also mean that the principle of power-sharing espoused by the national party has been effectively opposed,'' he said
under botha's concept of power-sharing, south africa's 26 million blacks would have a voice in national policy but the 5 million whites would retain control
he is unlikely to push for changes dramatic enough to win support from major black leaders, but made clear thursday he does not want to be seen as caving in to the far right
economic, social and political reform must continue, the president said, but he cautioned in the same statement: ``excessive demands often lead to excessive reactions.''
frederik de klerk, education minister and the national party leader in transvaal province, attributed conservative success to the demise of a smaller far-right party and displeasure with new wage freezes imposed on government employees
both seats in wednesday's by-elections went to conservatives in last may's national white elections but the winners were forced to resign, one on a technicality and one because of bankruptcy
de klerk noted that while the conservatives increased their winning margins compared to last year, national party support was stable. combined totals in the two rural transvaal districts wwere 15,478 votes for the conservatives and 11,830 for the nationalists, compared with 12,718 and 11,575 last year
andries treurnicht, conservative party leader, said the results would ``have a snowball effect'' in other elections
his party is favored to win a special election later this month and appears likely to cut into national party support in nationwide municipal contests in october
chris van der heever, chief conservative spokesman in transvaal, predicted the 6-year-old party would win control of local councils throughout rural transvaal and possibly in pretoria and blue-collar urban areas. he said the party also expects to do well in coastal areas, where many whites protested the recent opening of beaches to blacks
van der heever predicted the governing would put increasing emphasis on security and law-and-order issues. he and other conservatives suggested the view that botha's crackdown last week on anti-apartheid groups, which provoked international outrage, was an election gimmick
the independent pretoria news said in an editorial thursday: ``after being fed a diet of national party racism for decades, it is not surprising that the farmers ... voted for the old precepts of that party as espoused now by treurnicht.''
botha insists his reform program does not threaten white interests, which he pledges to protect through continued segregation of housing, schools and health services
it has few components so far
one would allow a limited number of multiracial neighborhoods, subject to approval by residents and the government. another, spurned by most prominent blacks, would form a ``national council'' where botha would negotiate a new constitution with black leaders to bring the racial majority into national politics
the national party has been in power since 1948 and has firm control of the 178-member house of assembly, with 133 seats to the conservatives' 22, but conservatives won 26 percent of the vote nationwide last may and expect to gain many more seats in the next general election. the anti-apartheid progressive federal party has 17 seats
separate parliament chambers for people of mixed race and those of indian descent were established in 1984, but have little power
both the national and conservative parties rely heavily on support from afrikaners, descendants of the dutch settlers who arrived in the 17th century. afrikaners make up about 60 percent of the white population
the city of nairobi is broke and it is raiding other budgets and intercepting employees' health fund contributions in order to continue providing essential services, it was reported thursday
j. musyoka-annan, the town clerk, told the kenya times that the city is owed about $38 million in unpaid rates and other charges. he did not say how much the city owed its creditors
in order to continue providing services to its 1.5 million residents, city officials have not been paying debts, forwarding employees' tax deductions to the government or paying their national health insurance fund contributions, musyoka annan said
he said officials are paying for other services by borrowing money from the world bank-financed water fund, which was set up to fund water projects in the city
property assessments, the city's only source of money, is not expanding and expenses are increasing, he said
president daniel arap moi dismissed elected councillors in 1982 and appointed a commision to run the city following public outcry over uncollected garbage, irregular hiring practices and mismanagement at city hall. says</head>
women who bear premature babies can provide more milk for their infants by not smoking, an agriculture department scientist reported thursday
physiologist judy m. hopkinson instructed mothers who delivered babies 8 to 12 weeks early to empty both breasts at least six times a day. she said 23 of the non-smoking mothers, or 80 percent, maintained enough milk after the infants went home. but only 3 of the 11 mothers who smoked, or 27 percent, continued to produce enough milk
hopkinson is located at the department's children's nutrition research center at baylor college of medicine in houston. her findings were reported here by the department's agricultural research service
in non-smokers, low milk production is usually due to ``mothers not pumping their breasts enough,'' she said. ``generally, it's not a physiological problem.''
but ``smokers have significantly lower milk volume than non-smokers,'' hopkinson said. the 11 smokers averaged 11 percent less milk during the first two weeks after giving birth and 40 percent less by the fourth week
the infants have to be tube-fed because they are too immature to suck and swallow, and ``mothers want to give them their milk,'' she said. ``it's one of the few things they can do, and it's a very emotional issue.''
but many women who deliver prematurely are not getting the appropriate information to produce enough milk, hopkinson said. most of the mothers can increase milk production by pumping more frequently. five times a day is enough to maintain volume, she said, and 8 to 10 times a day will increase milk volume within a week or two
hopkinson said mother's milk is preferred over formula or donor milk beckause it is more suited to the infant and may also enhance the infant's immunity to infections. even so, she said, for very low-birthweight babies, mother's milk must be fortified with extra protein and minerals, including calcium and phosphorous
shifting of a clay and limestone foundation is being considered as a possible cause of the ashland oil inc. oil tank collapse that fouled two rivers and threatened drinking water in parts of three states
we are looking at a number of things, including the quality of materials and possible issues surrounding the tank foundation,'' said matt hayman, spokesman for the national bureau of standards
two ashland contractors disagree about whether the stone and clay pad under the 4-million-gallon steel tank sank before the collapse or was eroded by escaping oil
workers began taking soil samples last saturday from the 120-foot diameter foundation that supported the tank bottom and will continue their search for clues next week, betsy mallison, spokeswoman for the state department of environmental resources, said wednesday
one of our researchers was there specifically to be included in the soil examination of the base,'' said hayman
the jan. 2 collapse allowed an estimated 730,000 gallons of oil to enter the monongahela river, which joins the allegheny river at pittsburgh to create the ohio river. about 23,000 suburban pittsburgh residents lost water service for most of the week after the collapse, and shutoffs were threatened in pennsylvania, ohio and west virginia towns that draw water from the ohio
employees of dennis jaskolski contracting co. helped dismantle the tank after it collapsed and found that portions of the foundation appeared to have sunk between 12 and 18 inches, said dennis jaskolski
after we moved the floor pieces off, you could see that a third of the foundation had dropped lower,'' he said
there appeared to be a defect in the stone base,'' jaskolski said. ``when the metal bottom was laying flat on top of it you couldn't see it, but then we started cutting up the floor.''
there is no visible settlement on the tank pad,'' said ralph zimmerman, whose company, ralph zimmerman excavating inc. of nearby clairton, laid the foundation
when the tank collapsed it ripped the bottom too, and where it ripped quite a bit of stone was washed out,'' he said
zimmerman said state and federal investigators questioned him about the work his company performed
bid specifications required a base of compacted clay 3 to 4 feet thick, topped by a foot of crushed limestone
ashland spokeswoman margaret thomson said company officials would not speculate on whether the foundation played any role in the collapse
others have speculated that the collapse might be traced to metal fatigue in the 45-year-old steel used for the tank, freezing temperatures the day of the accident or problems with vents in the tank. work</head>
the owner of a nursing home has been indicted on charges he induced 11 irish nationals to illegally enter the united states and work for him without permits, federal officials said today
a federal indictment handed up wednesday alleges that peter h. starr persuaded the 11 nurses' aides and orderlies to quit their jobs and move to the united states even though he was told that it was unlikely they would be granted work permits
starr, 35, of scituate, owner of the queene anne nursing home in hingham, allegedly recruited the workers through advertisements in a dublin newspaper. after receiving 75 responses, he traveled to dublin to interview the applicants before offering jobs to 11 of them, the indictment alleged
in may 1977, he applied for temporary permits allowing the 11 to enter the united states and work
starr was informed by the state division of employment security, which processes the applications for the federal labor department, that it was unlikely the requests would be granted. but then starr allegedly told the workers to obtain tourist visas and falsely state on their applications that they never had requested permission to work in the united states
the irish nationals are cooperating with investigators and likely would be witnesses if starr is brought to trial, u.s. attorney frank mcnamara jr. said
charles t. cobb, district director of the immigration and naturalization service, said the 11 men and women have been granted permission to remain in the united states until august and could request resident status. they range in age from the low 20s to 38, said cobb, who refused to release their names
starr faces up to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine if convicted.  
a travel agency owner who allegedly bilked customers out of $5 million disappeared from a cruise ship shortly before a mutiny of its crew in central america, passengers say
fernando inigo, the agency owner, left the cruise ship galazy before dawn in puerto quetzal, guatemala, promising crew members he would reboard in costa rica with money to pay them, passengers told the houston chronicle
crew members refused to continue working when they weren't paid
inigo and his wife, lorna, of san antonio are two of five defendants named in a lawsuit filed last week by the texas attorney general's office against golden cruisetours inc. and two of its affiliates
the three other defendants _ fernando mendrillo, fermin gutierrez and manuel fernandez _ only maintain postal boxes in san antonio, officials said
a hearing on the lawsuit is scheduled for friday in san antonio
assistant texas attorney general raul noriega, who said he had visited the inigos' house in san antonio, said neighbors have not seen the couple for several weeks
they appeared to have taken some possessions and left, noriega said. their child was removed from school, and the family's cars remained in the driveway
morris j. kirschberg, attorney for golden cruisetours, declined to comment on the case earlier this week but said through a secretary that he has not heard from the inigos since the lawsuit was filed
after the vessel left costa rica and passed through the panama canal, the galaxy's captain had all passengers leave the ship in panama city on feb. 21
the galaxy is owned by global cruises of panama, one of the affiliates named in the suit, of which inigo owns 5 percent, noriega said
he (inigo) was very nervous,'' said galaxy passenger dorothy c. hayes. ``we were told he wasn't feeling well.''
ms. hayes said inigo talked with her and other passengers before leaving the ship. ``he said that he had to leave in guatemala to meet with his bankers (in guatemala city) and then he would catch up with the ship in costa rica,'' she said. he never showed up, she added
in a letter to the associated press, passenger peggy enger of lakewood, colo., described conditions on the ship when passengers first boarded feb. 11 in acapulco
we entered into the main lobby, it was filthy, carpet was oil streaked, it smelled of diesel fuel,'' mrs. enger wrote
because of failures in the air conditioning system, cruise officials said only 50 passengers could sail, she said
i couldn't believe under those conditions that anyone would have signed up,'' mrs. enger said. she and her husband decided against sailing with the ship, which she said left port feb. 12, a day behind schedule
an attorney general's audit of golden cruisetours in january determined that the company had booked a high percentage of 36 future cruises on the galaxy, noriega said. each cruise carries about 200 passengers each; the cost was $1,500 cash in advance. a conservative estimate of receipts from would-be passengers on future cruises was $5 million, he said
improvements in the nation's efficiency in churning out goods and services slowed by almost half last year despite revised figures showing higher output in the the fourth quarter, the government said thursday
the labor department said productivity among non-farm businesses responsible for three-fourths of the nation's economic activity rose at an annual rate of 0.3 percent in the fourth quarter in contrast to a deterioration of 0.2 percent reported in preliminary figures last month
the revisions raised the productivity improvement for the entire year from 0.8 percent to 0.9 percent, slightly more than half the 1.6 percent gain of 1986, despite the lowest hourly labor cost increases in more than four decades
the efficiency improvements for the year were the smallest since 1982, when an economic recession depressed output so much that productivity actually declined 0.6 percent from 1981
anything less than 1 percent is a disappointing number,'' said roger brinner, an economist for data resources inc. of lexington, mass. ``it gives you very little room to buffer pay increases and not much leeway to improve the standard of living.''
the revised figures showed output of goods and services by non-farm businesses _ which account for about three-fourths of the nation's economic production _ rising by an annual rate of 5.6 percent in the fourth quarter
that is the greatest increase in nearly two years and compares with a rise of 5.1 percent in the preliminary figures before the gross national product was revised upward last week by the commerce department
but in achieving that higher output, businesses increased the total hours worked by their employees by 5.3 percent
brinner said that reflects an increase of 3 million in the number of americans with jobs last year and ``gives you an indication that we may have an employment glut as well as an output glut'' as seen in the high level of unsold inventories
still, the higher output helped reduce the annualized increase in labor costs associated with each unit of goods or services in the fourth quarter from 3.7 percent in the preiminary figures to 3.1 percent in the final ones, the labor department said
despite figures showing that hourly wages rose an average 2.8 percent for all of last year, workers still lost 0.8 percent of their income for each hour they worked after taking inflation into account, according to the revised statistics
manufacturing workers fared even worse. their average wage increases of 1.3 percent dropped their purchasing power after inflation by 2.2 percent for the year
productivity in manufacturing improved 3.3 percent over the year _ unchanged from the preliminary figures _ with output up 4.3 percent on only a 1 percent increase in the number of hours worked
that combination dropped the labor costs associated with each product coming out of the nation's factories by an average 1.9 percent in 1987, the report said
frankly, we don't foresee much improvement in productivity this year,'' said donald straszheim, chief economist for merrill lynch. ``productivity improvements require rapid growth and we haven't been experiencing much of that lately.''
an illegal alien deported to mexico died a day later while trying to cross back into the united states, officials said
police said juan lopez cruz, 28, was killed instantly wednesday when he fell off a catwalk under the tex-mex railroad bride as he attempted to cross into the united states near downtown laredo
a railroad official estimated the distance to the ground as 35 feet
members of a group of aliens who were also attempting to cross the border told police they met cruz on the mexican side of the rio grande. he offered to show them how to get across the railroad bridge, they said
the witnesses told police cruz was walking ahead of the group when he suddenly fell. the group of about five, which included some children, continued on the catwalk, crossing successfully, and notified a security officer of the accident, police said
the other aliens were turned over to the u.s. border patrol for deportation
officials said cruz had been picked up by u.s. immigration officials in san antonio and was deported tuesday. laredo police said they would contact the u.s. immigration office in san antonio for more information on the victim. woman</head>
aretha franklin, long ago canonized as the queen of soul music, has become the all-time biggest female grammy winner with 14 awards
before wednesday night's telecast of the 30th annual grammy awards show from radio city music hall, franklin fell behind opera diva leontyne price and jazz great ella fitzgerald, who held 13 and 12 trophies respectively
franklin soared ahead after picking up prizes for best female rhythm and blues vocalist for her lp, ``aretha,'' and with george michael for best rhythm and blues performance by a duo for their single, ``i knew you were waiting (for me).''
still, she has a long way to go to overtake grammy's all-time top winner, sir georg solti, conductor of the chicago symphony, whose recording of beethoven's 9th symphony won a grammy for best orchestral recording and raised his lifetime total to 26
vladimir horowitz, the pianist who had 20 grammys entering the ceremonies, won two more for best classical instrumental performance and best classical album for ``horowitz in moscow.'' he also received the president's special merit award from the academy
horowitz is followed on the list by composer henry mancini, with 20 awards; producer-musician quincy jones with 19; pop-rhythm and blues superstar stevie wonder with 17; composer john t. williams with 15; franklin with 14; price with 13; fitzgerald tied in 9th place with singer-songwriter paul simon with 12 grammys each; and conductor pierre boulez in 10th place with 11 trophies
the ptl television ministry said thursday it is banking on a telethon to help it make quarterly payments to the internal revenue service ordered by a federal bankruptcy judge
the fort mill-based ministry, hit by hard times since the fall of founders jim and tammy bakker, was ordered by u.s. bankrupcty judge rufus reynolds to make payments of $550,000 to the irs every three months to settle tax debts
reynolds settled on the amount wednesday after the irs argued for payments of $800,000 a quarter and ptl agreed to payments of $300,000 a quarter. the first payment is due may 2
it looks like the projections indicate we'll be able to meet the may 2nd obligation,'' said m.c. ``red'' benton, the ministry's executive vice president
the success in meeting the payments will greatly depend on a ptl telethon that began monday and will run through the end of march with the goal of raising $4.5 million above normal donations, he said
the payment is meant to be an interim settlement on ptl's debt to the irs and could be adjusted each quarter if necessary, reynolds ruled
the irs has said the total tax bill is between $61.8 and $82 million, while ptl has maintained the bill is closer to $5 million
determination of the final bill is still before the u.s. bankruptcy court, which has been handling the case since ptl filed for reorganization june 12
in a separate action last week, attorneys for the irs and ptl argued in u.s. district court over reynold's decision to prevent the tax agency from revoking ptl's tax exempt status while the ministry reorganizes. a ruling in that case is expectedsoon
ptl's bankruptcy trustee, david clark, told reynolds on wednesday that the ministry is ``in a period of transition away from the celebrity preacher.''
we will be seen by the audience as somewhat different, something fresh, as a ministry that they can have confidence in,'' he said
also wednesday, benton told the court that the ministry was considering selling some of the 1,600 to 1,700 acres of unused land it owns around its heritage usa christian retreat
we want to talk to realtors about how we can best market'' the land, benton told reynolds. ``we'll have to develop a plan for you.''
reynolds, though, cautioned ptl officials against selling developable land with a high money-making potential
reynolds said heritage usa could become self-sufficient apart from income generated by the ptl television ministry
are you going to abandon the christian city?'' the judge asked
we're still interested in having a christian city, a christian retreat,'' benton said
but benton said afterwards the ministry is trying to decide whether it wants to continue in the business of building homes
clark now oversees the ministry begun by the bakkers, who resigned last year in the middle of a sex scandal that continues to have repercussions in the world of televangelism
a prisoner who escaped 10 years ago from the federal women's prison here apparently lived a crime-free life in arizona using an acquaintance's identification cards, federal officials said
mary hughey cantrell, who was 30 when she failed to return from a 1977 christmas furlough, pleaded guilty wednesday to a charge of escape from the alderson federal correctional institution
she will be held at the prison pending her april 22 sentencing, federal officials said thursday. the charge carries a maximum five-year sentence and a $5,000 fine
federal public defender ira kirkendoll said cantrell went to arizona shortly after her escape and worked for several years as a maid in private homes and resorts
cantrell was arrested jan. 5 in phoenix, ariz., after the internal revenue service spotted a discrepancy in income tax returns for a harriet walker, cantrell's acquaintance, who had never worked in arizona
officials said they didn't know how cantrell gained possession of walker's identification or where walker lived
it's pretty unusual, the length of time,'' kirkendoll said after u.s. district judge elizabeth hallanan accepted cantrell's plea. ``apparently she has reformed to some degree.''
assistant u.s. attorney kirk brandfass said the woman's decade of crime-free living, aside from maintaining a false identity, should be considered at sentencing
my heavens, that ought to count for something,'' the prosecutor said outside hallanan's court in beckley
u.s. marshals wouldn't allow an interview with cantrell, who was sentenced to three years after a 1975 conviction for passing counterfeit money. cantrell, who still has about 470 days to serve on her original sentence, was paroled in may 1976 but was returned to the prison in early 1977 after a parole violation
the transportation department proposed a wide range of drug tests thursday for more than a half million airline employees from pilots to mechanics, although officials acknowledged they have no clear evidence of a drug problem in the industry
announcement of the drug testing program, which would go into effect after what may be a lengthy rulemaking process, came amid conflicting court cases on whether such tests are legal. a federal judge earlier this week declared random drug tests of civilian army employees as unconstitutional
but transportation secretary jim burnley said drug testing _ especially random testing _ ``is absolutely critical'' in the aviation industry to make certain travelers are not endangered by a flight crew member, mechanic or other employee in a safety-sensitive job being impaired by drugs
we can't wait for weeks and months while these (drug testing) cases wind themselves through the courts,'' burnley told a news conference. he said he was confident the department's testing program would eventually meet the court's approval
the union representing more than 40,000 airline pilots accused burnley of ``headline grabbing'' and questioned the need for a drug testing program in an industry where no drug problem has been shown
there's never been a scheduled air carrier accident in the united states that has been attributed to drugs,'' declared roger hall, a vice president of the air line pilots association. he promised to challenge any random drug testing rule in the courts when it becomes final
the association of flight attendants, which has 23,000 members, also criticized the broad scope of the department's testing proposal and said there see no justification for random testing
we're opposed to random testing. there's never been an incident where flight attendants have performed poorly in an evacuation because of drugs,'' said matthew finucane, the union's safety director
while burnley provided no specific evidence to show a problem with drug use among commercial airline employees, he insisted ``there isn't any reason to believe that aviation has been exempted'' from a problem that is widespread in society
i'm not going to wait until we have a mid-air collision because a pilot is impaired or we lose a plane because a maintenance persons (is on drugs) on the ground,'' said burnley
the transportation department estimates that 511,000 airline industry employees would be subject to the various drug tests called for in the proposed regulation. the employees include more than 50,000 pilots flying regularly scheduled commercial aircraft, 86,000 flight attendants and 297,500 aircraft mechanics
other airline workers that would be subject to the tests include cockpit crew members such as flight engineers and navigators, aircraft dispatchers and security personnel who work at screening checkpoints at airports
under the proposal, employees would be subject to a pre-employment test, periodic testing whenever a person is taking a physical, post-accident testing and random testing as well as test for reasonable cause. an employ would be subject to an initial test on a sample of urine and a more sophisticated test if the first test shows the presence of drugs
the airlines or other employers would have to submit a testing plan to the transportation department within 180 days after a final rule is issued. burnley said he expected a final rule before the end of the year, although he declined to be more specific
drug testing, especially random testing, is absolutely critical in our efforts to create a drug-free aviation system for the american people,'' said burnley. ``no matter how stringent our safety regulations ... all it takes is one person on drugs in one of these sensitive airline jobs to endanger the lives of hundreds of innocent people.''
the department's regulation covering airline employees has been expected for months. burnley's predecessor, elizabeth dole, called for increased testing in all modes of transportation after drugs were implicated in the jan. 4, 1987 collision of a freight train and an amtrak passenger train. the crash near baltimore killed 16 people and injured 170
burnley said the proposed regulation covering airline employees would be followed by similar proposals covering other transportation employees including railroad workers and commercial truck drivers
the proposal does not cover private, so-called ``general aviation'' pilots. burnley said the department sought to limit the scope of the testing requirement to airline employees involved in carrying commercial passengers
there have been a variety of drug-testing cases heard in the federal courts with conflicting decisions
a federal appeals court, for example, has upheld random drug testing of certain transportation department employees including air traffic controllers. but another appeals court on tuesday knocked down similar testing of civilian army employees. a federal court in san francisco, meanwhile, has declared post-accident drug testing of railroad workers as being unconstitutional
last monday the u.s. supreme court, in what is expected to be a critical case, agreed to hear an appeal involving random testing of u.s. customs service employees. a lower court had ruled in favor of the customs service employees, who had challenged the tests
four canadian and nine soviet skiers set off thursday under a hazy, primrose-colored arctic sunset to cross the north pole and make a statement about east-west cooperation
the 13 men face not only a 1,073-mile trek, but also must eat and sleep in the same tent for 100 days
the journey got off to a late and rocky start from the snowy fields of ice floes that link this northernmost tip of the archipelago known as severnaya zemlya _ which means ``northern land'' _ with the polar ice cap
their faith was tested on the eve of thier departure when expedition leader dmitri shparo proposed expanding the soviet team to nine members
it was an 11th-hour decision,'' said canadian team leader richard weber, revealing some of the uncertainty his countrymen felt in allowing a further shifting of numbers in favor of the soviets. ``but when we sat down, we couldn't come up with any good reasons why not.''
weber and shparo met with western and soviet reporters at a remote encampment on sredny island, 93 miles south of this departure point
shparo termed the canadian concession ``magnanimous.''
weber said shparo informed him wednesday that he didn't want to cut from the team any of the soviets who had been in training
by morning, which arrives late on the severnaya zemlya, spirits were high and the explorers lumbered through crowded barracks weighing packs and redistributing gear
an mi-6 helicopter shuttled the skiers and a small group of journalists to the starting point, a windswept jumble of ice floes frozen into a single white expanse that stretches 1,240 miles to the canadian arctic
the rev. laurie dexter of fort smith, northwest territories, an anglican minister, stood on a snowy ridge overlooking the solid field that is the arctic ocean and called on ``the faith we have in each other'' to take his fellow skiers safely across the pole and into a new age of understanding
the men, bundled in red suits trimmed with dog fur and sponsors' logos, sped off at 2:30 p.m. as the sun hung just over the horizon
the expedition will continue to canada's cape columbia, with an arrival scheduled for early june
the route has been covered in two parts by members of separate teams, but this is the first attempt at a transcontinental crossing of the pole
the joint expedition was planned for 1980, but the canadians abandoned the attempt when soviet troops drove into afghanistan in december 1979
shparo, 46, led the first soviet polar ski trek in 1979, and weber, 28, of old chesea, ontario, covered the cape columbia-north pole segment in 1986
the most interesting part for me will be the social factor of being in a very small tent with a large number of people for a very long time,'' weber told reporters who visited the ski team's headquarters in dickson, the soviet arctic circle settlement that is the northernmost city in the world
dexter said the tent measures about 14.8 feet square
there are inevitably frayed nerves and tensions, but all of us are experienced enough and mature enough to let those things pass and get on with the expedition,'' he said. talks</head>
pakistan and afghanistan agreed thursday on a nine-month timetable for the withdrawal of red army troops from afghanistan and said half the soviet soldiers should be out of the country in the first 90 days
the two points had long hindered progress toward a settlement aimed at ending nine years of fighting in afghanistan, where an estimated 115,000 soviet troops are backing the government against moslem guerrillas
but a u.n. report released thursday warned that success at the geneva talks could leave another primary problem unresolved: the return of more than 5 million afghan refugees who have fled to neighboring pakistan and iran
the report said the refugees are unlikely to return unless the afghan government of president najib is replaced by one that includes opposition and refugee representation
that didn't dampen the optimism of afghan foreign minister abdul wakil, who told reporters, ``nothing important stands in the way of concluding a settlement. from our side, things could be regarded as finalized.''
he said u.n. officials had established that ``all refugees want to return.''
agreement on the withdrawal timetable had been widely expected
when the u.n.-mediated talks began nearly six years ago, moscow offered a four-year withdrawal span and gradually lowered this
last month, soviet leader mikhail gorbachev said the estimated 115,000 red army troops could be out of afghanistan within 10 months starting in mid-may if a geneva settlment was signed by the middle of this month
wakil said he was confident that remaining ``other issues,'' which he did not specify, also would be resolved, provided ``pakistan could abide by the tacit and formal agreement not to raise anything new.''
pakistan represents the insurgents in the talks
pakistan has said that a successful settlement must be accompanied by formation of a broad-based transitional government to replace the afghan government
pakistan's chief delegate, acting foreign minister zain noorani, reaffirmed that position to reporters after meeting with mediator diego cordovez, who shuttled between the two sides for 2{ hours thursday
we are firmly convinced that a settlement without creating circumstances of peace and stability in afghanistan will not persuade 5 million afghan refugees to return,'' noorani said. he did not name any specific time limit as to when that government should be in office
noorani planned to return to islamabad for a weekend of consultations between the goverment and political leaders. he said pakistan would then decide whether it was prepared to sign a settlement with the najib government, which pakistan does not recognize
wakil reiterated that najib's policy of national reconciliation envisaged a ``coalition government'' open to all political forces, including the pakistan-based resistance movements
the resistance movements, claiming to represent about 200,000 guerrillas, have rejected any power-sharing with najib. they have presented a plan of their own for an islamic government
wakil also took issue with the u.n. report, prepared for the 43-nation u.n. human rights commission. it voiced reservations about kabul's plans for a ``national front'' of the various parties that would have a leading role in charting policies. it noted that such umbrella bodies exist in soviet bloc countries
wakil said the national front envisaged by kabul could not be compared with those existing in czechoslovakia and east germany. these, he said, came into being long ago and ``under completely different circumstances.'' stallone</head>
actress brigitte nielsen says she has no regrets about marrying sylvester stallone _ it was good for business
i have more success than i've ever had,'' nielsen, who has since split from the ``rocky'' star, says in the march 21 issue of us magazine. ``so whatever i have done, i must have done something right because i'm doing good, and more important, i feel good.''
she adds that ``my business was terrific whether i was married or not'' but ``it might have taken longer'' to make it if she had not married the actor
to stay on top, you have got to have personality and talent,'' she says. ``then it doesn't matter who you were married to.''
adding that she wants to be taken seriously, nielsen says it is ``frustrating to be seen as a bimbo.''
nielsen is engaged to jets defensive lineman mark gastineau
communities that once relied on a single industry for jobs and looked to corporate mangers for leadership must diversify their economies and take charge of their destinies, urban planners said thursday at an international symposium
before, like it or not, companies took care of life. you may not have liked everyting they did. but they were there. it was secure,'' said john clarke, a trenton, n.j., architect who headed a team that studied depressed mill towns in this once mighty steelmaking region
but when that goes away, suddenly you turn around and say, `gee, the leadership used to be the company.' now the leadership has to be you,'' clarke said at the international remaking cities conference
it's a painful transition experienced by older industrial centers worldwide, the experts said
the trend is inescapable in that we're moving from an industrial, manufacturing economy into a service economy,'' said james franklin, an architect and land planner with american institute of architects
there are many cities that already face the same problem and will continue to face it for a period of time,'' he said
the four-day conference is exploring ways to revitalize aging industrial cities in the united states and great britain
britain's prince charles, honorary chairman of the meeting, will get a first-hand look friday at the dispair and disrepair of the mill towns lining the monongahela river south of pittsburgh
an outspoken advocate of inner-city rehabilitation, the prince plans to visit a new jobs center for the region's blue-collar unemployed and a high school computer training classroom
on saturday he will address the approximately 350 people attending the conference, sponsored by the american institute of architects and royal institute of british architects
in his speech, the 39-year-old heir to the british throne is expected to comment on the recommendations made by conference delegates for revitalizing cities
the mayors are asking us ... do they have a right to determine land use and a right to determine the future development of the community. these communities have got to learn that'' their leaders have not only the right but the obligation to influence the use of former mill sites, clarke said
they've been so much under the mantle of the steel industry that their sense of the company town was so great that there was very little sense that they could in fact control what they had to do with an economy,'' said charles zucker, community planning consultant with the american institute of architects in washington, d.c., and a member of clarke's planning team
in its 120-page report, presented monday after a four-day study of area communities, the 17-member team recommended ``the greening of american industry'' with parks, gardens, marinas and shops to replace darkened hulks dominating the riverbank
although drawing praise from many, the report was criticized by those waiting and praying for the resurrection of the steel industry
the general feeling is ``you're getting a garden. you're getting flowers. you're getting no jobs,'' said tony mcgann, a community planner from liverpool, england, and another team member
in our area, we didn't want to see shipping die. we didn't want to see the shipping factories die. but they all died. they never came back,'' he said. ``so people who are waiting for steel to come back, they live in a cuckoo land.''
public participation is a key to success in urban planning, the conference participants said
we've seen what happens when nothing happens'' and when outsiders' views are thrust upon communities, said raymond rhinehart, a spokesman for the american institute of architects
no one, least of all urban planners, want regions to forget their industrial heritage. that's why the planning team suggested that several ironmaking furnaces near pittsburgh become museums
but there's another motive
displays of equipment used in the ``heroic and hard old days,'' make it clearer that ``you need to rethink you goals and move on with your life,'' franklin said
farmers who participated in last year's feed grain program will get about $1.45 billion in government ``deficiency'' payments this month, the agriculture department said thursday
milton hertz, executive vice president of the department's commodity credit corp., said the payments will included about $1.3 billion for corn farmers and $225 million for sorghum producers
the subsidies will be paid in generic certificates, which can be redeemed for ccc-owned surplus commodities
under the program, deficiency payments are required when average market prices fall below a prescribed target price. the payments make up the difference between the target and the market price or support level, whichever is higher
in addition to the $1.45 billion due this month, corn producers received about $2.6 billion in advance payments for 1987 participation, and sorghum producers got advances of $225 million
a white house conference on fighting drugs ended thursday with the chairwoman exhorting representatives to return to their communities to fight the scourge of drugs
lois haight herrington called for a ``final assault'' on drugs in the last year of the reagan administration
those interested in eliminating drugs cannot ``give themselves the luxury'' of relaxing after the three-day conference for a drug-free america because ``dealers, users and smugglers'' are ``waiting to see us let down, become distracted,'' ms. harrington said
members of the conference will present recommendations to president reagan, she said
the conference turned into a critique of the administration's record on what is being done. several speakers, including a member of reagan's cabinet, said that not enough is being done to eliminate drugs
we need to get away from a policy of containment,'' said rep. clay shaw, r-fla. ``we want you to come up with a plan for victory. let's fight it like we fought world war ii, not like vietnam. let's fight to win.''
a group of republican senators on thursday demanded that senate rules be changed to make it more difficult to arrest absent senators, the fate of sen. bob packwood last week when he missed a quorum call
their ``sense of the senate'' resolution proposed a rule change that would prohibit the seizure of an absent senator between 11 p.m. and 8 a.m. ``unless the pending business is of a compelling nature.''
the senate sergeant-at-arms arrested packwood, r-ore., in his office at about 1:30 a.m. last wednesday when he and most other republicans fled the chamber to prevent the senate from establishing a quorum. a quorum of 51 senators was needed to keep the senate in session, and the republicans were trying to end an all-night debate on a campaign spending bill
packwood literally was carried into the senate chamber by u.s. capitol police detectives accompanied by sergeant-at-arms henry giugni. giugni had been ordered to bring senators to the floor by a 45-3 vote of senators who were present
packwood's unique arrival gave the democrats a quorum and the senate remained in session all night
packwood seemed to take his arrest in good humor and later appeared at a news conference with giugni, laughing about the incident
other republicans were not amused. sen. malcolm wallop, r-wyo., complained thursday that the incident meant senators might have to remain in hiding in their offices. ``senators should not have to make a decision whether to leave the light on in your office at night,'' he said
senate majority leader robert byrd, d-w.va., who had made the original motion that absent senators be arrested, said thursday: ``we bored the american people today with almost four hours of talk about the `tough life' of senators.'' he called the discussion ``a tale of woe'' and suggested ``there are several million americans who would be glad to trade places with us.''
byrd criticized the resolution, citing the provision that would limit late-night arrest warrants other than for ``compelling'' reasons. ``who's to determine that?'' byrd said. ``the senate determines that and it determined that the other evening.''
the resolution, which was referred to the rules committee, also proposed that any arrest warrant include ``a written statement establishing the reasons for arrest.''
sponsors were sens. alan simpson of wyoming, john chafee of rhode island, william armstrong of colorado, rudy boschwitz of minnesota, thad cochran of mississippi, arlen specter and john heinz of pennsylvania, dan quayle of indiana, mitch mcconnell of kentucky, kit bond of missouri, dan evans of washington, robert kasten of wisconsin, alfonse d'amato of new york, gordon humphrey of new hampshire, jake garn of utah and wallop
tamil rebels dressed as soldiers raided a village and killed 16 people, most of them women or children, a military official said thursday
he said the tamils attacked with automatic weapons wednesday at morawewa village, 27 miles west of trincomalee port on the island nation's eastern coast
on thursday, three rebels were reported killed in a gun battle with police at a roadblock in the southeast. police chief s. wijesinghe of the ampara district said there were no police casualties
the officer reporting the morawewa raid said nine children, four women and three men were killed and three people wounded
all the dead were of the sinhalese ethnic majority except for one tamil, he said, speaking on condition of anonymity in accordance with police regulations. he blamed the attack on members of the liberation tigers of tamil eelam, the largest rebel group
members of the tigers militia led a four-year ethnic war for a separate tamil homeland. they were blamed for the killings of more than 200 sinhalese in october last year soon after the tigers renounced a peace accord designed to end the war
more than 8,000 people have been killed in the ethnic conflict, which began in 1983
tamils make up 18 percent of the country's 16 million people and most are hindus. they claim discrimination by the majority sinhalese, who are predominantly buddhist and control the government and army
political television ads grew more negative as well as more plentiful thursday with sen. albert gore jr. and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis going on the attack for the first time less than a week before super tuesday
gore, dukakis and vice president george bush all sent out critical ads in many of the 20 states holding primaries and caucuses next week
gore launched the first tv attack of his campaign, a pointed 60-second excerpt from the feb. 18 democratic debate in dallas
within those 60 seconds, gore accuses gephardt of voting against minimum wage increases, against creating the department of education, for tuition tax credits and for reagonomics _ and reversing his positions on all four issues
the next president of the united states has to be someone the american people can believe will stay with his convictions. ... you've got to be willing to stand your ground and be consistent,'' gore says
a gephardt spokeswoman said there would be no direct response to the gore ad
gephardt has been running commercials criticizing both gore and dukakis for several days in super tuesday states. dukakis began responding wednesday night with an ad assaulting gephardt's populist message that ``it's your fight too.''
the dukakis ad consists of a rolling list of corporate political action committees that have contributed to gephardt's campaign. ``is dick gephardt really fighting your fight, or theirs?'' asks the narrator. dukakis does not accept pac contributions
gephardt, making a stop at baltimore-washington international airport, called the dukakis ad ``absolutely ridiculous'' and said only 5 percent of his overall contributions are from pacs
he said all of his pac contributions were fully disclosed, and he charged that dukakis has received millions of dollars ``from special interests who do business with the state of massachusetts.''
it raises the specter of a serious conflict of interest,'' gephardt said and added that his campaign would release a partial list of those contributors friday
responding to gephardt's response, dukakis aide leslie dach said, ``the dukakis campaign does not take a dime of corporate pac money or any money from a lobbyist registered in the state of massachusetts.''
bush also joined the negative fray with an ad appearing in south carolina, which holds a gop primary on saturday. the ad denounces senate republican leader bob dole for not being able to get judge robert bork's supreme court nomination confirmed by the senate. and it says dole has failed to vote with the reagan administration 30 percent of the time
the candidates stepping up their media campaigns in the final stretch included bush and dukakis with their bulging campaign coffers and jesse jackson who has borrowed money to keep his presidential drive going
dukakis put tv ads in six additional super tuesday states between wednesday and thursday, bringing his total to nine _ north carolina, georgia, alabama, arkansas, oklahoma, washington, florida, texas and maryland
bush's ad director, sig rogich, said the vice president has been running ads in florida, texas, south carolina and most other super tuesday states. ``you'll see more of our ads now in the last few days before super tuesday,'' he said
jackson planned to start $100,000 worth of tv ads friday in eight southern states. the tv purchase, jackson's largest so far, targets alabama, florida, louisiana, mississippi, north carolina, south carolina, texas and virginia
dole's latest negative ad attacks bush for supporting reagan's veto of a protectionist textile trade bill and mocks his explanation: ``c'est la vie.''
frank fahrenkopf jr., chairman of the republican national committee, said the bush-dole match has become ``pretty rough'' but that that is not all bad, as long as they keep their advertising accurate
in many ways i've welcomed what's happened,'' fahrenkopf told reporters in boston. ``in january i was concerned with the lack of fire in the belly.''
soldier of fortune magazine was negligent in publishing a classified ad that led to the contract killing of a texas woman and should pay $9.4 million to the victim's family, a federal jury said thursday
gary wayne black, 18, and marjorie eimann, 64, filed the suit seeking $22.5 million from the self-styled ``journal for professional adventurers.''
sandra black, gary's mother and mrs. eimann's daughter, was shot to death feb. 21, 1985 at her home in bryan
an attorney for the magazine said it would appeal the verdict
considering the evidence the jury was presented, and the fact that we weren't allowed to present all our evidence, we're disappointed but not surprised,'' attorney larry thompson said
this fight goes three rounds like a lot of first amendment cases. we lost the first round, but put your money on us in the next two rounds.''
jurors said the magazine should pay $1.5 million to black and $400,000 to mrs. eimann. the two received $7.5 million in punitive damages. the jury heard testimony for two weeks and deliberated 12 hours
mrs. eimann shook hands and hugged the six jurors and said, ``i just want to thank every one of you for doing what you did for sandra. we loved her so much.''
mrs. black's husband, robert, is on texas' death row for paying john wayne hearn $10,000 to kill her. hearn is serving three life terms in florida for the black slaying and two others in that state
black contacted hearn through a personal services classified ad offering the services of vietnam veterans. hearn placed the advertisement in soldier of fortune in late 1984 and it appeared in four issues
the ad read, ``ex marines. '67-69 nam vets. ex-di, weapons specialist _ jungle warfare. pilot. me. high-risk assignments. u.s. or overseas.'' it also provided a telephone number
attorneys for the boulder, colo.-based magazine and its parent company, omega group ltd., did not dispute that the ad brought hearn and black together, but insisted magazine executives had no way of knowing the ad was for illegal activity
magazine attorneys insisted the responsibility for mrs. black's death rested with her husband and hearn and not the magazine
soldier of fortune witnesses defended the publication as a legitimate military journal, saying the personal services classified ads were run to provide employment for vietnam veterans who had difficulty finding work and wanted to do bodyguard work, security duty or mercenary fighting overseas
witnesses for the plaintiffs contended the ad's reference to ``high-risk assignments'' meant hearn and others using similar words in ads were making themselves available for criminal activity
a criminologist testified the personal services classified ads section _ dropped in 1986 _ appealed to paranoids
late in the trial, attorneys for the plaintiffs discovered that james graves, the magazine's managing editor, had signed an affidavit in a 1982 murder-for-hire case linked to the magazine's ads
his action was contrary to the insistence of magazine officials, who contended no one at soldier of fortune knew of any crimes linked to the classified ads. house</head>
nasa administrator james c. fletcher went to capitol hill thursday to argue for an $11.5 billion space budget but listened instead as space committee members complained that their recommendations were being ignored by the committee that holds the purse strings
i'm not so certain that anything we say in these hearings is going to make much difference,'' said rep. robert walker of pennsylvania, the ranking republican member of the house science &amp; technology subcommittee on space science and applications
there is an attitude in the budget committee at the present time that nasa will get no more money this year than they got last year,'' he said
the national aeronautics and space administration, trying to recover from the january 1986 challenger shuttle accident and gearing up for a start on a manned space station, will spend an estimated $8.9 billion this year, far below what the agency had requested
nasa had asked $767 million to begin the space station and but received just $425 million. president reagan's budget for 1989 would give the agency $11.5 billion, but lawmakers at thursday's hearing said no amount approaching that would be approved by the house appropriations committee, which sends legislation for spending to the full house
fletcher told the subcommittee that the budget now being considered could make or break the nation's space program
it is not an overstatement to say that the future of the u.s. civil space program rides at risk in this budget,'' he said
no one on the committee argued with him. but walker and others suggested that nasa had to do a better job in selling itself to the rest of congress
it seems to me they (nasa) have to bring people of credibility, like astronauts, to go in and buttonhole members of congress and explain the facts of life,'' he said. ``it seems to me that nasa is going to have to begin to get awfully aggressive in how the nasa budget is presented.''
walker said the american people are willing to support a rational space program but ``there is no pressure being felt on capitol hill at the present time, none whatsoever.''
rep. george brown, d-calif., a strong space program booster, talked of ``erratic funding'' for the space program
that is not the way to develop a strong, world-class program,'' he said. ``while these cuts have been happening, the military program doubled or tripled.''
rep. bill nelson of florida, the subcommittee chairman, said ``there is only one person who can really lead the nation's space program and that is the duly elected leader of this nation. the nation's space pgoram is going to depend on the degree of commitment coming from president reagan in this next year.''
fletcher protested that reagan is committed to the budget, that ``it is not a half-hearted budget.''
to that, nelson responded: ``i'm talking about real deeds as well as words. i'm talking about threats of vetoes that are real threats; i'm talking about sitting down at the table and working with the congressional leadership.''
contra leaders agreed thursday to meet their sandinista foes inside nicaragua, but insisted on the participation of cardinal miguel obando y bravo, who has drawn objections from nicaraguan president daniel ortega
we are accepting a face-to-face meeting in nicaraguan territory,'' director alfredo cesar said in a communique after a daylong meeting of the directorate
the contras thursday appointed adolfo calero, considered to be one of the more hardline directors, to head their delegation
ortega has proposed that the talks take place in southern nicaragua with his brother, defense minister humberto ortega, heading the sandinista delegation
the contras also said that obando y bravo, who was dismissed by ortega as a mediator after two previous negotiating sessions, must be present as a ``witness and guarantor.''
cardinal obando y bravo represents the only moral authority in nicaragua that can guarantee compliance'' with the peace agreement reached last year by the five central american presidents, cesar said
ortega had suggested that the meeting be held in the town of sapoa near nicaragua's costa rican border on march 10-12, but cesar said the time and place should be worked out later
he said guarantees of the contra delegation's safe passage must also established before the meeting
the communique signed by the five directors of the nicaraguan resistance, as the contra rebels are formally called, lambasted ortega for dismissing obando y bravo as a mediator
it called the action ``unilateral and dictatorial,'' and praised the cardinal of managua for his help in getting the peace talks going
the contras had been the first to propose talks inside nicaragua, which the sandinistas inititally rejected. now that the sandinistas have reversed their position, they must demonstrate their sincerity, said cesar
it would be very difficult for them to put this on the table as a bluff,'' he said. ``public opinion is going to be judging all these actions.''
the communique said the talks in nicaragua should be based on the agreement reached before the breakup of talks in guatemala last month
that includes a 30-day truce while the contra troops enter protected enclaves, a total amnesty, freedom of expression and a national dialogue, said cesar
declaring that new york city schools are ``on trial,'' a new chancellor was sworn in thursday to lead the 939,000-pupil education system and vowed to cut deeply into the central bureaucracy to gain needed reform
business as usual must come to an end, and it must do so today,'' said richard r. green, who ended a 30-year career in the minneapolis schools to take on the new york city post
frequently departing from the text of his 20-minute inaugural address, green laid out a reform agenda for the next year which included deep cuts in the central bureaucracy
by july 1, i will have a management team in place that i can rely on. and there will be some transfers out of 110 livingston,'' he said, referring to the downtown brooklyn headquarters of the city board of education
he also said he was determined to remove the time clocks that teachers are now required to punch. and he said he would work to find a way to make school facilities more readily available to parents' groups
green made no mention of his controversial suggestion of an 11-month school year which he made off-the-cuff wednesday while touring several schools
among those greeting green on the podium were mayor edward i. koch, gov. mario m. cuomo, and board of education president robert f. wagner jr
the otherwise serious ceremony also included laughter
when wagner began to administer the oath of office to green and said, ``i, state your name,'' green joked: ``i, state your name.''
green had surprised many at an earlier press conference by high-handedly signaling koch to sit down. koch turned the tables on green at his inaugural when, at the beginning of mayor's introductory remarks, he pointed with mock anger at green and said: ``sit down, chancellor!''
koch continued: ``you are the head of this new army. we are soldiers in your army. you tell us how to help you and those that don't, you give me their names.''
during his remarks, green said that koch had told him on a visit to city hall that ```you can have anything you want except more money.' that is a fair point but i consider that a negotiable issue.''
koch shrugged and shook his head
legislation approved by the senate banking committee grants banks broad new securities powers and in other provisions offers a mixed bag for users of financial services
the bill, passed on an 18-2 vote late wednesday night, substantially repeals the 1933 glass-steagall act, which separated banking from the securities business in the aftermath of the 1929 financial crash
if eventually signed into law, it would grant banks immediate power to underwrite mortgage-backed securities, commercial paper and municipal revenue bonds. banks would be able to deal in mutual funds and corporate bonds six months after enactment
in a concession to the securities industry, the bill withholds power from banks to underwrite corporate stock _ viewed by senators as the riskiest securities area _ unless congress authorizes that in a separate vote by april 1991
sen. william proxmire, d-wis., chairman of the committee and the bill's sponsor, said competition from banks likely will result in lower underwriting fees paid by businesses and state and local governments
mutual fund fees could edge down for individual investors and more competition in the underwriting of securities backed by home mortgages could save home buyers as much as $1,000 on a $100,000 mortgage, proxmire said
consumer groups also hailed a section of the bill sponsored by sen. christopher dodd, d-conn., that provides new safeguards on home equity loans
but they said limits on bank involvement in insurance, also sponsored by dodd, could reduce competition in that field
michelle meier, an attorney for consumer's union, said thursday she was disappointed in the insurance limits. she and five other consumer activists had argued in a letter to committee members that allowing banks into insurance ``could reduce the cost of insurance and force the insurance industry to become more efficient.''
dodd acknowledged thursday that his interest in limiting bank involvement in insurance stems from the concentration of insurance companies in connecticut
this is like hogs in iowa. to me it's important,'' dodd told reporters. but he added that there are sound arguments for being cautious about letting banks take on the risk of insurance underwriting
and, he said, ``there's plenty of competition. i defy you to go out to any hamlet or borough in america and not find insurance agents competing against each other.''
the home equity loan provision of the bill requires lenders to disclose the interest rate on loans in a clear and uniform manner as well as closing costs and repayment terms. it also would prohibit lenders from unilaterally changing the terms of a home equity line of credit after the contract is signed
meier and leslie gainer of u.s. pirg, a group associated with consumer activist ralph nader, said in a statement that the senate version is an improvement over a similar home equity bill in the house
another section would make it easier for consumers to shop for a place to put their money by requiring banks and mutual funds to advertise in a uniform manner the interest rate paid on deposits and money market accounts
proxmire, dodd and others predicted that the lopsided committee vote would ease passage of the legislation through the senate. but similar bills in the house face more uncertain prospects, where jurisdiction over the issue is shared by the energy and commerce and the banking committees
banking committee chairman rep. fernand j. st germain, d-r.i., who has expressed great skepticism about allowing banks too many new powers, is expected to introduce a proposal in the next several weeks. the finance subcommittee of energy and commerce is expected to follow with its own version
rep. edward j. markey, d-mass., chairman of the finance subcommittee, has said he favors phasing in new powers for banks _ a more cautious approach than adopted in the senate bill _ so federal regulatory agencies aren't swamped
it is essential that congress link the introduction of new powers to regulatory preparedness,'' markey said in a statement thursday
the state health department will investigate the hospital where a black teen-ager was taken after she said she had been sexually assaulted by a group of white men, a department spokesman said thursday
the department will ask for the medical records of st. francis hospital in poughkeepsie, which treated tawana brawley for nearly eight hours on nov. 28 following the attack, spokesman peter slocum said
miss brawley, 16, of wappingers falls, was found wrapped in a garbage bag along a road. she was smeared with excrement and ``kkk'' and ``nigger'' were scrawled on her body. she says she was kidnapped for four days and sexually abused by six men
her family has complained about her treatment at st. francis, where she was taken by ambulance on the day she was found
we are obviously interested in it simply because of the media reports,'' slocum said
the health department could impose a fine if it finds care was improper, ``but our primary concern, rather than any kind of punishment, is to make clear the standards of care are improved,'' slocum said
he was unsure how long the investigation would take
a source described as close to the brawley family but not identified told the poughkeepsie journal that the family was upset because miss brawley was released from the hospital unable to walk and lapsing in and out of consciousness
miss brawley went to the emergency room of the westchester medical center in valhalla twice on dec. 2. she was admitted after her second visit, hospital spokeswoman nancy mcpartlin said
she was discharged dec. 4, mcpartlin said. she said the hospital would provide no details about miss brawley's treatment
a spokesman for st. francis hospital denied the hospital did anything wrong when treating miss brawley
miss brawley was treated for a cut on the scalp and examined for possible hypothermia, spokesman frank hemrick said. she was tested to determine if she was raped, and the records were sent to the fbi
the test found miss brawley was not raped, according to several published reports. but a spokesman for the teen-ager, the rev. al sharpton, claims miss brawley was raped and the tests were botched
a bill to allow a state park to serve liquor to visiting democrats during their national convention in july survived some republican jabs in the georgia senate thursday
the democratic-controlled senate passed it, 40-13, and returned it to the house for consideration of a technical amendment
the bill was backed by gov. joe frank harris, a democrat and a teetotaler who last year vetoed a bill to expand the areas of stone mountain park where liquor can be sold to the public
sen. roy barnes, a democrat who is harris' senate floor leader, said the bill to allow the park's governing authority to sell liquor to private gatherings would aid some large functions planned at the park near atlanta ``in july.''
when republican sen. tom phillips tried to force another democratic speaker to name that event, barnes drew laughter by asking: ``isn't it true that the republicans chose as their meeting site bourbon street in new orleans?''
barnes argued the bill simply allowed the state to sell the liquor rather than forcing conventions to bring in their own
but democratic sen. max brannon, an opponent of liquor sales, said he was ``very shocked this is an administration bill'' and added: ``i know a liquor bill when i see a liquor bill.''
barnes drew laughter when he said: ``if i had my perfect world to do, there'd be a lot of things different in this world: we wouldn't have liquor, wouldn't have sin, wouldn't have republicans.''
pat robertson apparently will not seek a recount in south dakota's republican presidential primary even though he fell only a few hundred votes short of winning any delegates, gordon howie, robertson's state campaign director, said thursday
in official results, released thursday by the state board of canvassers, robertson came up 371 votes short of receiving the 20 percent of the gop vote he needed in order to receive any national convention delegates from the state
i think at this point it's unlikely'' a recount will be sought, howie said. ``i think we're going to be satisfied having beaten (vice president) george bush,'' he added
officially, sen. bob dole of kansas won the primary with 55.2 percent of the vote, robertson was second with 19.6 percent, and bush third at 18.6 percent. dole thus will get all 18 of south dakota's delegates to the gop national convention
howie said robertson's national campaign appears unlikely to file any complaint that could lead to a recount. ``obviously, we'd like to have delegates ... but indications are we're not going to challenge the vote,'' he said
