pat robertson should not hide from his religious past while seeking the republican presidential nomination, the rev. donald j. dunlap, robertson's pastor, said in an interview published thursday
robertson's ``apocalyptic theology'' concerning the biblical prophecy of the world's end could help mold his foreign policy as president, dunlap told the roanoke times &amp; world-news
robertson has tried to avoid campaign questions about his religious past and statements he made in writings and television broadcasts. ``those statements became a matter of the public record,'' said dunlap, pastor of freemason street baptist church in norfolk, of which robertson has been a member for 28 years
they were a mixture of his religious beliefs as they impacted upon his political beliefs,'' he added
he said that ``where he made public policy statements derivative of his religious beliefs, i think the media and his opponents have every right to question him on that as much as they have a right to question (vice president) george bush on his involvement in the iran-contra affair, as much as they have a right to question (kansas sen.) robert dole about votes he cast in congress.'' wounded</head>
an arab stabbed a teen-age jewish settler in the back thursday as he shopped for the jewish purim holiday in the occupied west bank city of hebron, the army and witnesses said
minutes later, angry jewish settlers attacked photographers taking pictures there, witnesses said
elsewhere in the west bank, israeli troops wounded four palestinians in violent protests
on the diplomatic front, u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz arrived in israel thursday night for a last-ditch effort to sell his peace proposal. he was met by foreign minister shimon peres, but no statements were made
legislators of prime minister yitzhak shamir's right-wing likud bloc have rejected the u.s. proposal, saying they will not agree to an international conference or to the exchange of land for peace
the scuffle in hebron, 20 miles south of jerusalem, began shortly after 16-year-old settler aharon peretz was stabbed
the army said later peretz was treated for slight injuries at a jerusalem hospital and released
a photographer on assignment for time magazine was struck with her camera by enraged jewish settlers. she fell to the ground unconscious, with a one-inch gash in her forehead that required five stitches
the attack reflected the growing anger of settlers and much of the israeli public at the news media, which they blame for tarnishing israel's image abroad and for inflaming unrest in the territories by their presence
in the arab village of idna on thursday, riot police fired on dozens of palestinians who stoned their jeep. an army spokesman said three arabs were wounded in the legs
troops shot a fourth arab youth in the neck after palestinians in beita, a village eight miles east of nablus, hurled rocks at soldiers, according to hospital officials and the arab-run palestine press service
in the gaza strip, troops fired 16 tear gas canisters to subdue about 250 girls demonstrating at their school in rafah, a palestinian reporter said
in hebron, photographers were standing outside the home where peretz received first aid when a settler attacked reuter photographer jim hollander as he took pictures of a little girl
hollander said the settler, without explanation, punched him in the face, breaking his glasses and giving him a swollen lip
when hollander's wife, rina castelnuovo, tried to break up the scuffle, another settler grabbed her camera and hit her in the head. she fell to the ground unconscious, blood gushing from her forehead, hollander said
she was on assignment for time
it was like revenge on the press,'' said israeli news photographer eli herskovitz, who was at the scene. ``those settlers went crazy.''
shamir said this week he was considering further restrictions on journalists in the occupied lands, and the haaretz newspaper reported thursday all senior army officers and most soldiers serving there support a press ban
reuter bureau chief paul taylor said the agency filed complaints with hebron police and the west bank military command. the army said it was investigating
soldiers later declared hebron a closed military area, detained dozens of arab residents and rounded them up in a central square
as detainees looked on, dozens of settlers staged a purim parade, dancing in the street and singing ``the people of our ancestors lives.'' soldiers with clubs guarded the marchers
purim is a religious holiday commemorating esther, the jewish queen of persia who saved the jews from destruction 24 centuries ago. celebrants wear costumes and spray harmless foam on passers-by
peretz, one of about 60 jews who live in hebron among 70,000 palestinians, ``felt a sharp jab in his back, turned and saw an arab with a knife,'' brooklyn, n.y.-born settler miriam levinger of hebron said in an interview
she said peretz chased his assailant several yards and threw a can of purim foam at him before collapsing
it was the third serious attack on a settler since unrest began dec. 8. according to u.n. figures, 76 arabs have been killed, including several by jewish settlers
israel took the gaza strip and the west bank from egypt and jordan in the 1967 middle east war
both peretz and his father, meir peretz, complained that reporters got in the way of soldiers trying to pursue the assailant
the head of jewish settlements in the west bank, shilo gal, condemned the attack on the journalists. harlingen</note>
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis accused rival richard gephardt on thursday of trying to impose ``a $50 billion burden on this nation's economy'' with an oil import fee
dukakis, barnstorming across texas in quest of the 183 democratic delegates at stake in the biggest super tuesday primary, also said the missouri congressman's trade legislation would ignite a global trade war like the one that ushered in the great depression
meanwhile, the dukakis campaign rolled out an anti-gephardt television ad. as the screen is filled with the names of banks, defense contractors, utilities and other big businesses whose political action committees have contributed to gephardt, a narrator asks, ``is dick gephardt really fighting your fight ... or theirs?''
to revive the ailing u.s. oil industry _ a major issue in texas _ dukakis said he favors targeted incentives to encourage small, independent producers to ``do their drilling and get that rig count up.'' in addition, he called for repealing the oil windfall profits tax, filling the strategic petroleum reserve and boosting natural gas production
gephardt supports a fee on oil imports. however, dukakis said, ``an oil import fee will put a $50 billion burden on this nation's economy. we don't need that.''
dukakis took another dig at gephardt in a speech at the harlingen airport. recalling an exchange monday in a williamsburg, va., debate when gephardt asked if dukakis is running ``for president of mexico or president of the united states,'' the governor said to cheers, ``i said, dick, if i'm president of the united states, i'm going to pay attention to our relationship with mexico, and i'm going to make sure that my proposals do not wreck the economy of mexico.''
a mariachi band greeted dukakis in harlingen and he repeated more than five minutes of his speech in spanish for the largely hispanic crowd. he promised that in january 1989, ``we're going to stop the shooting war in nicaragua and begin to go to work with our neighbors in mexico ... as partners to create opportunity on both sides of the border.''
dukakis, on a visit to a successful small manufacturer of rubber parts for oil drills in the east texas town of tyler, also took a shot at gephardt's trade policies, which call for retaliation in response to foreign nations' trade practices that are judged unfair
we can never agree to go back to policies that almost destroyed us 50 years ago. there's always somebody who suggests that: throw up the walls, hunker down,'' dukakis said
invoking a baseball metaphor, he recalled the towering left-field wall at fenway park, home of the boston red sox, and said, ``you can build that wall as high as you possibly can, and jim rice can still hit it out.''
later, in corpus christi, he said, ``trade wars are like nuclear wars. they have no victors, only victims.''
glenn hilbun, 31, a supervisor at the rubber parts plant, said, ``down here, a lot of people are not really familiar with what dukakis stands for. face it, texas is a bush state'' _ a reference to the republican vice president
polls in texas show a tight democratic field and many undecided voters
dukakis, considered strong in hispanic south texas, was trying to rally that support with stops here and at harlingen and laredo on the border before heading on to houston and lubbock. he heads west friday to denver, cheyenne and seattle, but was due back in san antonio saturday night
speaking to 350 supporters on a stage set under palm trees before corpus christi bay, he said the 1981 reagan tax cuts, supported by gephardt, are ``the primary cause of a trade deficit that has cost 2 million american jobs. we can't lead the world if we're in debt to it.''
dukakis said 1.25 million southern workers ``depend on exports for their jobs. these workers need a president who will use his authority to insist on fair treatment for american goods and services overseas. as president i will use that authority.''
even at mp industries, the thriving tyler business that got off the ground 11 years ago with help from a small business administration loan, dukakis found firsthand evidence of u.s. trade problems
a gleaming, green computerized $100,000 lathe bore the manfacturer's name on its side in bold letters: hitachi-seiki. another key piece of equipment came from italy
this is the story everywhere,'' said dukakis. ``we're buying streetcars in japan.''
the pta on thursday urged presidential candidates to ``pay more than lip service'' to the educational, after-school and health needs of the nation's children
a pta memo to all 10 candidates, released in time to catch their attention before the super tuesday primaries in 16 states, reflects a more activist stance on children's issues by the 6.1 million-member association, said arnold fege, the pta's director of governmental relations
until now, fege said, the group has focused on individual issues and never developed a complete agenda
we see a lot of the candidates kissing kids at rallies, but we don't hear much on what the candidates intend to do about children's issues,'' fege said. ``we want to force the candidates to take a position on these issues.''
the pta's message to the candidates, formally called ``a memorandum to the 41st president of the united states: a national children's agenda `because children are the future,''' asks the next president to convene a ``children's summit'' of parents, teachers, government officials and social service workers immediately after inauguration day. the group's task would be to ``recommend a coordinated, comprehensive and workable national youth and family policy.''
the four-page memo also recommends:
_increased spending on the chapter 1 and head start programs for disadvantaged children
_that the federal government work with the states to develop a plan to equalize spending on education among the states
_that public schools be encouraged to play a bigger role in providing early childhood, preschool and before- and after-school care
_that the federal government provide sufficient money for ensuring that all children be immunized against polio, diphtheria, measles, tetanus, whooping cough and mumps
_that the federal government assist states and local education agencies in providing preventive education programs on drug abuse, teen suicide, teen pregnancy and aids
_that the federal government commit whatever resources are necessary for adequate shelters, health services and education for homeless families and youths
fege acknowledged that the pta's recommendations are costly and he suggested that the money come from additional taxes, rearranging federal spending priorities or continuing the budget deficit
our organization has become indignant that the presidential candidates are not putting meaty children's issues on the agenda,'' fege said. ``we want them to pay more than lip service.''
negotiations aimed at reaching a new long-term grain agreement between the united states and the soviet union are scheduled to start next week in vienna, the reagan administration announced thursday
we look forward to our discussions with the soviets on a new u.s.-soviet long-term grain agreement,'' said a joint statement from agriculture secretary richard e. lyng and u.s. trade representative clayton k. yeutter
such an agreement would represent the third such arrangement between the two nations since 1975. the second was signed in 1983
we expect the vienna meeting to be the first step in the negotiating process,'' the statement said. it said the earlier accord ``have been important in stabilizing grain trade between our two countries and we are optimistic we will be able to achieve another mutually beneficial agreement.''
under the current agreement, which expires sept. 30, the soviets agreed to purchase 9 million metric tons of u.s. wheat and corn products annually for five years. four million tons of that amount must be wheat and 4 million tons must be corn
the soviets may satisfy their commitment to purchase an additional 1 million tons by buying wheat, corn, soybeans or soybean meal, or any combination of those commodities, with every ton of soybeans or soybean meal counting as two tons of grain
the announcement follows a sale by private exporters of 500,000 metric tons of subsidized u.s. wheat to the soviet union announced earlier this week. at recent prices it would have a value of $50 million
the sale was subsidized under the export enhancement program, in which private exporters receive surplus government commodities in exchange for shipping american grain overseas
more than 6.8 million tons of subsidized wheat has been sold to the soviet union under the program for delivery in the year that began last oct. 1
it represents a turnaround from 1986, when the soviets fell 3.8 million tons short of the minimum under the five-year agreement
the united states then made offers to the soviets under the export enhancement program and they resumed buying in may 1987
more than 81,000 aids cases were reported to the world health organization by the end of february, nearly double the number registered a year before, the agency said thursday
however, nearly one-third of the countries reporting had not updated their national figures for at least six months, the organization said
who said it was notified of 81,433 cases of acquired immune deficiency syndrome in 133 countries, with 4,167 new cases in february alone. by the same point last year, 91 countries had reported 42,404 people suffering from the deadly disease
the actual number of aids cases is believed to be twice the reported total, said dr. jonathan mann, head of who's aids program. he has predicted at least 1 million cases by 1990
the report said 42 countries had not updated their numbers for at least six months, including rwanda and the central african republic which last reported a combined figure of 959 cases in late 1986
the united states last month listed a total of 53,069 cases, up from 31,036 a year earlier. france reported 3,073 cases by dec. 31, more than 2{ times the 1,221 cases reported at the end of 1986
the numbers reported by canada increased less markedly. the figure stood at 1,488 in january, against 1,000 in april 1987
uganda reported 2,369 cases by the end of october, four times the number registered 12 months earlier. the number of people suffering from the disease in brazil more than doubled in 10 months, reaching 2,325 cases by dec. 7
of 28 european countries reporting to who, albania was the only one to list no cases. in the other 27 countries, the reported total of 10,177 cases represented a 128-percent increase within a year, who said
the aids virus attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to a wide variety of infections and cancers. it is most often transmitted through sexual contact
other means of transmission include transfusions of tainted blood or blood products, and the sharing of contaminated hypodermic needles or syringes by drug abusers. aids can also be passed from mother to child at or before birth
four libyan pilots who landed in egypt two days earlier flew their soviet-built warplanes home thursday in a rare example of cooperation between the combative neighbors, sources in both countries said
an egyptian government source said permission for the mig-23s to leave indicated cairo accepted a libyan explanation that bad weather and shortage of fuel forced the planes down. he spoke on condition of anonymity
cairo newspapers had presented the landings as a defection
egypt's official middle east news agency quoted a libyan air force spokesman as saying the planes ``returned to libya today (thursday).'' it said the confirmation was distributed by jana, the official libyan agency
it is a gesture of egyptian good will,'' the government source said of the decision to allow the planes to return home. he referred indirectly to a political rift that has allowed few such gestures in 15 years
he said the pilots and mig-23s left for libya from the mediterranean town of mersa matrouh, where they were taken after landing at a desert oasis near the border
on tuesday, mena quoted an official source as saying four libyan mig-23s had landed at an egyptian airfield. a source at the cairo airport said they put down at siwa oasis, 30 miles east of the border and 385 miles west of cairo
libya remained silent until thursday morning, when an air force spokesman who was not identified said the planes asked permission to land in egypt after running low on fuel
his statement, distributed by the official agency jana, said bad weather had thwarted repeated attempts to land in libya
president hosni mubarak confirmed the landing to reporters tuesday night and said of a reported asylum request by the pilots: ``egypt is their country. the matter is under study.''
in three cases last year, libyan fliers defected to egypt in a transport plane and two helicopters
the statement by the libyan air force spokesman thursday was a departure from usual practice in that it was couched in friendly terms
he said was quoted as saying: ``the pilots were treated in a fraternal way at the egyptian base. the aircraft, with their pilots, are on their way to return to their land of the great jamahiriyah (libya).''
egypt and libya have been at odds since egypt refused a merger proposal from libyan leader moammar gadhafi in the early 1970s. they fought a five-day border war in july 1977 after several bombings in cairo and other egyptian cities that egypt blamed on the libyans. robertson</head>
fallen tv evangelists jimmy swaggart and tammy bakker have been invited to be hosts of the annual loyal order of hibernians parade, but organizers say they won't be surprised if the answer is no
last year organizers invited lt. col. oliver north to be grand marshal of the half-block long st. patrick's day parade. the year before it was deposed philippine president ferdinand marcos. neither accepted
this year they want swaggart, who stepped down from his pulpit after tearfully admitting that he had sinned, to be grand marshal, said mayor jim lynch
they want mrs. bakker, wife of former ptl evangelist jim bakker, to be parade queen. bakker stepped down last year after revelations of sex and hush money
we had a little dissension on that, but one of the guys said if she wore green eye shade it would be ok,'' lynch said
they also want republican presidental candidate pat robertson, a former tv minister, in charge of publicity
he has a good irish bent for saying the first thing that comes to his mind,'' lynch said. ``we like him because he's not too bothered with facts.'' speaker</head>
rep. newt gingrich said thursday he has decided to delay seeking an ethics investigation of house speaker jim wright to give other activist republicans time to consider whether to join him in the action
gingrich, r-ga., said his announcement last month that he planned to ask the house ethics committee to initiate an investigation of wright prompted several other house republicans to inquire about joining his complaint
we've been meeting with people, answering their concerns and trying to give them an opportunity to decide whether they want to co-file with us,'' gingrich said
under house rules, any member can ask the ethics panel to investigate another member. the panel, composed of six democrats and six republicans, can reject such a request only by a majority vote
gingrich declined to identify the other republicans who had expressed an interest in joining the complaint against wright. he said he has briefed house republican leader robert michel of illinois, but does not expect michel to participate
there is a question of whether it would be appropriate for a leader who has to work with the speaker on a daily basis to be involved in this type of issue,'' gingrich said
he has called for an investigation of allegations of unethical conduct by wright, d-texas, that have been raised in news reports over the past 10 years
the reports include allegations that wright has failed since 1980 to file required financial disclosures reports from a company in which he is a partner and that he received 55 percent royalties on a book published by a friend whose printing company worked for wright's campaign committees
gingrich said thursday he still intends to seek an investigation of wright before the end of the month, even if no other congressmen join with him
louis g. seaton, former chief labor negotiator at general motors corp., died thursday after a brief illness. he was 81
seaton, who had homes in sarasota, fla., and orchard lake, retired in 1970 after more than 42 years with the world's largest automaker. he died in sarasota
he joined gm as a graphic artist in 1928, transferring to the industrial relationship department four years later
in 1946, he was named director of labor relations, with responsibility for day-to-day relations with the united auto workers and national contract negotiations until his retirement. he became a vice president in 1957
lou seaton was a pioneer in the fields of labor relations and personnel policy in general motors and the domestic automobile industry,'' said gm chairman roger smith
survivors include his wife, kathleen; a daughter; son; three brothers; 10 grandchildren and three great-grandchildren. a funeral was scheduled for monday in orchard lake
a former secret service agent said thursday that former presidents ford and carter will find far more privacy when no they no longer have federal agents protecting them
michael endicott, a secret service agent for 20 years who now provides private security for former president nixon, told the senate government operations federal spending subcommittee there should be a time limit on secret service protection of former presidents and their families
i believe the government should provide funding to the former president so that they can manage their own day-to-day security needs,'' endicott said. ``there is a need for a security or law enforcement presence around a former president that naturally flows from occupying the most important office in the country.''
but endicott, testifying on a bill that would reduce federal protection for former first families, said secret service protection often limits the recipient's freedom of movement. he said he has never felt nixon's safety has been threatened since he began to handle his security, traveling to cities around the world and attending sporting and other public events
at most of these events, we usually sit in the general public seats, even though vip boxes are usually available,'' he said. ``there is more privacy with fewer people. we are able to go to more ballgames now than when he had secret service protection.''
the big difference, he said, is that the secret service must ``protect against the potential threat, while i can protect from the actual threat.'' endicott said he, alone, travels with nixon, whereas the secret service must assign up to 24 agents to protect former presidents
endicott said most of the threats nixon has received have come from people unable to carry them out, such as inmates in mental institutions
former presidents ford and carter will find out what president nixon did,'' he said. ``there is a hell of a lot more privacy in smaller numbers.''
the legislation introduced by sen. lawton chiles, d-fla., would eliminate secret service protection for former presidents and their families after they have been out of the white house for five years. it provides for emergency and extended protection after that if it is deemed necessary by the treasury department
chiles said secret service protection for ford and carter and their families cost $8 million in 1986. nixon gave up his federal government protection, which then cost about $3 million a year, in 1985
the chiles bill also calls for a $300,000 annual limit on staff and office allowances, to be reduced over a nine-year period to $200,000. chiles told the hearing that programs for ex-presidents, including an annual $99,500 annuity, secret service protection, office allowance and staff, has gone from $380,140 in 1960 to about $26 million in the fiscal year that ended last sept. 30
the american people want former presidents to live a dignified retired life as an elder statesman, free from any real danger and free from any need to commercialize _ to huckster _ the office of the preisdency,'' he said. ``but the programs were left open-ended. things have gotten out of hand.''
each of the former presidents wrote letters to chiles on his legislation. ford and nixon agreed with its purpose on security protection
carter said the elimination of security ``would make it almost impossible for us to live a normal private life at home free of uninvited vistors, to attend major events if our attendance is publicized, or to travel to many places in our country or abroad.''
he said he can not afford private security. however, he said if secret service experts can reduce the level and cost of his protection, he would not object.  
pro-iranian kidnappers freed west german hostage ralph schray in west beirut on thursday after holding him for five weeks, and he was turned over to the west german embassy in damascus
the west german charge d'affaires, klaus auchenbach, refused to make any comments to reporters as he shuttled between the embassy and the foreign ministry, about a mile apart in the syrian capital
he said it was ``not worthwhile'' for them to wait around, indicating that schray would not appear in public
this raised speculation the former captive may not be as well as bonn portrayed him to be after his ordeal. the bonn foreign ministry had said earlier that schray, 30, was in ``good physical condition.''
friedhelm ost, the west german government's chief spokesman in bonn, said only that the syrian government had handed schray over to embassy officials
schray, a lebanese-born industrial engineer, was freed before dawn. a syrian military source in the lebanese capital said he was driven the 55 miles to damascus under heavy syrian escort
on wednesday, the holy warriors for freedom claimed responsibility for schray's abduction and said he would be freed within hours as a result of syrian mediation
the official syrian arab news agency said foreign minister farouk al-sharaa contacted his german counterpart, hans-dietrich genscher, by telephone to report that schray has been released and was safe in the hands of syrian troops in lebanon
the agency said genscher ``expressed his deep gratitude to syrian president hafez assad for all the efforts syria has exerted and reiterated bonn's determination to consolidate the traditional ties between the two nations.''
a few hours after his arrival in damascus, an embassy employee said schray was still inside the embassy. he spoke on condition of anonymity and would not comment on schray's physical condition
schray's lebanese wife, rana mounla, and his uncle george abu nassar, were seen leaving beirut in the early afternoon
mrs. schray, who is pregnant, said: ``i'm going to see him.''
she said: ``i'm taking clothes for him.''
she indicated the couple would return to beirut, saying: ``when we're back together in beirut tomorrow we'll both talk to you.''
schray's kidnappers also claimed responsibility for kidnapping two west germans in january 1987 _ rudolph cordes and alfred schmidt. schmidt was released in september, but cordes remains in captivity
schray's mother, fahima schray, said from fort myers, fla., that her son's captivity was ``the most terrible days of my life. it was so difficult.''
i couldn't sleep last night one minute. this morning, everything has changed completely, as if i'm a new woman,'' she said
there are 22 foreigners missing after being kidnapped in lebanon. they include nine americans, four frenchmen, three britons, a west german, an italian, an irishman, an indian and two unidentified men
the hostage held longest is american terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press. he was seized march 16, 1985
schray's release brought to seven the number of foreign hostages that have been released by kidnappers since september: two frenchmen, two west germans, a south korean, a norwegian and a swede
in their statement wednesday, the holy warriors for freedom said schray would be freed as ``goodwill gesture number two.'' they had also called schmidt's release a goodwill gesture
but they warned: ``we have an assortment of german targets on our hit list and also have a hand stretched out for dialogue.''
west german officials say the germans have been kidnapped in an effort to pressure bonn to release two lebanese shiite brothers
one of the brothers, abbas hamadi, has since been put on trial in duesseldorf on charges of kidnapping schmidt and cordes to press for the release of his brother, mohammed ali
mohammed ali is being held in frankfurt on charges of involvement in the 1985 hijacking of an american twa jetliner to beirut and the murder of a u.s. navy diver on board
the kidnappers warned that any pressure on them ``will only lead to ... the liquidation of the cordes case.''
the group is believed to be led by abdel-hadi hamadi, a third hamadi brother, who also is head of the security apparatus of hezbollah, or party of god, a fundamentalist iranian-backed faction linked to the kidnapping of the 22 foreigners still missing in lebanon
a house subcommittee chairman accused secretary of interior donald p. hodel of breaking faith in his budget proposal to increase operational funds for the national parks by only $3 million next year
congress intended that some $52 million in park fees being collected this year be added to the operations and maintenance account in the national park service budget for next year, said rep. bruce vento, d-minn
vento, who is chairman of the parks subcommittee of the house interior committee, told hodel ``you're breaching faith'' at a hearing of the full committee on the budget requests of the interior department
park operations and maintenance got $731 million for the current fiscal year. for the year beginning oct. 1, hodel is seeking $734 million
hodel referred vento to a passage in the committee's report to the house budget committee early last year recommending a ``stable funding base'' of $675 million
but in the catch-all spending bill enacted in december for the government as a whole, congress increased the park operations and maintenance account by about $15 million and then added $40 million in fee revenue for specified projects
that $40 million (is added) to the baseline,'' making it $715 million, argued rep. larry craig, r-idaho
our commitment was that we would not offset park fees against the base operating level,'' hodel told craig. ``i think we've kept faith. we're not being treated fairly.''
when his turn came, vento said, ``are you going to sit there and tell me there haven't been reductions in other park operations ... to offset the fees?''
hodel replied, ``i am,'' and vento rattled off a series of reductions of $2.7 million, $3.2 million and $3.9 million. ``what are they?'' he asked. he got no direct answer
the operations and maintenance request ``doesn't even provide the 2 percent (pay) increase for employees. you're going backward, not forward,'' vento said
israelis donned funny hats and costumes thursday to celebrate the jewish holiday of purim, but the festivities were overshadowed by three months of arab protests in the occupied territories
we have some very serious news, but first we want to wish you a happy purim,'' an israel army radio announcer said in a phrase that symbolized the joy and tension of the day
the radio then reported that israeli troops shot and injured at least three palestinian protesters and that a 16-year-old jewish youth was wounded when an arab assailant stabbed him in the the west bank town of hebron
the youth said he threw a canister of purim foam at the attacker, the national itim news agency said. pranksters spray the harmless foam at passers-by on the holiday
the radio marked purim with a prank, saying the transport ministry decided to replace all male taxi drivers with women because men are ``too arrogant, aggressive and ruin tourism.''
purim is a religious holiday honoring esther, the jewish queen of persia who saved the jews from destruction at the hands of the leader haman 24 centuries ago
jews celebrate the deliverance by reading the biblical book of esther in synagogues. whenever the reader mentions the name of the hated haman, the congregation shouts and shakes noisemakers
jews also mark the holiday by drinking wine, sending gifts and holding carnival parades. about 500,000 people gathered in tel aviv thursday to watch 1,500 people march in a purim parade
media pranks are considered an essential part of purim, but the jokes were overshadowed by the unrest in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, where 76 palestinians have died at the hands of israelis since dec. 8
on israel army radio, actor tuvia tzafir impersonated foreign minister shimon peres and prime minister yitzhak shamir switching their views on peace with the arabs
a cartoon in the daily maariv newspaper showed the government dressed for purim as a clown rocking on unsteady feet. the drawing showed a palestinian wearing the head of a peace dove but holding a knife and firebomb, and the army in the mask of a barking monster
the costumes chosen by children also reflected the political tension
in addition to young esthers, brides and ninja warriors, some boys in jewish west bank settlements dressed up as soldiers, complete with riot helmets, plastic shields and clubs. but one customary children's costume was missing this year _ that of the arab
in jerusalem, 27 students of the bezalel arts academy, which usually throws one of the best purim parties in town, were detained and others dispersed by police during a march wednesday
police said the students violated conditions of a permit for a purim procession when they unrolled signs saying, ``let's not lose our humanity.''
a swedish relief worker held captive in lebanon for 25 days said thursday the worst moment for him and a norwegian colleague was when they were given injections they feared would be fatal
the swede, 44-year-old jan stening, and william jorgensen, 58, of norway, were working for the u.n. relief and works agency when they were kidnapped feb. 5. the agency cares for palestinian refugees in lebanon
stening and jorgensen were freed tuesday and reunited with their families at a vienna hotel the next day, after arriving from beirut
at a news conference thursday, stening said: ``when we got those shots was a very tense situation.''
he said it happened a few hours before their release, and ``we both said goodbye ... because we said that was our very last moment.''
the purpose of the injections was to make them unconscious so they could be moved to another location, he said, but the captives thought the shots were meant to kill them
asked whether they were forced to take the injections, he said: ``we never discussed what we were forced to do. we just accepted everything.''
with stening was his wife lis, a stockholm lawyer, and his 12-year-old son daniel. he did not attend a news conference with jorgensen on wednesday night, explaining that he wanted more time with his family
jorgensen told reporters one of the kidnappers told them, ``we thought you came from a secret service'' but an investigation showed that to be a mistake
stening said four gunmen kidnapped them near sidon, south lebanon's provincial capital, as they were driving in a marked u.n. car from their base in tyre to beirut
both said they had no idea who abducted them. stening said the captors spoke arabic except for the last few days in an apartment that appeared to be in beirut, when one spoke english
usair has agreed to buy 50 boeing 737 jetliners with options for 30 additional aircraft, a deal worth $2.4 billion if all the options are exercised, the airline said thursday
delivery of the new jets will begin in april 1989 and continue through december 1991
the twin-engine, short-to-medium range aircraft is the most popular jet ever sold by the seattle-based boeing co. the deal with usair brings to 2,001 boeing 737s on order
edwin colodny, usair chairman and president, said the order ``is indicative of the health and vitality'' of the airline, which has its headquarters at washington national airport
our track record makes it possible to order these new aircraft which will benefit our passengers and the communities we serve,'' colodny said in a statement
usair group, the holding company for usair as well as piedmont aviation and pacific southwest airlines, recently reported a 1987 net income of $194.6 million on revenue of $3 billion
the three airlines together fly 166 boeing 737 aircraft, more than any other carrier. piedmont was the initial customer of the boeing 737 series 400 jetliner which is the newest version of the plane
the 50 aircraft on order will include of the smaller series 500 models that will be introduced by boeing in early 1989. the boeing 737s have a seating capacity ranging from 108 seats for the series 500 model to 150 seats in the series 400 jet
usair, which traditionally has concentrated its flights in the northeast expanded into the fifth largest airline company last year with the acquisition of psa and piedmont. while the three airlines still operate as separate carriers there are plans to merge them into a single carrier in the future
a general strike called to press for the end of gen. manuel antonio noriega's military rule lost steam thursday and the sponsors indicated they might end it
the indefinite stoppage began monday and already has lasted longer than any of five general strikes last year
a leader of the opposition national civic crusade told the associated press actions by the united states and other countries will become more important if internal pressure diminishes
many stores that closed on previous days reopened thursday. two factories resumed operations in the main industrial zone, which had been a virtual ghost town since monday. management personnel at others indicated they were preparing to resume production
some supermarkets and pharmacies had closed, but were open for business thursday
the banking situation was confused. international banks opened but limited the amount of withdrawals. lines formed outside privately owned local banks as word spread they intended to open, but some still were closed in the afternoon
riot police in trucks patrolled on thursday in several neighborhoods that were the scene of confrontations with stone-throwing youths tuesday and wednesday. no violence was reported
members of the civic crusade predicted wednesday night that support for the strike would decline, but were encouraged thursday by reports that it had gained support outside the capital and withheld a decision about ending it
roberto aleman, who heads the lawyers' component of the alliance of 200 business, professional, labor and political groups, said foreign pressure will be crucial in the coming days and weeks
anything that tends to damage the government of noriega, we support,'' he said. he praised actions designed to freeze panamanian government funds deposited in several u.s. banks
the government will find itself besieged by economic and diplomatic measures taken in the united states and latin america,'' aleman said. ``the measures will oblige the regime to take extremely unpopular measures such as raising taxes and firing public employees.''
he predicted that would increase popular discontent and lead to broader and more militant opposition
eliott abrams, assistant secretary of state for inter-american affairs, said wednesday the u.s. government is inclined to support such efforts
air panama suspended daily flights to miami, its only connection with the united states. sources at the state-owned airline said the purpose was to avoid any u.s. attempt to embargo aircraft
washington still considers eric arturo delvalle the legitimate president of panama. he was ousted last friday after trying to fire noriega, who commands the 15,000-member defense forces, which include the military and police
delvalle is in hiding in panama
the new government named former foreign minister aquilino boyd the new ambassador to washington. it was not clear whether he would try to take up the post still occupied by delvalle's ambassador, juan sosa
noriega was indicted last month in florida for alleged involvement in smuggling cocaine from colombia to the united states. he also is charged with allowing drug traffickers to launder profits in panamanian banks
a panama city newspaper quoted a member of the joint chiefs of staff as denying reports that that noriega was purging the armed forces
national assembly member guillermo cochez told a news conference wednesday the general ordered the early retirements of two colonels and two majors whose loyalty was suspect. cochez belongs to the opposition christian democrats
col. leonidas macias was quoted by the pro-government paper la estrella as saying: ``everything is normal and no one has been retired or dismissed.''
