the arizona senate on thursday rejected an attempt by gov. evan mecham's lawyers to introduce evidence at his impeachment trial about a key witness' sex life
this is neither a circus nor another episode of peyton place,'' said democratic sen. jesus ``chuy'' higuera, arguing against admission of the affidavit offered by the first-term republican governor's lawyers
the senate voted 21-8 against hearing the evidence but decided 26-3 to ask the maricopa county attorney to investigate the conduct of the witness, department of public safety director ralph milstead
milstead is expected to testify about an allegation that mecham ordered him not to cooperate with a probe of an alleged death threat against a former mecham aide who was testifying before a grand jury investigating the governor
clearly, the introduction of this evidence would make these proceedings more sensational and titillating,'' said republican sen. greg lunn
but he added: ``i don't believe the entire life of director milstead is on trial. the character and actions of governor mecham are on trial.''
lunn said evidence of an alleged 1982 sexual affair between milstead and a former dps employee would be clearly irrelevant and unfair
we've already done more for ralph milstead's sex life than a centerfold in cosmopolitan,'' said an exasperated republican sen. john mawhinney
republican sen. peter kay had spurred debate on the issue when he moved for admission of the affidavit. he said milstead's sex life was relevant to his character
the former dps employee had reportedly claimed that milstead had sex with her while he was married and once threatened her if she revealed their affair
moments after debate ended on the sex matter, an unidentified man in the spectator's gallery screamed out: ``you make me sick! i have to get out of here!''
the trial was recessed while the man was ushered out and taken to a room for questioning. he did not resist
earlier, the senate heard testimony that mecham tried to block the state attorney general's investigation of the alleged death threat because he believed the prosecutor was ``out to get him.''
james chilcoat, dps assistant deputy director, testified he was told by milstead that mecham instructed milstead not to cooperate with the attorney general's office
meanwhile, mecham took his case to the public, appearing on three national television shows thursday morning a few hours after he addressed a cheering crowd of 4,000 supporters at a rally wednesday night
mecham, who has stayed away from his impeachment trial since it began monday, also is accused of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and of misusing $80,000 in state money by loaning it to his auto dealership
mecham, 63, is the first u.s. governor to face an impeachment trial in 60 years. he also faces a may 17 recall election and a march 22 trial on felony charges accusing him of concealing the loan
chilcoat, a dps lieutenant colonel, gave details of the alleged threat similar to those related by two other dps officers who testified earlier
he said he was told that lee watkins, then mecham's prison construction chief, threatened in november that a mecham staffer then testifying before a grand jury about the campaign loan might ``go on a long boat ride'' or ``wind up at the bottom of a river'' if she continued talking
the department could see some embarrassment coming to the governor's office and obviously we were going to get blamed for that,'' chilcoat said. ``we had told the governor (about the threat) to reduce his risk and we were at a loss as to why he hadn't done anything.''
chilcoat said milstead personally gave mecham the information and came back dismayed
he (milstead) said the governor had instructed him not to go to the attorney general's office, not to help those people out there, that they were out to get him,'' chilcoat said
a two-thirds vote of the senate would be required to convict mecham on any count of the 23 articles of impeachment and remove him from office. the senate could, by another two-thirds vote, then bar mecham for life from holding any state office
mecham has remained highly visible since his trial began. on the network tv morning shows he said, ``i haven't broken any laws,'' and blamed arizona newspapers for his problems
mecham was asked on abc about the impact of former u.s. sen. barry goldwater's view that mecham should resign. ``barry doesn't know what's going on,'' mecham said. ``he's sort of past history.'' comments. no pickup</note>
secretary of state george p. shultz on thursday renewed an american drive to open arab-israeli peace talks by urging palestinian arabs to form a joint delegation with jordan for negotiations
jordan, with palestinians, is a good concept,'' shultz said. he cited family and cultural ties between palestinians living in the israeli-occupied west bank and gaza and those living in jordan
the structure is there, so there is a lot to be said for this approach,'' shultz said on a flight to israel following a meeting in london with jordan's king hussein. ``i think it is a good one.''
he described his two-hour meeting with the king as ``very worthwhile,'' but declined to give details to reporters traveling to the middle east with him
pleading that the situation was delicate, the secretary also would not say what approaches he had in mind for israel's prime minister yitzhak shamir and foreign minister shimon peres, whom he will meet separately on friday
but shultz hinted he was making headway in his effort to convene negotiations within a month
peres met shultz on his arrival thursday night, but no airport statements were issued
from israel, shultz plans to embark on quick flights to syria and egypt for more talks, then return to washington over the weekend
president reagan, in belgium for a north atlantic treaty organization summit, announced wednesday he was sending shultz for added talks with mideast leaders. shultz returned to the shuttle he began earlier this week
the u.s. proposal seeks to defuse the explosive situation in the west bank and gaza strip by opening talks soon on how the 1.5 million palestinians in the occupied territories could control their daily affairs
according to the u.s. plan, the israelis, jordanians and palestinians would then open negotiations in december on an overall peace settlement
israel took the lands from jordan and egypt in the 1967 middle east war
we are at an interesting and important time in this negotiation,'' shultz said thursday. ``and the best thing i can do as far as maximizing the prospects of getting anywhere is not to talk about it.''
still, shultz spoke forcefully about the merits of a joint jordanian-palestinian delegation. he urged all parties involved to adopt realistic goals
what i'm trying to do is to get people, all of whom have dreams, to focus on the dreams that have a foundation of reality . .. as i go around that is the message i try to carry,'' he said
the composition of the arab delgation that would talk peace with israel is a major issue confronting shultz on his swing through the region
jordan and syria demand a role for the palestine liberation organization. reporters in amman with shultz last week were informed jordan would no longer press the plo to agree to a joint delegation
the issue is important because the united states and israel both refuse to negotiate with an organization committed to dismantling the jewish state
shultz said all the parties _ the united states, israel, jordan and egypt _agreed palestinians ``have to have a say'' in the negotiations
to a very considerable degree,'' shultz said,``it's their rights, their human condition that's involved. ... by including them in a jordanian-palestinian delegation, you are making arrangements for that and i think that can work.''
at a news conference earlier in brussels, shultz took a tough stance on the plo while declaring that ``any suitable settlement has to deal the legitimate rights of the palestinian people.''
shultz insisted u.s. policy toward the plo had not changed since a 1975 law, enacted as a guarantee to israel, prohibited negotiating with the plo so long as yasser arafat's organization did not recognize israel's right to exist
but shultz said he wanted to meet with palestinians as soon as possible, even though a session could not be arranged right away
here is the 216-208 roll call thursday by which the house defeated a $30 million package of humanitarian aid to nicaragua's contra rebels
a ``yes'' vote is for the aid package
voting yes were 203 democrats and 5 republicans
voting no were 45 democrats and 171 republicans
xxx denotes those not voting
present denotes those who voted they were ``present'' at the time of the vote but did not vote ``yes'' or ``no'' on the issue
there is one vacancy in the 435-member house
