a former pro football player was indicted wednesday on charges of murdering a man 31 years ago in a case reopened at the request of the victim's mother
bobby hoppe, 53, was released on $7,500 bail wednesday in the 1957 slaying of teddy donald hudson. the 24-year-old hudson was killed by a shotgun blast fired into his car as he drove down a neighborhood street, police said
the charges against hoppe, a former washington redskins player who is now athletic director at chattanooga state technical community college, came 14 months after police reopened the case at the request of georgia hudson
police would not say what led them to arrest hoppe, who had been a suspect during the original investigation, and gave no motive for the slaying
police initially thought the death might be liquor-related, since in 1953 hudson was sentenced to prison on a liquor conviction and was a reputed whiskey runner
in addition, allegations were made during the original investigation that hoppe shot hudson over hoppe's sister, whom hudson was dating, but there wasn't enough evidence for an arrest, said police spokesman freeman cooper
hoppe declined to talk about the case. his lawyer, leroy phillips, said only that he is convinced of hoppe's innocence
at the time of the slaying, hoppe was a starting running back at auburn university, then called alabama polytechnic institute. he was on the team that won the 1957 national championship
after playing briefly for the redskins, hoppe was a teacher, coach and administrator at several high schools in chattanooga and in georgia
mrs. hudson asked police to reopen the case after a meeting of families and friends of murder victims, a support and counseling group. the case was taken up by two detectives on a newly-formed task force on long-unsolved murders
hoppe will be tried under state law as it existed in 1957, which means that he could receive 20 years to life in prison. current law allows the death penalty
richard gephardt parried a television attack on his presidential campaign with a challenge thursday, saying he'd return pac contributions if massachusetts gov. michael dukakis returned every dollar from those who do business with the state of massachusetts
dukakis spokesman leslie dach said the campaign has taken no money from any corporate pacs or registered lobbyists in massachusetts
the missouri congressman said he was defending his record against his rival's latest television advertisements, which implied he might have trouble representing american workers while accepting funds from their employers
i'll give back every penny of money that i've gotten from political action funds if he will return the money to all the people who have given him money who do business with or are licensed by the state of massachusetts,'' gephardt said in a short airport stop at baltimore-washington international airport
gephardt, who made two whistlestops in maryland five days before super tuesday balloting, has taken third place to dukakis and jesse jackson among likely maryland primary voters, according to the latest baltimore evening sun polls
after his airport news conference, he paid a courtesy visit to maryland gov. william donald schaefer. gephardt said he didn't come seeking an endorsement, and he didn't get one from the governor, who said again he will remain neutral at least through the maryland primary
the campaign exchanges between him and dukakis have turned increasingly scrappy as super tuesday nears
we will make public tomorrow (friday) a partial list of some of the interests that have given money to his campaign,'' gephardt told reporters gathered in a small airport terminal. ``he's got appointees of his own state government who are awarding contracts to many of the people who have given money to his campaign. is that a conflict of interest? i think that's a legitimate question.''
the missouri congressman said he not let special interests dictate his votes
i've never made a decision in my public life based on those contributions,'' he said. ``i have fought for a new trade policy. i have fought for a new tax policy and in my whole career i've fought against vested interests and the establishment of this country. and i find it odd that now gov. dukakis calls it into question whether or not i have been the one who fights for the working people of this country,'' he said
gephardt said only 5 percent of the $5 million to $6 million raised in his campaign for the presidency has come from pacs and is documented in the public record
responding to dukakis' latest attack that his oil import fee proposal would saddle americans with a $50 billion burden, he said the types of oil industry incentives supported by dukakis haven't worked in the past. he defended imposition of an oil import fee, saying it wouldn't cost consumers in the long run
the question is, do you want to pay 10 cents more a gallon now for gasoline and have the money all go to our treasury, or do you want to sit here and be vulnerable to opec and wait for a few years and let opec raise the price by 40 or 50 cents a gallon and take all the money to opec?''
terence c. golden, who has been administrator of the general services administration for nearly three years, resigned thursday because of his wife's health, a gsa spokesman said
golden, 43, became chief of the agency in june 1985, after serving as assistant secretary for administration at the treasury department. before joining the government in march 1984, he was a residential developer for a large dallas firm
the gsa is the government's housekeeping agency. it owns or leases 6,800 buildings nationwide
gsa spokesman joseph slye said golden sent his resignation in a letter to the white house. the letter was not released. the resignation is effective march 18, he said
the agency recently has been under attack for its handling of $55 million in government telecommunications contracts. the gsa's inspector general, the justice department and a senate committee are investigating allegations that agency employees leaked confidential information to competitors during bidding for the contracts
the gsa's handling of that contract is being scrutinized because the agency is also taking bids on a contract worth as much as $25 billion over 10 years to replace the government's phone network
at the gsa, golden opened 10 child-care centers in federal workplaces around the country and 25 more are planned for this year. he got congress to authorize $350 million to complete the federal triangle complex of buildings on pennsylvania avenue, which was begun during the roosevelt administration
in february 1987, he restricted smoking for 890,000 federal workers to designated areas in government buildings
the following may, he adopted new telephone regulations allowing federal workers to make daily phone calls home to check on children, spouses and day-care centers. formerly they could only call home in emergencies
he also persuaded congress and the president to provide more generous travel expenses to federal workers. attends school in arcadia, corrects 1989 to 1991 in 11th graf, bgng: ``ryan said ...''</note>
i came face to face with death at 13 years old,'' ryan white told the white house aids commission thursday
that was three years ago when he was diagnosed as having the deadly disease during surgery to remove part of his lung because of pneumonia. doctors gave him six months to live
but the indiana youngster told the panel he decided instead ``to live a normal life, go to school, be with my friends and enjoy day-to-day activities.''
as it turned out, those modest goals were not so easy to attain, mostly because of the ridicule heaped on him by others in kokomo
because of the lack of education on aids, discrimination, fear, panic and lies surrounded me,'' he told the commission. ``i was labeled a trouble-maker, my mom an unfit mother and i was not welcome anywhere. people would get up and leave so they would not have to sit anywhere near me. even at church, people would not shake my hand.''
finally, last summer, ryan, his mother and sister decided to move to another indiana town _ cicero. there things were different
they had the good fortune to move three doors away from jill stewart, who had just been elected president of the student council and welcomed ryan as a neighbor
she sat beside him thursday while ryan told his story, and then she told her own _ about how the 600 students at hamilton heights high school they attend in nearby arcadia ``had witnessed ryan's pain in his former community'' and how they decided ``there was no reason for ryan to go through that pain again.''
she told how school officials worked with the student council and parents to educate the community about acquired immune deficiency syndrome. eventually, she said, the students ran out of questions to ask about aids, which is an incurable disease that is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers and infected blood or blood products
by this time, they were asking how they could help ryan,'' she said
ryan said of his life: ``i'm a normal, happy teen-ager again. i have a learner's permit, i attend sports functions and dances. i made the honor role just recently, with two as and two bs. ... i believe in myself as i look forward to graduating ... in 1991.''
miss stewart, a 17-year-old senior who aspires to study human genetics _ or maybe law _ told the panel her story was intended to show how aids education in the schools can work to head off discrimination. that was part of the speech she had handwritten on a green-and-white sheaf of computer printer paper
then she ad libbed a few lines
in the end, she said, ryan _ who contracted the virus through contaminated blood agents given for threatment of the hemophilia he was born with _ helped his new classmates more than they helped him
no one realizes how much he has done for us,'' she said. ``he helps us put life in perspective in so many ways. these things you cannot measure.''
when the teen-agers were finished, the members of the white house commission applauded. industry</head>
industrial-state lawmakers, citing national security concerns, urged the reagan administration thursday to protect the domestic bearing industry against cheaper imports that are driving american manufacturers out of business
if we lose our domestic bearing industry, our military would become dangerously dependent on foreign nations to supply us with these vital components,'' said rep. nancy l. johnson, r-conn., and 38 other lawmakers in letters to commerce secretary c. william verity jr. and defense secretary frank carlucci
bearings are used in fighter jets, tanks, submarines, missiles and other defense systems. foreign competition has ``gravely injured'' u.s. manufacturers, mrs. johnson said
in july, the industry asked the commerce department to impose import restrictions on overseas bearing makers, but no action has been taken
mrs. johnson, who represents a western connecticut district with several major bearing employers, said nearly 65 percent of ball bearings sold in the united states now come from abroad, and that figure is growing
the congresswoman cited a 1986 defense department study that concluded bearings ``are a strategic industry, critical to the nation's defense.'' and the pentagon found that the domestic bearing industry is in ``imminent danger of being unable to support national defense needs'' and urged immediate action
nonetheless, two years after the release of this report, the federal government has still not implemented any steps to assist the bearing industry,'' mrs. johnson said
the industry filed for temporary relief under the trade expansion act of 1962 to provide u.s. companies with enough time to modernize
the anti-friction bearing manufacturers association, which represents 43 companies nationwide, asked the commerce department last summer to restrict foreign imports to 32 percent of the domestic ball bearing market and 18 percent of the roller bearing market. imports make up about 40 percent of the roller bearing market, mrs. johnson said
the commerce department has until july to make a recommendation to president reagan, but mrs. johnson has lobbied verity to expedite the process and was ``informally assured'' by the department that it would be moved swiftly, according to johnson aide caroline willson
the text of a written statement by president reagan commenting on the house's defeat of a democratic plan for ``humanitarian'' aid for the contras and for young victims of the nicaragua war:
the house has once again failed to approve an aid package for the nicaraguan democratic resistance. i call on the house and senate to act urgently to develop an aid package which is effectively deliverable and of sufficient quantity to sustain the nicaraguan freedom fighters. if not, the prospects for peace and democracy inside nicaragua will diminish quickly. jackson comment in arkansas</note>
jesse jackson, sweeping through country hard hit by depressed oil and farm prices, said thursday he wants to revitalize the u.s. oil industry and economy with a hemispheric energy alliance
the democratic presidential candidate said his proposal for a pan-american energy security alliance, in cooperation with canada and the latin countries, would free the united states from reliance on the opec nations
he said it could also be part of an overall cooperative strategy to help latin countries reduce their debt so that they could purchase more american products, thereby reducing the u.s. deficit
jackson picked up the endorsement of veteran state sen. gene stipe, who has served in the statehouse for 40 years, and a handful of other legislators here
he is the best thing in the race,'' said stipe, who until recently had supported sen. paul simon, d-ill
stipe said he now backs jackson because ``i can see he has a chance to be president. he has the momentum. after super tuesday, they're not going to be able to stop him.''
he predicted other white oklahomans would also back jackson and help him in the state's super tuesday primary
later, at the university of arkansas, jackson was endorsed by john j. hooker, a former tennnessee gubernatorial candidate who said he was representative of many more whites from his home state who supported jackson
after super tuesday, the rebels are going to come to jesse by the hundreds of thousands,'' he said to cheers
hooker said jackson's success in five northern states with voting-age populations of 1 percent or less had caught the attention of many whites who did not support jackson in his 1984 race
in an interview later, jackson declined to specify what his expectations were for super tuesday but expressed cautious optimism that he would pick up significant white votes
i can only say that i'm reaching out,'' he told the associated press
jackson said ``one can never be so certain about what's going to happen tuesday,'' but added: ``my sense is there's a higher comfort level'' among whites for his candidacy
jackson is trying to pull white voters into his camp, and campaign manager gerald austin said jackson's strategy is to pull in up to 10 percent of the white vote as well as his solid base of black support on super tuesday
at the state capitol, jackson was greeted by a standing ovation from a joint session of the legislature. he teased some lawmakers for wearing campaign buttons of other presidential contenders, telling them not to support candidates that ``are not viable.''
jackson is spending most of the pre-super tuesday campaign days bouncing across what he calls ``the new south'' and its bordering states. he is intent on making inroads in 105 congressional districts where his campaign sees a chance to gain a significant part of the 1,307 delegates up for grabs on tuesday
his campaign on friday will launch a $100,000 tv campaign in eight states, one featuring endorsements by comedian bill cosby and other spots highlighting jackson's accomplishments
jackson focuses on the new south, saying that voting rights and other freedoms have been won by blacks but economic inequity amounts to a new form of slavery
he is trying to pull white voters into his campaign for ``economic justice.''
his prospects in oklahoma, where more than 30 banks closed last year, are good, according to stipe, although sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee and rep. richard gephardt of missouri are also strong
protesters demanding lower prices set fire to stores in a third day of disturbances thursday. a merchant killed one protester and wounded another, authorities said
police said 300 people were arrested in santiago, the caribbean nation's second-largest city, where soldiers fired tear gas to disperse rioters. demonstrations were also reported in slum sections of santo domingo, the capital
a roman catholic church leader, monsignor agripino nunez collado, called on leaders of government, labor, business and the church to begin talks on the demonstrations and the country's economic problems
protests against inflation broke out last week in eight of the 26 dominican provinces, leaving five people dead and 20 injured. on saturday, president joaquin balaguer announced a 25 percent increase in the monthly minimum wage to about $75, but new demonstrations broke out this week
on thursday, protesters set fire to an undetermined number of stores in santiago and hurled firebombs at businesses in santo domingo
a merchant in the city fired a gun into a mob that tried to burn down his store, killing miguel cruz vazquez, 21, and wounding andres antonio batista, 18, police said
protest organizers, grouped as the front for popular resistance and popular unity council, said demonstrations would continue friday and saturday if the government did not move to curb inflation
the government has made no comment on the latest violence. last week, balaguer threatened to call out the army to contain unrest
inflation was 30 percent last year, according to private economists, and might top 50 percent this year
the protests have been the worst since balaguer took office 1{ years ago in the nation of more than 6.5 million people
the nation's largest labor federation, barred from all political activity, said thursday it would hold a national congress in april to discuss the ban
the federation, the congress of south african trade unions, threatened a three-day protest if the april 11-13 meeting is prohibited. it puts its membership at 750,000
other organizations also announced plans to defy the government's emergency regulations. eighteen opposition groups were barred last week from conducting any activity not approved by the government
the south african youth congress said it was changing its name in an attempt to get around the restrictions
nkosi molala, president of the newly banned azanian peoples organization, said he and two colleagues were detained by police for most of the day and questioned about a new group, the azanian coordinating committee. he said police warned him the new group would be banned, too, if it was a renamed version of the restricted organization
the south african council of churches is one of several groups which promised to take over projects of the 18 banned organizations. it said it defied a government order to submit copies of its monthly journal, ecunews, for review under emergency censorship laws
the church council said it was notified by minister of home affairs stoffel botha it had committed a criminal offense and he threatened legal action
the council is a coalition of most protestant churches in south africa, except for the white dutch reformed church
the council said it told botha it would not comply with any order under the state of emergency proclamation because the 20-month-old decree violated ``the christian understanding of justice,'' by eliminating the right of the accused to defend themselves in open court
the congress of south african trade unions has called for international disinvestment from south african business, redistribution of wealth to the workers and a complete boycott of south africa to pressure the government to change laws that deny a national vote to the black majority of 26 million
the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
