education secretary william j. bennett told the white house aids commission thursday he and surgeon general c. everett koop are in 95 percent agreement about how to attack the spread of the disease
as for the other 5 percent, bennett suggested it is ok for a doctor and an educator to differ on what to emphasize in their messages to the american public
they can handle it,'' he said
bennett's comments were in response to a statement by retired adm. james d. watkins, chairman of the commission, that many witnesses had told the panel differences among top federal officials were sending ``equivocal messages'' on aids education and prevention
during a brief evening session, the commission unanimously adopted 60 pages of recommendations watkins made last week as the basis for an interim report to be forwarded to president reagan next week
the formal report closely follows the watkins draft, including his call for an additional $20 billion in state and federal spending over the next decade to combat intravenous drug abuse and improve treatment for aids patients
the most rapid spread of the disease is now occurring among intravenous drugs abusers who catch aids by sharing contaminated needles and then pass the virus to their sexual partners and offspring
despite the call for sharply higher spending, the interim report is viewed as relatively uncontroversial compared with the issues watkins says the panel will address in its final report, such as testing, anti-discrimination and preventive education
the version approved by the panel did not delete any of watkins' specific recommendations, but contained additional wording in several sections
for example, a paragraph was added to the introduction to emphasize ``that available data do not provide a basis for comfort or complacency to any segment of our society. ... we express our concern that inaccurate and misleading statements suggesting that (the virus) cannot be spread through heterosexual activity could stimulate transmission among those who would see such reports as bases for ignoring the danger that does, in fact, exist.''
koop had told the panel tuesday he was ``outraged'' at media reports downplaying the danger of the virus spreading through vaginal intercourse
in a section that concentrates on the danger of intravenous drug users spreading the disease by sharing needles, language was added to say: ``in addition to direct transmission, the use of drugs that impair judgment can contribute to sexual transmission.''
commissioner theresa l. crenshaw, a physician who specializes in sex therapy, has expressed concern at several hearings that too much alcohol or marijuana use can lead people to do things they would not do if they were sober
the perfunctory evening session to adopt the final report followed a full day of hearings that featured bennett and, on a separate panel, ryan white, an indiana teen-ager who contracted aids during treatment for hemophilia
the most publicized difference between koop and bennett is over what emphasis to put on use of condoms and spermicides to prevent the spread of aids among sexually active people
whether it (the difference) is real or non-substantive, it is a real perception out there,'' watkins said
dr. koop and i are very close, extremely close,'' bennett said. ``i think koop and i agree 95 percent of the way. it's all right for the surgeon general and the secretary of education to speak a little differently about these things.''
he cited a hypothetical situation of a youngster discussing ``what he or she is doing'' with a doctor and with a counselor
the doctor's advice would probably emphasize the medical aspects, as it should,'' said bennett. ``the teacher or counselor's advice might emphasize other things. some shading of difference is ok. some measure of disagreement is ok.''
when the american people ask for leadership, they are not saying, `we're a bunch of dummies, tell us what to think,''' bennett said. ``they want to know our best thinking. and if our best thinking diverges on some points, they can handle it.''
bennett said he does not dispute koop's position that sexually active people, including teen-agers, must be aware that condom and spermicide use, although imperfect, are the only protection against contracting aids sexually
the difference, especially involving adolescents, is where to put the emphasis, bennett said
what he does not condone, the education chief said, is teachers going through ``a kind of incantation'' on abstinence and sexual monogamy in aids prevention classes, ``then proceeding for the rest of the class to talk (to teen-agers) about how to protect themselves.''
it's like saying, don't smoke, but if you do, smoke low tar. don't drink, but if you do, keep it to 70 proof. i think these are equivocal messages.''
koop told the commission earlier in the week that while he also believes the best advice is abstinence, or at least monogamy, ``i think it is also realistic to understand that sexually active teen-agers are unlikely to reverse their pattern and go backward, and therefore prevention for them has to be our third line of defense. ... we have to teach them about the protection of themselves and others through the use of condoms and spermicides.''
aids, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a incurable, contagious disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it incapable of resisting other diseases and infections
the disease is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from infected pregnant women to their offspring
the supreme court on thursday confirmed president abdou diouf's re-election to a second, five-year term with 73 percent of the vote
diouf won sunday's elections with 828,301 of the 1,135,501 votes cast. his nearest opponent, abdoulaye wade of the senegalese democratic party, polled 291,869 votes or 26 percent, said a communique
two other candidates split the remaining votes
results for the 120-seat national assembly were to be announced later. diouf's party had a lopsided majority in the old assembly
opposition leaders, including wade, claimed the voting was rigged. they have been detained since violent clashes between stone-throwing youths and riot police broke out monday and tuesday. the violence followed a preliminary government announcement that diouf was re-elected
a storm dumped freezing rain and up to 6 inches of snow on the east and midwest on thursday, downing power lines and causing hundreds of traffic accidents
meanwhile, rain and thunderstorms battered the central gulf coast region. during a six-hour period ending at 1 p.m. est, pensacola, fla., had 1.46 inches of rain, valparaiso, fla., 1.19 inches and milton, fla., .90 inches
dry weather prevailed over much of the rest of the nation
in indiana, downed tree limbs interrupted power in parts of indianapolis. up to 4 inches of snow fell on kokomo and 3 inches on lafayette, sheridan, portland and crawfordsville
power outages also hit thousands of homes in central illinois
freezing rain, sleet and snow fell on central ohio, where up to 5 inches of snow were expected
up to 5 inches of snow fell in eastern kansas, and more than 6 inches fell across parts of oklahoma and texas
a band of snow extended from western pennsylvania through central illinois to west-central texas, with freezing rain reported from ohio to missouri. rain and snow also fell over montana
earlier, the storm dumped up 13 inches on parts of the texas panhandle, thunderstorms triggered flash floods in east texas and a tornado ripped the roofs off mobile homes near galveston. the weather was blamed for at least four traffic deaths
up to 4 inches of snow were expected in parts of west virginia and up to 6 inches in northeastern pennsylvania. up to six inches were possible in southeastern new york state
temperatures were above 50 degrees from south-central texas to the southern and middle atlantic coast, with 70s in louisiana, mississippi and florida. temperatures generally were below freezing from the upper half of the mississippi valley to northern new england, with teens across northern sections of the great lakes region
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 17 degrees at houghton, minn., to 86 degrees at the southwest florida regional airport in fort myers
the low for the nation was 14 degrees below zero at international falls, minn
friday's forecast called for rain extending from the lower and middle mississippi valley to northern florida, the carolinas and the mid-atlantic coast, with thunderstorms from alabama to virginia. snow will extend from northern ohio to new jersey. rain and snow will extend from wyoming across the northern plains, with snow most likely in wyoming. rain will extend from the northern and central pacific coast to northwest montana, with rain likely in washington and western oregon. fair to partly sunny skies will prevail across the rest of the nation
temperatures will remain below 50 from the northern and central rockies to the middle and northern atlantic coast. highs will be in the 30s and upper 20s from eastern montana through the upper half of the mississippi valley to new england; above 60 from california through southern new mexico and across the lower mississippi valley to the southern atlantic coast, and in the 70s in southern california, southwestern arizona and extreme southern texas, and from southern louisiana to florida and southern georgia. to update with comments on bank funds.</note>
six republican and democratic congressmen introduced a bill thursday to impose an ``immediate, dramatic and devastating'' trade, air travel and currency embargo against the regime of panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega
the lawmakers said they would seek speedy congressional approval of the embargo bill
but they said they also hoped to prod president reagan to act independently to adopt a far stronger series of punitive sanctions against the noriega regime than he has approved to date
the proposed embargo would bar all imports from panama, prohibit all u.s. exports to that nation, bar all air travel between the two countries and prohibit u.s. banks from transferring any funds to panama and its banking system
by stopping the transfer of funds from u.s. banks to panama, we go for the jugular,'' said sen. alfonse d-amato, r-n.y., a principal sponsor of the embargo plan
because of panama's heavy reliance on its economic ties with the united states, the impact of a u.s. trade embargo would be immediate, dramatic and devastating to noriega and his cohorts,'' d'amato said
panamanian opposition leader ricardo arias calderon, president of the christian democratic party, told reporters later that a trade embargo would be ``strong medicine'' but that such a remedy is sometimes needed for people to regain their health
other sponsors of the embargo bill are sens. edward m. kennedy, d-mass.; david durenberger, r-minn.; bob graham, d-fla.; john kerry, d-mass.; and jesse helms, r-n.c
the senators told reporters they introduced the embargo legislation at the specific request of eric arturo devalle, who was ousted as panama's president after attempting to remove noriega as commander of panama's defense forces
noriega was indicted by a federal grand jury in miami last month for accepting $4.6 million to protect international drug traffickers using panama as safe haven
kerry said that imposing the embargo gives the united states the ``best chance'' of removing noriega but provides no guarantee of that result
but d'amato predicted imposing the embargo ``would spell the end of noriega within a matter of days.''
d'amato said the proposed ban on bank transfers to panama will worsen pananama's banking crisis and cash shortage
he said it would represent an important blow at a banking system he said has been used as a conduit for laundering billions of dollars in proceeds from illicit drug sales in the united states
a ban on panamanian goods will paralyze a $412 million market representing 60 percent of panama's total exports, d'amato said. a ban on u.s. exports to panama will affect a 30 percent slice of all panamanian imports, he said
delvalle's representatives have been attempting to seize cotrol of panamanian government assets in the united states through court action, saying the new government took power illegally
at the state department, spokeswoman phyllis oakley said the administration had taken measures to prevent the new government from gaining access to official panamanian funds in u.s. banks
she said deputy secretary john c. whitehead has signed a document certifying the administration's position that ambassador juan b. sosa has full authority over panamanian assets in any federal reserve bank or federally insured bank, ``to ensure that panamanian government funds in u.s. banks are not removed by the noriega regime.''
sosa has estimated that panamanian government deposits in u.s. banks total about $50 million
at a news conference thursday night at the panamanian embassy, an attorney for delvalle said federal courts in new york and boston have issued temporary restraining orders to prevent the transfer of official panamanian funds on deposit in u.s. banks to the panamanian government
we believe that whatever funds are in those institutions are at this point frozen and cannot be transmitted to the noriega regime,'' said lawyer daniel resnick
ms. oakley also said that, at sosa's request, 17 panamanian consular officers in the united states are no longer being recognized as representatives of that government
mrs. oakley said there has been no final decision on a proposal by delvalle's representatives that a $7 million fee for panama canal operations due the panamanian government on march 15 be withheld
but, she said, ``we have every feeling that the requests probably are going to be honored.''
in brussels on thursday, reagan gave a one-word answer when asked whether he felt noriega should be replaced: ``yes.''
secretary of state george p. shultz, who was with reagan at the nato summit, called noriega ``bad news'' but indicated that the administration must move cautiously in taking action against him
we want to do it properly, we want to do it right, we want to do it effectively,'' shultz said. his tone contrasted sharply with that of assistant secretary of state elliott abrams, who has said the administration is prepared to abide by the wishes of delvalle, whom it still regards as the constitutional leader of panama
reagan's national security adviser, colin l. powell, told reporters aboard air force one en route to washington that there was no obvious successor to noriega in panama
there is no apparent leader _ military or civilian _ waiting in the wings that you can have any reasonable form of assurance to say, `that's the guy who can succeed noriega.' so even if noriega should leave, we are anticipating a period of instability,'' powell said
in a another development, the chairman of a house foreign affairs task force on international narcotics control said he will ask congress to repudiate reagan's recent certification of five latin american nations as having fully cooperated with u.s. efforts to eradicate narcotics cultivation and trafficking
task force chairman rep. lawrence j. smith, d-fla., said he will introduce legislation next week to reverse the administration's action and decertify mexico, bolivia, peru, uruguay and the bahamas
he said the evidence is clear to him that none are in full cooperation with u.s. anti-narcotics efforts
smith said he also is considering adding laos and burma to the list of allegedly uncooperative nations but said they pose special problems and that further study is needed before a decision is made
the congressman said his list does not include colombia, whose government he said has tried to cooperate in eradicating narcotics cultivation despite intensive pressure from criminal narcotics cartels headquartered in the country
col. moammar gadhafi climbed onto a bulldozer and knocked down the gate of a tripoli prison thursday as thousands of libyans cheered, a western diplomat said
the official libyan news agency jana, monitored in rome, said 400 inmates were freed after gadhafi ``demolished'' the prison with the bulldozer. it said the former prisoners chanted slogans hailing ``the festival of liberty.''
the western european diplomat said he saw dozens of men with crewcuts come pouring from the prison, to be joyously greeted by relatives
the diplomat was reached by telephone by the associated press in rome. he spoke on condition of anonymity
he said about 50 other people, who appeared to be gadhafi aides, also drove bulldozers during the rally to knock down a wall surrounding the prison
the diplomat said gadhafi, clad in a military jacket and slacks, gave a 30-minute speech to the crowd in which the libyan leader praised his own record as leader of the 1969 revolution that brought him to power
on wednesday night, gadhafi said in a speech that he was releasing all libyan prisoners except those accused of plotting with foreign countries, according to jana. he promised to destroy the prison and invited prisoners' relatives to watch
the agency quoted him as saying the release included prisoners who plotted to assassinate gadhafi in the past
the libyan leader said, however, that the amnesty does not cover those ``accused of treason by linking themselves with foreign powers that have tried to use force to arrive at things of their own,'' according to jana, which said he put the number of those prisoners at 100 or fewer
gadhafi's regime has been described as merciless toward opponents. libyan dissidents have been assassinated abroad and libyan state television has sometimes broadcast executions of people convicted on treason charges
amnesty international, the human rights organization, said last september it received no reply to its appeals for 75 political prisoners it said were being held in libya
the united states bombed libya on april 15, 1986 after accusing the gadhafi government of supporting terrorism
in a crackdown on violators of china's one-child policy, authorities in southwestern china arrested people running an illegal operation to remove women's intrauterine devices, a state-run newspaper said thursday
the peasants daily said the group made huge profits by enticing women to remove their iuds with appeals to the traditional belief that ``more sons equal more happiness.''
the brief report said the group was headed by xu guanghui and ma heyuecai, but gave few details and did not say how many people were involved
it said people in the group removed iuds from 644 women in butuo county in sichuan province, using unsterilized bamboo and iron hooks. many women became infected and several died, the paper said
the iud is the main form of birth control in china's countryside
the belief in the importance of having a son has enjoyed a resurgence in the countryside following the breakup of communes and return to family farming. more children mean more hands to help at planting and harvest time
the population growth rate has jumped from 1.1 percent in 1985 to 1.4 percent in both 1986 and 1987. china's population of 1.07 billion increased by 15 million in 1987, or nearly 1.5 million over target, according to official statistics
china wants to limit the population to 1.2 billion by the year 2000
the government punishes violators of the one-child limit by imposing fines, but as peasants have become more prosperous, the fines have become less of a deterrent
authorities plan to tighten enforcement of the one-child limit by basing evaluations of officials' job performance in part on their conduct of family planning work. they also called for increased family planning education
the u.s. embassy in east berlin has posted a denial on its outside wall of a report in the communist party newspaper that the u.s.-mexican border resembles a battle zone
it also said people try to get into the united states, not out of it, as in the case of east germany
embassy officials posted the printed denial monday in a glassed-covered case attached to the wall of the embassy about 300 yards from the brandenburg gate in east berlin, where east germans can walk up and read it
the statement disputes a report in the party newspaper neues deutschland that calls the u.s.-mexican border a ``fighting zone.''
neues deutschland said there is often shooting in the area, with an ``average of 3,000 arrests per day,'' and u.s. border troops guarding it were trained to ``shoot instinctively.''
in its denial, the embassy says the border is a ``showplace and symbol of a complex social and economic situation'' and ``every u.s. citizen is free to leave the united states when they want to.''
apparently in reference to restricted zones along the berlin wall and the heavily fortified east german border with west germany, the embassy statement says the border between the united states and mexico has no fortifications
it has never had mine fields, automatic shooting devices, shoot-to-kill orders, moats or barriers of steel and cement, to hinder vehicles from crossing,'' the statement says, and in contrast to the situation in east germany, ``people attempt to enter our country.''
in addition to the berlin wall and armed guards, east germany has steel-mesh fences and walls along its nearly 870-mile border with west germany to prevent escapes to the west
the east germans for years also had mine fields and automatic shooting devices along the border, but began dismantling them several years ago
according to west german figures, 188 east germans have died trying to escape across the the border since the berlin wall was built in august 1961
a principal who banished a high school senior from homeroom for humming and singing along to the national anthem when it is played over the intercom says the dispute is a question of ``who's in charge.''
sara sprague, a 17-year-old member of the choir at north kingstown high school, said that her humming and singing were a ``spontaneous reaction to the music'' and that she was within her rights
principal paul rennick said sara was ``playing games'' by violating school policy requiring silence when the anthem is played
katherine janis, her homeroom teacher, said the humming was part of ``noisy and disruptive'' behavior by miss sprague, who has been banished for the past three weeks
the controversy began last month when she began humming to the anthem and was reprimanded by janis. the next day, miss sprague sang along _ quietly, she said _ and found herself in the assistant principal's office
the issue went public when sara wrote a letter to a local newspaper in protest
this is a pretty patriotic school. the flag is everywhere. george washington is on the walls,'' the principal said. ``it's not a question of patriotism, it's a question of who's in charge.''
miss sprague's mother, jane sprague, said she is backing her daughter
it's hard for me to believe that a school supported by local, state and federal taxes won't let students sing the national anthem if they want to,'' she said
moorpark has gone through four mayors in four months _ including three in one night
john lane, a sergeant for the los angeles police department, was mayor thursday after becoming the third person to accept the job wednesday night
at 8:08 p.m. wednesday, mayor john galloway resigned in an apparent effort to stave off a reorganization that would have put lane in the mayor's chair
mayor pro tem eloise brown took over. she served for 22 minutes before she was replaced. at 8:30 p.m., the council voted lane into the mayor's chair
ms. brown was partially to blame for her brief 22-minute reign. she voted against herself in the 4-1 vote ``because i am a good sport.''
dancing clay raisins, party animal spuds mackenzie and a piano-playing moonman edged out human actors in a list of popular tv advertising campaigns. it seems the humans cost too much and are too risky
we seem to be heading into a period when we see more created celebrities, not necessarily human beings, in commercials,'' said david vadehra, president of video storyboard tests inc
the new york-based consumer research firm based its 10th annual survey on interviews with more than 25,000 people about what commercials they liked best last year
leading the list was the campaign for california raisins, which used clay models of raisins dancing to the song ``heard it through the grapevine.''
second was bud light beer commercials, many of which featured the english bull terrier spuds mackenzie. other bud light commercials offered variations of what can go wrong if you simply order a ``light'' without specifying the brand
the ad campaign for pepsi soft drinks placed third, and miller lite beer commercials were fourth
ads for mcdonald's restaurants came in fifth. the campaign included some commercials that featured a piano-playing character shaped like a moon crescent who extolled dinner at mcdonald's to the tune ``mack the knife.''
more than 5,000 striking high school teachers and students marched through the city center thursday demanding increased government spending on education
no to austerity, spend more money on education!,'' the teachers chanted outside the education ministry. there are 25,000 high school teachers in athens
the public high school teachers, who make an average of $416 a month, want a 30 percent raise, improved health benefits and increased spending on education
the students demand a one-year reduction in the four-year vocational high school curriculum, fewer admission requirements for technical colleges and guaranteed jobs after graduation
they chanted ``we want work, bread, education!'' as they marched behind the teachers
both students and teachers want premier andreas papandreou's government to allocate 15 percent of the state budget to education
for 1988, the education budget totals 9.8 percent of overall government spending
veteran cosmonaut yuri romanenko appeared at a news conference on thursday to show the world he was in fine fettle after his record 326-day space voyage
the red-cheeked, 43-year-old romanenko said he had just come back from a vacation in kislovodsk, where he had been doing push-ups and other exercises to readjust his body to gravity after 11 months of weightlessness
romanenko, who returned to earth on dec. 29, said there were italian news reports that he suffered ill health effects from the flight, and he wanted to disprove them
i feel fine,'' he declared
a soviet space medical specialist and other space officials at the news conference agreed that romanenko, the mission commander, was in good shape
romanenko also assured reporters that a fellow spaceman was in no serious danger when pressure in his spacesuit suddenly dropped during a 3-hour, 40-minute spacewalk on april 12, 1987
cosmonaut alexander laveikin and romanenko had embarked on the spacewalk to learn why their orbital space station mir was not able to dock properly with a laboratory module called kvant
romanenko said a lever switched in the incorrect position caused a loss of air pressure in laveikin's spacesuit. asked if the depressurization was life-threatening, he responded, ``there was nothing particularly scary about it.''
he said normally the suit should be kept at 0.45 atmospheric units but the level dropped to 0.35 because a lever that controls pressure was set incorrectly
romanenko said the cosmonaut contacted mission controllers in the soviet union, who transmitted a command to regulate the pressure and ``within moments the pressure was back to normal, that is 0.45.''
on the spacewalk, laveikin and romanenko found what was preventing mir from docking with the kvant module: an ``alien object'' had gotten into the docking unit. romanenko said thursday the object was a cloth bag containing ``hygenic devices.''
the cosmonauts removed the bag and mission controllers sent a signal that successfully docked mir and kvant. soviet scientists had tried for a week to rescue the 11-ton kvant, which is used to conduct a variety of experiments, including those in biotechnology and astrophysics
an explosion tore through a dynamite factory thursday and killed five people, officials reported. eight people were injured
the victims in the blast in ablon, a normandy town near the english channel, were rene rubier, 53, director of the nobel p.r.b explosifs factory; his deputy, marcel delhom, 58; factory superintendent philippe gentil, 38, and two workers
it was the third explosion at the factory in three years. in march 1985, three people were killed. in march 1987, an explosion forced the plant to close until dec. 10 while new safety measures were implemented
the factory employs 135 people and produces about 20 tons of explosives a day for civilian use
jean amet, chief administrator of the calvados region, said the explosion occurred in a machine that packs the dynamite into blocks. he said the injured were in satisfactory condition
i saw a large flame which rose over the buildings, then, almost immediately, i heard a loud noise and the flash disappeared,'' said claude hubert, an ambulance driver who was about a half-mile away
the blast occurred shortly after the factory opened at 9 a.m
poland, east germany and czechoslovakia ended an unprecedented ``ecological summit'' thursday by pledging to combat pollution that may threaten half of the region's woodlands
the three-day meeting in the western city of jelenia gora reflected the neighboring countries' concern about increased pollution, particularly in border regions. it was their first high-level meeting devoted to the environment
more than 148,000 acres of forests in western poland are threatened with destruction caused by air pollution, officials say
deputy premiers from the three countries agreed ``to expand and deepen cooperation'' in environmental protection, the official polish news agency pap reported
they also decided to meet next year in czechoslovakia and draw up an environmental protection agreement, pap said
deputy premier jozef koziol of poland was quoted as saying the three countries have ``acknowledged the existing degradation and have undertaken to take swift joint effective measures in order to halt and then reduce environmental contamination.''
the pap report did not describe the measures
a polish television news report said the agreement provides for joint research on pollution-control technology and joint production of such equipment
east germany's delegation was led by hans reichelt and czechoslovakia's delegation by jaromir obzina
participants in an independent ecological seminar organized by the opposition freedom and peace movement, a banned polish peace and ecology group, wrote an open letter to the officials, saying 30 percent to 50 percent of the forests in the region would die by 1995 if pollution levels do not change
the letter, drawn up at the feb. 26-28 seminar in the southwestern city of gliwice, demanded that the public in the three countries be kept informed about environmental agreements and their progress
the letter said ``nothing or almost nothing is done to ensure'' the implementation of documents drawn up at meetings of soviet bloc countries
the ecology activists said the concentration of sulphuric oxides in the area is among the highest in europe and demanded that the three countries install equipment to control pollution at six coal-burning power plants in the region
poland has demanded czechoslovakia pay cleanup costs for several major oil spills in the oder river
the supreme court refused thursday to legalize a local union of solidarity steel workers, but members said they would continue their activities despite police harassment and threats of dismissal
in another development, a prison official said the outlawed labor federation's leader for the southern silesia industrial area has been on hunger strike since feb. 5 at a katowice prison. jan andrzej gorny is protesting what he describes as his ``unjust conviction.''
gorny is serving 1{ years on conviction of not paying alimony and using false identity cards. jerzy rybarczyk, a spokesman for the central board of penitentiaries, said gorny has been force-fed since feb. 9
opposition activists said gorny also was protesting denial of visits from his family, but rybarczyk said that issue was resolved
at the supreme court hearing, chief justice jan wasilewski upheld a lower court that ruled in december against registering the solidarity local at the steel plant in stalowa wola, southeastern poland
wasilewski said polish law prohibits more than one trade union at a plant
dozens of solidarity factory committees filed in the past year for legal recognition under a 1982 law that was supposed to provide for union pluralism. the supreme court has rejected all such appeals presented to it
we are going to continue ... our activities and widen them,'' said wieslaw wojtas, 31, who heads the solidarity local's 33-member organizing committee
he predicted management will treat the local's members ``more harshly'' now, but said they would resist any attempts to dismiss solidarity activists
we have considered the possibility of declaring a strike but we will use it only as a last resort,'' he said in an interview after the hearing. ``we have many other means before that.''
solidarity members at the stalowa wola plant have been watched, transferred to other jobs and summoned for talks with management, security police and local authorities, wojtas said
wladyslaw liwak, lawyer for the local, argued at the court hearing that prohibiting union pluralism violates international labor and human rights agreements signed by poland and hinders efforts for economic reform
solidarity, the first free trade union movement in the soviet bloc, was outlawed following a martial law crackdown in poland in december 1981
legislators rewriting brazil's constitution have voted to cut the minimum voting age from 18 to 16
legislators doubling as a constituent assembly voted 355 to 98 late wednesday in favor of reducing the minimum voting age. the proposal would be included in a final draft of the new constitution, which is expected to be considered by the two houses of congress later this year
if approved, the constitutional article would permit 5.7 million more voters, increasing the electorate to nearly 78 million of the nation's 141 million people
voting would not be mandatory for teens under 18 under the proposal, while remaining mandatory for those between the ages of 18 and 70
teen-agers interviewed by local newspapers about their new civic responsibilities had mixed reactions
leandro martins, 16, told the jornal do brasil newspaper his generation was not ``responsible enough'' to choose elected officials, while 17-year-old david oliveira was quoted as saying ``at last we can have some say in what goes on.''
the 559 legislators have been meeting since february 1987 to replace the authoritarian charter handed down by the military regime that ruled from 1964 to 1985
they also are deciding when brazilians will vote for president and the country's future system of government
burt reynolds says he'll probably marry longtime steady loni anderson within the year, and that the two want to have children
for a long time, i felt it was impossible to marry an actress,'' said reynolds, 52, said in the interview in the latest edition of us magazine
it's so difficult for an actor and actress to get married, to fight for the mirror. loni has been successful in breaking down all of those things,'' he said of the actress, who starred in the now-defunct television series ``wkrp in cincinnati'' among other roles
reynolds, himself a sex symbol, said ms. anderson, 43, has suffered the classic ``dumb blonde'' misperceptions
she's a college graduate, an art major and she's taught school. she's raised a fabulous daughter,'' he said. ``all of that speaks for itself. that's part of what makes me so proud of her.''
added ms. anderson: ``you'd think that when i peroxided my hair my brains went down the drain.''
chrysler motors corp. bowed to employee pressure and said thursday it won't sell its acustar inc. parts subsidiary. however, it said it will close or sell within 18 months four plants employing about 2,000 people
the united auto workers said it was pleased by the acustar decision but urged chrysler to find ways not to close the four plants: amplex van wert in van wert, ohio, trenton chemical in suburban detroit, detroit forge and detroit trim
the proposed sale of acustar, which employs about 28,000 in the united states, mexico and canada and had $3 billion in sales in 1987, had been vehemently opposed by uaw members who threatened plant-by-plant strikes
workers at chrysler plants throughout the company also had stopped attending management-union meetings and participating in other joint activities, and 1,000 picketed chrysler's highland park headquarters
we looked at all the offers, took into account the feelings of our employees and decided not to sell,'' said john guiniven, a spokesman for the no. 3 automaker
chrysler had said it was considering selling the subsidiary because it didn't want to invest in the research needed to upgrade some operations. chrysler already buys about 70 percent of its parts from outside sources
the four plants in jeopardy make trim for automobiles, chemicals used in auto paints and other parts. ``we are going to sell all four and if not, they will be closed,'' guiniven said
hundreds of beekeepers dumped their beehives outside parliament on thursday to protest imports of artificially sweetened foreign honey
earlier the beekeepers, some wearing white coveralls and black net face masks, marched through the city center shouting ``no more foreign honey!''
there are 20,000 beekeepers in greece, which produces more than 12,000 tons of honey. greece is the only member of the european community with a honey surplus and exports about 1,200 tons yearly, the agriculture ministry says
our goal is to stop the import of adulterated foreign honey which is being sold here as an european community product,'' said nicolaos papadopoulos, president of the attica beekeepers' cooperatives
other beekeepers claimed the imported honey was diluted with glucose to make it taste sweeter
greek-produced honey is thick and fudge-like, with a distinctive taste derived from the nectar collected by bees from thyme and other mountain herbs
juanita kidd stout was sworn in thursday as a justice of the pennsylvania supreme court, becoming the first black woman in the nation to sit on a state's highest court
gov. robert p. casey appointed the former philadelphia common pleas court judge to serve out the term of william d. hutchinson, who left for the federal bench
a justice will be elected to fill the seat in november. stout, who reaches the mandatory retirement age of 70 next year, is not running
stout, who served on the city's common pleas court since 1959, borrowed from the 4-h club motto in her remarks after taking the oath of office
i promise you that during my tenure on the supreme court of pennsylvania, however short it may be, i shall strive to make the best better,'' she said
the former english teacher has a reputation for correcting lawyers in court when they misspeak and for editing the opinions of colleagues
the trouble is, when judge stout sent me a note like that it was a correction. when justice stout sends me a note now, it will be a reversal,'' said common pleas president judge edward j. bradley, drawing laughter from the crowd in the supreme court chambers. falklands</head>
argentina said thursday it plans a ``defensive alert'' during scheduled british military exercises in the falkland islands and if necessary ``will execute corresponding defense plans.''
the foreign and defense ministries denounced the exercises, due to begin monday and end march 31, as ``violating ... (argentina's ) sovereign rights'' over the islands, which this nation claims were stolen by the british in 1833
argentina has said the exercises will chill efforts to restore relations, broken in 1982 when the two countries fought a bloody, 74-day war over the remote south atlantic islands
a joint comminque by the two ministries said the exercises contradict u.n. resolutions declaring the region a zone of peace. british officials have said the exercises are essentially defensive
the statement said that although argentina ``repeatedly has expressed willingness to resolve the dispute in peaceful and negotiated form'' the government is obliged to ``protect the lives and property of those who inhabit argentine soil'' and has adopted a defensive alert
the british exercises will be strictly watched, the ministries said
in the event it is necessary, corresponding defense plans'' will be executed, the communique said
the ministries did not go into specifics
but the statement warned foreign shipping that vessels will be subject to ``visit, inspection or capture under terms of international law'' by argentine authorities ``with the objective of avoiding their involvement in incidents.''
the maneuvers were reported to include planned use of phantom fighter jets and hundreds of british troops
on april 2, 1982, argentine troops captured the islands, but britain sent a task force and defeated the argentines. in the fighting, 712 argentines and 256 british were killed
brig. gen. ernesto crespo, air force chief of staff, said thursday that his branch will remain alert to any orders it may receive from the government regarding the british maneuvers
you must consider that this is not a simple exercise in the malvinas (falkland) islands,'' crespo said. ``it is much more important and involves peace in the south atlantic and, as a result, not only our country but other american states as well.'' picks up 3rd graf pvs, `the duke ...'</note>
britain's prince andrew waved to his wife, sarah, as he streaked overhead in a jet catapulted from the deck of the aircraft carrier nimitz on thursday during a tour off the california coast
the airshow was a highlight of the day at sea for the duke and duchess of york, both pilots, who also inspected one of the catapults and the massive chains that hold the ship's two 60,000-pound anchors
this is one of the loneliest walks i've ever done,'' the prince said moments before he boarded the s-3a viking anti-submarine warfare jet while sarah remained on deck
as the engines screamed, an apprehensive duchess, wearing a flight helmet, clutched a gift teddy bear and watched the jet hurled off the bow
the jet wheeled back for a low fly-by and husband and wife waved to each other before the pregnant duchess boarded a helicopter for a flight to long beach, where the royal yacht britannia is docked
the couple _ the duchess sporting a uss nimitz baseball cap _ had arrived aboard a navy helicopter. it landed on the carrier 60 miles west of los angeles as a loudspeaker announced: ``duke of york arriving.''
the duke, a helicopter pilot in the royal navy who saw action in britain's falkland islands war with argentina, saluted vice admiral john h. fetterman jr., commander of naval air forces in the pacific
trailing andrew was the duchess, in a blue dress and white coat with navy blue trim
the couple were presented leather flight jackets bearing the inscriptions ``duke of york'' and ``duchess of york,'' then sat down to watch an air show from the main deck of the nuclear-powered aircraft carrier
dramatic moisture blasts, an aircraft-enveloping fog caused as a jet breaks the sound barrier, brought a wide-eyed reaction from the duchess
helicopters demonstrated anti-submarine warfare techniques and supersonic jets made frequent fly-bys
jet after jet touched down on the deck at 160 mph, catching one of four cable arresters on the carrier's stern and stretching them 150 yards before coming to a halt. the planes then folded their wings and taxied to catapults
fetterman narrated for the duchess while the duke engaged in spirited conversation with the ship's skipper, capt. brent bennitt
all then went below for lunch. the menu included cream of asparagus soup, marinated mushrooms, melba toast with grilled parmesan cheese, chicken salad on a tomato wedge, cherries jubilee, mineral water and iced tea
spam? no spam,'' lt. tim o'leary, the ship's spokesman, said in response to reporters' queries
the couple, touring southern california to promote british trade, started the day with a visit hosted by the international foundation for learning disabilities at park century school in los angeles
british actress joan collins, a supporter of the charity, was on hand for the visit
the duke and duchess arrived in los angeles last friday and depart sunday
bandits ambushed an armored van on a superhighway thursday, put a hand grenade on the hood to force guards out of the vehicle and stole $1.3 million in cash and bonds, the italian news agency ansa reported
the van, carrying money from milan to two banks in sondrio in northern italy, was held up in the seregno area just outside milan by gunmen riding in four cars
a policeman in serengo contacted by telephone thursday said he had no details. ansa gave this account:
a gunman in one car shot out the van's tires. another car rammed the van from behind and a third cut it off from the front. the fourth car parked on the shoulder of the highway headed in the other direction
four men with pistols and rifles got out. when the driver and two guards stayed locked inside the van, the gunmen placed a grenade on the hood
fearing they would be blown up, the three got out. the driver was hit over the head with a pistol butt. the two others were forced to open the safe
the robbers grabbed the bags, jumped into the car parked on the other side of the highway and sped off toward milan
a police explosives' expert later detonated the grenade in a nearby field
a california condor thursday laid the first egg ever produced in captivity by a pair of the endangered birds, boosting efforts to save the species, the san diego wild animal park said
if the egg hatches at the end of its two-month incubation, it will be the first california condor ever conceived in captivity, officials said. only 27 of the birds exist, all in captivity, said park spokesman tom hanscom
biologists moved the egg from the nest to an incubator, according to plan, hanscom said. the egg may not produce an offspring because the female is old and her mate, a young male, may be sexually immature, park officials cautioned
by taking the egg from its parents at an early point, scientists hope to induce the pair to ``double-clutch,'' or produce a second egg to replace the lost one
california condors have been decimated in the wild by lead poisoning, caused by eating lead shot in animal carcasses, biologists said
the last california condor in the wild was captured and brought to the wild animal park on april 3, 1987 in a last bid to restore the vanishing species
fourteen of the birds are kept at the san diego park in enclosures not on view to the public. the 13 others are similarly housed at the los angeles zoo
since 1981, scientists have hatched 13 condors in captivity from eggs taken in the wild. the birds, which have a wingspan of about 9 feet, are dark reddish-brown with a curved beak
the centrist social democrats and liberals officially united thursday after eight months of stormy infighting over the policies of the merged party
the new social and liberal democrats party hopes to end the dominance of prime minister margaret thatcher's governing conservatives and the main opposition, the socialist labor party
the social democrats voted nearly 2-1 and the liberals more than 7-1 to merge in mail ballots after separate party conventions approved the merger last month. but only slightly more than half the party members voted
liberal leader david steel, who is expected to be elected leader of the new party, told a news conference it will give ``hope to a whole new generation.''
steel pledged to press for rejuvenation of the ailing national health service and run-down inner city neighborhoods
the social democrats' leader, robert maclennan, said britain ``needs a great national party, with roots in all our communities.''
maclennan called the conservatives ``complacent, centralizing, autocratic'' and the labor party ``the complacent, inert, bureaucratic alternative.''
david owen, who resigned as social democrat leader in opposition to the union, urged members to boycott the vote and called it ``a fiasco.'' he plans to continue the social democrats as a separate party
the two parties placed a distant third in last june's general election, in which mrs. thatcher won a third term as prime minister. homework</head>
a 12-year-old who earned $500 by going a year without television missed the first show she planned to watch thursday night. she was doing homework
i watched the last half of `cheers' because my homework ran into it,'' jenny machalleck said. ``i had planned to watch `cosby' but i was doing homework through that.''
earlier thursday, she received the $500 check promised by her parents if she could go for a full year without television. the deal they made on march 2, 1987, was to cure what she called a six-hour-a-day tv habit
thursday's experience _ missing tv while finishing school work _ was quite a change, said jenny, a seventh-grader. ``before, i would never worry about my homework. i would just watch tv,'' she said
as for her first sampling of tv in a year, she said, ``it was fun to watch because i hadn't watched in so long. but i found i hadn't really been missing anything.''
i was just not as enthusiastic as i thought i would be,'' she said
about 200 leftist rebels raided a northern mountain village, set fire to a police detachment and kidnapped a policeman, the military said friday
a report at the philippine constabulary headquarters in the capital said the attack by the communist new people's army rebels occurred thursday in sadanga, about 180 miles north of manila
it said police manning the outpost put up a brief fight but surrendered after two defenders were wounded. the report said the rebels confiscated police firearms, burned down the outpost and took a patrolman, helbert pacho, as a hostage before fleeing to the forest
a separate group of rebels ambushed reinforcements from a nearby police station, but the report did not say whether casualties resulted
the communists have been fighting to overthrow the government for 19 years
philip henry alston jr., a former ambassador to australia and a top campaign aide to former president jimmy carter, has died after a short illness. he was 76
alston, an influential atlanta lawyer who died wednesday, began supporting carter in 1966, the year he lost the governor's race to lester maddox
he was chairman of carter's successful gubernatorial bid in 1970 and headed the committee for jimmy carter, carter's national campaign organization, when carter was elected president in 1976
carter, as governor, appointed alston to the board of regents, and as president appointed him ambassador
alston, a navy veteran of world war ii, raised millions of dollars for the university of georgia
survivors include his wife, elkin goddard alston; a son; a daughter and five grandchildren. funeral arrangements were incomplete. grafs 5-6</note>
democrats michael dukakis and richard gephardt stepped up their attacks on each other for taking money from special interests thursday, with gephardt raising ``the specter of a serious conflict of interest.'' republican bob dole and democrat albert gore jr. touted new endorsements
dole won backing from a favorite of the republican right, former u.n. ambassador jeane kirkpatrick, and gore got support from charles robb, the former governor of virginia, and gov.-elect buddy roemer of louisiana
both parties' presidential hopefuls focused on the big round of primaries coming up across the south and elsewhere
republican front-runner george bush and rivals pat robertson and jack kemp were all in south carolina, where republicans vote saturday in what bush hopes will be a victory that propels him toward far more delegates in the rest of the south on super tuesday
a poll in friday's editions of the washington post suggested bush holds a decisive lead in the state. in the survey of 1,000 people who say they will vote in saturday's primary, 49 percent supported bush, 26 percent dole, 14 percent robertson and 7 percent kemp
robertson bought half an hour of air time on television stations around south carolina thursday night to ``set the record straight'' on religion issues. the former television evangelist said he believes in the separation of church and state, but added: ``i do not and i will not deny my beliefs or my church.''
dukakis, the massachusetts governor, began airing a television commercial that mocks gephardt's claim to be fighting against the establishment. the ad lists some of the corporate political action committees and other special interests that have contributed to gephardt's campaign
the missouri congressman fired back with an accusation that dukakis was bankrolled by ``an all-star cast of eastern establishment money interests'' as well as individuals and businesses that are regulated by his state government
i'll gladly give back every penny in pac contributions if mike dukakis will return the millions he's received from special interests who do business with the state of massachusetts,'' gephardt said. ``these are people who depend on the state government he runs for their livelihood, and it raises the specter of a serious conflict of interest.''
dukakis spokesman leslie dach said the campaign has taken no money from any corporate pacs or registered lobbyists in massachusetts
gephardt also found himself under attack from a new gore television commercial
gore's ad, aired across the south, is a 60-second clip from their debate in dallas two weeks ago, when gore accused gephardt of flip-flops on a list of issues, including president reagan's economic proposals. ``where are you this week on reaganomics?'' gore asks gephardt
on the campaign trail, dukakis defended his opposition to a fee on imported oil in texas, the big prize of super tuesday primaries and a state where local sentiment runs in favor of the tax. he said an oil import fee ``will put a $50 bilion burden on this nation's economy.''
he also lashed out at the heart of gephardt's populist message, his call for tough retaliatory trade sanctions, dismissing them as ``policies that almost destroyed us 50 years ago.''
gephardt was back in his home state after picking up $425,000 at two fund-raisers there a day before _ money that is critical for getting his message on television ads in the south
in kansas city, he visited a general motors automobile assembly plant that is scheduled to close in april because of poor domestic auto sales. he pledged a fight to open foreign markets to u.s. cars
among the other democrats, jesse jackson campaigned in the oil patch, telling the oklahoma legislature he hopes to revitalize the domestic oil industry through an alliance with canada and latin american countries to reduce dependence on opec states in the middle east
bidding to expand beyond his base of black voters, jackson won the endorsement of a vetern white oklahoma lawmaker and won a standing ovation from a joint session of the legislature
gore, whose entire presidential strategy depends on jump-starting his campaign in the southern primaries, gained in robb one of the southern endorsements he has most sought
robb, favored to win a gop-held senate seat this year in virginia, said gore's foreign policy and defense policy ``more closely aligns itself with what i think is right for our party and right for the country.''
dole appeared with kirkpatrick at a washington news conference, saying she ``symbolizes the soul of the reagan revolution.'' his campaign readied television commercials featuring the endorsement of kirkpatrick, a former democrat and university professor whose tough talk against communism endeared her to president reagan
dole also spoke at a white house conference on drug abuse and urged a federal death penalty for drug ``overlords and kingpins.'' he opposed distributing clean needles to drug addicts, as is being done in new york to combat the spread of aids, saying ``it also endorses addiction.''
bush continued to focus most of his southern campaign on south carolina, and in rock hill he invoked a quote from former baseball player yogi berra in stressing his experience
i won't make the wrong mistakes,'' bush said
kemp kept up his tough talk on panama, calling for revoking the panama canal treaty if that country's military strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega, indicted on u.s. drug charges, retains power
if they want to keep noriega, we're going to have to keep the panama canal,'' kemp said
robertson, the gop wildcard candidate who is also focusing on south carolina, traveled by bus along the towns of the pee dee river
robertson's organizational strength helped him score a two-to-one victory over bush in alaska's precinct caucuses the day before
prime minister yitzhak shamir said wednesday he was considering further restrictions on news media access in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, saying journalists have harmed israel
shamir did not say what steps he might take. under current regulations, soldiers are authorized to temporarily close parts of the occupied territories to reporters. the army frequently uses this measure to keep the news media from the sites of violent clashes
in a sharply worded attack, shamir accused journalists of being biased against israel and suggested such bias was part of official editorial policy
there is no lack of people (israeli officials) who are ready to explain what is happening,'' shamir told american jewish leaders in jerusalem
the trouble is they (reporters) don't want to listen. they are looking for arab sources of information. maybe they even have some instructions from their establishment.''
shamir called on american jewish leaders to quell within their ranks any criticism of israel, saying it was ``non-jewish to join an anti-israeli front of non-jewish people.''
several prominent american jews, including actor-director woody allen and rabbi alexander schindler, head of jewish reform congregations in the united states, have criticized israel in past weeks for its crackdown on arab protests in the occupied territories
by u.n. count, 76 palestinians have been killed and hundreds wounded in unrest in the occupied lands since dec. 8
a vermont office worker won a prize wednesday for a poem judged among the six best of 20,000 entries in a worldwide competition among english-speaking poets
arthur stone of morrisville, vt., was the only american among six finalists chosen by ted hughes, the british poet laureate, and irish poet seamus heaney. they selected the six from a list of 600 compiled by six other poets from the entries
it's a nice thing to happen _ it's rather surreal to be a poet in america,'' said stone after receiving a check for 500 pounds ($885) and a fountain pen in the arvon international poetry competition. the prizes were awarded at sotheby's auction house in london
the quality of the poetry was very high and we wished we could have given more prizes,'' said hughes, who spent a week with heaney reading the 600 poems in cambridge, mass., where heaney is a professor at harvard university
there were 100 more poems we would have liked to give prizes to, but we will put them in an anthology with the finalists and the 10 runners-up,'' he said
the runners-up, who won 250 pounds ($440), included four americans: brendan galvin, mary karr, patrick madden and pat maquire. their hometowns were not immediately available
the top prize of 5,000 pounds ($8,850) went to selima hill, whose poem ``the notebook'' is the imaginary diary of a patient in a psychiatric hospital. the other five finalists were not ranked
stone, 43, was born in long beach, calif., grew up in the mojave desert and now works for the office of alcohol and drug abuse in vermont
he said in an interview he writes poetry as a pastime, jotting down ideas on bits of paper and often getting his best ideas just after waking up or just before going to sleep
asked what his colleagues think of his poetry, stone said: ``well, they refer to me as `the poet' rather than the information and planning specialist, which is my job.''
stone has had poems published in american literary magazines and calls ``late arrival,'' the 51-line prize-winning poem, ``a realistic confessional about my initiation into the world.''
it starts with his birth and plunges quickly into memories of his boyhood, with people telling him their experiences and advising him to learn from them
stone said his poem was triggered by a work of another american poet, denis johnson
there's a lot of cross-fertilization in the arts and it's extremely important,'' stone said. ``i'm active in theater and i play saxophone in a jazz ensemble. it all helps me with my poetry.''
arvon is a foundation which teaches writing. the contest was its fifth. the organization gets its name from the arvon seat of poetry in the ``mabinogion,'' the book of welsh medieval tales
police searched homes of suspected neo-nazis in 61 west german cities wednesday, confiscating nazi flags and arresting four people, officers said
a police official in stuttgart, where federal authorities coordinated the searches by state and local police, said the arrests came during raids on homes of right-wing extremist suspects in munich, duisburg, grevenbroich and hanover
the official, who spoke on condition of not being further identified, said that more than 90 homes in all were searched for evidence of membership in the illegal neo-nazi group action front of national socialists-national activists. the national government banned the group in december 1983 on the ground it advocated violence against leftists and foreigners and promoted outlawed nazi ideology
the searches were apparently carried out in conjunction with the release from prison of prominent neo-nazi michael kuehnen, a former west german army lieutenant who headed the outlawed action front organization
kuehnen was freed from butzbach prison north of frankfurt on wednesday after completing a 3{-year sentence for distributing banned right-wing extremist propaganda, said jochen schroers, a spokesman for the frankfurt prosecutor's office, in a telephone interview
a coach from communist romania's olympic team met with immigration officers at a secret location wednesday after appealing for asylum in canada, an immigration department spokesman said
he's in a secluded place, a safe place with security,'' spokesman gerry maffre said in ottawa
the coach was not identified, but olympic sources and canadian news media said he was dumitru focseneanu, the romanian bobsled coach whose team had 27th and 30th place finishes at the winter olympic games in calgary last week
we're trying to find out what he really wants to do,'' maffre said
the bobsled coach reportedly refused to board a bus taking the 22-member romanian team to calgary airport monday night and sought refugee status
the federal immigration department was handling the case. the soviet union filed an angry protest over an immigration hotline set up in calgary to handle emergencies and possible defection cases
the romanian was the only known defector among more than 1,800 olympic athletes and 1,000 coaches and officials from 57 countries. but three romanian speed skaters and their coach left calgary abruptly the day before the games began amid speculation the athletes planned to defect
city police superintendent len esler said the defector approached two police officers at the athletes' village at the university of calgary about 9:30 p.m. monday and ``requested political asylum.''
esler said the man was taken to a police station where immigration officers picked him up. he refused to give the man's name ``for his safety and the safety of his family.''
focseneanu was in calgary last december during a bobsled world cup competition
the romanian embassy in ottawa refused to comment
wilf lindner, manager of the calgary immigration center, said the man would be allowed to stay only after a medical examination, a security check into his background and an immigration department hearing
all decisions are made on a case-to-case basis,'' he said
the chicago cubs on wednesday promised to stay at wrigley field unless faced with ``circumstances beyond the cubs' control.''
mayor eugene sawyer, who had demanded the commitment from the club's owners, the tribune co., before signing an ordinance allowing night games at the 72-year-old ballpark for the first time in cubs history, said he was satisfied
i am extremely pleased that the tribune co. has responded positively to my firm commitment of assuring chicago cubs fans that our national league team will stay in chicago,'' the mayor said
last week, the city council voted to allow the cubs to play eight night games this year and 18 in each of the following years until 2002. wrigley is the only major-league ballpark without lights
in a letter to the mayor, the team vowed to stay at wrigley field ``as long as they have the ability to hold games and conduct business as described in the ordinance, and events or circumstances beyond the cubs' control do make this, in their reasonable judgment, either not practicable or not financially feasible.''
the letter from john w. madigan, executive vice president of the tribune co, didn't specify what circumstances could prompt the team to move
but don grenesko, cubs executive vice president for business operations, said over the weekend that the team wanted an escape clause if voters banned alcohol at the park
wrigley field neighbors fearful of unruly fans and traffic problems night games could bring have threatened to launch a campaign to vote the precinct dry
the national assembly opened a special session wednesday to try to clear the way for general elections. two opposition parties meanwhile squabbled over a plan to merge
the one-week special session, the third this year, was called to adopt new laws governing legislative elections, expected in mid-april
whether the assembly would be able to adopt new election laws was not clear, because rival political parties could not agree on the issue
the adoption of new laws is necessary to hold the general elections
efforts to merge two opposition parties appeared successful last week but snagged on the role that kim dae-jung should play in a new integrated party to be formed
the opposition agreed to join forces to mount a united front in the coming voting for parliament following its presidential defeat last december, 
since kim young-sam resigned the presidency of the main opposition reunfication democratic party last month, pressure has been building on kim dae-jung to resign as well as chief of his party for peace and democracy
kim dae-jung said he would step aside if the opposition unites, but he indicated this week he would continue to remain active
fifty-three reunification legislators wednesday accused kim dae-jung of reneging on his promise to resign and demanded he take a back seat in the united opposition party
kim dae-jung's followers proposed wednesday that the new party be led by the two kims
kim young-sam objected to the idea, but said he would be satisfied with being an ordinary party member. he said he wanted to atone for the opposition defeat last december
the two kims divided 56 percent of the opposition vote in south korea's first direct presidential elections in 16 years. that gave the victory to roh tae-woo of the governing democratic justice party, who received a 36.6 percent plurality
since that defeat, both kims have been under public pressure to retire from politics
some remembrances make for odd, inconclusive theater
take ``wenceslas square,'' which opened wednesday at the new york shakespeare festival public theater. it's a fragmented memory play about an american theater professor who returns to prague several years after the 1968 soviet invasion and discovers what repression can do to people who have tasted freedom
that seems like an unlikely subject for larry shue, best known as the author of ``the foreigner'' and ``the nerd,'' two cheerfully goofy comedies that triumphed in new york despite critical sniffles from the press
shue, who died in a plane crash in 1985, apparently based the play on an incident in his own life. the comedy-drama focuses on the professor and his assistant, a young photographer who has agreed to shoot pictures for the scholar's book. shue was the photographer, and he tells the story in flashback
the episodic play seems unfinished, not completely worked out, as it follows the professor, played by jonathan hadary, and his assistant (bruce norris) during their eastern european adventure. the duo meet and interview a variety of theater and government people, all played either by victor garber or dana ivey
individual scenes in ``wenceslas square'' are often effective and very funny, but transitions are choppy. maybe that's why director jerry zaks utilizes a turntable set that keeps the play on a dizzy merry-go-round course
shue tries to show the accommodation the czechs made to restrictions on their personal and artistic lives. it's something the professor and his assistant gradually perceive, but the evening never builds to a dramatic pay-off. one wonders what the play would have been like if shue had been able to do some rewriting
still there are some wonderful, gentle comic moments, many of them provided by an impeccable cast. garber has a delightful scene as a befuddled czech trying to decipher the vagaries of the english language, while ivey is appealing as the man's sympathetic, ever-helpful wife
the play doesn't so much end as just stop when the professor and his assistant complete their two-week stay. you really don't know much more about them after their visit than before. at least shue has made the trip a modestly amusing journey
japan and the united states agreed wednesday that the tokyo government will pay a larger share of the costs of running u.s. military bases in japan
under the new agreement, signed by foreign minister sosuke uno and the acting u.s. embassy charge d'affaires, l. desaix anderson, japan will pay all benefits and allowances for the 21,000 japanese base workers, including transportation, housing and retirement expenses
the united states pays the salaries of the japanese workers
the pact will replace a year-old accord and boost japan's share of allowances for japanese base workers from a maximum 50 percent to 100 percent by 1991, the u.s. embassy said in a statement
japan's financial contribution will account for about 40 percent of the annual cost of maintaining u.s. bases in japan once the protocol is fully implemented, the statement said
tokyo and washington signed an initial accord in january 1987, requiring japan to cover up to half the expenditures for japanese workers at u.s. bases. wednesday's agreement amends that pact
in fiscal 1987, japan set aside $128 million to offset costs for japanese employees at the bases. with the yen's rise of about 100 percent against the dollar over the past three years, however, the cost to the united states of maintaining the japanese base workers has skyrocketed
the new agreement follows a pledge by prime minister noboru takeshita during a visit to washington in january to increase japan's contribution toward maintaining u.s. forces in japan
millionaire philanthropist armand hammer said he will spearhead a campaign to raise $1 billion a year to wipe out cancer by the year 2000
the extra capital ``would provide the resources we need to cure cancer in the next 10 years,'' hammer said in a telephone interview from los angeles on wednesday
the money will go directly to research at the national cancer institute in bethesda, md., said hammer, a non-practicing physician who turns 90 in may. ``there will be no overhead charges,'' he said
the institute's annual research budget is $1.4 billion
hammer, chairman and chief executive officer of occidental petroleum corp., already has donated $100,000 for cancer research and has received commitments from nine other industrialists to do the same
about 475,000 people died last year from cancer. the death rate from most major forms of the disease has improved little over the past 15 years
however, the director of the national cancer institute, dr. vincent devita, expressed guarded optimism on whether the extra dollars would lead to a cure. at the very least, it would ``make a dent,'' devita said
with the help of a mass media campaign, the drive will seek to raise $500 million in private contributions, which hammer hopes will be matched in federal funds. some congressmen already have agreed to support the effort, he said
libyan leader col. moammar gadhafi said wednesday he was releasing all libyan prisoners except those accused of plotting with foreign countries, the official libyan news agency jana reported
jana also said that gadhafi announced he would reach out to the united states once it changed its policies toward his country
both statements came in a speech to the general people's congress, the north african country's highest policy-making body, according to jana dispatches monitored in rome
gadhafi said about 400 prisoners would be freed from the tripoli prison on thursday and the prison would be torn down, jana said
among those being freed are prisoners who plotted to assassinate gadhafi before and after he seized power in 1969, he was quoted as saying
i forgive them regardless of the sentences passed against them,'' the colonel was quoted as saying
the amnesty does not cover those ``accused of treason by linking themselves with foreign powers that have tried to use force to arrive at things of their own,'' jana quoted gadhafi as saying. there are less than 100 such prisoners, he said
it was not clear where these remaining prisoners would be kept if the tripoli prison is demolished
according to jana, gadhafi also announced abolishment of ``extraordinary trials'' and said all cases will be referred to a ``people's court'' run by the people's congress
gadhafi's regime gained a reputation over the years as being ruthless toward political opponents. numerous libyan dissidents were assassinated abroad and his regime periodically televised public executions for alleged treason
last septemer, the human rights organization amnesty international said it received reports of libyan prisoners being beaten on the soles of their feet or hung upside down from a perch and beaten. it said it received no reply to its appeals for 75 political prisoners it says are being held in libya
on relations with the united states, gadhafi was quoted as saying the ``animosity will remain'' until the united states ``recognizes our right to live, respects us over our own land and asks for cooperation with us as equal. and then we shall stretch our hands to it.''
he said the united states denies rights to libyans because it recogniezes only a 12-mile territorial limit in the u-shaped gulf of sidra. libya claims the entire gulf
u.s. and libyan forces clashed in the gulf in march 1986, and a month later u.s. jets bombed libya in retaliation for libya's alleged involvement in international terrorism
