if you're heavily into the bon jovi and the beastie boys, you're in probably the only demographic group that won't find something to like in two widely divergent music specials offered by cbs
on saturday, willie nelson is host of his own network special, ``willie nelson, texas style,'' a tribute to his home state which he reveals in a soothing hour of country, rock and blues music combined with an affectionate travelogue to some of his favorite lone star places
then on monday, barry manilow pays homage to jazz and big band music in ``barry manilow: big fun on swing street,'' set in an imaginary neighborhood of break dancers, saxophone players and blues singers, where the '40s meet the '80s
manilow wasn't, shall we say, successful in his last network venture, the 1985 cbs musical movie ``copacabana,'' which marked his acting debut. this time, he sticks to the music. there is no dialogue in ``swing street,'' a bluesy, jazzy, coolly evocative, extended music video
there's no dumb sketches on it. we did that on purpose,'' said manilow, during a recent break in the midst of his two-year tour. ``bruce and jack and i sat down and wrote a conceptual hour that takes the viewer on a trip down this imaginary place called swing street, during which we meet all the characters who inhabit swing street, and they are played by the guests. there's no talking except for the voiceovers, and it's all music, because i wanted to do a music special with a capital m.''
bruce and jack are manilow's collaborators, bruce sussman and jack feldman. their concept also produced an album, ``swing street,'' that features the performers on the special, plus stan getz, who was in the hospital when the special was taped, manilow said
sussman suggested that this kind of high-style music special is the wave of the future on network television, which still tends to rely on the standard host-guest-song-sketch kind of variety program
one of the problems with variety television is that mtv has forever changed variety television, and it hasn't responded to that,'' sussman said. ``this is something else, it's not mtv, but something that certainly has been influenced by that development.''
who knows whether this is going to make it rating-wise,'' said manilow, ``but what was definitely not making it was somebody standing up there saying, `my next guest is dionne warwick, my next sketch is,' you know. this sort of had a point of view, even if it was odd.''
the special includes manilow songs such as ``hey mambo'' and ``black and blue,'' but also standards such as ``summertime'' and ``stardust.''
manilow's guests are jazz singers carmen mcrae and diane schuur _ her duet with manilow on ``summertime'' is a show-stopper _ saxophonists gerry mulligan, tom scott and dana robbins, bass player stanley clarke and singer phyllis hyman, plus the vocal groups full swing and kid creole and the coconuts
nelson's special is as bright and sunny as manilow's is dark and smoky, with footage of nelson walking around his hill country home, playing host to his band members and friends on his golf course, riding his bicycle down to mona's yacht club for a game of dominoes with the locals, and floating down the rio grande with jazz guitarist jackie king
next door to the golf course is willie's own recording studio _ dubbed ``cut 'n' putt'' _ where bruce hornsby does a session. ray charles joins willie at alley oop's on east sixth street in austin, and asleep at the wheel jams with him at carl's corner, a truck stop
willie also takes a sentimental tour of his boyhood home of abbott, texas, where his sister bobbie recalls their grandmother tying young willie up to keep him from running off
she staked him just like she did the cow,'' bobbie laughs
that didn't stop me from running away,'' willie recalls. ``it slowed me down some.''
elsewhere in television:
blake honored _ director blake edwards will be honored at the second annual american comedy awards with the lifetime creative achievement award. edwards made such films as ``the pink panther,'' ``victor-victoria, ``10,'' and more recently ``blind date'' and ``that's life.'' the awards show will be broadcast may 17 on abc
have americans really changed their spending habits?
it is still too early to say, but that might be one of the developing consequences of the great stock market crash of october
before the crash it was common to hear about the foolish spending habits of ordinary americans. among other criticisms, for example, it was said that they were living beyond their means, financing their lifestyle with credit
at one point late last year the savings rate fell under 2 percent, a record low. as personal income stagnated, the use of credit rose
it was perhaps the live-for-now consumer style that best exemplified the time. jobs were plentiful and money was available, and enticements of the marketplace left little time for worrying about future recessions
then came the crash. and while statistics show that only a small percentage of american households had any direct ownership of stocks, the suddenness of the decline seemed to shock them into an awareness of sudden dangers
confidence shrank. immediately following the crash, the university of michigan survey recorded a sharp rise to 45 percent in the percentage of families expecting bad times financially. only 38 percent foresaw good times
consumer spending slowed. in fact, in the fourth quarter it declined from the previous quarter at a 3 percent annual rate. motor vehicle and parts purchases fell 36 percent. furniture and household equipment dipped 3 percent
people even cut into their food budgets. spending on food fell 2 percent, clothing and shoes 7 percent and gasoline and oil 1 percent. and for the most part, that pattern extended into the first month of this year
meanwhile, personal saving as a percentage of disposable income averaged 4.8 percent in the fourth quarter, compared to a third-quarter rate of 2.8 percent. and the higher savings rate continued into january
while it cannot be attributed to the crash, evidence of another turnabout was becoming clear: the american economy was relying less on consumption and more on production, a turnabout that had been awaited for two decades
during that long period, americans seemed willing, able and happy to hawk their jewels _ personal, industrial and, some critics maintained, even those of a spiritual nature. it was a time of great material success, and greed
the danger, americans were told throughout that two-decade period, was that no nation could continue to consume more than it produced without wasting its economic power. but consumption continued nevertheless at every level of life
lately, however, the scene appears to have changed. the growth of consumption has waned in relation to that of production. manufactured goods, not just agricultural products, are being exported. money is being saved. and people have a wise eye on the future
the michigan survey now shows that confidence has returned to where it was before the crash _ but with a big difference. the confidence expressed is mainly about the near term, not for the more distant horizon
what appears to have happened is that families are more cautious judges; they feel safe in expressing confidence over the next year because they understand the forces at work. they simply don't see a recession coming
but, unlike the pre-crash confidence readings, consumers are less certain about the next five years. that suggests realism; nobody can say what might happen five years ahead. that being so, overconfidence is foolishness
the new attitude appears healthier. goals appear to be more realistic. tempered by the crash, people seem aware that an economic quake is possible, and that the time to deal with the possibility is now _ not after it happens
vaid rani chawla has her dearest wish. she is going to have a son, after two daughters
it means an end to the biting taunts of her mother-in-law and neighbors. she will gain ``honor'' by having a boy
i wanted people to say that a son is born in chawlas' house. one son is a must,'' said mrs. chawla, who now is six months pregnant
she knows for sure it's a boy because she had amniocentesis, a test many indian women use to learn the sex of their unborn. if the test shows a girl is on the way, many women have abortions
the practice is drawing fire from social activists who say it is a perverted use of modern science to perpetuate age-old social prejudices against women
the test is intended to detect congenital deformities, but it has come to be known as the ``boy-girl test'' in india
widely used in developed countries, amniocentesis is a procedure in which a small sample of the amniotic fluid that bathes the fetus in the womb is withdrawn by a long hypodermic needle
the fluid contains cells that have flaked off the fetus. the chromosomes in these cells can be examined for evidence of birth defects, but they also tell the sex of the fetus
boy or girl _ know the sex of the unborn child,'' say advertisements by clinics in indian newspapers
mrs. chawla, 32, shyly admitted she would have had an abortion if her test had proved ``negative'' _ meaning another girl
there are no definite numbers on how many abortions occur after such tests. one authoritative study said 78,000 female fetuses were aborted from 1978 to 1983 nationwide following sex-determination tests. abortions are legal in india, a country of 780 million people, as part of the government's population-control program
while the issue has generated demands for banning amniocentesis clinics, doctors who run the lucrative businesses say it is better to abort a female fetus than to subject an unwanted child to a life of suffering
people are willing to keep producing children until they get a son,'' said k.k. loomba, who runs new delhi's most popular boy-girl testing clinic. ``tell me, is it not better to let them have a choice so they don't have six daughters before they have a son?
either you should educate the masses that there is no difference between sons and daughters or give them a choice. this test, in fact, is helping the population-control program of the government.''
but vibhuti patel, a women's rights activist from bombay, counters: ``by this logic it is better to kill the poor rather then let them suffer poverty and deprivation.''
both sides agree that the answer lies in social education to try to end entrenched anti-female attitudes
in india, sons are looked upon as potential wage earners and as support for parents in old age. girls are considered a constant burden on resources, and money is needed for their dowry at the time of marriage
a developing consumer society has increased demands for dowry from the traditional jewelry to cars, refrigerators, even houses
this has given rise to ``bride burning,'' the killing of young wives by greedy husbands and in-laws _ usually by setting the women ablaze with kerosene from kitchen stoves and saying it was an accident. at least two women die such fiery deaths every day in new delhi
there are no short-term solutions to the problems of women in india,'' said madhu kishwar, editor of manushi, india's only feminist magazine. ``banning amniocentesis is not the answer because it only will go underground and there will be no monitoring.''
ashok kumar, a businessman waiting in a clinic while his wife was being tested, expressed the attitude of many indians
we have three daughters,'' he said. ``they will get married and go away while a son will carry my name forward.''
besides, he added, old people and neighbors constantly bothered his wife about it
we were made to feel that something was missing.''
he said that even though he and his wife cannot afford four children, they decided to take another chance for a son
it is estimated that up to 1 percent of americans suffer from post traumatic stress disorder, a mental illness brought on by especially harrowing experiences. while not limited to a single group, the disorder afflicts as many as half a million vietnam veterans. this is one veteran's story
it was before dawn, still dark in the cemetery where vietnam veteran john coughlin was paying another visit to the graves of two friends. suddenly, his mind flashed back to vietnam where he'd flirted with death, where his legs had been torn by shrapnel, where he had earned three purple hearts
though it was now 1978, long after his return home from battle, he suddenly sensed that he was under attack. it was may 8, near the anniversary of a battle in which many of his friends were killed, and suddenly the viet cong seemed all around again
he grabbed a shotgun from his car and fired off 14 shots, yelling insults at the imagined enemy. ``i'm going to get every one of you that killed my buddies,'' he vowed
some of the shots struck the back of a police station across the street from the cemetery in quincy, just south of boston
as police gingerly surrounded him, he shouted, ``i don't want any hassle. just leave me alone. i want to die just like billy and jo jo.''
john coughlin died last nov. 5 alone, save his war souvenirs and his american and marine flags. the medical examiner said he died of an overdose of doxepin, an antidepressant drug. friends said he died of a broken heart. he was 42
his legacy was that tragic episode in the cemetery that brought a new awareness to the plight of as many as half a million vietnam veterans suffering from post traumatic stress disorder, the delayed trauma of combat
coughlin was the first vietnam veteran to successfully use the syndrome as a defense against criminal charges
charged with unlawful possession of a firearm, he was allowed to serve two years on probation while undergoing psychiatric treatment, and the charges were eventually dropped
i was convinced that regardless which tab you put on it, there was a mental illness there and no justice would be served in prosecuting him,'' said gerald m. kirby, a former assistant district attorney who handled the case. ``fortunately nobody had been hurt.''
although coughlin was not a crusader for veterans' rights, his attorney, lawrence siskind, said the court's action helped give recognition to post traumatic stress disorder as a serious mental illness
this was a court that said there's a problem,'' siskind said. ``it wasn't just peace groups or veterans groups marching on washington anymore. now somebody could say the va should do something, because here it was accepted.''
dr. ted nadelson, chief of psychiatry services at the boston va medical center, said coughlin ``was kind of a leading edge of a wedge'' that led to that recognition of the illness
dr. terence m. keane, director of the ptsd center at the va center, said the disorder has been treated for at least 100 years, but it wasn't until 1980 that the american psychiatric association gave it greater recognition and status by assigning the name
in 1981, the va ruled that veterans could receive service-connected disability payments if they were diagnosed as having the stress disorder no matter when it developed after discharge. other types of service-connected disabilities must be claimed within a year of discharge
coughlin was cursed with each of the ills of the disorder _ flashbacks, nightmares, intense depression and anxiety, difficulty in relationships and the use of alcohol and drugs
vietnam was so difficult for him, and yet, like other veterans, he couldn't give it up, said nadelson. ``that is an important issue for vietnam veterans, the attachment to it,'' he said
coughlin felt guilt about surviving when friends had been killed. in the last years of his life, he lived in the past among his war memorabilia
he told friends and relatives a few days before his death that he wanted to pull his life together. he said he planned to get a job and move from the room he rented in a three-story rooming house in boston where a dozen other tenants lived, some of them, like him, down on their luck
his room resembled a vietnam bunker, its shades drawn and its walls painted black. he kept a large american flag on one wall over the windows. two smaller american flags were folded away. on the wall behind his bed hung a marine flag. cardboard boxes were filled with vietnam snapshots, including a few of viet cong bodies, and newspaper articles on vietnam, some about him
his proudest possession was an american flag his father gave him when he returned home
i guess that was the first time my father was proud of me, when i got decorated in vietnam,'' he said with tears in his eyes last july in an 18-minute interview videotaped in color with nadelson to help in understanding the stress disorder. he said that the father of a friend of his had taken the place of his own father, a businessman who was often busy working
many troubling feelings remained with coughlin up to his death, nadelson said
when he signed up for a second vietnam tour, coughlin said, it was not just for flag and country. part of it was rage
and liking it,'' he told the psychiatrist. ``addictive. i'm talking about killing, the feeling, the power.''
coughlin was nervous and emotional on the tape, at times shaking and weeping. his comments were often disjointed and lacking elaboration, and at times it was unclear what he meant. one of his front teeth was missing and he wore a scraggly beard
he said he was scared when he first went to vietnam
the first couple months there you're afraid. you see everything. then it doesn't matter after you see death so much. it just doesn't matter. you don't allow yourself to have the feelings. you numb out and then all of a sudden you're put back into people where things are like it never happened
you experience life and death, the closeness ... and all of a sudden you're put back into what they call a real world, a supposedly civilized world, and you cannot cope. it's not that you don't want to. it's that you're afraid to get close. you're afraid to express feelings. the whole atmosphere of people not understanding ...''
like many other veterans who fought in the unpopular war, coughlin received hate mail and calls from people who opposed the war, according to relatives and friends. typical was one letter containing a picture of a destroyed village that said, ``you did this.''
his look and his attitude was that society had basically thrown him out,'' said robert solmente, a boyhood friend. ``i'd say he died of a broken heart.''
coughlin grew up in braintree, a middle class boston suburb. his father died in 1981. his mother and two sisters are his only immediate survivors. he never married. the family declined to discuss his case publicly
he graduated from braintree high school in 1963. his loves were cars and sports
john leroy, who was coughlin's football coach at the school and is now principal, remembered him as an average student but an idealistic and competitive young man who worked hard. although a second-string guard on the team, he rarely, if ever, missed a practice
he enlisted in the marines on jan. 12, 1965. fourteen months later, he was in vietnam
during one battle, he waded through open rice paddies and waist-high water under heavy fire to gain a vantage point on enemy positions and call in artillery fire. for this, he received a commendation from the commanding general of the 1st marines
between august and november of 1967, he was wounded three times, the last time so badly that he had to be evacuated by air from the battlefield and sent to a navy hospital near boston. he was discharged from the marines on oct. 25, 1968
i had nightmares right from maybe a month, month and a half after living with my parents,'' coughlin said. ``they suggested i go seek help ... wasn't safe to be in the house.''
for several years, he lived with four or five other veterans in a house in suburban holbrook. he went from job to job; he parked cars for $1.75 an hour, he was a bouncer at a playboy club in boston, he worked as a salesman. he started drinking heavily and using drugs to escape
from 1970 to the end of his life, he was in and out of va hospitals 26 times
in september 1984, six years after the flashback in the quincy cemetery, he draped a flag over his shoulder at his holbrook home, brandished a hunting knife and begged police who were called to the scene to shoot him. ``he stated that he was like a wounded dog and should be put out of his misery,'' said holbrook police chief john white
it's hard to relate to someone that hasn't experienced what you have,'' coughlin said in the taped interview. ``it's hard to have them understand. it becomes very hard to make the split between what is real and what is fantasy. the biggest problem is letting go of the past, especially when you're proud of something and people are trying to take that away.''
despite all of his problems, he said that if he had his life to live over he would change little, but he might do some things differently
i made private first class out of boot camp,'' he recalled. ``out of 78, four of us got promoted. my father came all the way down from boston to south carolina to see that. i wouldn't trade that for nothing.''
george esper is the ap northeast regional reporter, based in boston
pat robertson has built a name, fortune and accelerating political career on a televison network dedicated to preparing the world for the second coming of jesus christ. yet the republican presidential aspirant now bristles at the label television evangelist
it's become, in my estimation, a bigoted slur,'' robertson said after his second-place finish in the iowa caucuses. religious broadcaster is the term he prefers
during his 30 years in that field, whatever the label, robertson brought charismatic faith and conservative politics to his stands on social and political issues, including who is fit to govern
individual christians are the only ones, really, and jewish people, those who trust the god of abraham, isaac and jacob, are the only ones that are qualified to have the reign, because, hopefully, they will be governed by god and submitted to him,'' robertson said in a 1985 broadcast of his program, ``the 700 club.''
three years later, his political advisers paint robertson as a yale law school-educated businessman, emphasizing the abilities it took to build his christian broadcasting network from almost nothing to the nation's third-largest private cable operation
hardly mentioned these days are the special religious gifts he has talked of in the past
religious revival is a major part of robertson's belief. the secret to revival is powerful prayer, including, some believers say, speaking in tongues, a state in which a person filled with the holy spirit talks in a language unknown to him and to his listeners
robertson's first such experience with that gift came when his son timothy was ill. robertson has written that the boy had a fever of 105, was unconscious and experiencing muscle spasms
i laid my hands on him and cried out again. ... i was suddenly aware of how much god loved him. ... i just consciously lifted tim up to the lord. ... suddenly i was aware of the love of god enfolding him and the power of god going through him. he opened his eyes, murmured, `daddy, i gotta go to the bathroom.'''
in his joy at his son's recovery and in his efforts to praise god, robertson said he began speaking in tongues
with revival and prayer also comes healing, a major part of robertson's past fund-raising telethons. he described one incident that occurred during a telethon
i grabbed one of the ringing phones and heard a little child on the other end saying she had a terrible scar on her face and wanted me to pray that god would remove it. i prayed and hung up. seconds later the phone rang again. it was the girl's grandmother
she was almost hysterical. `my grandchild hung up the phone and turned around and the scar, that horrible scar, was gone. ... god had wiped it off her face!'''
during other telethons, according to robertson:
_an 84-year-old man who had been blind for three years had his sight restored. so did the blind piano player on ``the 700 club.''
_a woman was healed, on camera, of arthritis of her spine
_a baby's twisted foot was healed before the eyes of her father
_and 25 people were instantly healed of deafness
besides the ability to speak in tongues and heal, robertson in his autobiography credits the holy spirit with giving him other gifts
one of the manifestations of the holy spirit that was operative in my life was the word of knowledge. i could tell, almost instantaneously, if a person was speaking the truth or falsehood,'' he said
robertson also says his belief carries the gift of prophecy
in a 1980 mailing to ``the 700 club'' members, robertson said the european economic community was the beast with seven heads and 10 horns prophesied in the bible, and that the anti-christ will emerge from it
this anti-christ would bring great persecution to christians and jews. given the current european disdain for both the christian gospel and the nation of israel, it is not hard to imagine parts of the book of revelations coming to pass,'' robertson said
if his calculations were correct, he said, the anti-christ was 27 years old and ``being groomed to be the satanic messiah.''
robertson's strong support for israel is based on his interpretation of the bible, which he believes prophesies the end of the world
in his 1984 book ``answers to 200 of life's most probing questions,'' robertson wrote, ``we are getting very close to the time when god is going to say that the human race has gone far enough. that is why i firmly expect to be alive when jesus christ comes to earth.''
during a 1981 ``the 700 club'' program, robertson said the united states is referred to only once in the bible but will play an important role in the world's end by offering aid to israel in its fight againt the palestinians
the palestinians have been raping, killing and bombing innocent israelis for years,'' robertson said
while robertson may play down his religious gifts and background as he seeks the republican nomination, his supporters do not
in 1986, when robertson announced that he was considering a run for the presidency, he was introduced by the rev. harold bredsen, who said, ``only a man who god has anointed, only a man who loves god and, whatever cost, obeys god _ only that man can lead us in this hour. we are here tonight because we belive that you, pat, you are that man.''
supporters still see him in that light, according to the rev. billy mccormack, director of robertson's freedom council in louisiana
they really do feel that the time has come for god to raise up a man _ as he has in past history _ daniel, gideon, david, paul, nehemiah and john the baptist,'' mccormack said
leadership. moral strength. excellence in education. toughness
it is on words such as these that presidential campaigns are built
each of the 10 candidates has fashioned his campaign around one or more themes, seeking to convince voters that his is the right vision to lead america into the 1990s
with voters in 20 states holding primaries or caucuses this tuesday, here are snapshots of the candidates and the issues they are running on
bush is running, more than anything else, as ronald reagan's co-pilot
i am proud to have stood with this president through thick and through thin, and in good times and bad times, next to ronald reagan, without cutting and running,'' the vice president told supporters in dallas last month
bush has vowed, ``i'm not going to raise taxes, period,'' and he has called for lowering the tax on capital gains from 28 percent to 15 percent. ``i want to be the fellow to hold the line on the taxes, and the way to do it is to discipline the congress, not the american people,'' he says on the stump
bush also says repeatedly he wants to be known as ``the education president.'' he calls education ``the best answer to poverty'' and the surest route to jobs. he has promised to boost funding for head start, a pre-school program for poor children, and to maintain pell grants, college scholarships based on need
bush also has proposed a new form of u.s. savings bonds that would allow parents to earn interest tax-free on bonds for their children's college education. bush hints that he will be more generous than reagan in funding other education programs and fighting illiteracy, a cause his wife, barbara, has championed
bush, 63, stresses his experience as a congressman, director of the central intelligence agency, ambassador to the united nations and envoy to china and, since 1981, vice president. he was an early and ardent supporter of the intermediate-range nuclear forces treaty with the soviets and has said he would press aggressively for further arms control breakthroughs, including a ban on chemical weapons
i've been to 74 countries as your vice president, met most of the world leaders,'' he says, boasting that he will be ready to provide strong leadership in foreign affairs from his first day in the oval office
he's one of us,'' the dole campaign likes to tell voters
i believe my lifetime record of public service _ from the battlefield to capitol hill _ offers the kind of leadership the country is looking for as we face the tremendous challenges that lie ahead,'' says the kansas senator
dole, 64, is running as a conservative, pragmatic lawmaker who has mastered the art of compromise in his 19 years in the u.s. senate, including two years as majority leader. ``i've made the tough choices,'' he says
dole espouses a modified spending freeze to balance the federal budget by 1993. he has suggested limiting every program, including social security, to budget increases of two percent in order to end the deficits as high as $230 bilion a year that have doubled the national debt during the reagan years
dole often cites the key role he played five years ago in forging a compromise that ended a half-decade of financial turmoil for the social security system
dole backed the inf treaty after some initial hesitation. he is also sponsoring legislation to provide $400 million in grants to help pay for child care. he has refused to say he would not raise taxes under any circumstances
the upstate new york congressman and former professional football quarterback is the champion of free enterprise, supply-side economics, low taxes and the status quo in social security, including full cost-of-living increases
kemp, 52, a nine-term congressman, is an enthusiastic supporter of the strategic defense initiative who has promised a full and early deployment of a space-based anti-missile system. he has opposed the inf treaty
kemp is an ardent free-trader who has promised to veto any ``protectionist'' trade legislation. he has sponsored legislation to set up a north american free-trade zone
in reply to a questionnaire from a non-partisan group, the roosevelt center for american studies, kemp said he was running as an alternative to candidates in both parties ``who look to the future with such anxiety and pessimism that they can think only of ideas that would impose austerity and pain, protectionism and isolationism. they would meet the challenge of budget deficits by increasing taxes, cutting back on social security benefits for the elderly, and weakening our national defense
they would meet the challenge of competition by raising new walls to foreign imports. and they would meet the challenge of securing global peace by conceding territory and human freedom to those who respect the rights of neither. i believe there is a better way, a more confident way, and that is why i am running for president.''
the former television evangelist and founder of the christian broadcasting network says he is running to arrest the ``moral decay'' that he believes is eroding the american family and american institutions
a critic of the inf treaty, robertson promises to take a tough stand against communism. he has claimed repeatedly that the soviet union has secretly installed nuclear missiles in cuba
he is a pronounced critic of public education and supporter of aid for private education
he has called the federal deficit the single worst problem facing the country, and contends he could save billions of dollars by squeezing waste and attacking mismanagement in the federal bureaucracy
robertson, 57, has said he would ``shift away from welfare programs which encourage family breakup.'' he has suggested increased the personal deduction for children, and said that if working women get tax deductions for child-care, mothers who stay home to raise their children should also receive tax breaks
robertson has said that the other candidates are too focused on government programs, when the real problem underlying the united states' economic problems ``is moral decay.''
we need as a people to come together and say we will restore the greatness of america through moral strength,'' says robertson
dukakis, 54, is running largely on his record in his nine years as governor of massachusetts, a state that has bolted out of the economic doldrums in the past decade
the son of greek immigrants, dukakis says the message of his campaign is ``good jobs and real opportunity'' for all, with special emphasis on education and research
speaking of his own family's success story, dukakis says, ``i am running for president because i believe all americans have a right to share in that dream. i believe i have the strength to run this country, the experience to manage our government, and the values to lead our people.''
he says the united states cannot stand ``four more years of credit-card economics.'' but he has proposed tougher tax collection, not tax increases, as the key to reducing the deficit, and claimed it could bring in as much as $110 billion from tax scofflaws and cheats
he has been an outspoken critic of the reagan administration's strategic defense initiative and its aid to the contra rebels in nicaragua
he proposes to expand support for education and overhaul welfare programs along the lines of massachusetts' successful effort to place welfare recipients in jobs
dukakis has also proposed a universal health insurance program for workers in his home state and asked, ``isn't is about time that this nation committed itself to basic health security for its citizens?''
he has espoused public-private partnerships to tackle problems such as housing and homelessness
he opposes the gephardt amendment in the house-passed trade bill, which would mandate automatic u.s. retaliation against countries that fail to trim their trade supluses
no candidate has summarized his campaign in fewer words than gephardt, 47, a veteran of six terms in congress from st. louis, mo.: ``it's your fight, too!''
behind those pugnacious words is a candidate who has led efforts in congress to take a tough stance against countries with huge imbalances in their trade accounts with the united states
to his critics, the gephardt amendment to the trade bill smacks of protectionism that could lead the world into a tariff war with no winners
but for gephardt, with his now famous commercial about the $48,000 hyundai _ which is what he claims the korean car would sell for if the u.s. applied the same tariffs that the koreans do on imports _ it is simply a way of letting the world know that the united states means business
gephardt voted for president reagan's big cut in tax rates in 1981. he has been a leading opponent of aid to the nicaraguan contra rebels
he has called for a new agriculture policy to help family farmers, and accused corporate america of being greedy and short-sighted
once an opponent of abortion, gephardt now opposes efforts to pass a constitutional amendment to make abortion illegal
the tennessee senator, who turns 40 on march 31, has tried to establish himself as the conservative in the democratic field, although he has been a liberal on social issues and health programs during his 11 years in congress (the past three in the senate)
i choose to stand up for what i believe in: an end to the arms race, environmental protection, better schools and economic strength,'' says gore
gore has voted in the past for humanitarian aid for the contra rebels, although he opposed the reagan administration's most recent request. he opposes military aid to the contras
the son of a senator, gore has built his campaign around a southern strategy, hoping that a strong showing there will vindicate his decision not to contest the iowa caucuses and new hampshire primary
he claims to differ from the other democrats with his support for reagan policy in the persian gulf, the invasion of grenada and the midgetman missile
hart, the former colorado senator, has hitched his off-again, on-again campaign to his ``new ideas,'' including military reform and economic restructuring
he has offered the most detailed budget blueprint of any candidate, outlining plans to cut the deficit by more than $100 billion by 1993 and to balance it by 1995
his blueprint includes cuts in military spending and farm subsidies. he would raise the minimum wage and provide more aid for schools and colleges. he wants to impose a $10-per-barrel fee on oil imports and keep the top tax rate at 33 percent for upper-income taxpayers
hart would also make wealthy social security recipients pay income taxes on 85 percent of their benefits, tax capital gains at death, raise cigarette and liquor taxes, and impose a 10-percent levy on purchases of furs, planes and other luxuries
the baptist minister and civil rights leader has called for major cuts in pentagon spending and major increases in federal spending on schools and other social programs
jackson, 46, a native of south carolina who now lives in chicago, has called for ``an end to economic violence.''
there's something wrong when corporate owners make exhorbitant profits while workers lose their jobs,'' says jackson. ``the workers must unite across lines and race, sex and religion.''
jackson has called star wars ``an impossible technological solution to a political problem. it will cost over a trillion dollars if pursued, and in the end will not produce a defense but an arms race in the heavens.''
he has proposed keeping a 38.5 percent tax bracket for wealthy americans and promised to reduce the deficit by cutting military spending ``without cutting our defense, make corporations and the wealthy pay their fair share of taxes and put america back to work.''
jackson says reducing the trade deficit will require ``controlling u.s.-based multi-nationals which close u.s. factories and take jobs overseas'' and ``increasing third world living standards so they can buy more from us.''
i'm not a neo-anything,'' boasts the illinois senator. ``i'm a democrat.''
i'm proud to stand up for the values of franklin roosevelt, harry truman and jack kennedy. i stand for leadership that cares,'' he told the roosevelt center
simon is a longtime supporter of federal education programs and author of 11 books, including one decrying americans' ignorance of foreign languages
to get people back to work, simon has proposed an $8 billion, last-resort public works program that would pay 10 percent more than welfare or unemployment could offer
he has promised to send congress within 60 days of taking office ``a comprehensive long-term (care) program that will move on the huge unmet long-term care needs our society has.''
he believes that reducing the unemployment rate and lowering interest rates are the keys to cutting the federal deficit. if necessary, he says, he will seek an income tax surcharge on the wealthy
broiler chickens, you might say, have more than kept abreast of the times, they have a leg up on most other farming operations
indeed, says an agriculture department report on the nation's broiler industry, raising chickens these days ``seems more like a factory assembly line'' than part of farming's livestock sector
consider what has happened to broiler production and consumption in the united states, remembering that the young birds were once called frying chickens, or fryers, and were a seasonal treat for most families
now, broilers are everywhere and in many forms, packaged whole or cut up; in specialized parts such as wings, legs and breasts; ready to cook; even cooked, baked or barbecued. not to mention all the fast-food variations
this highly integrated, efficiency conscious industry virtually exploded with growth after specialized broiler operations emerged in the late 1930s and early 1940s,'' the report said. ``unlike more diverse beef and hog industries, broiler production is now dominated by a handful of operators, most of whom control their products from incubation to retail.''
when a hog or cattle producer has ``finished'' animals ready for market, they are sold live to a slaughter plant, which in turn may sell the carcasses at wholesale to other buyers. eventually, the beef and pork reaches consumers
but the broiler sector's first point of sale typically is not at the farm, the report said. it's later when the slaughtered, cut up or ready-to-cook birds are sold to wholesalers or retailers
the report is in the march issue of farmline magazine published by the department's economic research service. most of the article is attributed to economist lee christensen
improved genetics, better balanced rations and environmentally controlled housing increased producers' efficiency in raising chickens,'' the report said. ``this helped the industry produce large amounts of economically priced product and capture a greater portion of the market for meat.''
christensen cited some statistics to back up that assertion:
_growers turn out heavier birds in less time. a broiler weighing 3{ to 4{ pounds can be produced in 7 to 8 weeks, about half the 12 t0 14 weeks it took 30 years ago
_it takes only about 2 pounds of feed or less to grow a pound of broiler, down from 4 pounds of feed to 1 pound of bird in the 1940s
_as a result, the average time it takes to raise a group of birds, or brood, is nearly two weeks shorter than a decade ago, allowing growers to produce an extra brood each year. most turn out more than six broods annually
behind the increase in production has been a corresponding rise in consumption,'' the report said. ``much of it occurred while meat consumption levels in general were climbing. now, however, overall meat consumption is leveling off, while broiler consumption continues to rise.''
the report added: ``in all, consumption grew more than 29-fold, from about two pounds per person in 1940 to an estimated 60 pounds in 1987.''
as broilers became specialized, great shudders ran through the poultry industry. christensen said the independently owned small-flock operations that marketed chickens through small processing plants disappeared, giving way to a highly integrated industry dominated by relatively few processors
most of these firms, he said, are located in northeastern arkansas, northern georgia and alabama, central missouri, eastern texas, the delmarva peninsula of delaware and maryland, north carolina and central california
in 1984, 134 firms _ operating 238 federally inspected plants _ processed more than 4 billion birds weighing nearly 18 billion pounds,'' christensen said. ``the four largest firms during that year operated 41 plants that slaughtered 33.7 percent of all the broilers produced.''
by comparison, he said, in 1964, 201 firms operated 320 plants and slaughtered a third fewer chickens
a typical firm might include a hatchery, feed mill, processing plant, and field service, management and marketing staffs, he said. the birds are produced under contracts with growers who provide the facilities and management. typically, it takes 150 to 300 contracts to provide a processor's annual needs
the farmer, or grower, also has experienced concentration. in 1982, the u.s. agricultural census showed 30,100 farms producing broilers, down from 42,185 in 1959. but total output rose to 3.5 billion birds from 1.4 billion during the same period, with the average rising to 116,844 birds in 1982 from 33,637 in 1959
also, the number of broiler farms that each year sell more than 100,000 birds increased to 13,214 in 1982 and represented 89 percent of total production. in 1959, there were only 2,254 of the large farms, and they accounted for less than 29 percent of total output
christensen said many problems remain, including cycles of production and prices, and disease outbreaks. but chicken consumption will probably continue to climb for some time, fueled by a growing population and rising per capita consumption, perhaps to 67 pounds by 1990 and 95 pounds per person by the turn of the century, he said
the broiler industry, however, will not be easy for newcomers, meaning that future growth will have to come from existing firms
new firms cannot afford to jump into the business of raising chickens,'' christensen said. ``the capital investment needed to establish new broiler production and processing facilities is very large, and would be undertaken only after careful analysis.''
a 9 percent decline in new home sales in january pushed sales activity to its slowest pace since the end of the last recession
a downturn in housing often has been a harbinger of recession, but analysts said wednesday they believed falling mortgage rates offered hope of a rebound in home sales in coming months
the commerce department said sales of new single-family homes fell in january for the third consecutive month, dropping to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 535,000 units. that was the slowest pace since the last recession was ending in december 1982
private economists say the 0.6 percent decline in orders to u.s. factories for manufactured goods in january may not be as serious as it first appears
the commerce department said wednesday orders for both durable and non-durable goods dropped to a seasonally adjusted $212.6 billion in january, down $1.25 billion from december, when orders rose 2 percent
it was the first setback in orders since a 1.4 percent drop in august, but economists noted it reflected a swing in the volatile transportation category
federated department stores inc. has agreed to be acquired by r.h. macy &amp; co., but an undaunted campeau corp. proceeded with its rival bid for the nation's fifth largest retailer
federated and macy said wednesday they had signed a definitive agreement under which macy would begin a cash tender offer of $74.50 a share for about 80 percent of federated's 89.6 million outstanding shares, or a total of $5.25 billion. stock in the merged company was included in the deal
campeau said late wednesday it was increasing its previously announced $66 cash tender offer to an effective $68 a share
sears, roebuck &amp; co. says it was beginning a three-year overhaul of its flagship merchandise group to make each segment of its retail business more competitive
the restructuring, which will trim an undetermined number of people from the merchandise group's management, will make sears stores more responsive to customer needs and wants, officials said wednesday
banks recorded their least profitable year since the great depression in 1987, but a top federal regulator sees better days ahead
the nation's federally insured commercial banks earned $3.7 billion last year on assets of $3 trillion, down from $17.5 billion earnings in 1986, l. william seidman, chairman of the federal deposit insurance corp., said wednesday. but he said the drop in earnings was due entirely to large banks adding to reserves to cover anticipated losses on third world loans
federal reserve board chairman alan greenspan says congress should consider trimming social security and other entitlement programs as it searches for ways to reduce the federal budget deficit
greenspan held out little hope wednesday for major deficit reductions in other areas _ although he proposed a 15-cent gasoline tax
oil futures prices remain weak amid confusion over the true level of u.s. oil reserves
on the new york mercantile exchange, crude oil for april delivery closed 5 cents lower at $15.67 per 42-gallon barrel wednesday. the contract had been down as much as 30 cents early in the day
among refined products, wholesale gasoline for april delivery finished at 44.90 cents per gallon, off .39 cent
near-term contracts for wholesale heating oil moved counter to the market's bearish trend with the contract for april delivery settling at 43.93 cents per gallon, up .46 cent
analysts said reports of relatively low supplies of heating oil, compared to levels of previous years, touched off the buying in that sector
but in general, analysts said the market was confused by discrepancies in official estimates of crude oil reserves as compiled by the american petroleum institute and the department of energy
a gap between the estimates issued in recent weeks has put traders on the defensive
there is a scarcity of hard fundamental information right now,'' observed william byers, an analyst with bear, stearns &amp; co. ``we've come to the end of the heating seasons, and traders are looking for something to hold on to.''
afg industries inc., which last week agreed to be taken private in a $940.5 million buyout by its chairman, is being confronted by a competing, higher offer
the investment partnership forstmann little &amp; co. offered wednesday to acquire afg for more than $33 cash a share, although it conditioned the size of the premium on its ability to meet with management and to review internal corporate information
afg announced feb. 25 that it had agreed to a two-step buyout valued at $33 a share by a new company by a new company headed by afg founder and chairman, r.d. hubbard
that offer would pay $33 cash a share for 94 percent of afg's stock and $33 per share in preferred stock or a combination of cash and stock, for the rest of the shares. based on afg's 28.5 million common shares outstanding, the offer had an indicated value of $940.5 million
afg rose 12{ cents to $32.25 a share wednesday on the new york stock exchange. the new offer was announced hours after the market closed
forstmann little, which specializes in leveraged buyouts, stated its offer was not conditioned on financing commitments being obtained. it indicated its decision on the final size of its buyout offer depended on ``prompt receipt and evaluation of information regarding the company'' and on an opportunity to meet with afg management
the firm stated it was capitalized at about $2.7 billion, with $2.4 billion of that available for future acquisitions
irvine, calif.-based afg, one of north america's leading makers of flat glass, declined through a spokesman to comment on the proposal
forstmann little is in the process of acquiring stanadyne corp., a major manufacturer of plumbing fixtures and diesel fuel injection systems, in an $820 million leveraged buyout
in a leveraged buyout, a company is acquired mainly with borrowed funds that are repaid with the target company's cash flow or by the sale of its assets
the firm also has led buyouts of lear siegler inc., dr pepper co., sybron corp. and topps co. inc. in recent years
analysts widely had expected competing offers to emerge for afg, deeming the hubbard bid as relatively low
hubbard's offer was made by clarity holdings corp., a newly formed company headed by hubbard
afg became well recognized outside its own industry in 1986 when it launched an unsuccessful hostile takeover bid for lear siegler, the aerospace and manufacturing conglomerate based in santa monica, calif
in 1987, afg made an unsucessful hostile bid for gencorp. of akron, ohio, which formerly was known as general tire &amp; rubber co
late last year, afg announced it had agreed to purchase ford motor co.'s glass-making operations in canada, which with annual sales of about $150 million was the industry leader in that country. no terms were disclosed for that deal, which closed early this year
a merger agreement with r.h. macy &amp; co. hasn't dampened the frenzied bidding for federated department stores inc., as rival suitor campeau corp. has escalated its attempt to acquire the nation's fifth-largest retailer
following federated's announcement wednesday that it had agreed to be acquired by macy for cash and stock worth more than $5.45 billion, campeau sharply revised its own all-cash proposal in an attempt to woo federated shareholders
federated and macy said they had a definitive agreement under which macy would acquire federated and form a new company, macy's-federated inc. the deal still must be approved by shareholders of both companies
macy, the nation's 10th-largest retailer, operates 96 stores in 14 states, while federated has 650 stores _ including such department stores as bloomingdale's, filene's and bullock's _ in 36 states
under the agreement, macy would pay $74.50 a share in cash for about 80 percent of federated's 89.6 million outstanding shares, or a total of $5.25 billion. the remaining federated shares would be exchanged for stock in the new company
campeau, which had been offering $68 a share _ totaling $6.1 billion _ for all of the outstanding federated shares, responded by changing its offer to $75 a share for 80 percent of federated's stock. in a subsequent merger, campeau would pay $44 a share for the remaining stock, giving the total deal a combined value of $68 per share, campeau said
campeau also said it would file suit to challenge $45 million in fees that federated agreed to pay macy if their deal fell through. if the fees are invalidated or withdrawn, campeau said it would pay $46.20 per share for the 20 percent of federated shares remaining after a merger
campeau's new proposal expires at midnight est march 15
the amended campeau bid was announced after the close of trading on the new york stock exchange, where federated's stock fell $1 a share to $66.75
wall street analysts said it was hard to predict what federated's shareholders would do, given the difficulty of putting a value on the stock portion of macy's offer
macy is privately held, so it is difficult to know how much its shares are worth
it's really tough to figure out which is a better deal,'' said joseph ronning, a retail industry analyst with brown brothers harriman &amp; co
if you want immediate money, go for cash'' in the campeau offer, said monroe h. greenstein, an analyst with bear stearns &amp; co. inc
but in the long term, greenstein said, he considered the macy bid better because it offered better potential for future growth for federated
no matter who ends up controlling federated, the new owner is expected to sell the company's gold circle discount stores and ralphs supermarkets
among cincinnati-based federated's department stores are the bloomingdale's, burdine's, filene's, i. magnin., rich's, abraham &amp; straus and lazarus chains
either macy or campeau were expected to sell several of those chains if they acquired federated. abraham and straus and rich's were considered likely candidates for a sale by macy, because they are direct competitors with macy stores in new york and atlanta, respectively
under the macy agreement, federated management would have a strong voice in the new company, filling 40 percent of the seats on its board of directors
however, federated chairman howard goldfeder, 61, said at a news conference wednesday he would resign after helping macy chairman edward finkelstein implement the merger
goldfeder said he expects to be paid $3.06 million when he leaves the company under a ``golden parachute'' severance agreement approved by federated's board of directors. similar payments are due other top federated officers
in deciding to merge with macy, the federated board had considered the $68 a share campeau merger offer as well as an indication from campeau that the offer could be increased to $69.50 under certain unspecified conditions, macy and federated said
the companies stated that federated's board had turned down campeau's alternative $66-a-share tender offer as inadequate, but it did not characterize the $68 and $69.50 bids
federated refused to elaborate on the statement, and macy referred all questions on the board's discussion to federated
new york-based macy was taken private by a management group in a $3.6 billion leveraged buyout in 1986. its stores rang up $5.21 billion in sales during the fiscal year ended last aug. 1
campeau, through its allied stores division, owns the jordan marsh, stern's, ann taylor and maas brothers chains
here are the nation's nine largest general retailers, ranked by sales in their 1987 fiscal year, which ended jan. 31:
