stores _ 650
states _ 36: alabama, arizona, california, colorado, connecticut, delaware, florida, georgia, illinois, indiana, kansas, kentucky, louisiana, maine, maryland, massachusetts, michigan, missouri, nevada, new hampshire, new jersey, new mexico, new york, north carolina, ohio, oklahoma, oregon, pennsylvania, rhode island, south carolina, tennessee, texas, virginia, washington, west virginia, wisconsin
ownership _ public, 21,000 shareholders
headquarters _ cincinnati. 1987</head>
the united states continued to import more electronics than it exported last year, although exports increased at the fastest pace since 1980, the electronic industries association said today
exports of electronic products grew to $40 billion last year, 20 percent over the $33.4 billion in 1986, while imports rose to nearly $57.9 billion, up 15 percent from $50.3 billion in 1986, the trade group said
peter f. mccloskey, the group's president, said a lower dollar, improved quality and aggressive marketing are making u.s. exports more competitive in the world marketplace
in 1980, exports rose 21 percent over the previous year, while imports rose 13 percent. but between 1981 and 1986, the increase in imports outpaced the rise in exports, the association said
the trade group also said its analysis of commerce department figures showed canada was the no. 1 importer of u.s. electronics last year, buying more than $5 billion worth. the united kingdom ranked second at $3.9 billion, japan was third with $3.8 billion and west germany was fourth at $3.1 billion
japan continued to top the list of foreign suppliers of electronic products to the united states, with sales of nearly $25 billion last year, the group said. it was followed by taiwan with nearly $5.6 billion in sales, korea with $4.3 billion and singapore with $4.0 billion
three years of price increases are beginning to take their toll on foreign car sales, as buyers taking another look at american models find improved cars with stickers as much as $2,000 lower than comparable imports
automakers in japan and western europe have been forced to raise prices to compensate for the plummeting dollar, which has fallen 50 percent against their currencies since 1985
while the european companies felt the bite sooner, industry analysts said japanese car sales also appear to be softening, particularly for smaller companies and nissan, which has been hurt by a lack of new products
there is definitely suffering,'' said thomas o'grady, industry analyst with integrated automotive resources in wayne, pa
general motors corp., ford motor co. and chrysler corp. have turned the weak dollar to their advantage by holding down prices instead of matching their foreign competitors increase-for-increase as before
they are all looking at 1988 as the year of the return of the domestic (car) or the start of that return,'' said chris cedergren, industry analyst with j.d. power and associates in agoura hills, calif
price increases have added as much as $6,000 to the sticker of a german car and $3,000 for a japanese model since the dollar began falling. the price difference between a japanese car and a comparable american model has reached $1,500 to $2,000, analysts said
japanese car prices have risen nearly 25 percent in the past three years. european autos have risen less on a percentage basis but more in dollar terms because they predominantly are luxury models that cost more to start with
european makers felt the pinch from the weak dollar first because japanese auto prices had a built-in cushion: u.s. dealers faced with heavy demand had been tacking $1,000 to $2,000 on to the sticker price and still selling all the cars they could get
buyers didn't begin to notice that japanese cars were growing more expensive until late in 1986, when dealers had used up the cushion and began raising prices. but even then, the difference meant only a few dollars more in monthly payments
furthermore, buyers who had been weaned from american cars by the quality and reliability of japanese cars were willing to pay a little extra for the imports, said joseph phillippi, analyst with shearson lehman hutton in new york
as a result, while total car sales declined 10.7 percent in 1987, japanese import car sales fell only 9.7 percent while gm, ford and chrysler's domestic car sales together fell 16.7 percent
the currency-related price increases pushed european makers such as bmw, mercedes-benz and porsche further into the ultra-luxury stratosphere with new cars that cost $40,000 to $70,000, and pushed many buyers out of the market
during january, sales fell by about 28 percent for mercedes-benz, volvo and porsche, 51 percent for alfa-romeo and 60 percent for peugeot
but the japanese fought back. companies such as toyota motor corp., honda motor co. and mazda motor corp. accepted smaller profits and squeezed steady efficiency improvements out of their factories at home to protect their u.s. market share
helped by the strength of the japanese yen, used to buy raw materials from weaker-currency nations, they were able to keep price increases so small that the big three accused them of predatory pricing in the united states
they also began shifting some production to the united states and began offering or planning cars to fill the void left by the europeans in the $20,000 to $30,000 luxury market
but despite their efforts, higher prices have begun to hurt japanese car sales. while toyota and honda remain strong, other makes are showing signs of strain
in january, nissan's import car sales fell 19.6 percent in january from a year ago and isuzu's sales fell 16.7 percent. japanese makers also are reporting higher inventories of unsold cars and are increasing their use of buyer incentives, analysts said
still, they warn, the big three have only a limited time to take full advantage of the import weakness and win back some of the buyers they lost to the japanese earlier in the decade because the japanese will adapt to the new currency level
the japanese will have fully adjusted within 18 months from now,'' o'grady said
the tiny investment banker james d. wolfensohn inc. has gotten a big name to hang out his shingle at the firm: former federal reserve chairman paul volcker
volcker was named wednesday as chairman of the new york-based firm, and also as a professor at princeton university
the announcements ended the months of speculation over volcker's next career move that followed his decision last year not to accept another term at the fed
volcker's international reputation and widespread connections stemming from his tenure at the central bank were highly prized by wall street, and his decision to join wolfensohn represents a coup for the firm
volcker, who served as director of the federal reserve from 1979 to 1987, ``brings great experience in the whole area of finance and general economic matters,'' said james wolfensohn, the firm's founder, president and chief executive officer
he's a great negotiator and will help run client relations and add to the breadth of the services we bring to our clients,'' wolfensohn said
wolfensohn said the six-year-old firm specializes in work with major american and international companies and their strategies in mergers and acquisitions
he said he has known volcker for at least 10 years
volcker, who graduated from princeton's woodrow wilson school of public and international affairs in 1949, is the first to hold the school's frederic h. schultz class of 1951 professorship of international economic policy
the princeton post and the position with wolfensohn are effective immediately
at a news conference wednesday morning in princeton, volcker said he declined professorship offers from a number of other universities, including harvard, from which he received his master's degree in political economy in 1951
i had discussions with a number of ivy league and non-ivy league universities,'' he said. ``i think it is fair to say that there was a certain pull here for my alma mater, though i have a another alma mater in the ivy league
i felt comfortable here. the school combines my interest in the public service and in economic policy.''
volcker said he intends to spend the coming months at princeton meeting with graduate students and attending a faculty seminar on international trade
i'm delighted to have the opportunity to get the kind of intellectual stimulus you can get here and i hope to contribute a little bit,'' he said. ``i'm somewhat intimidated by the fact that i'm having to go back and do a little teaching. i'm hoping for a little assistance to help me through those early stages.''
during the 1988-89 academic year he plans to teach both semesters at the graduate and undergraduate levels
sears, roebuck and co. says a three-year overhaul of its $28 billion retail stores operation will make the nation's biggest general retailer more responsive to customers and more profitable for investors
retailing analysts see the shakeup as an attempt to revive sluggish sales and profits within the company's merchandise group, which saw its share of sears' total revenue slip to about 58 percent in 1987 from more than 65 percent in 1985
basically what we find today is a sears company not as strong as it was last year,'' analyst allan bortel, a senior vice president for shearson lehman hutton inc., said wednesday
sears says its planned new retailing structure would improve its competitiveness, which in turn would better serve its customers and shareholders
if we have a leaner management organization, because we will be that much more competitive, we will be delivering greater revenues and greater income to the bottom line,'' said company spokesman philo holland after sears announced the restructuring wednesday
the restructuring, which will trim an undetermined number of people from the merchandise group's management staff of about 4,000, is aimed at making each department of every sears store more competitive, officials said
the plan calls for each department, from womens apparel to lawn and garden supplies, to be reorganized under its own, unique management structure
the apparel business will be run differently from the hardware business,'' holland said. ``you need different organizational structures to compete in different businesses.''
michael bozic, chairman and chief executive officer of the merchandising group, stated that the restructuring would reduce the number of management levels, making each segment of sears' merchandise business leaner and more independent
we are competing in many diverse businesses, each with its own unique structure, and (we) have been essentially using one organizational format to compete in all of these businesses,'' bozic said
the changes we make will result in a company that is better structured to maintain its position as america's premier retailer,'' he said
officials said they had no estimate of the number of employees to be affected or the cost savings involved
the ultimate size and structure will be determined by how we choose to compete in the different businesses we are restructuring,'' holland said
he said the reduction in management personnel would be achieved through attrition, severance bonuses and early retirement offers
bortel said he didn't expect massive layoffs or sales of valued assets in the near future
sears is a very conservative company and does not do anything in a radical way,'' bortel said in a telephone interview from san francisco
worldwide demand for oil may drive prices up to nearly twice present levels and increase dependence on persian gulf supplies, according to a study by harvard university
the yearlong study released wednesday said the improved economies in industrial nations since oil prices dropped in 1986 have discouraged conservation efforts and reduced oil stockpiles
former federal reserve chairman paul volcker has been named to a professorship at princeton university and the chairmanship of james d. wolfensohn inc., a new york city investment banking firm
volcker, who graduated from princeton's woodrow wilson school of public and international affairs in 1949, is the first to hold the school's frederic h. schultz class of 1951 professorship of international economic policy
the princeton post and the position with wolfensohn are effective immediately, volcker said wednesday
a growing amount of tax money withheld from workers' paychecks is being misused by employers, often never finding its way to the government, the internal revenue service says
the total of these delinquent social security and income taxes rose by 49 percent from 1982 through 1987, to almost $3.73 billion, william m. wauben, irs assistant commissioner for collections, said wednesday
he said about 338,000 employers have failed to pay or account for that sum
on-time peformance by the nation's major airlines improved slightly during january, but three out of every 10 flights still were at least 15 minutes late, the transportation department said
the 14 airlines that are monitored in the monthly report had 69.2 percent of their flights arriving within 15 minutes of schedule, compared with 66.4 percent in december, the report released wednesday said
southwest airlines had the best record in february with 85 percent of its flights arriving on time, while continental airlines had the worst mark with a 65 percent on-time arrival record
new rules are being prepared to help farmers pay off loans owed to the farmers home administration, including provisions that allow the agency to write off some of the debt so that families can stay on the land, officials say
joe o'neill, an fmha spokesman, said wednesday the new rules probably will be ready by june. in many cases, over-burdened borrowers could have much of their debt written off, trimmed back to reflect their assets in hopes of keeping them in business. he said he had no estimate of how much debt the fmha might write off under the new rules
the stock market posed a small gain wednesday as the dow jones average of 30 industrials finished up .83 at 2,071.29
the dollar strengthened in foreign exchange trading, while gold prices were narrowly mixed. bond prices edged higher in light trading
cocoa futures prices fell to life-of-contract lows for the fourth consecutive day on fears that the international cocoa organization will be unable to control the effects of steadily rising production
soaring sales to japan and britain helped send total u.s. wine exports in 1987 to 11.87 million gallons, a 64 percent increase over the previous year, a trade group reported
the dollar's decline against foreign currencies, including a 55 percent drop against the japanese yen over the past two years, was largely the cause, the wine institute said wednesday
u.s. wineries also have begun more aggressive promotions to overseas markets, said sam folsom, a spokesman for the san francisco-based institute
overall, u.s. exports totaled $60.8 million in 1987, up from $34.8 million the year before. calfornia wines account for about 95 percent of american wine exports
exports account for only 3 percent of all california wine shipments, but the sales are considered important because domestic sales have been less than dynamic in recent years, according to wine experts
japan is one of the fastest growing markets
there's a growing awareness of califoria wines, particularly among japanese yuppies,'' said wine consultant jon fredriskson
japan was the largest export market in terms of dollars, importing $14 million worth of american wine, or 2.25 million gallons, up from $7.3 million worth in 1986
canada imported $10.9 million, but in greater bulk. its imports reached 3.3 million gallons, up from 2.6 million in 1986. in terms of gallons, it was the largest importer of american wine. graf pvs, young said ... a version moving on general news wires.</note>
the head of the food and drug administration said today the agency hopes to make a decision in a few months on whether aspirin manfacturers can advertise claims that their products help reduce a first heart attack
fda commissioner frank e. young said he was pleased with a voluntary agreement from the nation's aspirin manufacturers wednesday not to make such claims until data from a recent study can be fully analyzed
young, interviewed on abc-tv's ``good morning america,'' said people with high blood pressure, liver disease, gout or ulcers face the risk of bleeding complications from aspirin and should seek the advice of a doctor on its usage
he also said that while there is some evidence that healthy men between the ages of 45 and 85 might use an aspirin every other day to reduce the risk of heart attack, there is no evidence that it would help women or younger men
we didn't want to see people get hurt. we felt it important to get the facts in...'' young said. ``we hope to make our decision within a few months.''
summoned by a letter that reminded them of the fda's regulatory power, aspirin manufacturers met for more than an hour on wednesday with young, who then announced the agreement at a news conference
young said the agency was concerned that aspirin ads citing a recent medical journal study could be misleading
the manufacturers agreed to exercise voluntary restraint and refrain from further promotion of the study results until the facts of the study are known and the necessary analyses were completed and appropriate physician labeling made available,'' young announced in a formal statement
though he called the action ``voluntary'', young said later on public television's ``macneil-leher news hour'' that if the manufacturers ``go and make a misbranded claim then we could take action. ... the extreme action is to call the product misbranded and seize it.''
the commissioner insisted that the meeting was not called in response to advertising already run, saying he was ``so busy'' that he never read, listened or watched advertising
young said the meeting was prompted by publicity surrounding an aspirin study published jan. 28 in the new england journal of medicine
in the study, more than 11,000 physicians over the age of 40 took one aspirin every other day, while another group of physicians took placebos, or fake aspirin. at the end of 57 months, the study showed that those taking aspirin had 47 percent fewer heart attacks
young said the study was incomplete and the fda has not approved aspirin for use in the prevention of an initial heart attack
until the fda analyzes the study and formulates formal physician instructions on the use of aspirin against first heart attacks, young said drug companies cannot promote aspirin for this use
there are no loopholes in the agreement for ads already prepared, he said
from this time forward, any ads in the pipeline will not be grandfathered (escape enforcement),'' said young
william c. macleod, director of consumer protection at the federal trade commission, which regulates drug advertising, refused repeatedly at the news conference to say if his agency had taken any action regarding ads by aspirin manufacturers, nor would he say that inappropriate ads had been run
in a feb. 24 letter, young ``invited'' the drug manufacturers to attend a meeting at his fda office to discuss the aspirin findings. he wrote of his concern that ``the dissemination of certain types of information is clearly premature.''
the letter also cited the federal law that forbids mislabeling drugs
the agency did not identify the manufacturers attending the meeting, and most of those leaving the closed-door session refused to comment. an exception was dr. edward henry of squibb pharmaceutical products, who would say only: ``we're all in agreement. it was a very good meeting.''
several drug companies have produced ads promoting the use of aspirin to help prevent a second heart attack. these were based on a 1985 study that was analyzed by the fda
but the study announced in january was the first to suggest that aspirin could help prevent a primary, or first, heart attack
young said his concern is that the latest study involved a narrow group _ all physicians in good health _ and that the aspirin therapy is not appropriate for everyone, particularly the young. he said the study showed that aspirin therapy could increase the risk of stroke
the commissioner also said unsupervised aspirin use can cause intestinal bleeding and aggravate gout, peptic ulcer, and kidney and liver disease
to take it willy-nilly every other day, particularly if you are a young man or woman, you are more apt to have a stroke or suffer from a bleeding ulcer,'' he said
young said it will take about six months for the fda to analyze the aspirin study and then publish new labeling rules for the drug. further reagan quotes and background. a version moving on general news wires.</note>
president reagan indicated today he believes panamanian gen. manuel antonio noriega must go, while secretary of state george p. shultz said economic sanctions against noriega's government were being ``considered carefully.''
reagan, during an unscheduled meeting with british prime minister margaret thatcher at the conclusion of the nato summit, was asked during a picture-taking session if he thought noriega should relinquish power
yes,'' the president responded. he did not elaborate
during a subsequent photo session with belgian prime minister wilfried martens, reagan was asked if the united states was ready to seize panamanian assets in american banks
i can't give you an answer yet,'' he replied. ``we still have a lot of talking to do.''
reagan last friday said he had no plans to intervene militarily in panama and said he thought the american options were limited in the area
shultz called noriega ``bad news'' but said that no decision had been made on sanctions
assistant secretary of state elliott abrams had raised the prospect in washington on wednesday that the next payment due to panama for panama canal operations would be withheld if such a request were made by ousted president eric arturo delvalle
state department deputy spokeswoman phyllis oakley said that the request already had been received
at a news conference today in brussels following the conclusion of the nato summit, shultz told reporters, ``noriega is bad news for panama, he's bad news for the region.''
he said there were a ``variety of things'' the united states could do, including restricting the flow of money into the panamanian treasury. ``that is being considered carefully,'' he said. ``we want to do it properly, we want to do it right, we want to do it effectively.''
in washington, abrams said the administration would respond to a request by delvalle to withhold the canal payments
if he tells us he doesn't want that money going to noriega, then we're not going to give it to noriega.''
panama receives a reported $80 million in canal-related fees annually. four members of the house merchant marine and fisheries committee demanded wednesday that the administration halt all such payments to panama
the united states continues to regard delvalle as panama's constitutional president and seeks the removal of noriega, under federal indictment on drug smuggling charges, from the nation's political life
delvalle was ousted last week after attempting to fire noriega and has been in hiding in panama since then
at stake is a $7 million u.s. payment due march 15 for canal tolls, fees and services. much more is involved in what appears to be a parallel u.s. effort to keep the new panamanian government from gaining access to official accounts in u.s. banks
william d. rogers, of the arnold &amp; porter law firm in washington, said the administration was taking legal steps to ensure that the banks may make disbursements only to the panamanian ambassador who served under delvalle, juan b. sosa
rogers, who represents delvalle and his allies here, said the state department was issuing ``formal certifications'' that it regards sosa as ``the accredited representative of the recognized government of the country.''
at the state department, ms. oakley said only that such certifications were being prepared. she declined to specify their purpose
asked about the u.s. position on that issue, abrams told the cable news network: ``we know who the legitimate government of panama is. if the government of president delvalle says to american banks, `don't pay money to noriega,' then all those banks are going to come to the state department and say, `who's got the authority here? noriega or delvalle?'
we're going to answer that question. delvalle is president of panama. and noriega has been fired and he does not have legitimate authority here.''
sosa estimated that u.s. bank deposits of the panamanian government total $50 million
rogers seemed confident that the u.s. government action would preclude any panamanian government withdrawals from u.s. accounts, but neither abrams nor ms. oakley offered confirmation of that claim
also on wednesday, u.s. district judge lloyd f. mcmahon in manhattan issued a temporary restraining order blocking republic national bank from turning millions of dollars over to the new government
the noriega opponents dropped the suit afterward when the bank agreed to transfer the funds to the federal reserve bank of new york
rogers said the settlement does not affect four other banks being sued: marine midland na, irving trust co., bankers trust co. in new york, and the bank of boston in that city
the point is not to get money but to deny money to noriega,'' he said. include volkswagen comment. picks up 10th graf pvs, a nhtsa ... a version moving on general news wires.</note>
the national highway traffic safety administration and volkswagen appear to be working together to keep the public from learning if sudden acceleration is still a problem in audi 5000 cars, a congressman says
nhtsa, which last year ordered a massive recall of the vehicles for installation of a device to fix alleged throttle problems, has failed to press volkswagen of america inc. to place post-recall reports of sudden acceleration on the public record, rep. george hochbrueckner, d-n.y., said wednesday
in a letter to nhtsa administrator diane steed, hochbrueckner said he was ``disturbed by evidence ... which suggests that nhtsa willingly acquiesced to (volkswagen's) refusal to turn over the incident reports.''
he demanded that volkswagen turn over all documents relating to post-recall reports of sudden acceleration to congress, rather than to the agency responsible for investigating the complaints
congress has no power to compel the documents be turned over to it, said andy kennedy, an aide to hochbrueckner
nhtsa is auditing its january 1987 recall of 255,336 1978-86 audi 5000s for installation of the throttle device. the agency has received 1,750 complaints of sudden acceleration in audi 5000s, resulting in 1,269 accidents, 430 injuries and five deaths
a nhtsa memorandum by wolfgang reinhart, dated last january, said the agency asked vw for the documents in june 1987, but they were not included in the automaker's response in july
the documents were made available by volkswagen for inspection in its washington office rather than being delivered to nhtsa, the memo said. ``the source documents were reviewed by (nhtsa) personnel and the summaries were found to be accurate summations of the very bulky source documents,'' it said
volkswagen late wednesday issued a statement in response saying that ``nhtsa has not given us any special concessions, neither have we been relieved of any of the burden of responding to the agencies' requests for information.''
the automaker said the summaries were an interim report. ``at no time was it suggested that this status update would take the place of the technical data required by nhtsa, or that we had refused to provide nhtsa with this data, or that we would permanently retain the data in our possession,'' volkswagen said
a nhtsa spokesman said there had been other instances in which nhtsa had requested summaries of complaints rather than the complaints themselves. he was unable to say how common the practice was
he declined to comment specifically on hochbrueckner's allegations. the spokesman demanded anonymity, citing agency policy
