republic national bank of new york has agreed to transfer millions of dollars in panamanian funds to the federal reserve bank and in return, foes of panama's dictatorship have dropped a lawsuit against the bank
the settlement was announced wednesday evening, hours after a federal judge signed an order barring republic national from releasing the contested funds to the regime of military strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega
the judge's action came at the request of panamanian president eric arturo delvalle, ousted last week following his unsuccessful attempt to fire noriega but still recognized by the u.s. government as the legitimate head of panama
the suit appeared to be part of a coordinated effort to deny money to noriega's cash-strapped regime, which already has been cut off from u.s. aid. the state department also has asked a group of banks not to disburse panamanian government funds to noriega
filed on behalf of the republic of panama at manhattan federal court, the suit asserted a ``massive transfer of funds'' to noriega had already occurred and up to $10 million more would be transferred unless the court stopped it
but late in the day, the bank said the lawsuit ``has been voluntarily dismissed and republic national bank of new york has transferred to the federal reserve bank of new york, any funds held by it of banco nacional de panama.''
william d. rogers, attorney for the noriega opponents who brought the lawsuit, confirmed the settlement in a telephone interview from his washington office. but rogers said he didn't know much much money had been transferred to the federal reserve bank for safekeeping
the point is not to get money but to deny money to noreiga,'' said rogers, adding that the settlement doesn't affect similar lawsuits against three other new york banks: bankers trust, irving trust and marine midland
those banks were included after the original lawsuit was filed but were not immediately included in u.s. district judge lloyd f. macmahon's temporary restraining order which had been signed earlier in the day
noriega, military leader of panama, was indicted on drug charges by two u.s. grand juries in florida feb. 4. delvalle sought to dismiss noriega feb. 25 but was ousted by noriega supporters and has gone into hiding
on tuesday, delvalle took steps through his supporters to freeze panamanian assets outside the country
panama's u.s. ambassador, juan b. sosa, who has maintained that delvalle's ouster was unconstitutional, said he had no precise figures on the amount of money in panamanian accounts but estimated it to be $50 million
according to court papers, sosa told all four banks by telex tuesday that only he was authorized to approve transfer of money from the panamanian accounts
a pair of connecticut entrepreneurs have in hand the blueprints they think will alter the popular image of modular homes as boxy structures that sway in the breeze
harvey f. gerber jr. and his wife, wendy a. horgan, have formed a company that will sell modular houses designed by an architect to look like and compete with the best custom-built homes
it's a new market with few competitors
the incentive to homebuyers is that so-called ``high-end modular homes'' can be built at a lower cost and much faster than comparable stick-built homes that are constructed from the ground up, gerber said
the four styles offered by gerber builders inc. are two-story homes, with large porches, 9-foot ceilings, family rooms, multiple bathrooms and at least three bedrooms. the houses also allow for personalized touches, such as a choice of flooring, siding and trim molding
the price ranges from about $70,000 to $130,000 for a 2,000-square-foot house, depending upon whether a buyer purchases an unfinished model or a completed home. the price of land isn't included
what we have here is a product that is aimed at a high-end market. it is going to be indistinguishable from the best stick-built homes,'' gerber said during a recent interview
gerber, 39, and his wife are both former wall street attorneys. they got their start in construction 10 years ago when they began renovating historic buildings in new york city. they had branched out into condominium construction in new jersey when they decided to focus on modular homes
they chose connecticut because of their connections to the state. ms. horgan, originally from new canaan, received her master's and law degrees from the university of connecticut. gerber attended yale and got his law degree from fordham university
the company has constructed a victorian-style model on its 11-acre headquarters site in newtown, an affluent suburban community about 70 miles north of new york city. the firm is constructing three other models on a parcel in sussex county, n.j
the completion of the model was the culmination of three years of design work and planning that has cost the company about $1 million, gerber said
the company's goal is to sell at least 100 homes the first year and begin construction of connecticut's first modular home factory at the newtown site
if all goes well, ground could be broken on the proposed 57,000-square-foot factory this summer. the factory would produce 300 homes a year and the product line would be expanded to include lower-priced and more expensive models along with the intermediate-priced models now being offered
the gerber homes currently are constructed by contempri homes in taylor, pa., and shipped to connecticut. all the gerber homes have been designed by deborah berke, who teaches architecture at yale university and runs a business in new york city
modular homes account for about 5 percent of all housing starts nationwide, and perhaps 15 percent of new houses in the northeast, where most modular home factories are located, said barbara martin, special projects consultant for the buildings systems council of the national association of home builders in washington, d.c
she could name only three companies selling high-end modular homes
george oswald of techno craft inc., another modular home company, predicts that 50 percent of the housing starts in the northeast will be modular homes by the year 2000
techno craft, which opened a 100,000-square-foot factory in mcelhattan, pa., last year, already has about $80 million in orders for its luxury homes
we're the ones who broke the sound barrier by going into the high-end (modular home) market,'' oswald said
the smallest techno-craft home is 2,600 square feet, with its colonial mansion models ranging up to 7,000 square feet, oswald said. the cost averages about $50 a square foot. the homes are sold finished and are available only through developers
gerber plans to sell to individual home buyers and small contractors
his current models cost about $65 a square foot completed, or about $130,000. it would take a crew several days to assemble the six pieces of each model and then about three more months to complete the home, gerber said
to those wanting to save money, the company will sell unfinished homes for about $35 a square foot, or about $70,000. for that price, the home comes with much of the work done, such as all the plumbing and electrical wiring run, and the insulation and wallboard installed. but an unfinished house has no roof, no siding, and the plumbing and wiring need to be hooked up
the company also will sell kits to those more than 30 miles away from its newtown office
we've gotten universal praise from every bank, appraiser, engineer, contractor and prospect who has visited the house (in newtown) prior to its formal opening,'' said gerber. ``at the same time, we haven't had the ultimate test, which is market exposure. we can't conclusively say we've designed a hula hoop, although that's what we believe.''
italian financier carlo de benedetti must identify his allies before government regulators will allow an extension of his offer for societe generale de belgiqe s.a, belgium's biggest holding company, a banking commission official said thursday
the official, who asked not to be named, said the french investment firm cerus s.a, through which de benedetti has sought control of societe generale, had asked to extend its offer beyond friday's original deadline
but the banking commission demanded that cerus names all its allies, specifying how many shares of societe generale each owns, by friday night before approving the request, the official said
cerus itself has a 18.6 percent stake in societe generale. but de benedetti claims he and his allies control 47.2 percent of the company's 28.2 million shares
a rival alliance centered around the french investment cie financiere de suez and belgium's biggest insurer, groupe ag, says it has a majority stake of 52 percent
both sides have voiced doubts on the claims of their opponents, and have each laid claim to the company's proposed capital increase of 12 million shares, which was approved by a brussels court tuesday
the ruling, however, is subject to confirmation by by a higher court
de benedetti wants to turn the 166-year-old societe generale into a holding company with interests across europe and wants to run the day-to-day affairs
the rival alliance wants to keep societe generale anchored in belgium
the company has interests in about half of belgium's 50 biggest companies and has an important stake in the country's gas, electricity and petroleum sector and belgium's largest bank
