the u.s. auto industry may be trimming back on engineers, but the british auto industry is going out of its way to find more
the problem is the long, steady decline of auto manufacturing in the 1960s and 1970s, when young engineers looking for interesting, better paying jobs entered other fields
now that automaking in britain is on the rebound, the country's society of motor manufacturers &amp; traders has mounted a large-scale effort to restore pride in its car industry, said godfrey messervy, the society's president
messervy, in town for the society of automotive engineers annual convention, said britain is suffering from a shortage of engineers even though it is home to leading-edge innovators such as lotus engineering
there's a tendency for them not to go into the motor industry,'' messervy said
sales have begun to recover along with pay scales, he said, and makers have been improving efficiency and winning back sales in an import-dominated market
car sales in 1987 were a record of more than 2 million in the united kingdom, and the share of the market held by british-built car rose to 48.3 percent from 44 percent in 1986
but the nation doesn't seem aware that it again is growing a strong auto industry and messervy's society wants to change that
targeting schools, it is trying to convince parents and students that the auto industry is a good field for engineers and offering school career counselors 12-week introductions to the industry, sometimes with full pay
the society also is lobbying the government to repeal a 10 percent tax on car sales that doesn't apply to other consumer goods. in a nation with the lowest per-capita car ownership rate in western europe, messervy said repeal of the tax would boost car sales by 200,000 a year
