an investment group led by beazer plc and shearson lehman hutton inc. launched a tender offer today of nearly $1.3 billion for koppers co. inc., a construction and chemicals company
koppers, which is based in pittsburgh, had no comment on the offer, which was initially disclosed in an advertisement in today's edition of the wall street journal. the offer expires march 30
beazer is a general construction company based in london and shearson is a new york-based investment banking firm
the offer of $45 a share is being made by bns inc., a company that is reportedly 49 percent owned by beazer and 45 percent by shearson. the remainder is held by county natwest international inc., a british investment bank
the bid triggered speculation on wall street that a higher offer might arise. in trading on the new york stock exchange, koppers stock jumped $6.37{ a share to $51.50 by midday
the bid is conditioned on, among other things, tender of a majority of koppers' common shares, approval by the non-managment directors of koppers, approval by beazer's shareholders and the bidding group's satisfaction that certain elements of delaware antitakeover laws are invalid
in a letter released in london, brian c. beazer, chairman and chief executive of beazer plc, told charles r. pullin, koppers' chairman and chief executive, that the proposed transaction ``offers excellent opportunity for people connected with koppers.''
he wrote that koppers would become ``part of a worldwide organization with the extensive resorces, depth of expertise and financial strength.''
beazer said it planned to operate koppers as an independent autonomous business and that there were no plans to move its headquarters from pittsburgh
it said affiliates of bns currently own 2.1 million kopper shares, or about 7.45 percent of koppers' outstanding common stock
robert o'gara, a spokesman for koppers, said the company had no comment on the offer and refused to comment on whether koppers' board planned to meet to discuss it
he said koppers had nearly 28.6 million common shares at the end of 1987, which would make the value of the tender offer about $1.29 billion
koppers' main businesses are construction materials and services, which mainly involve road construction, and chemical and allied products
koppers reported its profit for 1987 fell to $10.2 million, or 36 cents share, from $74.1 million, or $2.59 a share, a year earlier. the results included a charge of $59.4 million in 1987 due to settlement of a lawsuit
revenue for 1987 rose to $1.52 billion from $1.4 billion a year earlier
beazer said it earned $82.8 million on sales of $1.7 billion in its latest fiscal year ended june 30, 1987
beazer already has interests in the united states. it bought gifford-hill &amp; co., a cement-maker based in dallas, in 1986
