as a top economist for nikko securities ltd., one of japan's largest brokerage firms, robert a. brusca has had to do more than just showcase his abilities for forecasting u.s. economic growth or the trade gap. for one thing, he's had to develop a taste for green tea
after about the seventh cup in one day i've had just about all the green tea i care to have,'' said the 37-year-old brusca, chief economist in the fixed-income division of nikko securities co. international inc., a nikko subsidiary
since joining nikko about two years ago and becoming the first american to be named a chief economist in that company, brusca has learned that foreign diplomacy and economics often go hand in hand _ and that having a sense of humor helps puts the two in harmony
his job is to keep nikko clients in japan and elsewhere abreast of u.s. economic conditions and to advise them on investments, particularly in the area of government bonds
but trying to predict the ups and downs of interest rates can sometimes be as difficult as learning the proper way to bow in japan; to exchange meishis, or business cards; or to drink green tea, japan's counterpart to coffee
in japan, ``everything is proper. the business meetings are very formal. people are very polite,'' said brusca, an affable man with thin brown hair and glasses. his wife, candace, is an aspiring actress
when you arrive at a meeting, you're introduced formally. you're seated in an office or a meeting room with tea tables and overstuffed chairs
then you exchange business cards. they're always handled with two hands, and once they're exchanged you leave them directly in front of you. each person takes turns to talk. it's considered rude to interrupt.''
despite the formality, the wry humor that has become brusca's trademark in the financial world still manages to find a frequent outlet
i was talking with two japanese executives who had been working together for 15 years,'' he recalled. ``the conversation turned to first names and it came out that those two didn't know each other's first name
i said, `everyone has the same first name (in japan) _ mister.'''
the two stoic men managed to crack a smile, brusca noted with pride
his weekly reports to clients on the state of the world's economy can be equally amusing. one dated jan. 29, for instance, used the comic book characters batman and robin in describing how economic strength in the fourth quarter was likely to give way to weakness through 1988
one of their favorite tricks was to turn their car sharply while moving at high speed so that it would skid backwards while going in the same direction until traction overtook inertia and they were able to reverse direction. the u.s. economy is experiencing a bat turn of sorts ...''
and then there was the report two weeks earlier that focused on west germany's reluctance to stimulate its economy to help improve its trade imbalance with the united states
i want to draw the distinction between being thoughtless and being mindless,'' he wrote. ``thoughtlessness implies an ability ... to be more considerate of the needs of others. mindlessness implies an inability to think clearly about anything ..
from my perch overseas their (west germany's) policies look mindless, but possibly they are merely thoughtless.''
brusca says those offbeat analogies are often deleted when translated from english to japanese
the people who read the japanese (version) have no idea i have a sense of humor,'' he said. ``and sometimes the people who read the english version have no idea i have a sense of humor.''
it's his unflinching wit, though, that helps get the detroit native quoted in business publications and on televised financial news shows. he also writes a regular column in ``financial world'' and is a contributor to nikkei financial daily
when asked nine days after the oct. 19 stock market collapse how wall street planned to commemorate the crash of 1929, he quickly responded, ``with paper hats and paper losses.''
but brusca warns: ``don't mistake that i'm not serious. i'm very serious about what i do. but the use of humor helps. it's a very high-pressure job. you can be ungodly serious or you can stay loose.''
advising investors about how and when to spend their hard-earned money is a tough business, and nikko didn't hire brusca just for his good humor
large japanese securities firms have gone out of their way in the past few years to hire experienced americans to act as teachers of sorts in helping ``westernize'' their foreign employers, brusca said
before nikko, he worked as a money market economist and ``fedwatcher'' at irving trust co. in new york. he also was a senior economist at the federal reserve bank of new york, where he analyzed international banking activity
brusca also holds doctorate and master's degrees from michigan state university
