the two broadest measures of the nation's money supply rose in the week ended feb. 22, the federal reserve board reported thursday
the fed said the measure known as m2 rose to a seasonally adjusted $2,952.8 billion from $2,946.4 billion the previous week
an even broader measure, m3, increased to a seasonally adjusted $3,724.2 billion from $3,721.5 billion
the narrowest measure of the money supply, m1, rose to a seasonally adjusted $762.1 billion from $759.9 billion
m1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts and non-bank travelers checks. m2 is m1 plus accounts like savings deposits and money-market mutual funds. m3 is m2 plus less-liquid accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations of $100,000
in judging its monetary policy, the fed has indicated it is monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the difference between short- and long-term interest rates. it also has shifted its attention from m1 to the two broader money supply measures
for the latest 13 weeks, m2 averaged $2,920.6 billion, a 4.3 percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 13 weeks. m3 averaged $3,684.3 billion, up 5.2 percent, while m1 rose 2.2 percent to an average of $756.1 billion
the fed said in early 1988 that it would like annual growth for m2 and m3 to be between 4 percent and 8 percent, which is slightly lower than the 1987 target of 5.5 percent to 8.5 percent. the fed has not set a specific target range for m1 since early 1987
in other reports:
_the federal reserve bank of new york reported commercial and industrial loans at major new york city banks fell $1.07 billion in the week ended feb. 24, compared with a gain of $444 million a week earlier
_the federal reserve said bank borrowings from the federal reserve system averaged $187 million day in the week ended wednesday, up from $132 million
_the federal reserve bank of st. louis reported that the monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at federal reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation, was $272.5 billion in the two-week period ended wednesday, up from $272.1 billion two weeks earlier
some cattle futures prices plunged the 1{-cent limit allowed for daily trading thursday due to slack demand for beef and reports of a packer plant closing, analysts said
on other markets, grain and soybean futures retreated; energy futures were down; precious metals were mixed; and stock-index futures advanced
tight supplies of slaughter-ready cattle have driven up the prices asked by producers, but sales of beef have slowed during the lenten season and packing houses are caught in middle, analysts said
swift independent packing co. said thursday it would close its dumas, texas, slaughter facility next week, at least temporarily, and traders on the chicago mercantile exchange feared other plants also would close, said chuck levitt, an analyst in chicago for shearson lehman hutton inc
a wave of plant closings could lead to a backlog of finished cattle, ultimately forcing cash cattle prices lower, he said
the sell-off was exacerbated by the record-high number of unfilled buy orders for live cattle going into thursday's session, said tom o'hare, an analyst in new york for smith barney, harris upham &amp; co
when live cattle for april delivery fell below the key support level of 71.20 cents a pound, traders rushed to offset those open ``long'' positions with sell orders, accelerating the slide, he said
when you have a lot of open interest it has the potential for making the market very volatile,'' o'hare said
a lot of people have gotten in in the last couple of weeks, but the movement of beef carcasses and boxed beef has been insufficient to make people continue to be long.''
hog futures retreated on reports that japanese inspectors had detected residues of sulfamethazine, a possibly carcinogenic feed additive, in shipments of u.s. pork, analysts said
live cattle settled .80 cent to 1.50 cents lower with the contract for delivery in april at 70.62 cents a pound; feeder cattle were 1 cent to 1.50 cents lower with march at 79.07 cents a pound; hogs were .02 cent to .80 cent lower with april at 42.45 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were unchanged to .30 cent lower with march at 52.25 cents a pound
soybean futures prices dropped sharply on the chicago board of trade. grain futures also ended lower
the beginning of the south american soybean harvest, coupled with expectations of increased farmer selling of soybeans, created concern that abundant supplies could depress cash prices, analysts said
the wheat market drifted lower amid nervousness about the agriculture department's new series of surplus wheat auctions, analysts said
the usda sold 10 million bushels of surplus wheat on tuesday. but the agency announced after thursday's close that it had sold just 1.4 million of the 10 million bushels it had offered on wednesday. another auction on friday has the potential of putting another 10 million bushels of surplus wheat onto the open market
corn prices fell only slightly, with support stemming from ideas the soviet union had purchased more u.s. corn than the usda has confirmed, said ted mao, an analyst for shearson
wheat settled 1} cents to 2} cents lower with march at $3.04\ a bushel; corn was \ cent to 1\ cents lower with march at $2.00} a bushel; oats were 2 cents to 7{ cents lower with march at $1.86 a bushel; soybeans were 4\ cents to 8 cents lower with march at $6.23 a bushel
oil futures started out strong, then sold off sharply and settled near the day's lows on the new york mercantile exchange
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 17 cents lower with april at $15.50 a barrel; heating oil was .44 cent to 1.04 cents lower with april at 42.89 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .27 cent to .55 cent lower with april at 44.40 cents a gallon
gold futures followed oil prices lower on new york's commodity exchange, while silver futures moved higher due to silver's value as an industrial metal, said bette raptopoulos, an analyst for prudential-bache securities inc
gold settled $3 to $3.40 lower with april at $429.10 a troy ounce; silver was 4.3 cents to 4.8 cents higher with march at $6.264 a troy ounce
stock-index futures slipped lower on the chicago mercantile exchange, where the contract for march delivery of the standard &amp; poor's 500 index settled .10 point higher at 268.45. the underlying spot index lost .09 point, closing at 267.89
workers contemplated other jobs and city officials thought about attracting other employers after general motors corp. said it planned to close the only plant still making pontiacs in pontiac
while company officials blamed market conditions for the demise of the pontiac fiero, workers said engineering innovations and better promotion could have helped
pontiac general manager michael losh blamed the market conditions for sagging fiero sales, from 101,720 in 1984 to 47,156 last year
workers were sent home tuesday after losh announced that the plant will shut down after the 1988 model year, idling 1,109
the fiero plant was one of the first at gm to accept japanese-style team organization of workers and was used as a model for other plants, united auto workers local 653 president harold cox said
but some workers said the teamwork idea evidently did not extend to business decisions
we built the best quality in the corporation for four years,'' said one, dale jorden of clarkston. ``why are we being laid off?''
analysts and others pointed to an overall drop in sales of sporty, two-seater cars like the fiero. toyota mr2 and mazda rx7 sales also have lagged
in addition, the fiero had problems including engine fires so frequent that gm recalled the entire 1984 fiero production run late last year
gm already had closed a foundry, another car assembly plant, a heavy-duty truck plant and a bus plant in pontiac and put more than 1,200 other fiero workers on layoff
the fiero is the last pontiac manufactured in pontiac, though the division will still be based there, noted city council president emmett elliott jr., who is also a local 653 officer
it was a business decision, but from my position, i'd say it was a bad decision,'' elliott said. ``they sell a product all over the country and label it a `pontiac' and now they don't even build it here.''
mayor walter moore estimated the city will lose $200,000 in tax revenue and said he has asked to meet with gm officials to discuss bringing new work to the plant
but council president pro tem peter tenuta said it was not gm the city should talk to. ``we should do everything we can to try to fill those buildings with non-automotive-type jobs,'' he said
cox said he was sorry gm did not do more to promote and market the car, which was labeled revolutionary when introduced nearly five years ago because of its mid-engine design, space-frame and plastic body panels
dick long, uaw local 653 vice president, said delaying engineering changes such as addition of power steering undoubtedly hastened its demise
i think the engineering community let us down,'' long said
the announcement came without warning. only last week gm approved a $15 million special advertising campaign for the fiero. gm's chevrolet-pontiac-canada group called 12 skilled toolmakers back to their jobs last week to work on tooling for a redesigned 1990 fiero
dave d. campbell, a gm vice president and director of operations for the pontiac group, said the decision came at a meeting monday after an intensive review that began only three or four weeks ago
losh would not speculate on whether the fiero plant might reopen to build a new product
campbell said one possible future product would be a plastic-body replacement for the pontiac firebird and chevrolet camaro that is scheduled for the 1991 model year
a detention hearing for stock speculator john mulheren, accused of threatening a witness in the ivan boesky insider trading probe, has been moved from new jersey to new york
u.s. district judge kevin duffy ordered the hearing moved up from 2 p.m. friday in fort monmouth, n.j. to 10 a.m. in manhattan at the request of defense lawyer otto obermaier
the defense attorney said he wanted the hearing moved up ``to prevent the prosecution from delaying _ and allowing mr. mulheren, ultimately, to be released on bail.''
obermaier claimed federal prosecutors would seek a psychiatric evaluation of mulheren to hold him, in effect, without bail for 30 days
assistant u.s. attorney robert gage, while denying the government wanted to delay bail proceedings for mulheren, conceded: ``it would be irresponsible for us not to get an adequate medical opinion.''
mulheren, 38, the senior partner at the jamie securities co., was arrested on weapons charges feb. 18 by police in rumson, n.j. and a federal criminal complaint filed in manhattan accused him of threatening a witness in the boesky probe, identified only as ``witness x.''
mulheren was released without bond tuesday on the new jersey charges, but was immediately taken into federal custody
the new hearing is scheduled before u.s. magistrate kathleen roberts
bond prices barely budged in lethargic trading thursday as the market looked for more evidence on the strength of the economy
the treasury's bellwether 30-year bond finished unchanged and its yield held steady at 8.31 percent, the same as late wednesday
most traders were said to be keeping a low profile in anticipation of the labor department's unemployment report for february, which is due out friday and could shed some more light on the economy's strength
it's been a dead calm in the bond market for the last several days,'' said harold nathan, senior financial economist for wells fargo &amp; co. in san francisco. he said a new decline in commodity prices, often viewed positively by bond traders concerned about inflation, failed to cheer the markets
he said the market appears to have adjusted to a recent slight relaxation in monetary policy by the federal reserve board, and was looking to the employment report for additional evidence on the economy
we are not dipping into recession, but the question is how fast are we growing,'' he said
prices of short-term governments were unchanged to 1-32 point higher, while intermediate maturities and 20-year issues were unchanged, according to figures provided by telerate inc
the movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the price of a bond with a $1,000 face value
the merrill lynch daily treasury index, which measures price movements on all outstanding treasury issues with maturities of a year or longer, rose 0.04 to 114.01. the shearson lehman hutton composite index, which makes a similar measurement, rose 0.19 to 1,192.39
in corporate trading, industrials and utilities were unchanged in light trading, according to the investment firm of salomon brothers inc
moody's investment grade corporate bond index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, fell 0.03 to 286.16
yields on three-month treasury bills were unchanged at 5.60 percent. a basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. six-month bills rose 4 basis points to 5.86 percent and one-year bills edged up 2 basis points at 6.16 percent
the federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, traded at 6 7-16 percent, down from 6{ percent late wednesday
a chicago gynecologist was indicted for perjury and on obstruction of justice charges thursday over his testimony on behalf of the a.h. robins co. concerning its dalkon shield birth control device, the justice department said
dr. louis g. keith, 53, an obstetrician-gynecologist at northwestern university medical school in chicago, testified falsely in a lawsuit about his role in tests regarding the transfer of bacteria by the tail string of the intrauterine shield, a federal grand jury alleged
contrary to his testimony, keith didn't design, direct or conduct the experiments about which he testified, said the nine-count indictment returned in u.s. district court in tampa, fla
keith testified that tests showed the tail string of the dalkon shield didn't transfer fluids or bacteria
keith's testimony came during a trial in tampa on march 15, 1983, in which a woman, linda harre, was seeking damages for injuries allegedly suffered by the dalkon shield
the maximum penalty for violating the perjury law is five years in prison and a $10,000 fine. the maximum penalty for obstruction of justice is five years in prison and a $5,000 fine
the a.h. robins of richmond, va., sought protection from creditors under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code in august 1985 after thousands of women alleged they were injured by the dalkon shield. some 200,000 claims have been filed by women who said the birth control device caused spontaneous abortions, infections, sterility and other problems
a maker of 12-inch sidewalk bicycles is offering to replace wheels that could shatter if overinflated, the consumer product safety commission said thursday
the replacement program involves about 40,000 model bmx-12 bikes made by rand international of farmingdale, n.y., the agency said. bikes were sold through otasco and other stores in the east, south and southeast prior to january 1987
the 12-inch boys' bikes are blue and can be identified by the rand label on the stem of the front fork
the safety commission said no injuries have been reported, but there is the danger that if the tires are overinflated the rims could shatter, causing a hazard to bystanders
rand is offering free replacement wheels to consumers who write to rand international, 51 executive blvd., farmingdale, n.y., 11735. interested consumers can call rand at 1-516-249-6000 or the safety commission at 1-800-638-2772
media general inc. as expected, rejected a $1.75 billion buyout proposal from television producer burt sugarman on thursday
in a four-sentence letter to sugarman, media general president james s. evans said the founding bryan family, which owns a controlling interest in the company, deemed the offer unacceptable
evans stated the family would vote against the proposal if put to a shareholder vote, and that ``under the circumstances no further action on the part of the board is appropriate
sugarman controls 9.8 percent of media general's 28 million shares of publicly-traded class a common stock and has offered $61.50 per share for the remainder of the company's class a and class b stock, or a total of about $1.75 billion
about 71 percent of media general's privately-held class b shares are owned by chairman d. tennant bryan and vice chairman j. stewart bryan iii. the rest is owned by relatives and others closely associated with the family and media general
the 559,168 class b shares have the power to elect seven of the company's 10 directors. furthermore, any change in control of the company requires approval from two-thirds of the class b holders
after sugarman made his buyout offer on monday, the bryans issued a statement that their stock was not for sale at any price
sugarman was traveling and was unavailable to comment on evans' letter, said spokesman jeffrey taufield in new york
media general class a shares fell $1.25 to $46.12{ a share thursday on the new york stock exchange
media general owns a number of daily newspapers, plus 32 weeklies and several television stations. moved on general news wires.</note>
the senate on wednesday night narrowly approved a resolution by senators from steel-producing states opposing a $400 million world bank loan to help mexico upgrade its steel industry
it doesn't make any sense where we have unemployed steel workers walking up and down the streets of the cities of this country,'' said sen. howard metzenbaum, d-ohio, who with sen. john heinz, r-pa., proposed the resolution
the resolution was attached on a 48-45 vote to legislation that would outlaw most uses of lie detector tests by private employers. final action on that bill is scheduled for thursday
heinz complained that the amount of aid in the loan is equivalent to what would be a $4 billion bailout of the u.s. steel industry _ which is 10 times larger than the mexican steel industry _ at a time when american steel employment has dropped by 56 percent over the past 12 years
however, the resolution was opposed by sens. christopher dodd, d-conn.; bill bradley, d-n.j.; ted stevens, r-alaska; john chafee, r-r.i., daniel j. evans, r-wash., and nancy kassebaum, r-kan
bradley said the loan is just the type of aid needed to assure that a non-marxist government will continue to rule in mexico. other opponents of the resolution said the senate should not be interfering in every decision made by the world bank
earlier wednesday, metzenbaum said treasury secretary james a. baker iii has agreed to vote against the loan if he cannot persuade the bank to delay its consideration. the world bank board, which is made up of 22 members representing 151 member countries, is scheduled to take up the loan proposal thursday
baker agreed to the move following a meeting called by senate majority leader robert byrd, d-w.va., metzenbaum said
metzenbaum said he warned baker that support for the world bank in congress could evaporate if the loan were made. the united states provides 20 percent of the world bank's funding
it is absurd for the american government to contribute to a world bank policy that will hurt the american steel industry and american steel workers,'' the senator said
the kind of assistance the world bank plans to give to mexico to make its steel industry more competitive is exactly the kind of assistance this administration has refused to give to our own industry here at home,'' he said
a treasury department spokesman said it is the agency's policy not to comment on a vote until it occurs
